His pass catching ability should once again be a major asset in Week 3 when he faces an Atlanta defense that has struggled to defend backs in the passing game over the past three seasons.
report: Alvin Kamara rushed 13 times for 46 yards and caught all six of his targets for 53 yards in Sunday's Week 2 win over the Browns.

impact: Kamara had a busy opening drive, surging to 36 yards on four touches with 17 coming on his first carry. That would be a sign of things to come as the reigning Offensive Rookie of the Year was a focal point of the Saints’ offense all afternoon. The only thing missing was a touchdown. Kamara was stuffed on third-and-goal from the half-yard line in the fourth quarter and was later vultured by fullback Zach Line, who caught a one-yard touchdown on the very next play. He tortured fantasy owners again in overtime by having a walk-off touchdown overturned on replay. Predictably, Drew Brees punched it on the following play. Kamara has averaged a slightly underwhelming 3.81 yards per carry this year, but his weekly touchdown upside and monster workload in the passing game will continue to keep him in the RB1 conversation. Look for him to put up another silly stat line next week against the Giants.
report: Alvin Kamara totaled 66 yards on 16 carries while corralling 15-of-20 targets for an additional 124 yards Sunday in the Saints’ Week 3 victory over the Falcons.

impact: He added five catches for 47 yards on a team-high nine targets.  What else more is there to say?  Kamara and Todd Gurley are head and shoulders above the rest of the pack as the elite fantasy players.  They do it week in and week out without skipping beats.  New Orleans settled for four first-half field goals before Kamara took over after the break, scoring nine-, four-, and 49-yard touchdowns, with the 49-yarder sealing the win.  The Redskins are next in Week 5.
report: Alvin Kamara rushed 19 times for 134 yards and three touchdowns in the Saints' 33-18, Week 4 win over the Giants.

impact: Mark Ingram returned from his four-week suspension to make his 2018 debut and made the start for the Saints.  He went on his way to out-carry Kamara 16-6 and out-touch him 18-9 overall.  Ingram also scored two goal-line plunge touchdowns in the first half.  Kamara owners are going to be seriously concerned after this one.  Kamara averaged 22.75 touches per game Weeks 1-4 but took a major back seat to Ingram tonight.  Perhaps coach Sean Payton was just overworking Ingram to get him up to speed and possibly getting Kamara some extra rest after the big workloads the first four weeks with the Saints now heading into their bye.  But Kamara is highly unlikely to come close to his Weeks 1-4 usage the rest of the way.  He's going to need big plays to maintain elite RB1 status, and those didn't come Monday night.  The Ravens are up next in Week 7.
report: Alvin Kamara rushed just six times for 24 yards and caught 3-of-4 targets for 15 yards in the Saints' Week 5 win over the Redskins.

impact: Kamara got the start and out-touched Mark Ingram 19-14 one game after Ingram out-touched Kamara 18-9 in his 2018 debut. Both players received goal line looks, but only Kamara cashed his in. We would expect today's touch distribution to be closer to the norm than Week 5's going forward. With Taysom Hill emerging as a bigger nuisance, however, Kamara will remain a mid-range to low-end RB1 for Week 8 in Minnesota.
report: Alvin Kamara rushed 17 times for 64 yards and a touchdown in the Saints' Week 7 win over the Ravens, adding two catches for 11 additional yards.

impact: Kamara scored on a shovel pass on the Saints’ opening drive. His second TD came on a goal-line carry in the final seconds of the first half. Kamara dominated snaps early and out-touched Mark Ingram for the second straight week. He looks to have reestablished himself as the clear feature back going forward. Kamara has a blowup spot in Week 9 in what should be a high-scoring game with the Rams.
report: Alvin Kamara rushed 13 times for 45 yards and a touchdown and caught 7-of-8 targets for 31 yards and a receiving touchdown in the Saints' Week 8 win over the Vikings.

impact: Kamara was cooking early in this game. Elusive as always, Kamara totaled 50 yards on the first two drives, capping both with touchdowns. The first was an 11-yard run in which he broke multiple touchdowns, and the second was a 16-yard catch in which he put a nice move on Lamarcus Joyner to get open. He added another one-yard score just before halftime, finishing the first half with 84 total yards and three scores. New Orleans’ offense fell into a lull in the second half, allowing the Rams back into the game, but Kamara got things back on track with a hurdling 17-yard gain to spark a field-goal drive in the fourth quarter and finished things off with a fourth-down conversion to run out the clock. Even with Mark Ingram back, Kamara now has six touchdowns in his last three games. He will be a high-end RB1 next week against the Bengals.
report: Alvin Kamara rushed 19 times for 82 yards and two touchdowns and hauled in 4-of-5 targets for 34 yards and another score in the Saints' Week 9 win over the Rams.

impact: Kamara had rushing scores from four and one yard out, giving him his fifth game this season in which he's scored multiple touchdowns. With the Saints coasting, he and Mark Ingram shared more opportunities than previous weeks, but Kamara till dominated the snaps when the Saints where in scoring position. With 12 touchdowns now on the season, Kamara will be a set-and-forget option in Week 11 at home against the Eagles.
report: Alvin Kamara rushed 12 times for 56 yards and two touchdowns while catching 4-of-5 targets for 46 yards in Sunday's Week 10 win over the Bengals.

impact: The Saints dominated this game, and Kamara certainly did his part on the ground, but his biggest play came on his only target. With the game already well in hand, the Saints decided to go for it on fourth down at the edge of field goal range. Lined up out wide, Kamara got a step on Malcolm Jenkins, caught a perfectly thrown pass from Drew Brees, and fought through a tackle attempt to get into the end zone. The score kept Kamara's now five-game scoring streak alive, and he has nine touchdowns over that span. He will be a good bet to add to that number against the Eagles on Thanksgiving.
report: Alvin Kamara rushed 13 times for 71 yards and turned his only target into a 38-yard touchdown in the Saints' Week 11 win over the Eagles.

impact: The Chiefs romped, but Kelce continued his recent trend of quiet games against the Bolts. He has just two catches in two career games in "StubHub Center." The Chiefs have so many weapons that down weeks are bound to happen for Kelce, but he will be back out there as a top-three TE1 against the Steelers in Week 2. Patrick Mahomes has the looks of a quarterback who is going to get all of his studs big plays.
report: Travis Kelce caught just 1-of-6 targets for six yards in the Chiefs' Week 1 win over the Chargers.

impact: One week after he was held to one catch against the Chargers, Kelce erupted for just the third two-touchdown game of his career. Kelce split CB Cameron Sutton and LB Jon Bostic on his first score, corralling an absolute laser from Patrick Mahomes. For the second, he caught a low throw near the goal line for a 25-yarder. Kelce will get the 49ers in what could be a high-scoring Week 3 affair.
report: Travis Kelce caught 7-of-10 targets for 109 yards and two touchdowns in the Chiefs' Week 2 win over the Steelers.

impact: Patrick Mahomes spread the ball around in this one, but he kept coming back to Kelce, who was seemingly open on every play. The tight end finished the first half with 93 yards including a great one-handed grab in the two-minute drill, and he could have had a bigger day if the Chiefs were forced to throw more in the second half. He will remain a top-two tight end option next week in Denver.
report: Travis Kelce hauled in 8-of-10 targets for 114 yards in the Chiefs' Week 3 win over the 49ers.

impact: Kelce went catch-less on three targets in the first half but became Patrick Mahomes' go-to option after the break.  His touchdown came on a short pop pass to the right from two yards out in the fourth quarter.  Later in the same quarter, Kelce was drilled in the stomach and ribs area on an end-zone target and buckled to the ground before leaving the field with trainers.  It's possible he simply had the wind knocked out of him.  After catching one pass for six yards in the opener, Kelce has 22 catches for 301 yards and three touchdowns the last three weeks.  He gets the Jaguars in Week 5.
report: Travis Kelce caught 7-of-12 targets for 78 yards and one touchdown in the Chiefs' Week 4 win over the Broncos on Monday night.

impact: Kelce continued to look like the best tight end in the league in this one. He shook Telvin Smith to get open for a 15-yard catch on the opening drive, and he left Barry Church in the dust when he put on the brakes and changed direction on his 40-yard catch-and-run in the second quarter. He should have had a touchdown on that drive, but he dropped the pass. Kelce now has at least 100 yards in three of his last four games. He will be the top option at tight end next week in New England.
report: Travis Kelce hauled in 5-of-8 targets for 100 yards in the Chiefs' Week 5 win over the Jaguars.

impact: Kelce got most of his yards on a 44-yard third down catch in the first quarter. He led the Chiefs in receiving, but was faded in the red-zone in favor of Kareem Hunt and Demetrius Harris. Kelce has been held out of the end-zone in three straight weeks. He's due for some positive regression in Week 8 against Denver.
report: Travis Kelce caught five passes for 95 yards in Week 7 against the Bengals.

impact: Kelce got most of his yards on a 44-yard third down catch in the first quarter. He led the Chiefs in receiving, but was faded in the red-zone in favor of Kareem Hunt and Demetrius Harris. Kelce has been held out of the end-zone in three straight weeks. He's due for some positive regression in Week 8 against Denver.
report: Travis Kelce caught five passes for 95 yards in Week 7 against the Bengals.

impact: Four of Kelce's catches came in the first half. That's also when he scored his lone touchdown, finding the end zone on a nine-yard strike from Patrick Mahomes early in the second quarter. Sunday erased a three-game touchdown drought for Kelce, who has now eclipsed 70 yards in six of his last seven outings. He's been a thorn in Denver's side, scoring in each of his last five games against KC's division rival. Kelce and the Chiefs begin the second half of their season next week at Cleveland.
report: Travis Kelce corralled six-of-10 targets for 79 yards and a touchdown Sunday in the Chiefs’ Week 8 win over Denver.

impact: The Northeast Ohio native played in his first game in Cleveland of his career and did not disappoint. Kelce  repeatedly found holes in the Browns offense all afternoon. His scoring strikes came from 11 and 13-yards out, the latter which was an all-hands spear in coverage to open the second half and put the Chiefs up 28-15. Kelce is on pace to set new career-highs across the board and will be the top fantasy option at tight end in Week 10 when the Chiefs host the Cardinals.
report: Travis Kelce caught 7-of-9 targets for 99 yards and two touchdowns in Sunday's Week 9 win over the Browns.

impact: It breaks a two-game scoring streak for Kelce. Kelce finished behind only Tyreek Hill in targets and yards, but there just wasn't much volume for him with Patrick Mahomes throwing for only 249 yards. Even if Sammy Watkins returns, Kelce should rebound in a potential Week 11 shootout against the Rams.
report: Travis Kelce caught 6-of-7 targets for 46 yards in Week 11 against the Cardinals.

impact: Kearse worked as the Jets' No. 4 receiver behind Quincy Enunwa, Robby Anderson, and Terrelle Pryor.  He only saw two targets and lacks fantasy value.
report: Jermaine Kearse netted -1 yard in the Jets' Week 2 loss to the Dolphins.

impact: Kearse didn't make his first catch until deep in the third quarter. He's a non-factor in a Jets offense that can't support more than one wideout.
report: Jermaine Kearse caught 2-of-5 passes for 23 yards in Week 4 against the Jagaurs.

impact: Kearse would likely need Quincy Enunwa to miss time to become a fantasy factor.
report: Jermaine Kearse caught 1-of-4 targets for 14 yards in the Jets' Week 5 win.

impact: Kearse's stock was pointing up after taking over as Gang Green's slot receiver in Week 5, and he made good on increased playing time following Quincy Enunwa's second-quarter ankle injury.  Enunwa did not return, and Kearse went to work on the interior of Indianapolis' defense with crisp routes and chunk gains on slants.  There are indications Enunwa's injury could be severe.  Kearse will be worth grabbing in 12- and 14-team PPR leagues this week.
report: Jermaine Kearse caught 9-of-10 targets for 94 yards in the Jets' Week 6 win over the Colts.

impact: Sam Darnold was horrendous in this one, throwing three interceptions, and completing just 40.5% of his passes, doing a lot of work on the final meaningless possession with dump-offs to Trenton Cannon out of the backfield.  Kearse was a hot name in fantasy this week after he caught 9-of-10 targets for 94 yards against the Colts last week.  He was expected to play a major role with Quincy Enunwa (ankle) and Terrelle Pryor (groin) both out.  He wasn't targeted in the second half and had no chance on his two first-half ones.  Kearse will be tough to get behind next week on the road in Chicago.
report: Jermaine Kearse failed to catch either of his two targets in the Jets' 37-17, Week 7 loss to the Vikings.

impact: Sam Darnold was horrendous in this one, throwing three interceptions, and completing just 40.5% of his passes, doing a lot of work on the final meaningless possession with dump-offs to Trenton Cannon out of the backfield.  Kearse was a hot name in fantasy this week after he caught 9-of-10 targets for 94 yards against the Colts last week.  He was expected to play a major role with Quincy Enunwa (ankle) and Terrelle Pryor (groin) both out.  He wasn't targeted in the second half and had no chance on his two first-half ones.  Kearse will be tough to get behind next week on the road in Chicago.
report: Jermaine Kearse failed to catch either of his two targets in the Jets' 37-17, Week 7 loss to the Vikings.

impact: Kearse got all his yards early before getting shutout in the second half. It's the second straight week Kearse has been a non-factor despite his expanded role. With Robby Anderson and Quincy Enunwa candidates to return in Week 9, Kearse isn't worth rostering in fantasy leagues.
report: Jermaine Kearse caught 3-of-10 passes for 30 yards in Week 8 against Chicago.

impact: Even with Quincy Enunwa and Robby Anderson back in the lineup, Kearse led the team with eight targets. As has been the case recently, he did not do much with the work, and the Jets’ struggling passing game is unlikely to create much fantasy value moving forward. Kearse can be left on the wire.
report: Jermaine Kearse hauled in 3-of-8 targets for 20 yards in the Jets' Week 9 loss to the Dolphins.

impact: Pedestrian slot man Kearse is safe to drop entering the Jets' Week 11 bye.
report: Jermaine Kearse caught 2-of-4 targets for 16 yards in the Jets' Week 10 loss to Buffalo.

impact: Lynch's highlight came on a pitch play where he got to the perimeter of the Browns' defense and followed an impressive downfield block by Martavis Bryant to gain 59 yards.  Lynch failed to score due to repeated goal-line stuffs, but this was his biggest rushing-yardage performance since 2014 with Seattle.  Lynch now has 20 or more touches in three straight games.  In an improving Raiders offense, he will be a high-end RB2 play in Week 5 at the Chargers.
report: Marshawn Lynch rushed 20 times for 130 yards and caught 3-of-5 targets for 27 yards in the Raiders' Week 4 win over the Browns.

impact: Lynch's volume goes as the Raiders' game script goes, and the Raiders' game script got completely out of hand in this one. Jalen Richard even got involved late with Oakland in full-on catch-up mode, finishing with six catches on the day. Lynch is still averaging 15.4 carries and has received at least 18 in Oakland's three competitive games this season. With Seattle next up, Lynch should resume the RB2-usage we're accustomed to.
report: Marshawn Lynch rushed nine times for 31 yards, adding two catches for 10 yards in the Raiders' Week 5 romping by the Chargers.

impact: It was a frustrating day for the entire Raiders' offense, which would have gotten shut out if not for a garbage-time field goal to "cut the deficit" to 27-3.  Lynch has been Oakland's best offensive player, but he has been boom or bust in fantasy because the Raiders have too often found themselves in negative game script.  Lynch now draws a Week 7 bye to rest his 32-year-old legs.
report: Marshawn Lynch rushed 13 times for 45 yards and caught 3-of-5 targets for 14 yards in the Raiders' Week 6 loss to Seattle.

impact:
The Colts did not stretch the field -- just one of Luck's 39 completions gained more than 20 yards -- but Luck looked mostly comfortable against a talented Bengals pass rush and picked apart the defense at times in Frank Reich's up-tempo, no-huddle attack.  He absorbed only nine hits and two sacks among 61 total dropbacks. 
 Luck showed enough in this game to be viewed as a locked-in QB1 going forward.  He gets a softer Week 2 matchup in Washington.
report: Andrew Luck completed 39-of-53 passes for 319 yards, two touchdowns, and an interception in the Colts' Week 1 loss to Cincinnati.

impact: He was sacked once for a two-yard loss. Luck got off to a hot start, completing four-of-five passes for 40 yards on the Colts’ opening drive including a seven-yard touchdown strike to tight end Eric Ebron. He had his most success throwing to T.Y. Hilton, connecting seven times for 83 yards and a touchdown. That touchdown came on a two-yard bunny with 7:32 remaining in the fourth quarter. Luck endured his share of struggles despite the victory. He was intercepted twice, both by safety D.J. Swearinger. The first pick was on a ball tipped at the line of scrimmage but the second came on a pass Luck never should have thrown as Swearinger read his eyes the whole way. Sunday marked Luck’s first win as a starter since Week 17 of 2016. He’ll try to make it two in a row next week when the Colts travel to Philadelphia to take on the reigning World Champs.
report: Andrew Luck completed 21-of-31 passes for 179 yards with two touchdowns and two interceptions while adding two yards on four carries Sunday in the Colts’ Week 2 win over the Redskins.

impact: Luck struggled through the rain and continued to fail to push the ball downfield on his throwing attempts. He had just 80 yards passing before the final two possessions, the latter closed with him being pulled for Jacoby Brissett on the Hail Mary attempt to win the game. Luck's yards per pass attempt have progressively dropped each week, going from 6.0 to 5.8 to 4.1 this week. Luck's athleticism is still prevalent and he added a 33-yard run down the sideline, but his limitations driving the ball through the air have turned him into a dink-and-dunk passer. Luck will enter Week 4 as QB2 against the Texans.
report: Andrew Luck completed 25-of-40 passes for 164 yards with a touchdown in Sunday's Week 3 loss to the Eagles.

impact: The 62 attempts and 464 yards both set new career-highs for Luck.  At one point, the Colts trailed by three possessions in the second half.  But Luck rallied the team back as the Texans tried to give it away to the Colts, who were able to force overtime.  Luck entered the day at the bottom of the barrel in yards-per-attempt, but he unleashed more downfield throws in this one, hitting T.Y. Hilton for a pair of 40-plus-yard grabs.  Hilton eventually pulled his hamstring in the fourth quarter, leaving Nyheim Hines as Luck's top target.  The two hooked up for two red-zone touchdowns, with the other two going to Zach Pascal and Eric Ebron.  Luck's arm figures to surely be a bit tender this week ahead of a Thursday night date in Foxboro with the Patriots where he'll be a volume-driven QB1.  The Colts have zero running game.
report: Andrew Luck completed 40-of-62 passes for 464 yards and four touchdowns in the Colts' 37-34, Week 4 loss to the Texans.

impact: Although Luck's 6.18 yards per attempt was once again shaky, tonight was nothing but positives. Luck's spiral continued to tighten as he showed feathery ball placement in the short-to-intermediate parts of the field. Luck's deep ball is still not all the way back. He is lacking his pre-injury drive and appeared to lack feel the few times he really uncorked it. That should not bury the lede that he was confident and commanding with what was essentially an entire second-team offense thanks to injuries. His only real mistake was his first pick, a forced throw under pressure. The 29-year-old quarterback is firmly on the comeback trail. He has 10 days to rest up for a road trip to New York to face the Jets.
report: Andrew Luck completed 38-of-59 passes for 365 yards, three touchdowns and two interceptions in the Colts' 38-24, Week 5 loss to the Patriots.

impact: Luck survived countless drops and pass-catcher injuries for a monster fantasy performance, even in the face of defeat.  Throwing to the likes of Mo Alie-Cox, Erik Swoope, "Marcus Johnson," and "Zach Pascal," Luck kept the Colts in the game even as their defense collapsed.  Performances like these are a testament to Luck's legitimate greatness.  He may have lost deep-ball prowess, but he is a surefire every-week fantasy starter.  The Colts host the reeling Bills next.
report: Andrew Luck completed 23-of-43 passes for 301 yards, four touchdowns, and three interceptions in the Colts' Week 6 loss to the Jets.

impact: He wasn’t sacked. Sunday ended Luck’s streak of three straight 300-yard passing games, though he still had a productive week with four touchdowns, a total he’s now reached in three of his last four outings. Two of Luck’s TDs went to T.Y. Hilton, who returned this week following a two-game absence. Luck took it easy with Indy up big in the second half, attempting just eight passes after halftime and ceding the final two drives to backup Jacoby Brissett. The 29-year-old’s only real slip-up came when he let a high snap go through the back of the end zone, resulting in a safety. The former first overall pick will look to stay hot next week when the Colts travel to Oakland for a date with the 1-5 Raiders.
report: Andrew Luck completed 17-of-23 passes for 156 yards and four touchdowns while adding three rushes for five yards Sunday in the Colts’ Week 7 victory over Buffalo.

impact: He wasn’t sacked. Sunday ended Luck’s streak of three straight 300-yard passing games, though he still had a productive week with four touchdowns, a total he’s now reached in three of his last four outings. Two of Luck’s TDs went to T.Y. Hilton, who returned this week following a two-game absence. Luck took it easy with Indy up big in the second half, attempting just eight passes after halftime and ceding the final two drives to backup Jacoby Brissett. The 29-year-old’s only real slip-up came when he let a high snap go through the back of the end zone, resulting in a safety. The former first overall pick will look to stay hot next week when the Colts travel to Oakland for a date with the 1-5 Raiders.
report: Andrew Luck completed 17-of-23 passes for 156 yards and four touchdowns while adding three rushes for five yards Sunday in the Colts’ Week 7 victory over Buffalo.

impact: Luck continued his recent touchdown binge by dishing out another three scores on Sunday. He's now delivered at least three touchdowns in each of his last five games. Even with T.Y. Hilton held in check (one catch for 34 yards), Luck still found success in the passing game, peppering his tight ends with targets while also showing strong chemistry with newcomer Dontrelle Inman (six catches for 52 yards). Luck has attempted passes at a prolific rate this year but that wasn't the case Sunday as the Colts actually attempted more runs (40) than passes (31) while riding Marlon Mack to victory. Luck and the Colts will take a two-game winning streak into their bye week.
report: Andrew Luck completed 22-of-31 passes for 239 yards and three touchdowns while losing two yards on two carries Sunday in the Colts’ Week 8 win over the Raiders.

impact: Luck’s first touchdown could not have been much easier. The Jaguars just lost Eric Ebron on the opening drive, and Luck hit him for an easy 53-yard score. Jacksonville kept leaving pass catchers wide open after that, and Luck kept punishing them, hitting Jack Doyle for 20 yards, T.Y. Hilton for 35, and Mo Alie-Cox for 27 all before the end of the first quarter. He kept things going in the second, connecting with an again wide-open Ebron for a 12-yard touchdown before finding Alie-Cox for his third score of the half. Things ground to a halt in the second half, however. Luck’s interception was not his fault – it bounced off Alie-Cox – but he struggled to move the offense, allowing the Jaguars back into the game. Luckily for him, the defense stepped up late, and the Colts held on. Luck faces another divisional test next week when the Titans come to town. He will be a solid QB1 in that matchup.
report: Andrew Luck completed 21-of-29 passes for 285 yards, three touchdowns, and an interception in the Colts' Week 10 win over the Jaguars.

impact: The three-touchdown effort was Luck's seventh straight. Only 2007 Tom Brady and 2004 Peyton Manning posted longer streaks. Luck was a little more old school Luck in this one, getting cookin' with T.Y. Hilton down the field. The highlight was a 68-yard touchdown strike against Adoree' Jackson. Hilton got a step and then Luck delivered a perfect deep ball in stride. Luck is playing like an MVP candidate after his arm looked rusty the first few games of the season. He could easily extend his three-touchdown streak to eight against the pathetic Dolphins in Week 12.
report: Andrew Luck completed 23-of-29 passes for 297 yards and three touchdowns in the Colts' Week 11 blowout of the Titans.

impact: Lockett did not do much in this game, but he was able to get open deep where Russell Wilson hit him for a 51-yard touchdown. That kind of play makes Lockett an interesting dart throw every week, but he needs to produce more consistently to be a reliable fantasy option. With Doug Baldwin dealing with a knee injury, he might get his chance moving forward. Lockett should be added in most leagues.
report: Tyler Lockett hauled in 3-of-4 targets for 59 yards and a touchdown in the Seahawks' Week 1 loss to the Broncos.

impact: Lockett now has 3-59-1 and 5-60-1 lines to open the season.  Both touchdowns took big plays to score, as Lockett made a near-impossible grab draped in CB Kyle Fuller's coverage in the back corner of the end zone from 19 yards out in this one.  Fuller should have been flagged for interference but it didn't matter.  Lockett is very boom-or-bust-ish but gets a tasty date with the Cowboys at home in Week 3.  He'll be on the WR4 radar for that one.
report: Tyler Lockett caught 5-of-7 targets for 60 yards and one touchdown in the Seahawks' Week 2 loss to the Bears.

impact: He did most of his damage on one play, breaking off a 52-yard touchdown late in the first half on a play where Kavon Frazier blew his assignment. That was about it for Lockett, though the long touchdown may have been enough to push fantasy owners over the top. Lockett should remain Russell Wilson’s top receiving weapon in Doug Baldwin’s absence, though a tough matchup against Cardinals All-Pro corner Patrick Peterson awaits him in Week 4.
report: Tyler Lockett collected four catches for 77 yards and a touchdown on six targets Sunday in the Seahawks’ Week 3 win over the Cowboys.

impact: Lockett was second on the team in targets with Doug Baldwin returning to action, but led the team in receiving yardage on Sunday. After scoring in the opening three weeks of the season, Lockett failed to reach the end zone for the first time this season. With Baldwin returning, Lockett will be a WR3/FLEX option Week 5 when the Seahawks host the Rams.
report: Tyler Lockett caught 5-of-6 targets for 53 yards in Sunday's Week 4 win over the Cardinals.

impact: Lockett made the most of his opportunities in a game Russell Wilson completed just 13 passes. His touchdown was a 39-yarder on which he ran right past Marcus Peters, and he ran a great route to get the safety turned around on a 44-yard gain in the fourth quarter. With the Seahawks running a run-heavy, deep-shot offense, Lockett might end up being their most valuable fantasy receiver. He will have a good shot at some more big plays next week against the Raiders in London.
report: Tyler Lockett hauled in 3-of-5 targets for 98 yards and a touchdown in the Seahawks' Week 5 loss to the Rams.

impact: Lockett has now scored in 5-of-6 games.  Unfortunately, he was otherwise quiet in a game where the Seahawks leaned heavily on their rushing attack, and Doug Baldwin was Seattle's lone player to exceed four targets.  The Seahawks have a Week 7 bye forthcoming.  Lockett has earned every-week WR3/flex treatment.
report: Tyler Lockett caught 3-of-4 targets for 13 yards and a touchdown in the Seahawks' Week 6 blowout win over the Raiders.

impact: Lockett has now scored in 5-of-6 games.  Unfortunately, he was otherwise quiet in a game where the Seahawks leaned heavily on their rushing attack, and Doug Baldwin was Seattle's lone player to exceed four targets.  The Seahawks have a Week 7 bye forthcoming.  Lockett has earned every-week WR3/flex treatment.
report: Tyler Lockett caught 3-of-4 targets for 13 yards and a touchdown in the Seahawks' Week 6 blowout win over the Raiders.

impact: Lockett has now scored in three-straight games, and 6-of-7 on the year. He beat sticky Nigel Lawson coverage for six. Lockett was lucky to find the end zone in Detroit, as Russell Wilson attempted only 17 passes. He will hope for more volume in what should be a higher-scoring game against the Chargers in Week 9.
report: Tyler Lockett caught 2-of-2 targets for 34 yards and a touchdown in the Seahawks' Week 8 win over the Lions, adding two rushes for 13 additional yards.

impact: It was the fourth-straight game Lockett drew four or fewer targets. Unlike the first three, he did not find the end zone. Lockett will still remain in the WR4 mix for Week 10, as the Seahawks are going to have to up their passing volume to have any shot at keeping up with the Rams.
report: Tyler Lockett caught 3-of-4 targets for 22 yards in the Seahawks' Week 9 loss to the Chargers.

impact: The 85 yards from scrimmage were Lockett's most in four games. Lockett's 23-yard score was a thing of beauty against tight Troy Hill coverage. Hand fighting, Lockett won a tough battle and caught a perfectly-delivered Russell Wilson pass. It was his seventh touchdown of the season. Weekly target volume is difficult to predict in the Seahawks' run-heavy offense, but Thursday against the Packers could be another high-scoring game, raising Lockett's floor.
report: Tyler Lockett caught 5-of-6 targets for 67 yards and a touchdown in the Seahawks' Week 10 loss to the Rams, adding an 18-yard carry.

impact: Lockett also drew a 48-yard DPI on a bad Russell Wilson underthrow. One of Lockett's five grabs looked like it could maybe be overturned on review, but a timeout-poor Mike McCarthy opted not to challenge. The 71 yards were Lockett's most in five games. Lockett has been visiting the end zone with regularity but has drawn more than six targets only one time all season. He will be a high-risk WR3/4 for Week 12 against the Panthers.
report: Tyler Lockett caught 5-of-5 targets for 71 yards in the Seahawks' Week 11 win over the Packers, adding a one-yard rush.

impact: His performance might not be as surprising as Will Dissly leading the Seahawks in receiving, but Lindsay certainly was not expected to finish with the same number of carries and rushing yards as Royce Freeman in the season opener. That said, this is probably not a fluke. Lindsay earned his roster spot with a big training camp, and he saw plenty of snaps with the first-team offense in the third preseason game. While he might not get as many chances in the running game moving forward – it seemed to be something of a "hot hand" situation – he looks like the No. 2 ahead of Devontae Booker.
report: Phillip Lindsay rushed 15 times for 71 yards and hauled in 2-of-3 targets for 31 yards and a touchdown in the Broncos' Week 1 win over the Seahawks.

impact: Lindsay had 15 touches compared to eight for Royce Freeman and three for Devontae Booker as he was the first Denver running back to ever have over 100-yards from scrimmage in each of his first two career games in franchise history. Lindsay has built off a strong preseason to overtake a lead role in this Denver backfield, but still doesn't have a firm grasp on the goal line work, which will keep him as a RB2/FLEX option Week 3 when the Broncos head to Baltimore.
report: Phillip Lindsay rushed 14 times for 107 yards with one reception for four yards in Sunday's win over the Raiders.

impact: Lindsay threw several "punches" during a scrum for a loose football at the end of the second quarter. They were more arm swings than punches, and none of them seemed to land. It was right under the nose of an official, however, and he ended up getting tossed. Lindsay had 20 yards on four carries before exiting. Royce Freeman and Devontae Booker should see more snaps with Lindsay in the locker room.
report: Phillip Lindsay was ejected from Week 3 against the Ravens for throwing a punch.

impact: After being ejected from last week's loss against the Ravens, Lindsay resumed his spot as the lead dog in this backfield.  He out-touched Royce Freeman 14-8 with Devontae Booker a distant third at two touches.  Both Lindsay and Freeman scored red-zone rushing touchdowns, with Lindsay's coming from one yard away.  Despite his 5'8/190 frame, Lindsay is a tough inside runner with great speed.  He could have read his blocks a bit better tonight, but Lindsay continues to produce when given the ball.  He'll be an RB2/3 next week at the Jets.
report: Phillip Lindsay rushed 12 times for 69 yards and one touchdown in the Broncos' Week 4 loss to the Chiefs.

impact: He out-touched Royce Freeman 15 to 8, while Devontae Booker was active only in the passing game with five catches.  Despite coachspeak the Broncos "want to involve Freeman more," Lindsay has earned and run away with Denver's lead-back job.  Lindsay will remain a quality RB2/flex option against the Rams in Week 6.
report: Phillip Lindsay rushed 12 times for 61 yards and caught 3-of-4 targets for 20 yards in the Broncos' Week 5 loss to the Jets.

impact: Lindsay appeared to have a 12-yard receiving score in the third quarter, but it got called back by a Courtland Sutton offensive pass interference penalty. For the first time in a full game, Lindsay got out-carried by Royce Freeman, though he still out-touched and out-gained his rookie teammate. Both players continued to lose passing-down snaps to Devontae Booker, a weekly unforced error from the Broncos' under siege coaching staff. It was encouraging to see Lindsay catch six passes, a number that doubled his previous best total. Lindsay will remain on the RB2/3 borderline for Denver's short-week TNF matchup with the Cardinals.
report: Phillip Lindsay caught 6-of-7 targets for 48 yards in the Broncos' Week 6 loss to the Rams, adding four carries for 18 additional yards.

impact: Lindsay added a six-yard reception. It felt like Lindsay was delivering chunk gains every time he touched the ball, so it was disappointing that he got the rock just 16 times in a 45-10 victory. Part of the problem was short drives, as five Cardinals turnovers kept setting the Broncos up with gorgeous field position. Seven of Lindsay's 14 carries gained at least five yards, while five gained at least nine. Lindsay also had a 24-yarder called back by holding. Running circles around Royce Freeman every week — although good in his own right most of the year, Freeman went just 13/37/1 this evening — Lindsay is well established as an RB2.
report: Phillip Lindsay rushed 14 times for 90 yards and a touchdown in the Broncos' Week 7 win over the Cardinals.

impact: Lindsay added a six-yard reception. It felt like Lindsay was delivering chunk gains every time he touched the ball, so it was disappointing that he got the rock just 16 times in a 45-10 victory. Part of the problem was short drives, as five Cardinals turnovers kept setting the Broncos up with gorgeous field position. Seven of Lindsay's 14 carries gained at least five yards, while five gained at least nine. Lindsay also had a 24-yarder called back by holding. Running circles around Royce Freeman every week — although good in his own right most of the year, Freeman went just 13/37/1 this evening — Lindsay is well established as an RB2.
report: Phillip Lindsay rushed 14 times for 90 yards and a touchdown in the Broncos' Week 7 win over the Cardinals.

impact: He punched in a goal-line touchdown during the first quarter and also had a two-point try later in the game he could not convert. The 18 carries were a career-high for Lindsay, who has now gone for 90-plus rushing yards in back-to-back weeks. The undrafted rookie could have had a bigger day but he had at least two long runs erased by holding penalties on his offensive line. Lindsay's speed was evident Sunday as the 24-year-old Colorado State alum broke off chunk gains whenever he had an opening. He out-touched back-field mate Devontae Booker (who was also excellent on Sunday) by a significant 21-13 margin. Lindsay will see his workload reduced once Royce Freeman returns from his sprained ankle, but in the meantime, he's worth firing up as an RB2 in all fantasy formats. He'll face the Texans at home in Week 9.
report: Phillip Lindsay rumbled to 95 yards and a touchdown on 18 carries while also contributing three catches for 17 yards on three targets Sunday in the Broncos’ Week 8 loss to the Chiefs.

impact: He added 24 yards on two catches, too. The Texans boast what's arguably the league's top rush defense, inevitably keeping Lindsay bottled up for 3.5 YPC on 17 hard-fought totes. Devontae Booker frustratingly vultured the Broncos' only rushing score of the day, but Lindsay still worked ahead and out-touched him 19-5. Including Week 8, Lindsay's now out-touched Booker 40-18 in Denver's last two games without Royce Freeman. The undrafted rookie will see his recent surge in touches reduced once Freeman returns after the bye, but it's clear the team has no fear in featuring him if Freeman misses any further action.
report: Phillip Lindsay fought for 60 yards on 17 carries in the Broncos' Week 9 loss to the Texans.

impact: The rookie flashed his signature speed with a 41-yard touchdown burst during the second quarter, then made a second end-zone visit in the fourth, this time scoring on a direct snap from two yards out. Lindsay butchered a fourth-and-one chance during the second quarter, but that was his only false step in an otherwise flawless performance. Even with Royce Freeman back from a two-game absence, Lindsay still won the touch battle 15-8 while out-gaining Freeman by 76 yards. At 5'8/190, Lindsay isn't the biggest dog in the fight, but he hits the hole as hard as any back in the league. The former Colorado Buffalo will remain a locked-in RB2 when the Broncos return home to face Pittsburgh in Week 12.
report: Phillip Lindsay blew up for 79 yards and two touchdowns on 11 carries while nabbing four catches for 27 yards on five targets Sunday in the Broncos’ Week 11 win over the Chargers.

impact: The Titans opened the game trying to "establish" Derrick Henry -- Henry handled the first eight touches in Tennessee's backfield -- but Lewis eventually took over as the team's clearly-superior option.  Lewis' all-purpose game gives the Titans' offense more diversity than one-dimensional Henry brings to the table.  Elevate Lewis to a borderline RB2 when the Titans host the Texans next.
report: Dion Lewis rushed 16 times for 75 yards and a touchdown and caught 5-of-8 targets for 35 yards in the Titans' Week 1 loss to Miami.

impact: It was a game best-suited for Tennessee to lean on teammate Derrick Henry, which is exactly what the club did. Henry out-touched Lewis 18-15, with all of the former's touches coming via carries. Unfortunately for owners of this backfield, performances like this are bound to occur throughout the year depending on game script. Lewis remains the more coveted of the duo considering his usage in the Titans' passing game.
report: Dion Lewis rushed 14 times for 42 yards and hauled in his only target for one yard in the Titans' Week 2 win over the Texans.

impact: Derrick Henry was Tennessee's main back in this one, out-touching Lewis 18 to 12.  Lewis' touch counts have descended each week, falling from 21 in the opener to 15 in Week 2 and 12 today.  With an inconsistent timeshare role, Lewis will remain a shaky flex option when the Titans host the Eagles in Week 4.
report: Dion Lewis rushed nine times for 26 yards and caught 3-of-3 targets for 14 yards in Tennessee's Week 3 upset win over Jacksonville.

impact: He "added" zero yards on four carries. A struggling running game and a second-half deficit conspired to keep Lewis on the field instead of Derrick Henry, and he responded with a nice PPR outing. He made a couple big plays in the passing game in the second half, but his biggest was a fourth-down conversion in which he made a man miss and went 17 yards up the sideline in overtime. With the offense looking better and Buffalo on deck, Lewis will be an RB3 next week.
report: Dion Lewis hauled in all nine of his targets for 66 yards in the Titans' Week 4 win over the Eagles.

impact: He out-touched Derrick Henry 15 to 11 and has seemingly emerged as the Titans' preferred back, although it remains a fairly even committee.  Still rarely scoring touchdowns and firmly in a timeshare, Lewis will be a low-upside flex option when Tennessee hosts Baltimore in Week 6.
report: Dion Lewis rushed 12 times for 34 yards and caught 3-of-4 targets for 14 yards in the Titans' Week 5 loss to Buffalo.

impact: That's right, 14 yards on seven touches (2.0 yards per touch) for Lewis in Week 6. It was an abysmal outing for anyone donning silver and navy blue as everyone fell victim to Baltimore's 11-sack shutout defensive stand. Derrick Henry out-touched Lewis 8-7 but even he managed just 26 yards and an average 3.25 yards per touch. Lewis will be needed (and should out-touch Henry) in the Titans' Week 7 matchup against the Chargers' explosive offense.
report: Dion Lewis handled five carries for nine yards and caught both of his targets for another five yards in the Titans' Week 6 loss to the Ravens.

impact: Lewis carried the Titans' offense, outrushing Derrick Henry and finishing behind only Tajae Sharpe in receiving. It's a nice rebound after Lewis managed just 14 total yards last week. Lewis has been better than Henry through the first seven games and there's no reason to downgrade his rest-of-season outlook. The Titans have a matchup against Dallas after their Week 9 bye.
report: Dion Lewis rushed 13 times for 93 yards and caught six passes for 64 yards in Week 7 against the Chargers.

impact: Lewis carried the Titans' offense, outrushing Derrick Henry and finishing behind only Tajae Sharpe in receiving. It's a nice rebound after Lewis managed just 14 total yards last week. Lewis has been better than Henry through the first seven games and there's no reason to downgrade his rest-of-season outlook. The Titans have a matchup against Dallas after their Week 9 bye.
report: Dion Lewis rushed 13 times for 93 yards and caught six passes for 64 yards in Week 7 against the Chargers.

impact: The 23 touches marked a new season-high, besting his previous mark of 19 from the Titans' last game, a London loss to the Chargers in Week 7.  The Titans have slowly been moving more and more toward Lewis as their clear No. 1 back after trying to force Derrick Henry earlier in the season.  It's clear Lewis is the best fit for this offense, and he's now totaled 279 yards and a score over his last two outings on 42 touches.  He'll be an RB1/2 next week against his former Patriots teammates, especially with the Titans likely to be playing from behind.
report: Dion Lewis rushed 19 times for 62 yards and caught all four of his targets for 60 yards and one touchdown in the Titans' 28-14, Week 9 win over the Cowboys.

impact: Lewis was a Week 10 fantasy disappointment in a game where Derrick Henry scored twice, but the 22 touches are still highly promising for Lewis' going-forward outlook.  Keep rolling with him as an every-week RB2 when the Titans visit the Colts next.  Indianapolis' run defense has collapsed since early in the year, and they also hemorrhage receiving production to running backs.
report: Dion Lewis managed 57 yards on 20 carries and caught 2-of-2 targets for 11 yards in the Titans' Week 10 win over the Patriots.

impact: Both the touches and yards were Lewis' fewest in over a month. The Titans offense never got in rhythm. Marcus Mariota was discombobulated by the blitz and departed with an elbow injury late in the first half. Blaine Gabbert should not be on an NFL football field. Provided Mariota can get back for next Monday's game against the Texans, Lewis should bounce back to the 15-20 touch range as an RB2.
report: Dion Lewis rushed 10 times for 24 yards in the Titans' Week 11 loss to the Colts, adding an eight-yard reception.

impact: After 15 targets in Week 1, we expected Landry to come to close to that number once again with the Browns shelving Josh Gordon, but that was not the case on Sunday. He still managed five receptions, the 19th consecutive game in which he's had at least five or more catches, the longest streak in the league. Landry will remain a strong WR2 asset Week 3 against the Jets.
report: Jarvis Landry caught 5-of-7 targets for 69 yards in Sunday's Week 2 loss to the Saints.

impact: Landry committed a drop but was helping Baker Mayfield move the chains for the Browns' transformed offense after Tyrod Taylor (concussion) was forced from the game. Landry was the lone Brown getting his numbers while Taylor was under center, but his fantasy fortunes should improve with Mayfield taking over. Landry has a soft Week 4 matchup in the Raiders.
report: Jarvis Landry caught 8-of-15 targets for 103 yards in the Browns' Week 3 win over the Jets.

impact: Landry's ten targets led the team, but he was part of the problem in Cleveland's drop-pass fest and failed to get loose for any big plays.  Finishing with four catches snapped Landry's streak of catching five or more balls in 20 straight games.  Still, Landry has been targeted 18 times in roughly six quarters by Baker Mayfield, by far most on the team.  Keep rolling him out there in Week 5 against a Ravens defense struggling to slow slot receivers.
report: Jarvis Landry caught 4-of-10 targets for 34 yards and a touchdown in the Browns' Week 4 loss to Oakland.

impact: Landry was held in check by a Baltimore secondary. He had just one catch for 10 yards in the first half and needed receptions of 27 and 17 yards on the final three drives of the game to turn in a respectable line. Landry has had two 100-yard game surrounding three lackluster games, but is averaging a career-high 13.0 yards per catch with at double-digit targets in four of the first five games. He is strong WR2 in Week 6 against the Chargers.
report: Jarvis Landry caught 5-of-10 targets for 69 yards in Sunday's Week 5 win over the Ravens.

impact: Landry was stymied by the Chargers secondary all afternoon. His two receptions were the fewest he's had in a game since Week 14 of the 2015 season. Landry has struggled in the transition over to Baker Mayfield catching 11-of-29 targets for 114 yards over Mayfield's three starts. Despite those lowly numbers, Landry will be  in a spot to bounce back against a giving Tampa Bay secondary in Week 7.
report: Jarvis Landry caught 2-of-9 targets for 11 yards in Sunday's Week 6 loss to the Chargers.

impact: After just 11 catches for 114 yards over Baker Mayfield's first three starts, Landry had a season-high 10 catches on Sunday. Things started slowly as Landry had just four catches for 23 yards at the break, but then came on strong in the second half, securing 6-of-8 targets for 73 yards and a score. Landry found the end zone for the second time this season, a 16-yard score in which he made a diving catch and extended the ball over the goal line on his way to the ground to tie the game with 2:28 left in regulation. Landry has double-digit targets in every game this season and heads to Pittsburgh in Week 8 after already having a 100-yard game versus the Steelers in Week 1.
report: Jarvis Landry caught 10-of-15 targets for 97 yards and a touchdown in Sunday's Week 7 loss to the Buccaneers.

impact: After just 11 catches for 114 yards over Baker Mayfield's first three starts, Landry had a season-high 10 catches on Sunday. Things started slowly as Landry had just four catches for 23 yards at the break, but then came on strong in the second half, securing 6-of-8 targets for 73 yards and a score. Landry found the end zone for the second time this season, a 16-yard score in which he made a diving catch and extended the ball over the goal line on his way to the ground to tie the game with 2:28 left in regulation. Landry has double-digit targets in every game this season and heads to Pittsburgh in Week 8 after already having a 100-yard game versus the Steelers in Week 1.
report: Jarvis Landry caught 10-of-15 targets for 97 yards and a touchdown in Sunday's Week 7 loss to the Buccaneers.

impact: Landry led the team in targets and catches, but was only able to catch targets near the line of scrimmage, an ongoing problem. Over Baker Mayfield's five starts, Landry is averaging 11.6 targets per game but just a lowly 4.3 yards per target. He has been held under 40-yards receiving in three of those games. With his low weekly floor, Landry is creeping down to WR3 status as the season moves along. The Browns host the Chiefs in Week 9.
report: Jarvis Landry caught 8-of-12 targets for 39 yards in Sunday's Week 8 loss to the Steelers.

impact: Landry opened the game with a 17-yard catch on the second play of the game, but then was quiet the rest of the afternoon as he failed to gain yardage after the catch on his targets near the line of scrimmage. Landry has been nondescript with Baker Mayfield under center, averaging 50 yards per game over those six games with just 5.3 yards per target. Despite the pedestrian output, Landry will find himself as a lower-end WR2 in Week 10 when the Browns host the Falcons.
report: Jarvis Landry caught 6-of-7 targets for 50 yards in Sunday's Week 9 loss to the Chiefs.

impact: Baker Mayfield was on fire, but Landry ended up having his second-worst game of the season. Mayfield was spreading the ball around, finding nine different players for completions. The Browns were also riding their run game, rolling up 211 yards. Landry now has just eight grabs for 72 yards in two games since Freddie Kitchens took over as offensive coordinator. He will return from the Browns' Week 11 bye as a mid-range WR2 against the Bengals' burnable defense.
report: Jarvis Landry caught 2-of-5 targets for 22 yards in the Browns' Week 10 win over the Falcons.

impact: LaFell punched in a six-yard touchdown late in the first half but was otherwise held in check. That was his first end-zone visit since joining Oakland last month. LaFell will likely take on a bigger role as the Raiders look to replace Amari Cooper, who was traded to Dallas last week. Still, he's best left on the waiver wire.
report: Brandon LaFell chipped in with three catches for 39 yards and a touchdown on four targets Sunday in the Raiders’ Week 8 loss to the Colts.

impact: Oakland's No. 1 receiver at this point, non-Jared Cook division, LaFell started strong with four catches in the first half, but he could not corral either of his targets after the break. One of those was a bad route which almost resulted in an interception at the goal line. LaFell does not need to be rostered in most fantasy leagues.
report: Brandon LaFell hauled in 4-of-6 targets for 47 yards in the Raiders' Week 10 loss to the Chargers.

impact: LaFell skied for a jump ball win in the third quarter but immediately came down hobbled. It's a huge loss for a team already missing Martavis Bryant and Jordy Nelson. LaFell had caught two passes for 29 yards before going down, finding the end zone for a five-yard score where he beat Patrick Peterson. LaFell is headed for an MRI.
report: Brandon LaFell is "feared" to have suffered a ruptured Achilles' tendon in Sunday's game against the Cardinals.

impact: Newton's 13 carries and 58 yards rushing were both team-highs. Dallas' defense did a tremendous job keeping Newton bottled up through the air, but the eight-year pro eventually took care of business on the ground, including a score inside the five-yard line. Cam averaged a career-high 8.6 rushing attempts per game last season, so perhaps more lines like Sunday's are in store for the 2015 MVP over the next 15 games. Carolina's backfield essentially split carries behind Newton as Christian McCaffrey handled 10 carries and C.J. Anderson mustered seven.
report: Cam Newton completed 17-of-26 passes for 161 yards and bulldozed his way to 58 yards and one touchdown on 13 carries in the Panthers' Week 1 win over the Cowboys.

impact: Newton added 42 yards on five carries to lead the Panthers in rushing.  At the end of one of those runs, early in the first half, Newton was illegally helmet-to-helmet-ed by Falcons S Damontae Kazee.  Kazee was ejected, and Cam looked to truly be concussed, and dazed at the very least.  He supposedly quickly passed a concussion test and didn't miss a play.  Newton still didn't miss a beat; his receivers merely let him down multiple times with drops.  The scores went to Jarius Wright (five yards), Torrey Smith (three), and rookie D.J. Moore (51).  A final heave from 26 yards out to Moore on the final play fell incomplete.  Newton will get the Bengals next week.
report: Cam Newton completed 32-of-45 passes for 335 yards, three touchdowns, and one interception in the Panthers' 31-24, Week 2 loss to the Falcons.

impact: Christian McCaffrey did the heavylifting with 194 yards from scrimmage, but Newton was the red-zone executioner with touchdowns to Devin Funchess and C.J. Anderson, one zone-read keeper, and another where Newton bootlegged around the left edge to pay dirt.  Newton will head into Carolina's Week 4 bye hot with back-to-back top-seven weekly fantasy quarterback performances.  The Panthers should get back stud RG Trai Turner (concussion) after the break.
report: Cam Newton completed 15-of-24 passes for 150 yards and two touchdowns, and rushed 10 times for 36 yards and two additional scores in the Panthers' 31-21 win over the Bengals in Week 3.

impact: He was sacked once for a loss of five. This game got all the way off the rails and Newton played a huge part in the insanity. Cam got off to a decent start, connecting with Curtis Samuel on a 25-yard touchdown in the first quarter (Samuel deserves credit for breaking a number of tackles on his way to the end zone). Newton was mostly held in check after that, however, shooting the Panthers in the foot with a pair of second-half interceptions, both on passes intended for tight end Ian Thomas. He redeemed himself somewhat by leading a scoring drive on the game's final possession, setting up a miraculous, 63-yard, walk-off field goal by Graham Gano. Newton didn't look particularly sharp coming off the Panthers' bye week. Perhaps he'll fare better with Greg Olsen (foot) due back from injury next week at Washington.
report: Cam Newton completed 21-of-35 passes for 237 yards with two touchdowns and two interceptions while adding 29 yards on four carries Sunday in the Panthers’ Week 5 victory over the Giants.

impact: The Panthers struggled to get into a rhythm on an afternoon where the Redskins dominated time of possession. Newton didn't help with some inaccurate passes, though he was keeping drives alive with tough runs. Things might have been different if not for a pair of lost D.J. Moore fumbles. Newton found a returning Greg Olsen four times for 48 yards. Newton has an attackable Week 7 matchup in the Eagles' struggling secondary.
report: Cam Newton completed 27-of-40 passes for 275 yards, two touchdowns and an interception in the Panthers' 23-17, Week 6 loss to the Redskins, adding nine carries for 43 additional yards.

impact: Newton shook off a dreadful first half to complete 21-of-30 passes for 245 yards and two touchdowns in the final two quarters, finding Devin Funchess for an 18-yard score and Greg Olsen for the game winner at the goal line as Carolina overcame a 17-0 deficit for the 21-17 victory.  Newton's second-half performance was truly heroic, particularly a fourth-down completion to Torrey Smith for 35 yards.  Newton gets a tougher Week 8 matchup against Baltimore, but he has been a high-floor, high-ceiling fantasy quarterback all year regardless of opponents.
report: Cam Newton completed 25-of-39 passes for 269 yards and two touchdowns and rushed seven times for 49 yards in the Panthers' Week 7 upset win over Philadelphia.

impact: His 52 rushing yards led the team.  Newton was cooking with rookie D.J. Moore in the first half, hooking up with the first-round pick five times for 90 yards, including a 33-yard seam shot to set up an eventual Christian McCaffrey touchdown catch from six yards out on a ball intended for Devin Funchess at the goal line that was batted into the air.  Newton was lucky to not be picked on the play.  His other score went to Greg Olsen from 11 yards away.  Newton has multiple touchdown passes in six straight games, and he gets the brutal Bucs' defense at home in Week 9.
report: Cam Newton completed 21-of-29 passes for 219 yards and two touchdowns in the Panthers' 36-21, Week 8 win over the Ravens, adding 52 rushing and a third touchdown on 10 attempts.

impact: A dominant real-life performance did not quite translate to fantasy as Newton lost yardage to Curtis Samuel and D.J. Moore trick/motion plays. The Panthers were also content to let Christian McCaffrey do work at the goal line. Newton did have a rushing score, but it got called back by an illegal motion penalty. Cooking with gas for a while now, Newton gets the Steelers' improving defense on Thursday Night Football for Week 10.
report: Cam Newton completed 19-of-25 passes for 247 yards and two touchdowns in the Panthers' 42-28, Week 9 win over the Bucs, adding 10 carries for 34 additional yards.

impact: Newton rushed just twice for 10 yards. The Panthers marched down the field on their opening drive for a 7-0 lead, but that would prove to be the highlight of the night for Newton and company. The Steelers immediately tied the game with a 75-yard JuJu Smith-Schuster score and Newton answered with one of the worst throws of his career. Trying to avoid a safety on a botched screen, Newton blindly heaved what turned into a pick six to ILB Vince Williams. Newton later never felt T.J. Watt's pressure on what was nearly a lost fumble. Newton was shaken up after the monster hit but stayed in the game. He has 10 days to get healthy for a Week 11 matchup with the Lions.
report: Cam Newton completed 23-of-29 passes for 193 yards, two touchdowns and an interception in the Panthers' 52-21, Week 10 loss to the Steelers.

impact: Cam easily led the Panthers down the field on the opening drive, completing 5-of-6 passes for 80 yards and a score, but it was mostly a struggle for the rest of the first half. Aside from an 82-yard connection with D.J. Moore in which the rookie did most of the work, Newton did not have much more success in the third quarter, and he suffered an injury scare when a couple defenders fell on the back of his leg. The injury seemed to spark him. He led a quick touchdown drive to tie the game the next series. Following a Lions touchdown, he marched the Panthers back down the field for another score in the closing moments. Instead of kicking the possible game-tying extra point, the Panthers put the ball in Newton's hands for the possible win. It ended up being a bad decision. Despite a lifetime in the pocket, Newton overthrew an open receiver in the end zone. It is a disappointing loss, but Newton once again had a nice fantasy day. He will be a locked-in QB1 next week against the Seahawks.
report: Cam Newton completed 25-of-37 passes for 357 yards, three touchdowns, and an interception in the Panthers' Week 11 loss to the Lions.

impact: Njoku saw the second-most targets on the team, but had a hard time converting them into anything tangible. He had two drops in the third quarter on back-to-back plays that thwarted a Cleveland drive. Njoku remains an upside option for fantasy in Week 2 versus the Saints, but is far from established as a entrenched fantasy starter at this stage.
report: Browns TE David Njoku caught 3-of-7 targets for 13 yards in Sunday's Week 1 game versus the Steelers.

impact: Njoku matched a team-high seven targets, but was a letdown for the second consecutive week for fantasy purposes. Through two weeks, he's now secured just 7-of-14 targets for 33 yards. Despite the back-to-back down games, his target volume is still tangible for a depressed fantasy position. Until he starts to turn that into production however, Njoku is only a TE2 option in Week 3 versus the Jets.
report: David Njoku caught 4-of-7 targets for 20 yards in Sunday's Week 2 loss to the Saints.

impact: It could have been a bigger day if not for Njoku committing his third drop of the season in the second half.  Nevertheless, Baker Mayfield has helped Njoku immensely after the high-upside tight end managed 33 scoreless yards on 12 targets from Tyrod Taylor in the first 2 1/2 games of the season.  Since Mayfield took over the offense, Njoku has caught seven of the rookie quarterback's nine targets for 88 yards.  Njoku will stay on the TE1 fringe when the Browns host the Ravens next.
report: David Njoku caught 5-of-7 targets for 52 yards in the Browns' Week 4 loss to the Raiders.

impact: Njoku set season-highs across the board in targets, catches and yards on Sunday. As good as his game was, he could've had much more as he suffered two dropped passes in the game. The move to Baker Mayfield has energized Njoku  as he now has 11 catches for 111 yards on 18 targets the past two weeks after nine catches for 69 yards through the opening three weeks. Despite failing to score on the season, Njoku will be a starting option at a depressed tight end position Week 6 against the Chargers.
report: David Njoku caught 6-of-11 targets for 69 yards in Sunday's Week 5 win over the Ravens.

impact: Njoku found the end zone for the first time this season in the 4th quarter on a 1-yard touchdown pass with the game way out of hand. It was Njoku's first red zone target on the season. After a season-high 11 targets last week, Njoku received 12 more looks on Sunday, giving him 30 total targets over Baker Mayfield's three starts. Njoku is in a dream spot next week against a Tampa Bay defense that has allowed the most receiving yards per game to opposing tight ends to begin the season.
report: David Njoku caught 7-of-12 targets for 55 yards and a touchdown in Sunday's Week 6 loss to the Chargers.

impact: Njoku was held without a catch in the first half on Sunday, dropping his lone target over the opening two quarters. In the second half, he got the Browns going right away, catching a 15-yard touchdown over Adarius Taylor to get the Browns within a score. Njoku has now established himself firmly as the number two option behind Jarvis Landry in the Cleveland offense. Since Baker Mayfield has taken over, Njoku has reeled in 22-of-35 targets for 228 yards and two touchdowns. Njoku draws another positive matchup in Week 8 against the Steelers.
report: David Njoku caught 4-of-6 targets for 52 yards and a touchdown in Sunday's Week 7 loss to the Buccaneers.

impact: After failing to register a mark in the box score last week, Njoku bounced back to have a modest day, but he was fourth on the team in targets. Njoku's highlight of the day was a 19-yard catch and run in the first quarter that set up the first score of the game for the Browns. Njoku now has at least four catches and 50 yards receiving in five of his past six games, which more than usable at a depleted tight end position. Njoku will enter Week 10 as a back-half TE1 in Week 10 against the Falcons.
report: David Njoku caught 4-of-5 targets for 53 yards in Sunday's Week 9 loss to the Chiefs.

impact: It was a beautiful day for the Browns' offense, but Baker Mayfield was spreading the ball around as Nick Chubb dominated on the ground. It was just the second time in seven Mayfield starts that Njoku was held below 50 yards. Njoku will be a risky TE1 against the Bengals when the Browns come off bye in Week 12.
report: David Njoku caught 1-of-1 targets for 18 yards in the Browns' Week 10 win over the Falcons.

impact: Nelson caught a 23-yard pass on the second offensive play of the game then all but disappeared afterwards. He has now posted 35 receiving yards or less in 11 consecutive games dating back to last season. Nelson is not a starting option Week 3 versus the Dolphins.
report: Jordy Nelson caught 2-of-4 targets for 30 yards in Sunday's Week 2 loss to the Broncos.

impact: Nelson more than tripled his season yardage total. He went 2/73/1 on the Raiders' opening drive, capping it off by getting completely free in the end zone for a 12-yard score. 139 of Nelson's yards came in the first six minutes. He was obviously much quieter thereafter, but it was more than enough to keep Nelson on the fantasy radar. With the Raiders rotating big receiver days, Nelson will be a WR3/4 for Week 4 against the Browns.
report: Jordy Nelson caught 6-of-8 targets for 173 yards and a touchdown in the Raiders' Week 3 loss to the Dolphins.

impact: Nelson has turned it up since the Raiders moved him to slot receiver two games ago, shredding Cleveland and Miami for a combined 11/221/2 stat line.  He tacked on a pair of two-point conversions in Sunday's overtime win.  Nelson has earned WR3/flex treatment entering a Week 5 date with the Chargers.
report: Jordy Nelson has caught 5-of-8 targets for 48 yards and a touchdown in the Raiders' Week 4 win over the Browns.

impact: This was a very disappointing outcome in a game where Amari Cooper (concussion) and Seth Roberts (concussion) both went down.  Derek Carr refused to pull the trigger on difficult throws, however, and Seattle's pass rush dominated Oakland's beat-up offensive line.  Nelson will emerge from the Raiders' Week 7 bye as a shaky WR3/flex option.
report: Jordy Nelson caught 2-of-3 targets for six yards in Week 6 versus Seattle.

impact: Nelson briefly left the game with a quad injury, but he returned. Nelson now has a total of 36 yards in the last four games. He can safely be dropped in all formats.
report: Jordy Nelson did not catch his only target in the Raiders' Week 10 loss to the Chargers.

impact: Jones was targeted on a couple deep balls, but he and Matthew Stafford were unable to hook up on any big plays against an underrated Jets secondary.  Better days are obviously ahead.  Jones will be a WR2 next week in San Francisco.
report: Marvin Jones caught 4-of-8 targets for 54 yards in the Lions' Week 1 loss to the Jets.

impact: Jones routinely created separation from the Niners' secondary but Matthew Stafford couldn’t find his deep ball on Sunday. The most egregious misfire from Stafford came in the second quarter when Jones had nothing but green grass in front of him but the two couldn’t connect. That must have been frustrating for fantasy owners, though Stafford delivered a peace offering in the form of a five-yard touchdown pass to Jones with 8:36 left in the fourth quarter. Jones has now caught exactly four passes for 54 yards in each of his first two games. Say what you will about Marvin, but at least the man's consistent. Jones and the Lions will host the Patriots in Week 3.
report: Marvin Jones hauled in four catches for 54 yards and a touchdown Sunday in the Lions’ Week 2 loss to the 49ers.

impact: Jones started and looked close to 100 percent playing through his ankle injury. He got wide open out of the slot for a deep 33-yard touchdown for his only highlight of the night. Jones finished behind Golden Tate (8) and Kenny Golladay (7) in targets, but there hasn't been much dropoff from his strong 2017. Jones is a FLEX play for Week 4 against the Cowboys.
report: Marvin Jones caught 4-of-6 passes for 69 yards and a touchdown in Week 3 against the Patriots.

impact: Jones made a highlight-reel catch in the second quarter, pulling in an absurd over-the-shoulder grab to beat Chidobe Awuzie for a 34-yard pickup. He was targeted in the end zone later in the half but the pass from Matthew Stafford was off the mark. Jones hasn’t had a blow-up game yet in 2018 and it’s fair to expect fewer of those this season with Kenny Golladay becoming a bigger part of the Lions’ passing game. Of course, both of them took a backseat to Golden Tate (8-132-2) on Sunday. Jones will be a mere WR3 next week against the Packers.
report: Marvin Jones chipped in with three catches for 56 yards on six targets Sunday in the Lions’ Week 4 loss to the Cowboys.

impact: Playing through an ankle injury, Jones made his one catch count with a diving touchdown in the back of the end zone.  He almost had a second score from 42 yards out on a shot play when the defense jumped offside, but Jones was unable to control the ball through the ground after diving for it.  Jones gets a week to rest and get healthy with the Lions heading into their bye.
report: Marvin Jones caught an eight-yard touchdown on four targets in the Lions' Week 5 win over the Packers.

impact: Jones also drew a 25-yard DPI. It was a quiet day for the Lions' entire receiver corps, but Jones now has just 93 yards over his past three games. He is averaging a disappointing 45 on the year. Jones should still have blow-up games, but Kenny Golladay's emergence has rendered him a low-end WR3 in fantasy.
report: Marvin Jones caught 3-of-4 targets for 29 yards in the Lions' Week 7 win over the Dolphins.

impact: Jones also drew a 56-yard defensive pass interference penalty. The targets, catches, yards and touchdowns were all new season highs for a player who entered the game the owner of a 19/270/3 line on the year. Jones' first score came after Tedric Thompson gave up on a play where Matthew Stafford appeared sacked. For the second, Jones split the corner and safety and made a nice sliding grab in the end zone. The huge game was nice to see, but Jones will follow it up with a tough matchup in the Vikings. He's a risk/reward WR3.
report: Marvin Jones caught 7-of-10 targets for 117 yards and two touchdowns in the Lions' Week 8 loss to the Seahawks.

impact: Jones' eight targets and the catches and yards led the team in the first game without Golden Tate after his trade to the Eagles.  Theo Riddick also saw eight targets, essentially taking Tate's place on third downs in the slot, but the offense failed miserably all afternoon, scoring just three field goals.  Jones' usage was encouraging, however, and he out-targeted Kenny Golladay 8-4.  Jones will be a WR2 next week when the Lions travel to take on the Bears.
report: Marvin Jones caught 6-of-8 targets for 66 yards in the Lions' Week 9 loss to the Vikings.

impact: Jones didn't see the field until late in the first quarter, but he immediately piled up 18 yards on back-to-back carries. The sophomore back led the Pack's three-man backfield in both carries and rushing yards. He is clearly going to be a factor. If Jones can improve his pass protection, he could make a decisive move ahead of Jamaal Williams. He needs to be 100 percent owned in fantasy.
report: Making his 2018 debut, Aaron Jones rushed six times for 42 yards in the Packers' Week 3 loss to the Redskins, adding a five-yard reception.

impact: Jones once again came off the bench behind Jamaal Williams. His first touch did not come until the final play of the first quarter, but Jones proceeded to easily out-gain Williams 82-27 while out-touching him 12-11. It was Jones who scored the Pack's lone ground touchdown, running over a defensive back at the goal line. Jones has now out-produced Williams in each of his 2018 appearances. Each of Jones, Williams and Ty Montgomery will continue to see work, but only Jones is currently worth FLEX consideration. The Pack travel to Detroit for Week 5. The Lions have been getting destroyed on the ground.
report: Aaron Jones rushed 11 times for 65 yards and a touchdown in the Packers' Week 4 win over the Bills, adding a 17-yard reception.

impact: He also caught two balls for 19 yards.  Jones didn't get a second-half touch until there was less than 30 second left in the game.  He fought hard for extra yards on his seven carries, but Jones was mothballed with the Packers in catchup mode.  It was pretty much all Ty Montgomery in the backfield after the break.  Jones should get more work next week against the Niners as an RB3.
report: Aaron Jones rushed seven times for 40 yards in the Packers' Week 5 loss to the Lions.

impact: Jones caught two passes but gained zero yards. Jones' score was a 33-yarder on a delayed handoff. Jones exploded through a monstrous hole once he got the ball. Jones also took a safety on an ill-advised, packed-in run call from the Packers' own one-yard line. Jones continues to run laps around Jamaal Williams, but stubborn coach Mike McCarthy refuses to phase him out of the Packers' offense. Jones will be a risk/reward RB2 for next week's likely shootout with the Patriots.
report: Aaron Jones rushed 12 times for 86 yards and a touchdown in the Packers' Week 8 loss to the Rams.

impact: Jones continued to start but lost a few series to Jamaal Williams. His night was overshadowed by a costly fumble to open the fourth quarter with the Packers driving. The Packers went away from Jones after that, but he's clearly ahead of Williams going forward. Jones is an RB2 for Week 10 against Miami.
report: Aaron Jones had 14 carries for 76 yards and caught 2-of-4 targets for 10 yards in Week 9 against the Patriots.

impact: Jones dropped a pass on the team's first play, but it didn't matter. He stayed on the field and still got four touches for 54 yards on Green Bay's opening drive, paving the way for his monstrous two-score afternoon. Jones was averaging a league-high 6.0 YPC heading into Sunday, and yet somehow increased that mark to 6.76 YPC at the end of the day. He didn't even step onto the field for the Packers' final possession and still out-touched Jamaal Williams 18-3. Consider this game an official passing of the torch as Jones should receive RB1 usage (and flourish with it) for the remainder of the season.
report: Aaron Jones handled 15 carries for 145 yards and two touchdowns, tacking on three catches for 27 yards in the Packers' Week 10 victory over the Dolphins.

impact: Jones was running completely wild in the first half, at one point taking over a drive with receptions of 15, 22 and 24 yards, the third of which went for a score. Jones made an excellent 1-on-1 catch on a corner route in the end zone. His rushing touchdown was an eight-yarder on a toss play on the Pack's opening drive. The second-year pro now has four scores over his past two games and has rendered Jamaal Williams a distant memory. Jones is going to be in the RB1 mix from here on out. The Pack get the Vikings in Week 12.
report: Aaron Jones rushed 11 times for 40 yards and a touchdown in the Packers' Week 11 loss to the Seahawks, adding five receptions for 63 yards and an additional score.

impact: Julio was invisible in the first half, drawing just two targets from Matt Ryan. Jones’ biggest contribution of the afternoon came when he dusted Ken Crawley for a 58-yard pickup in the fourth quarter. It should have been an easy touchdown but Ryan didn’t put enough air under it. This was a serviceable game for Jones, though the veteran was vastly overshadowed by teammate and fellow Alabama alum Calvin Ridley (7-146-3). After tangling with Marshon Lattimore on Sunday, Jones will get another tough draw next week against underrated Bengals corner William Jackson. At least it will be a home game for Atlanta.
report: Julio Jones contributed five catches for 96 yards on six targets Sunday in the Falcons’ Week 3 loss to New Orleans.

impact: Jones remains too classy for touchdowns, but he was once again a monster in this game. Seemingly open every time Matt Ryan needed a big play, Jones converted third down after third down for an offense which was rarely stopped. He padded his stats with 66 yards on the Falcons' final, desperation drive. While a touchdown or two would be cool, Jones is averaging 126 yards a game and has a great matchup with the Steelers on deck. He remains a high-end WR1.
report: Julio Jones hauled in 9-of-12 targets for 173 yards in the Falcons' Week 4 loss to the Bengals.

impact: Stunningly, Jones was held without a catch for three quarters. He did a decent job of salvaging his fantasy line in the fourth quarter, when a non-competitive game was already over. Despite the disappointing day, Jones still has a monster 564 yards through five games. He will be in the WR1 overall discussion for Week 6 against the pathetic Bucs.
report: Julio Jones caught 5-of-9 targets for 62 yards in the Falcons' Week 5 loss to the Steelers.

impact: Jones remained allergic to the end zone even with Calvin Ridley and Mohamed Sanu leaving early, but that did not stop him from making play after play against the Bucs' overmatched secondary. He was seemingly running free all game, and he converted several big third downs throughout. Even with a couple down games thrown in, Jones is on pace for 1,885 yards through six games. A touchdown or two would be nice, but Jones remains a high-end WR1.
report: Julio Jones hauled in 10-of-14 targets for 143 yards in the Falcons' Week 6 win over the Bucs.

impact: Standard day at the office for Jones; he got his 100 yards and remains without a touchdown on the season.  There was an opening for one, but Matt Ryan underthrew Jones on what should have been a walk-in 60-yard touchdown.  Ryan hit his hand on a helmet on the follow-through, and Jones had to stop for the ball, drawing a 38-yard pass interference instead.  On two of the next three plays, Ryan tried to get Jones the ball in the end zone, but Jones was double-covered both times.  Jones also lost a fumble in this one.  The Falcons are on their bye now before going to D.C. in Week 9.
report: Julio Jones caught 9-of-12 targets for 104 yards in the Falcons' 23-20, Week 7 win over the Giants on Monday night.

impact: Standard day at the office for Jones; he got his 100 yards and remains without a touchdown on the season.  There was an opening for one, but Matt Ryan underthrew Jones on what should have been a walk-in 60-yard touchdown.  Ryan hit his hand on a helmet on the follow-through, and Jones had to stop for the ball, drawing a 38-yard pass interference instead.
