On two of the next three plays, Ryan tried to get Jones the ball in the end zone, but Jones was double-covered both times.  Jones also lost a fumble in this one.  The Falcons are on their bye now before going to D.C. in Week 9.
report: Julio Jones caught 9-of-12 targets for 104 yards in the Falcons' 23-20, Week 7 win over the Giants on Monday night.

impact: You read that right; a Julio Jones touchdown.  Jones' score came on a fourth-quarter quick screen where an offensive lineman took out Josh Norman in press coverage and Julio broke Ha Ha Clinton-Dix's tackle attempt in front of the goal line before diving in.  The touchdown was Julio's first in a string of 90 consecutive scoreless catches.  Jones dominated Norman all game, also gaining 46 yards on a flagrant defensive pass interference flag when Norman literally tackled him from behind to prevent another would-be long score.  Jones will remain an elite WR1 play in Week 10 at Cleveland, which lost impressive rookie CB Denzel Ward to a hip injury in their loss to Kansas City.
report: Julio Jones caught 7-of-10 targets for 121 yards and a touchdown in the Falcons' Week 9 win over the Redskins.

impact: Jones also drew a 13-yard DPI. Jones' score — his second of the season — was his second in as many weeks. He caught a bubble screen with the Falcons on the one-yard line. Jones has now cleared 100 yards in four-straight games and six times on the season. He's up to 1,040 yards, putting him on pace for 1,849. That would be third most all time. Jones' 1,871 from 2015 is second most all time. The Falcons face the Cowboys in Week 11.
report: Julio Jones caught 7-of-11 targets for 107 yards and a touchdown in the Falcons' Week 10 loss to the Browns.

impact: Since snapping his insane touchdown-less streak, Jones has now scored in three-straight games and has topped 100 yards in all three.  Jones has topped 100 yards in five consecutive games and six of the last seven.  Jones had a quiet first half against Dallas (2-38) but got going after the break and skied over the top of CB Chidobe Awuzie for a 34-yard score to tie the game at 19-19 deep in the fourth quarter.  Julio gets the Saints on Thanksgiving.  He went 5-96 against New Orleans in Week 3.
report: Julio Jones caught 6-of-9 targets for 118 yards and one touchdown in the Falcons' 22-19, Week 11 loss to the Cowboys.

impact: LeGarrette Blount started, and Theo Riddick was the clear pass-down back, but whenever Johnson was in the game he was clearly the team's best playmaker in the backfield.  Blount hurt his knee in the second half, so perhaps that will open up more work for Johnson next week at San Francisco.
report: Kerryon Johnson rushed five times for 17 yards and caught all three of his targets for 20 yards in the Lions' Week 1 loss to the Jets.

impact: Johnson was the most impressive of Detroit’s three ball-carriers on Sunday, though game script dictated a pass-heavy approach with the Lions playing from behind most of the afternoon. The rookie led Detroit’s backfield with 13 touches, which is five more than he saw against the Jets in Week 1. It’s likely Johnson will eventually emerge as the Lions’ lead back but for the moment, he remains locked in a timeshare with power back LeGarrette Blount and pass-catcher Theo Riddick. Until that changes, the rookie will be tough to employ for fantasy purposes. We’ll see what he can muster next week against New England.
report: Kerryon Johnson rolled to 43 yards on eight carries while adding five catches for 23 yards on six targets Sunday in the Lions’ Week 2 loss to San Francisco.

impact: Johnson is the first Lions' running back to run for 100 yards since 2013. He continued to have to hot hand over LeGarrette Blount, though both ended up with 16 carries. Johnson has separated himself from Blount through the first three games, and should emerge as the lead back moving forward. He's on the FLEX radar against the Cowboys in Week 4.
report: Kerryon Johnson had 16 carries for 101 yards in Detroit's Week 3 win over the Patriots.

impact: Coming off a 101-yard breakout in Week 3, Johnson got off to a booming start in this one, shredding the Cowboys for 32 yards on the first play from scrimmage. Unfortunately his involvement dwindled after that, particularly after halftime as the rookie was limited to just three second-half touches. The Auburn alum salvaged the day for fantasy owners by punching in an eight-yard touchdown early in the fourth quarter. Despite soundly outperforming LeGarrette Blount for the second straight week, Johnson out-touched the veteran by a slim 10-7 margin while only seeing six more snaps. With Blount continuing to eat into Johnson's workload, the 21-year-old will just be a back-end RB2 for next week's home game against the Packers.
report: Kerryon Johnson delivered 55 yards and a touchdown on nine carries while converting his lone target for a one-yard gain Sunday in Detroit’s Week 4 loss to the Lions.

impact: Johnson found the edge for 24 yards on the Lions' first play from scrimmage and never looked back. The Lions' 248 yards rushing were their most since the Barry Sanders era in 1997. Continually ripping chunk gains, Johnson's longest was a 71-yarder to begin the second quarter. Untouched through the hole, Johnson found the sideline. Johnson's YPC is now a ridiculous 6.43 through 69 carries. His 19 totes today were a new season high. LeGarrette Blount remained involved, but Johnson is forcing the Lions' hand. He's a locked-in, upside RB2.
report: Kerryon Johnson rushed 19 times for 158 yards in the Lions' Week 7 win over the Dolphins, adding two receptions for 21 additional yards.

impact: Sunday was a day of peaks and valleys for Johnson, who scored by leaping over the pile for a one-yard, goal-line touchdown with 1:05 remaining in the first half. Prince Amukamara stripped Johnson in the third quarter, resulting in Detroit's second turnover of the afternoon. That was a costly mistake for Kerryon, though the rookie redeemed himself by scoring a late touchdown on a 13-yard screen pass from Matthew Stafford. The 21-year-old was checked for a left ankle injury in the fourth quarter but only missed a handful of snaps. Johnson ceded some passing-down work to Theo Riddick but out-touched fading veteran LeGarrette Blount by an overwhelming 20-6 margin. Johnson and the struggling Lions will try to erase a three-game losing skid next week against a Panthers squad that was thoroughly whooped by Pittsburgh on Thursday night.
report: Kerryon Johnson produced 51 yards and a touchdown on 14 carries while also snaring six catches for 38 yards and another touchdown on six targets Sunday in Detroit’s Week 10 loss to the Bears.

impact: Johnson was a clear ancillary option in the Browns offense behind Carlos Hyde. Johnson managed six targets, but converted just one for a reception. With Tyrod Taylor's rushing mentality, Johnson may find opportunity hard to come by after catching at least 50 passes in each of his first three seasons and is only a fringe FLEX option next week versus the Saints.
report: Browns RB Duke Johnson rushed five times for 17 yards and caught 1-of-6 targets for eight yards in Sunday's Week 1 game versus the Steelers.

impact: Johnson had his second disappointing game in a row to start the year as he managed just five touches, his fewest in a game since Week 1 of last season. Through two games, Johnson has totaled just 35 yards on just 11 touches. He's not even worth consideration in fantasy at this stage until his opportunity expands heading into a Week 3 matchup versus the Jets.
report: Duke Johnson rushed three times for three yards and caught two passes for seven yards in Sunday's Week 2 loss to the Saints.

impact: He has finished with six touches or fewer in each of Cleveland's first four games.  Johnson did convert a two-point conversion on run around the edge of Oakland's defense, but he also dropped a pass and was out-touched by Carlos Hyde 22 to 6.  Johnson is waiver-wire material outside of Dynasty leagues.
report: Duke Johnson rushed twice for 11 yards and caught 4-of-6 targets for 45 yards in the Browns' Week 4 loss to Oakland.

impact: Johnson was again was a non-factor in the offensive game plan for the Browns. After averaging 4.6 receptions a year ago, Johnson now has 10 receptions on the season through five games. He is not worth holding onto in fantasy formats outside of Dynasty leagues.
report: Duke Johnson rushed five times for 35 yards while catching one pass for seven yards in Sunday's Week 5 win over the Ravens.

impact: This was by far Johnson's best game of the season, adding three plays of over 20 yards on the day with the highlight being a 32-yard catch and run. Despite the big day in producing yardage, Johnson still only managed six touches, giving him six or fewer touches in every game this season. Johnson is a risky-FLEX play Week 7 against the Buccaneers with his current volume levels.
report: Duke Johnson rushed twice for 36 yards while catching 4-of-5 targets for 73 yards in Sunday's Week 6 loss to the Chargers.

impact: We wouldn't read much into this. Johnson is listed ahead of Chubb out of seniority but may not start depending on what formation the Browns open in. Chubb remains the favorite to lead Cleveland in Week 7 carries.
report: Duke Johnson is listed as the starter for Week 7 against the Bucs.

impact: With hopes that Johnson would gain usage after the trade of Carlos Hyde, things remained the same as always for Johnson as he was out-touched by rookie Nick Chubb 18-to-5. The touch total is especially discouraging as the Browns trailed the entire game. Johnson now has six or fewer touches in every game this season and is not a fantasy option until usage truly changes.
report: Duke Johnson rushed one time for -4 yards while catching all four of his targets for 23 yards in the Week 7 loss to the Buccaneers.

impact: With hopes that Johnson would gain usage after the trade of Carlos Hyde, things remained the same as always for Johnson as he was out-touched by rookie Nick Chubb 18-to-5. The touch total is especially discouraging as the Browns trailed the entire game. Johnson now has six or fewer touches in every game this season and is not a fantasy option until usage truly changes.
report: Duke Johnson rushed one time for -4 yards while catching all four of his targets for 23 yards in the Week 7 loss to the Buccaneers.

impact: The more things change, the more they stay the same with Johnson's usage. He caught two passes on the opening possession of the game and then was never heard from again. Johnson has now had six or fewer touches in every game this season and is not a fantasy option until he begins to see tangible volume.
report: Duke Johnson rushed two times for zero yards while catching 2-of-3 targets for 16 yards in Sunday's Week 8 loss to the Steelers.

impact: With running backs coach Freddie Kitchens promoted to offensive coordinator this week in the wake of Todd Haley's firing, Johnson was noticeably used more than at any point this season. After having now more than six touches in any game this season, Johnson led the team in targets, receptions and yardage while catching scores from 19 and five yards out on the afternoon. Johnson and the coaching staff took advantage of a weak linebacking unit in coverage which was encouraging for further use when the matchup dictates Johnson being a focal point of the offense. Cleveland will have a chance to prove that becoming a trend as Johnson plays the Atlanta Falcons in Week 10, who are the league's worst team defending backs out of the backfield on the season.
report: Duke Johnson caught all nine of his targets for 78 yards and two touchdowns while rushing one time for eight yards in Sunday's Week 9 loss to the Chiefs.

impact: Johnson's 11-yard touchdown in the third quarter was a third down checkdown from Baker Mayfield. Johnson now has 17 touches over Freddie Kitchens' two games as offensive coordinator. His previous two-game high for 2018 was 11. Johnson will have an excellent Week 12 matchup in the Bengals when the Browns come off bye.
report: Duke Johnson caught 4-of-4 targets for 31 yards and a touchdown in the Browns' Week 10 win over the Falcons, adding three carries for 15 additional yards.

impact: It was a pedestrian debut for Johnson, though he somewhat salvaged the day for fantasy owners by punching in a late goal-line touchdown. That score gave the Cardinals their first points of the afternoon with 5:47 remaining in the fourth quarter. With Arizona way behind, the Cardinals mostly abandoned their running game in the second half with Johnson receiving just three carries after halftime. Arizona wasn't competitive on Sunday and could be in for a rough season. Negative game-script could hinder Johnson throughout the year, including next week in a tough matchup against the Rams.
report: David Johnson accrued 37 yards and a touchdown on nine carries along with five catches for 30 yards on nine targets Sunday in the Cardinals’ Week 1 loss to Washington.

impact: He was shockingly not targeted in the first half, and he finished the game with just one catch, although he had another called back by a penalty. Benching Sam Bradford is the first order of business, but the Cardinals have to better utilize Johnson if they want to have any success on offense, especially with Larry Fitzgerald dealing with a hamstring issue. Johnson will be more of an RB2 in a tough matchup with the Bears next week.
report: David Johnson rushed 13 times for 48 yards and hauled in 1-of-2 targets for three yards in the Cardinals' Week 2 loss to the Rams.

impact: The bright spot was a 21-yard touchdown catch in the 1st quarter off a play action where Johnson dusted a linebacker in coverage for an easy pitch and catch. A week after promising to get Johnson more usage split out as a receiver, that was not the case on Sunday. Johnson has now found the end zone in two of the first three games, but has now rushed 34 times for 116 yards (3.4 YPC) with 10 catches for 63 yards. With the Cardinals potentially turning to Josh Rosen as their starting quarterback things may begin to shift for Johnson moving forward, but he will only be a RB2 option next week against the Seahawks due to his floor potential when he fails to find the end zone.
report: David Johnson rushed 12 times for 31 yards while catching 4-of-4 targets for 30 yards and a touchdown in Sunday's Week 3 loss to the Bears.

impact: Despite coming off the field for multiple passing situations, Johnson managed to have his best game of the early season Sunday. Johnson broke off a long run of 21 yards and a long catch of 30 yards as Arizona finally fed him the ball for the first time in a game this season. He scored a 1-yard touchdown in the 2nd quarter after a pass interference in the end zone. Despite his slow start, Johnson has still managed to find the end zone in three of the first four games. Johnson will be in the lower-RB1 mix Week 5 against the 49ers.
report: David Johnson rushed 21 times for 71 yards and a touchdown while catching 3-of-4 targets for 41 yards in Sunday's Week 4 loss to the Seahawks.

impact: Johnson averaged a thoroughly underwhelming 3.1 yards per carry against the Niners but for fantasy purposes, all that matters is that he scored two touchdowns. Both were of the goal-line variety. That gives Johnson four touchdowns in his last three games and five for the year. After seeing a bizarrely light workload early on, the Cardinals have shown a renewed commitment to Johnson, feeding him 45 touches over the last two weeks. D.J. has been alarmingly inefficient this year but now that his volume is on the rise, Johnson can safely be reinserted as a weekly RB1 in all fantasy formats. His next test will come against the Vikings in Week 6.
report: David Johnson collected 55 yards and two touchdowns on 18 carries while snagging two catches for 16 yards on three targets Sunday in the Cardinals’ Week 5 victory over San Francisco.

impact: Johnson's struggles continued, but he managed to salvage his game with a late one-yard TD. He dropped a red-zone target, lost a fumble, and was stuffed on fourth-and-goal from the one-yard line before his touchdown. Johnson's pass game role remained small, finishing with just two catches for 15 yards. Johnson has looked nothing like the back he was in 2016. Despite a lackluster season to this point, Johnson will be a must-start against a Broncos defense which has given up back-to-back 200-yard rushers.
report: David Johnson rushed 18 times for 55 yards and a touchdown in Week 6 against the Vikings.

impact: If you were watching, you know how infuriating this was. The Cardinals' clueless coaching staff continued to run Johnson right up the middle, only looking to get him into space deep into garbage time in the fourth quarter. It was play-calling so bad it had to be seen to be believed. That's been a theme all season, of course. It appears tonight's disaster could cost OC Mike McCoy his job. Even if it does, Johnson will have a hard time hitting RB1 value against the 49ers' middle-of-the-road run defense in Week 8. There is shockingly little talent around him.
report: David Johnson rushed 14 times for 39 yards in the Cardinals' Week 7 loss to the Broncos, adding three receptions for 31 additional yards.

impact: It was a 20-touch, 100-yard day for Johnson, but his usage wasn't as encouraging as the box score indicates. All four of his targets came on underwhelming screens to the flats, forcing the all-world talent to create his own yardage starting from behind the line of scrimmage. Even his 59 yards rushing and -13 air yards were similar to his per game averages (47.9, 3.8). Josh Rosen attempted a season-high 40 passes, at least showing some evolution in the Cardinals' offense, but there's still undeniably a lot to be desired with how Johnson's being used on a weekly basis. Hopefully the bye week allows enough time to re-think and creatively unleash him against the Chiefs' poor rush defense in Week 10.
report: David Johnson rushed 16 times for 59 yards, tacking on four catches for 41 yards in the Cardinals' Week 8 victory over the Niners.

impact: It's easily the best game of the year for Johnson, who saw a season-high 28 touches. Both of his touchdowns came in the red-zone -- scoring on a nine-yard strike from Josh Rosen in the first quarter and capping off the Cardinals' opening drive of the second half with a goal-line TD. Johnson has been more involved since OC Byron Leftwich took over playcalling in Week 8. He'll be in the RB1 mix for Week 11 against the Raiders.
report: David Johnson rushed 21 times for 98 yards and a touchdown and caught 7-of-9 targets for 85 yards and a receiving touchdown.

impact: Johnson was penalty away from a much bigger day, as a Ricky Seals-Jones holding call nullified a late 57-yard score. Johnson's biggest play that counted was a 53-yard fourth quarter rumble where he put Raiders S Marcus Gilchrist on skates. The 100-yard day on the ground was Johnson's first of the season, though he has now piled up 337 yards from scrimmage over the past two weeks, re-establishing himself as a mid-range RB1. The Chargers are on deck for Week 12.
report: David Johnson rushed 25 times for 137 yards in the Cardinals' Week 11 loss to the Raiders, adding a 17-yard reception.

impact: Jeffery's first catch did not come until the second quarter, and he appeared gassed after the 31-yard gain in his first game action this season. Tired or not, that was just the start of a big game. He had a great box-out catch on third-and-goal for his touchdown, and he earned a first down on a late game-tying drive with a catch-and-run on a screen. Now healthy and with his quarterback rounding into form, Jeffery should be considered a back-end WR2 in a suddenly promising matchup against the Vikings next week.
report: Alshon Jeffery hauled in 8-of-9 targets for 105 yards and a touchdown in the Eagles' Week 4 loss to the Titans.

impact: Jeffery nearly had a third catch on a late third down but could not hold on after taking a colossal shot to the back. It did not feel like Jeffery was getting erased by Xavier Rhodes, but the box score certainly reflects that. Jeffery figures to see more shadow treatment (Janoris Jenkins) in Week 6 when the Eagles venture to New York to take on the Giants for Thursday Night Football. He'll be on the WR2/3 borderline for that one. Jenkins is having a tough year.
report: Alshon Jeffery caught 2-of-8 targets for 39 yards in the Eagles' Week 5 loss to the Vikings.

impact: It was an easy night at the office for Jeffery, who benefitted from Carson Wentz's play-making ability on the run. Jeffery had few issues with Janoris Jenkins' coverage. The Eagles' No. 1 receiver is up to three scores in three games since making his 2018 debut. He'll be a back-end WR2 for next week's date with the Panthers.
report: Alshon Jeffery caught 8-of-12 targets for 74 yards and two touchdowns in the Eagles' Week 6 win over the Giants.

impact: Through no fault of Jeffery’s, the Eagles wound up losing this game despite building a 17-0 halftime lead. Jeffery dominated his matchup against Panthers CB James Bradberry, frequently looking like a man among boys and whipping Bradberry for an early 11-yard touchdown on an inside move. Alshon has been an elite producer since returning from his shoulder injury. He will face a talented but downward-spiraling Jaguars defense next.
report: Alshon Jeffery caught 7-of-10 targets for 88 yards and a touchdown in the Eagles’ Week 7 loss to Carolina.

impact: Through no fault of Jeffery’s, the Eagles wound up losing this game despite building a 17-0 halftime lead. Jeffery dominated his matchup against Panthers CB James Bradberry, frequently looking like a man among boys and whipping Bradberry for an early 11-yard touchdown on an inside move. Alshon has been an elite producer since returning from his shoulder injury. He will face a talented but downward-spiraling Jaguars defense next.
report: Alshon Jeffery caught 7-of-10 targets for 88 yards and a touchdown in the Eagles’ Week 7 loss to Carolina.

impact: As expected, Jeffery did not have a big game while drawing shadow coverage from Jalen Ramsey, but he by no means disappeared. He was able to get open for two catches in the first half including a third-down conversion where he bullied his way to the sticks after the catch. His third catch was another conversion on third down to help extend a touchdown drive, but that was about it for Philly's No. 1. He should have more success against Dallas following the bye week.
report: Alshon Jeffery hauled in 4-of-5 targets for 35 yards in the Eagles' Week 8 win over the Jaguars.

impact: Jeffery wasn't much of a factor in this one. This could have been a worse game, but Jeffery got half of his yards on a 17-yard catch late in the fourth quarter. His only red-zone opportunity was a dropped touchdown after a hard hit in the end-zone. Jeffery is trending down after getting held to 35 yards last week. He's in a rebound spot against the Saints in Week 11.
report: Alshon Jeffery caught 4-of-8 targets for 48 yards in Week 10 against the Cowboys.

impact: Jeffery went down with the ship in a game Carson Wentz managed just 156 yards, and it is yet another down game for the Eagles' No. 1. After starting out strong, Jeffery has four catches in each of the last three games and has failed to top 50 yards in any game during that run. The good news is the Eagles get to face a Giants defense which Jeffery dominated for 74 yards and two scores in Week 6. He will be a back-end WR2 for that matchup.
report: Alshon Jeffery caught 4-of-5 targets for 33 yards in the Eagles' Week 11 loss to the Saints.

impact: James drew the start and opportunity with Vance McDonald still sidelined with a foot injury. He will only be a fringe TE2 option in Week 2 against the Chiefs if McDonald remains inactive.
report: Steelers TE Jesse James caught 3-of-5 targets for 60 yards in Sunday's Week 1 game versus the Browns.

impact: James also drew a defensive holding penalty in the end zone. The 100-yard game was the first of James' career, and came in spite of Vance McDonald making his 2018 debut. James was left completely uncovered multiple times by a Chiefs defense preoccupied with stopping Antonio Brown and JuJu Smith-Schuster. Today won't be the last time that happens, but especially with McDonald now involved, James' big days are going to be too difficult to see coming to consider him an appealing TE2 streamer.
report: Jesse James caught 5-of-5 targets for 138 yards and a touchdown in the Steelers' Week 2 loss to the Chiefs.

impact: The Steelers continued their game of tight-end seesaw with James winning the prize over Vance McDonald this week. Nearly all of James' yardage came on a 51-yard deep heave from Ben Roethlisberger early in the fourth quarter. That marked the longest play of his career. It was also the longest play the Ravens have given up this year. The Penn State product will have a big game every now and again, but he's not someone fantasy owners can realistically rely on a week-to-week basis. He'll be back at it Thursday night against Carolina.
report: Jesse James pulled in two grabs for 53 yards on three targets Sunday in the Steelers’ Week 9 victory over the Ravens.

impact: The Ravens' game plan was definitive in this one.  They ran the ball on the first 13 plays of the game and wound up with a whopping 54-to-19 run-to-pass ratio.  Jackson's lone turnover came on a third-quarter broken play where he forced a pass with his feet unsettled, trying to make something happen.  Otherwise, he looked under control and exceptionally dynamic on the ground.  Robert Griffin III barely made an appearance.  If Jackson gets another start -- which is pending Joe Flacco's (hip) health -- he will be an upside QB1 play in Week 12 against the Raiders.
report: Lamar Jackson rushed 27 times for 117 yards and completed 13-of-19 passes for 150 yards and an interception in the Ravens' Week 11 win over the Bengals.

impact: Funchess had a terrible third-down drop in the first half and went into the break with a measly three grabs for 16 yards on five targets.  He played better in the second half, making a nifty sideline grab on the final drive to give Carolina a chance.  Funchess saw four more targets than he did in Week 1 and figures to continue to see increased usage as a fantasy WR3 without Greg Olsen (foot).
report: Devin Funchess caught 7-of-9 targets for 77 yards in the Panthers' Week 2 loss to the Falcons.

impact: Funchess was Carolina's leading receiver in a game where Cam Newton completed only 15 passes for 150 yards, and Ron Rivera's team leaned heavily on its running game for the win.  As Greg Olsen remains "month to month" with a broken foot, Funchess will be an every-week WR2 for the foreseeable future.  Fantasy owners need to hang onto Funchess tightly through Carolina's Week 4 bye.
report: Devin Funchess caught 4-of-7 targets for 67 yards and a touchdown in the Panthers' Week 3 win over the Bengals.

impact: Funchess had his most success after halftime, corralling three of his five second-half targets for 41 yards. His biggest play didn’t show up in the box score as Funchess delivered a crushing block on Janoris Jenkins, freeing Curtis Samuel to score a 25-yard touchdown in the first quarter. Funchess battled dehydration throughout the afternoon and even left for a brief stretch to get an IV in the second half, though he only missed a handful of snaps. The 24-year-old has drawn seven-plus targets in each of his last four games, though his workload will likely take a hit with Greg Olsen due back in Week 6. The Panthers are in D.C. next week.
report: Devin Funchess delivered four catches for 53 yards on seven targets Sunday in the Panthers’ Week 5 win over New York.

impact: It was arguably Funchess' best overall game of the year, which is encouraging since it came as Greg Olsen made his return to the lineup. Funchess made a few excellent catches, but the highlight was his 23-yard touchdown grab in the second quarter. Funchess skied over Quinton Dunbar in the end zone before essentially taking the ball off Dunbar's chest. Producing as a solid WR3, Funchess has an appetizing Week 7 matchup in the Eagles' struggling secondary.
report: Devin Funchess caught 5-of-8 targets for 74 yards and a touchdown in the Panthers' Week 6 loss to the Redskins.

impact: Funchess’ touchdown came on a sluggo route to beat Eagles top CB Ronald Darby from 18 yards away. Funchess came out of Michigan younger than most prospects and needed a few years to develop as a rotational receiver, but he is a legit No. 1 at this point. And he has stayed productive despite Greg Olsen’s (foot) return. Nevertheless, Funchess will be more WR3 than WR2 when the Panthers host a stingy Ravens defense next.
report: Devin Funchess caught 6-of-11 targets for 62 yards and a touchdown in the Panthers’ Week 7 win over the Eagles.

impact: It was a quiet day for Funchess as the Panthers bludgeoned the Bucs on the ground. D.J. Moore and Curtis Samuel also stole yardage on gadget plays. More uneven since Greg Olsen's healthy return, Funchess will be a mid-range WR3 for Thursday night's game against the Steelers.
report: Devin Funchess caught 4-of-5 targets for 44 yards in the Panthers' Week 9 win over the Bucs.

impact: Funchess' targets were as many as D.J. Moore and just one more than Curtis Samuel. He has now been held below 50 yards in back-to-back games and is trending toward back-end WR3 status. The Panthers are traveling to Detroit for Week 11.
report: Devin Funchess caught 3-of-5 targets for 32 yards in the Panthers' Week 10 loss to the Steelers.

impact: Funchess’ day got off to a good start when he got loose for 23 yards on the opening drive, but it could have been better had he held on for what should have been a short score on that drive. That was just the start of his struggles. Funchess could not come down with a beautifully thrown deep pass on his next target and dropped what should have been a big gain the next drive. After halftime, he failed to come down with what would have been a tough catch on third down, and he dropped another pass on the opening drive of the fourth quarter. He did convert a long third down late, but this was a disappointing outing. Funchess will look to turn things around next week against the Seahawks.
report: Devin Funchess hauled in 2-of-8 targets for 39 yards in the Panthers' Week 11 loss to the Lions.

impact: Jackson took a tumble in the fourth quarter after coming down with a 35-yard catch. He had a monster game prior to getting hurt, delivering five receptions for 146 yards and two touchdown on just five targets. His absence will open up snaps for Chris Godwin at wide receiver, though the Bucs are leading and looking to kill clock right now.
report: DeSean Jackson left Sunday's Week 1 game against the Saints with a concussion and will not return.

impact: Incredibly, Jackson has now caught all nine of his targets for 275 yards and three touchdowns two games in.  The Bucs are destroying opponents on play-action passes and calling aggressive deep shots on first-down plays, when defenses are in their base personnel and not equipped to handle Jackson's devastating speed.  Keep D-Jax rolling as an upside WR2/3 play in Week 3 versus Pittsburgh.
report: DeSean Jackson caught 4-of-4 targets for 129 yards and a touchdown in the Bucs' Week 2 win over the Eagles.

impact: Much like last week, the Bears trailed by multiple scores at the half. That only fueled Jackson's boom-bust style, allowing the burner to top 100-yards for the third time this season. He notably finished second on the team in targets behind Mike Evans (9). Jackson will stay a bye-week commodity even with Jameis Winston under center following the Bucs' Week 5 bye.
report: DeSean Jackson caught 5-of-8 targets for 112 yards in the Bucs' Week 4 loss to the Bears.

impact: He did not manage to top 100 yards, but Jackson kept his good run going in this one despite a less than efficient outing. It could have been an even bigger game, but Jackson was not able to catch up to a deep target in the second half, and Jameis Winston was picked off on another deep attempt to his speedy receiver. Getting consistent opportunities, Jackson will be an upside WR3 next week against the Browns.
report: DeSean Jackson hauled in 4-of-9 targets for 77 yards in the Bucs' Week 6 loss to the Falcons.

impact: Jackson scored the first touchdown of the game on a 14-yard end around in the first quarter. He then nearly reeled in a touchdown on the following drive that was broken up by Denzel Ward. Ward followed Jackson for the majority of the afternoon as Ward's size and speed was best suited for Jackson rather than that of Mike Evans. Jackson's 14-yard catch in overtime on third down set up the game-winning field goal. Heading into Week 8, Jackson will be a boom-or-bust WR3 option against the Bengals.
report: DeSean Jackson caught 2-of-5 targets for 25 yards while rushing twice for eight yards and a touchdown in Sunday's Week 7 win over the Browns.

impact: Jackson was the intended target on Ryan Fitzpatrick's second interception. It was essentially an arm punt. One week after reportedly requesting a trade, Jackson watched Mike Evans and Adam Humphries dominate targets. Playing mostly good ball with Fitz this season, D-Jax will try to bounce back as a WR3 against the Redskins in Week 10.
report: DeSean Jackson caught 2-of-4 targets for 32 yards in the Bucs' Week 9 loss to the Panthers.

impact: Jackson got up for this one against his former team but didn't do much of anything notable while also dropping a pass.  Ryan Fitzpatrick took one deep shot to Jackson, but it didn't have a prayer and was well covered.  Jackson has seen his playing time dip and is a boom-or-bust WR3/4 ahead of a date with the Giants.
report: DeSean Jackson caught 5-of-8 targets for 67 yards in the Bucs' Week 10 loss to the Redskins.

impact: His seven targets encouragingly tied Mike Evans' for the team lead. It was ultimately a bust day, though, as Jackson failed to cash-in on his normal deep targets. He'll be a boom-or-bust WR3/4 against the Niners again next week whether it's Jameis Winston or Ryan Fitzpatrick who's throwing to him.
report: DeSean Jackson caught 4-of-7 targets for 38 yards in the Bucs' Week 11 loss to the Giants.

impact: Freeman found the end zone for a one-yard touchdown plunge on the opening drive of the second half, but hardly found any traction with the Broncos playing from behind all game. Freeman has now totaled 23 carries for 99 yards through two weeks with no receptions and has been out-touched by fellow rookie Phillip Lindsay 32-to-23 so far through two weeks. Freeman appears to be a touchdown-or-bust fantasy option moving forward and a fringe FLEX option Week 3 versus the Ravens.
report: Royce Freeman rushed eight times for 28 yards and a touchdown in Sunday's Week 2 win over the Raiders.

impact: He added a catch for five yards. Denver's special teams unit set up the offense at the six-yard line following a punt block early in the first quarter, and Freeman made good on the opportunity with a six-yard touchdown on his first carry. Despite the score, Freeman appeared on his way to another timeshare throughout the first half, but that changed when Phillip Lindsay was ejected late in the second quarter. Freeman responded with 37 yards on eight carries in the second half including several long gains. Unfortunately for Freeman, Lindsay should be back in the rotation next week, keeping him in the FLEX range despite a good matchup against the Chiefs.
report: Royce Freeman rushed 13 times for 53 yards and a touchdown in the Broncos' Week 3 loss to the Ravens.

impact: He wasn't targeted in the pass game.  Freeman was out-touched 14-8 by Phillip Lindsay, who gained 79 yards and also scored a one-yard touchdown.  Freeman's score was more impressive from 14 yards out as he looked to be bottled up for a loss before plowing through a couple defenders on his way to the end zone.  The Broncos were running the ball down the Chiefs' throat all night, but OC Bill Musgrave went away from the ground game late for some reason.  Freeman has scored in three-straight games and will be a TD-dependent RB2 next week at the Jets.
report: Royce Freeman rushed eight times for 67 yards and one touchdown in the Broncos' Week 4 loss to the Chiefs.

impact: He now has single-digit touches in three of his last four games, disappointing after many fantasy owners blew fourth-round picks on Freeman.  Freeman quickly lost Denver's lead back job to Phillip Lindsay, who out-touched him 15 to 8 in Sunday's blowout loss.  Freeman will remain a touchdown-dependent flex option when the Broncos return home to host the high-flying Rams next.
report: Royce Freeman rushed five times for 31 yards and caught 3-of-4 targets for 16 yards in Denver's Week 5 loss to the Jets.

impact: Freeman was not targeted in the passing game. For the first time in a game in which Phillip Lindsay did not get ejected, Freeman out-carried him, though Lindsay still out-touched and out-gained his rookie teammate. As you can see from Freeman's stats, he did not do anything to make that the new balance of power going forward. Lindsay will still be the preferred fantasy play for Week 7 against the Cardinals.
report: Royce Freeman rushed nine times for 22 yards in the Broncos' Week 6 loss to the Rams.

impact: Freeman appeared healthy in his return from a high-ankle sprain but didn't move the needle much for Denver, managing a long run of just seven yards. He salvaged the day somewhat by punching in a three-yard touchdown—his fifth of the season—during the third quarter, though the rookie saw seven fewer touches than Phillip Lindsay. Freeman has been operating as the 1B to Lindsay's 1A, though his size advantage over Lindsay makes him a threat to vulture goal-line carries. The Broncos host Pittsburgh in Week 12.
report: Royce Freeman delivered 23 yards and a touchdown on seven carries while securing his lone target for a seven-yard pickup Sunday in Denver’s Week 11 win over the Chargers.

impact: It is the second down game in a row for Fuller, who did not have his first catch until the fourth quarter and whose biggest contribution was drawing a DPI deep down the field to set up a game-tying field goal. He should have had a long touchdown before those plays, but Deshaun Watson just missed him. The duo will hit on those plays eventually, but it might not happen next week in Jacksonville. Fuller will be more of a WR3 in that spot.
report: Will Fuller hauled in 2-of-3 targets for 33 yards in the Texans' Week 6 win over the Bills.

impact: Fuller led the team in receiving and tied DeAndre Hopkins for the team lead in targets, a good sign after Fuller spent the last two weeks effectively running wind sprints as a decoy with three targets in each game. Hopefully, finally over his longstanding hamstring injury, Fuller should resume WR2/3 treatment when the Texans face the Dolphins on Thursday Night Football next. Keke Coutee (hamstring) won’t play, freeing up a few extra targets for Fuller.
report: Will Fuller caught 6-of-8 targets for 68 yards in the Texans’ Week 7 win over the Jaguars.

impact: Jacksonville set out with a clear plan at the start of the game, and Fournette was the centerpiece. He had six carries in the first quarter, and Jacksonville kept feeding him even after the Colts jumped out to an early lead. He repaid the faith with a one-yard touchdown in the second quarter which he helped set up with a 31-yard gain on a screen. He kept the good times rolling on the opening drive of the second half which he capped with a one-yard touchdown catch, and he helped keep the offense moving with four catches after the break. Most importantly, he emerged from a game healthy for the first time this season. He faces a much tougher test next week against the Steelers, but he will be a back-end RB1 in that matchup.
report: Leonard Fournette rushed 24 times for 53 yards and a touchdown and hauled in all five of his targets for 56 yards and another score in the Jaguars' Week 10 loss to the Colts.

impact: Fournette started off hot, rushing 14 times for 74 yards in the first half, but then was bottled up on the ground after the break. He still found a way to maximize his touches in the second half, adding receptions of 26 and 21 yards while finding the end zone on a leaping 2-yard touchdown run that put the Jaguars ahead 16 points. Fournette now has 29 and 30 touches in his two games since returning from injury, securing his role as a bellcow fantasy option. The Jaguars head to Buffalo in Week 12.
report: Leonard Fournette rushed 28 times for 95 yards and a touchdown while catching two passes for 46 yards in Sunday's Week 11 loss to the Steelers.

impact: Foles' efficiency looks decent on paper, but he gripped the ball too long in the pocket, took six sacks, and needed an entire half to get the offense moving against a bad defense.  Foles remains a high-end NFL backup, but he's obviously a severe downgrade from Carson Wentz.  ESPN's Adam Schefter reported Sunday that Wentz will have a real chance to return for Week 3 against the Colts.
report: Nick Foles completed 35-of-48 passes for 334 yards and a touchdown in the Eagles' Week 2 loss at Tampa Bay.

impact: Foles' efficiency looks decent on paper, but he gripped the ball too long in the pocket, took six sacks, and needed an entire half to get the offense moving against a bad defense.  Foles remains a high-end NFL backup, but he's obviously a severe downgrade from Carson Wentz.  ESPN's Adam Schefter reported Sunday that Wentz will have a real chance to return for Week 3 against the Colts.
report: Nick Foles completed 35-of-48 passes for 334 yards and a touchdown in the Eagles' Week 2 loss at Tampa Bay.

impact: Fitzgerald is still a big name but he's not playing like one right now. For the first time in 15 NFL seasons, Fitzgerald will enter Week 6 without a touchdown. The Cardinals completed just 10 passes all afternoon but somehow they won anyway against the injury-depleted Niners. Fitzgerald has shown up on the injury report with hamstring and back ailments the past few weeks and is clearly operating at less than 100 percent. He'll be difficult to trust next week against his home-town Vikings.
report: Larry Fitzgerald chipped in with two catches for 35 yards on three targets Sunday in Arizona’s Week 5 win over the 49ers.

impact: Fitzgerald's targets were up after getting held to five catches over the last two weeks.  He didn't have any red-zone chances, but it's a step in the right direction. Fitzgerald has taken a backseat to Christian Kirk since Josh Rosen took over. He's hard to trust as a FLEX for Week 7 against the Broncos.
report: Larry Fitzgerald caught 5-of-8 passes for 39 yards in Week 6 against the Vikings.

impact: Fitzgerald's targets, catches, and receiving yards were all season-highs in his first game under new OC Byron Leftwich. Prior to Sunday, Fitzgerald hadn't exceeded 40 receiving yards since Week 1. Josh Rosen attempted a season-high 40 passing attempts, too, instilling life into a formerly lifeless aerial attack. With Fitzgerald now the focus of an assumed-to-be developing offense, there's suddenly reason to hold onto him moving forward. Consider him a confident WR3 against the Chiefs when the Cardinals return from their bye in Week 10.
report: Larry Fitzgerald hauled in 8-of-12 targets for a season-high 102 yards and one score in the Cardinals' Week 8 win over the 49ers.

impact: It's a step back after Fitzgerald had touchdowns the last two weeks. Fitzgerald led the team in targets, but the Cardinals' offense struggled to maintain drives with Josh Rosen facing constant pressures. Chad Williams is looking at a potential multi-game absence, so Fitzgerald's target share will have him in the WR3 mix against the Raiders in Week 11.
report: Larry Fitzgerald caught 6-of-10 targets for 50 yards in Week 10 against Kansas City.

impact: That's efficiency, though Fitz obviously deserved more looks. Rookie QB Josh Rosen could complete just nine passes against the Raiders' league-worst defense. Fitz's first score was delivered on a rope into the end zone. For the second, he inside-outed CB Rashaan Melvin. Fitz's usage had not been a recent concern. He should bounce back in the target department for Week 12 against the Chargers.
report: Larry Fitzgerald caught 2-of-4 targets for 23 yards and two touchdowns in the Cardinals' Week 11 loss to the Raiders.

impact: Flacco carried his strong preseason into Week 1. He threw all his touchdowns in the first three quarters before getting rested in a blowout. Flacco has had an Alex Smith fire lit under him after the Ravens drafted Lamar Jackson and looks primed for a rebound with an improved supporting cast. He'll get the Bengals on Thursday Night Football in Week 2.
report: Joe Flacco completed 25-of-34 passes for 236 yards and three touchdowns in Baltimore's Week 1 game against Buffalo.

impact: Flacco also lost a fumble that essentially sealed the game in the fourth quarter. Utterly failing to feel the pressure as he rolled out to the sideline, Flacco got thunderously tomahawked from behind as he attempted to wind up for a bomb. It's the kind of mistake he's made far too often in his career. His first pick was an inexcusable throw into triple coverage. The second, a lame duck he tossed while getting hit. The biggest positive was Flacco's connection with speedster/deep threat John Brown, whom Flacco targeted 10 times. The Ravens host the Broncos in Week 3.
report: Joe Flacco completed 32-of-55 passes for 377 yards, two touchdowns and two interceptions in the Ravens' 34-23, Week 2 loss to the Bengals.

impact: Flacco bounced back from his rough performance last Thursday night. He made a couple nice throws to John Brown down the sidelines, one of which Brown caught for a 44-yard gain in the second quarter, and consistently found Michael Crabtree when he needed a completion. With a great matchup against the Steelers up next, Flacco will be a streaming option.
report: Joe Flacco completed 25-of-40 passes for 277 yards and a touchdown in the Ravens' Week 3 win over the Broncos.

impact: Flacco hit John Brown on a 33-yard touchdown to open the game. He added a goal-line TD to Alex Collins after a Steelers first quarter turnover and connected on a number of deep shots. It's a solid rebound for Flacco after two straight middling games. Fueled by the Ravens trading up for Lamar Jackson, Flacco is on pace for 5,012 yards and a 32:8 TD/INT ratio through four weeks. Baltimore has another division game with the Browns in Week 5.
report: Joe Flacco completed 28-of-42 passes for 363 yards and two touchdowns in the Ravens' Week 4 win over the Steelers.

impact: Flacco wasn't at his best Sunday, but suffered from multiple dropped passes from his receivers in the rain. It was the first time that he failed to throw a touchdown pass since Week 12 of last season. Flacco's lone turnover came on tipped pass at the goal line in which he was targeted Nick Boyle in the end zone. Flacco will enter Week 6 as a middling QB2 option on the road against the Titans.
report: Joe Flacco completed 29-of-56 passes for 298 yards with an interception in Sunday's Week 5 loss to the Browns.

impact: Flacco wasn't needed as the Ravens took a 14-0 lead into the half and never looked back. Baltimore's defense sacked Marcus Mariota a whopping 11 times on the day, inevitably allowing Flacco to stand around and handoff to Alex Collins (19/54/2) until the final whistle. The Titans quietly boast an efficient pass rush, so an outing such as this was expected. Have no fear in turning right around and starting/streaming Flacco everywhere across all formats in Week 7 against the Saints.
report: Joe Flacco completed 25-of-37 passes for 238 yards, one touchdown, and one pick in the Ravens' big Week 6 win over the Titans.

impact: A standard day at Flacco's 2018 office. Flacco has not surpassed two scores since Week 1. Today's touchdowns went to Mark Andrews and John Brown. Flacco lost another potential score when Lamar Jackson cashed in a gadget look. Flacco continues to seem thrilled every time he is split out wide for Jackson to run a play. The Ravens are headed to Charlotte for Week 8.
report: Joe Flacco completed 23-of-39 passes for 279 yards and two touchdowns in the Ravens' 24-23, Week 7 loss to the Saints.

impact: Filling in for a suspended Jameis Winston, Fitzpatrick was sensational in his season debut, embarrassing the Saints on their home turf. The Harvard man was especially dominant in the first half, completing 11-of-14 passes for 210 yards and two touchdowns before the break while submitting a perfect 158.3 quarterback rating. The Saints’ secondary looked out of sorts on Sunday and Fitzpatrick took full advantage of their ineptitude by hurling four touchdowns including a 58-yard seed to DeSean Jackson on the Bucs’ opening drive. That was the first of two scores for D-Jax, who registered 146 yards on five catches. FitzMagic was also Tampa’s second-leading rusher and sealed the game with a 12-yard scramble late in the fourth quarter. It’s doubtful the 35-year-old will overtake Winston for the starting job but he’s certainly worked his way into the streaming conversation. Even in a daunting matchup against the Eagles next week, he could be worth a try.
report: Ryan Fitzpatrick completed 21-of-28 passes for a career-high 417 yards with four touchdowns and no interceptions while adding 36 yards and a touchdown on 12 carries Sunday in the Buccaneers’ Week 1 win over the Saints.

impact: Bucs playcaller Todd Monken came out as aggressive as ever, calling a play-action bomb on the first play from scrimmage.  DeSean Jackson smoked Jalen Mills and scored from 75 yards out.  O.J. Howard added a 75-yard catch-and-run TD, and Chris Godwin and Mike Evans both chipped in red-zone scores.  Firing on all cylinders in an entertaining offense, Fitzpatrick has earned QB1 treatment ahead of next Monday night's home date with Pittsburgh.  As the Bucs have started 2-0, it's becoming very fair to wonder if Fitzpatrick will keep the starting quarterback job when Jameis Winston's suspension ends in Week 4.
report: Ryan Fitzpatrick completed 27-of-33 passes for 402 yards, four touchdowns, and one interception in the Bucs' Week 2 win over the Eagles.

impact: Fitzpatrick became the first quarterback in league history to pass for 400 yards in three consecutive games. The night started slow for Fitzmagic and the Bucs' offense, who went into the half trailing 30-10. Tampa Bay rallied and scored the final 17 points of the evening, though, falling just one Ben Roethlisberger scramble-and-heave to JuJu Smith-Schuster away from getting the ball back and potentially pulling off the comeback win. Fitzpatrick has been absurd through three games, totaling 1,230 passing yards, 11 touchdowns, and four picks. With Jameis Winston set to return, only time will tell whether the record book's newest member will have a starting gig in Week 4.
report: Ryan Fitzpatrick completed 30-of-50 passes for 411 yards, three touchdowns, and three interceptions in the Bucs' Week 3 loss to the Steelers.

impact: Fitzpatrick was reportedly only "one or two plays away" from being benched in Week 3, too. Coach Dirk Koetter pulled the trigger in Week 4 as the Bucs went into the half trailing 38-3. Fitzpatrick totaled 126 yards and one interception before riding the pine.
report: Ryan Fitzpatrick was replaced by Jameis Winston to start the third quarter in Week 4 against the Bears.

impact: Fitzpatrick was reportedly only "one or two plays away" from being benched in Week 3, too. Coach Dirk Koetter pulled the trigger in Week 4 as the Bucs went into the half trailing 38-3. Fitzpatrick totaled 126 yards and one interception before riding the pine.
report: Ryan Fitzpatrick was replaced by Jameis Winston to start the third quarter in Week 4 against the Bears.

impact: He added an 18-yard scramble and a two-point conversion to Chris Godwin.  FitzMagic rallied the Bucs back from a multi-score deficit after Winston threw four interceptions, but it wasn't enough as the Bengals held on with a game-winning field goal in overtime.  We have to believe the Bucs will stick with Fitzpatrick as their Week 9 starter at Carolina.  Winston has simply been too careless with the football,  and Fitzpatrick has shined in Todd Monken's offense.
report: Ryan Fitzpatrick replaced Jameis Winston in the third quarter of Sunday's Week 8 loss to Cincinnati and completed 11-of-15 passes for 194 yards and two touchdowns.

impact: In true Fitz fashion, he kept throwing touchdowns and attempting deep bombs but also tossed a pair of ghastly interceptions. The first was air mailed 10 feet over Mike Evans' head in the first half. The second was a fourth quarter arm punt. Fitz found each of O.J. Howard and Adam Humphries for a pair of scores. He completed just five total passes to Mike Evans, DeSean Jackson and Chris Godwin. Fitz was bad enough in the first half that coach Dirk Koetter was asked if he considered going to Jameis Winston. His response was a succinct "no." He also confirmed Fitz will remain the starter for Week 10, where he will be dealing with the keepaway Redskins.
report: Ryan Fitzpatrick completed 24-of-40 passes for 243 yards, four touchdowns and two interceptions in the Bucs' 42-28, Week 9 loss to the Panthers.

impact: He added 35 rushing yards on eight scampers.  The Bucs moved the ball with ease all afternoon, but the offense fell totally apart once it got deep into Redskins territory.  FitzMagic lost a fumble on a sack on 2nd-and-goal from the two-yard line late in the fourth quarter after missing a wide-open Mike Evans on the previous play, spiking it at his feet.  His first interception was an overthrow at the goal line over Chris Godwin's head, and the second was thrown right to the cornerback deep in Tampa's own end.  The yards were great for Fitzpatrick, but nothing else went right.  The Bucs will head on the road to face the Giants in Week 11.
report: Ryan Fitzpatrick completed 29-of-41 passes for 406 yards, no touchdowns, and to interceptions in the Bucs' 16-3, Week 10 loss to the Redskins.

impact: Fitzpatrick tossed three picks, including one grenade that might as well have been handed to a defender, before being benched Sunday. Fitzpatrick may have started his final game for the Bucs this season.
report: Ryan Fitzpatrick was replaced by Jameis Winston in the second half Sunday.

impact: The final straw was Fitzpatrick's duck he threw in the back of the end zone to DeSean Jackson while the receiver was being triple-teamed. Fitzpatrick did rush one in from the goal line, salvaging what would've been an even worse day, but the magic had clearly run its course. Jameis Winston came off the pine and threw for more yards (199) in less than two quarters, likely signaling the end of Fitzpatrick's (second) stint as starter.
report: Ryan Fitzpatrick completed 12-of-16 passes for 167 yards and three interceptions before being benched in the Bucs' Week 11 loss to the Giants.

impact: Griffin is not fantasy-relevant in an offense that doesn't feature its tight ends.
report: Ryan Griffin caught his lone target for 12 yards in the Texans' Week 4 win over the Colts.

impact: Griffin "exploded" for six catches and 65 yards against Dallas last week, but he could not build on the breakout here. It is unlikely he fares much better next week in Jacksonville.
report: Ryan Griffin did not catch any of his five targets Week 6 against the Bills.

impact: He led the team in targets and got loose for a 38-yard touchdown bomb over the top of Indy's defense with two Colts DBs in trail position.  This is Green's age-30 season, but he has shown no signs of slippage.  He will remain a mid-range WR1 play in Week 2 against the Jimmy Smith-less Baltimore secondary.
report: A.J. Green caught 6-of-8 targets for 92 yards and a touchdown in the Bengals' Week 1 win over the Colts.

impact: Coupled with his score from Week 1, Green is now halfway to his 2017 touchdown total five days into the season. Green's first three catches all went for scores. The second was the highlight. Green caught a quick slant, shed a few tackles and was off to the races for 32 yards. The third was just too easy as Marlon Humphrey played laughably soft coverage in the end zone. Green will do battle with the Panthers' zone defense in Week 3.
report: A.J. Green caught 5-of-9 targets for 69 yards and three touchdowns in the Bengals' Week 2 win over the Ravens.

impact: It was a bit of a frustrating fantasy game for Green, who just missed a long catch, had a touchdown called back on an offensive line penalty, and had a catch negated by an accepted defensive pass interference penalty. He made up for all of that on the final drive, however, getting open in the front corner of the end zone and coming down with a sliding catch for the game-winning score. With Andy Dalton cooking, Green will be a locked-in WR1 next week against the Dolphins.
report: A.J. Green hauled in 4-of-8 targets for 78 yards and the game-winning touchdown in the Bengals' Week 4 win over the Falcons.

impact: Green broke the Bengals record with his 32nd 100-yard game. He was getting open with ease despite getting shadowed by Dolphins shutdown CB Xavien Howard. Green was held out of the end-zone against a Dolphins defense that leads the league in red-zone defense, but he's had a great start to the season, going over 50 yards in every game. Green gets a matchup with the Steelers in Week 6.
report: A.J. Green caught 6-of-10 targets for 112 yards in Week 5 against the Dolphins.

impact: Green had a couple drops in the first quarter.  His day was relatively quiet as he dealt with Joe Haden's coverage.  Green should bounce back in a big way next week in a shootout spot against the high-octane Chiefs.
report: A.J. Green caught 7-of-12 targets for 85 yards in the Bengals' Week 6 loss to the Steelers.

impact: Green had over 100 yards in the first half. He was a huge mismatch for Orlando Scandrick, but the Bengals struggled to sustain drives all night. Green had a near-touchdown but tripped and was tackled inside the five-yard line. He faded in the second half, finishing with just one catch over the final two quarters. Green will remain a WR1 for Week 8’s matchup with the Bucs.
report: A.J. Green caught 7-of-14 targets for 117 yards in Week 7 against the Chiefs.

impact: Grant led the team in receptions as a major part of Indianapolis' new short-passing offense, which doesn't stretch the field but allows Andrew Luck to pick apart defenses on quick throws.  Grant's possession-receiver game fits this style of play.  He'll be a PPR-specific WR4/flex in Week 2 at Washington.
report: Ryan Grant caught 8-of-9 targets for 59 yards in the Colts' Week 1 loss to the Bengals.

impact: So much for Grant’s #RevengeGame. He wasn’t even targeted until the fourth quarter. A week after securing a career-high eight catches, Grant was pretty much an afterthought in this one, drawing fewer targets than teammates T.Y. Hilton, Jack Doyle, Eric Ebron and Chester Rogers. Grant can be avoided in a tough matchup next week at Philadelphia.
report: Ryan Grant delivered two catches for 30 yards on two targets Sunday in the Colts’ Week 2 victory over Washington.

impact: Grant scored the lone touchdown for the Colts and 5-yard fade route which he won a contested catch. After receiving nine targets in the season opener, Grant has totaled just six targets over the past two weeks despite finding the end zone Sunday. Grant now has 13 catches for 124 yards and a touchdown through three games.
report: Ryan Grant caught 3-of-4 targets for 35 yards and a touchdown in Sunday's Week 3 loss to the Eagles.

impact: Grant also dropped a couple balls on quick slants.  His seven targets were fifth-most on the team as he's far down the totem pole in Indy.  Grant will not be a recommended fantasy play Week 5 on the road against the Patriots, though he'll be forced to play a ton with T.Y. Hilton (hamstring) likely to sit.
report: Ryan Grant caught 5-of-7 targets for 64 yards in the Colts' Week 4 loss to the Texans.

impact: Even with Leonard Fournette leaving with an injury, Grant did not see much action against the Giants. Perhaps that changes if Fournette is forced to miss time, but T.J. Yeldon is the back to add.
report: Corey Grant rushed once for three yards in the Jaguars' Week 1 win over the Giants.

impact: Grant ended up forming a near-even committee with T.J. Yeldon in Leonard Fournette's absence. The Jags worked hard to exploit Grant's play-making ability as a pass catcher. He was a spark plug who picked up a number of key first downs. Despite his big-play ability, Grant will be a low-end RB3/FLEX if Fournette remains sidelined for Week 3 against the Titans.
report: Corey Grant caught 6-of-7 targets for 56 yards in the Jaguars' Week 2 win over the Patriots, adding four rushes for 13 additional yards.

impact: Grant started the game in place of Leonard Fournette (hamstring), but the Jags wound up going with T.J. Yeldon because Grant was so ineffective.  Grant was barely even seen in the second half, while Yeldon finished with 13 touches to Grant's 7.  All in all, it was an abysmal offensive effort from a Jaguars team that played so well versus New England the week prior.  Fournette was close to playing and figures to return in Week 4 against the Jets.
report: Corey Grant rushed six times for 11 yards and caught 1-of-2 targets for a combined loss of one yard in the Jaguars' Week 3 loss to Tennessee.

impact: The Dolphins appear to be using a three-way rotation behind Kenny Stills, with Grant, Albert Wilson, and Danny Amendola vying for targets.  It's a tough situation to bank on from a fantasy football standpoint.
report: Jakeem Grant caught 5-of-7 targets for 38 yards in the Dolphins' Week 1 win over the Titans.

impact: Grant led the Dolphins in Week 1 targets with 7, then took a backseat against the Jets.  He is the No. 4 receiver behind Kenny Stills, Danny Amendola, and Albert Wilson, and DeVante Parker could be activated at any time.
report: Jakeem Grant caught 2-of-4 targets for 37 yards in the Dolphins' Week 2 win over the Jets.

impact: That's maximizing your opportunities. The highlight was a 52-yard score Grant caught from
report: Jakeem Grant caught 2-of-3 targets for 70 yards and two touchdowns in the Dolphins' Week 3 win over the Raiders.

impact: Even with DeVante Parker (quad) sidelined, gadget player Grant was invisible. He has 12 touches through four games. Grant offers rare burst and explosion, but his production will be too scattershot to predict in the Dolphins' low-volume offense.
report: Jakeem Grant caught 2-of-2 targets for 17 yards in the Dolphins' Week 4 loss to the Patriots.

impact: Grant's targets have been in steady decline the last two weeks. He managed a 71-yard punt return touchdown, but he doesn't have much of a role on offense.
report: Jakeem Grant was held without a catch in Week 5 against the Bengals.

impact: Grant was questionable for this game after battling a shoulder injury throughout the week. The injury didn't seem to bother him, though obviously he wasn’t a big factor in this one. Grant won’t be a fantasy option against Detroit in Week 7.
report: Jakeem Grant brought in three-of-four targets for 32 yards Sunday in the Dolphins’ Week 6 win over the Bears.

impact: Grant has just 84 yards receiving over his past four games but will likely be needed for a bigger role in Week 8. Both Albert Wilson and Kenny Stills got banged up against the Lions, and the Dolphins are headed on a short week for Thursday Night Football. Grant is a waiver wire add to keep in mind.
report: Jakeem Grant caught 2-of-2 targets for 32 yards in the Dolphins' Week 7 loss to the Lions.

impact: Grant was limited throughout the week with an Achilles injury, and it seemed to be re-aggravated late into the third quarter Sunday. If it's as serious as a cart usually entails, Grant's season is likely done.
report: Jakeem Grant (Achilles) was carted off the field in Week 10 against the Packers.

impact: He averaged 6.8 yards per carry compared to Kenyan Drake's 3.4 YPC clip.  Gore dominated one first-half drive that resulted in Kenny Stills' ten-yard TD, parlaying three carries into 38 yards on that possession alone.  Gore lacks standalone value behind Drake, but he's going to remain a thorn on Drake's fantasy side.  Gore is worthy of an RB5/6 roster spot in 12-team leagues.
report: Frank Gore rushed nine times for 61 yards in the Dolphins' Week 1 win over the Titans.

impact: He remained the second portion of Miami's RBBC, logging 10 touches to Kenyan Drake's 15.  Gore did handle heavy work in crunchtime as the Fins worked to maintain a fourth-quarter one-score lead.  Gore is a low-upside flex option, but his role is secure.  He should get 8-12 touches in Week 3 versus Oakland.
report: Frank Gore rushed nine times for 25 yards and caught his lone target for a gain of 19 in the Dolphins' Week 2 win over the Jets.

impact: Gore got the "start." That's about all he did as the Dolphins needed just 39 total plays to rip the Raiders. Most of the action came through the air. Gore has been heavily involved through the Dolphins' first three games but has done little to suggest he's going to threaten Kenyan Drake's touch superiority.
report: Frank Gore rushed six times for 12 yards in the Dolphins' Week 3 win over the Raiders.

impact: Gore started and then bizarrely closed out the game with the Dolphins trailing 38-0. That was the score when Gore found the end zone for his first touchdown of the season. The 35-year-old back is on pace for 696 yards from scrimmage as he averages 4.81 yards per carry. With Kenyan Drake clearly not impressing the coaching staff, perhaps Gore might actually force his way into bye week FLEX consideration. We would still steer clear in Week 5 against the Bengals.
report: Frank Gore rushed 11 times for 41 yards in the Dolphins' Week 4 loss to the Patriots, adding two receptions for 16 yards and a touchdown.

impact: Gore started and continued to out-carry Kenyan Drake, who got most of his work in the fourth quarter. He was effective on the ground, but fell out of the gameplan with the Dolphins trailing late. Miami has been committed to using Gore in as the front man in a committee with Drake. He should remain the slight touch favorite for Week 6 against Chicago.
report: Frank Gore rushed 12 times for 63 yards in Week 5 against the Bengals.

impact: Gore, the NFL's oldest running back, is the first player to rush for 100 yards against Chicago this year. Go figure. The veteran brought the hammer in overtime, cruising to 47 yards during the extra period. He broke off a 32-yard run in overtime, which marked his longest rushing play in almost three years. Gore looked gassed after that run and was soon replaced by Kenyan Drake, who proceeded to lose a goal-line fumble. Miami's backfield remained a near even split on Sunday with Drake out-touching Gore 17-16. Those two will continue to work in tandem next week against the Lions.
report: Frank Gore registered 101 yards on 15 carries while turning his lone target into an 18-yard catch Sunday in the Dolphins’ Week 6 victory over the Bears.

impact: Gore out-touched Kenyan Drake 11-10 but got out-gained 87-33. It was Gore's least-productive game since Week 3. Coach Adam Gase has made it clear his backfield usage is not going to change. Gore will be a low-upside RB3 for Week 8's Thursday night game against the Texans.
report: Frank Gore rushed 10 times for 29 yards in the Dolphins' Week 7 loss to the Lions, adding a four-yard reception.

impact: Gore was the focal point of the offense in this game. He saw eight carries in the first quarter, 11 in the first half, and finished the game with 20 of the Dolphins’ 26 carries. He managed just 53 yards on those attempts, but that total was enough for him to pass Barry Sanders on the all-time yards from scrimmage list. It does not make sense for the Dolphins to keep using Gore ahead of Kenyan Drake, but that looks like exactly what will happen. That will keep Gore as a low-upside but high-floor fantasy option in deeper leagues.
report: Frank Gore carried the ball 20 times for 53 yards in the Dolphins' Week 9 win over the Jets.

impact: Gore topped 500 yards rushing for a 14th straight season, putting him atop the record books as the only player to do so. Kenyan Drake (shoulder) was forced to exit for a brief stint in the second quarter, but Gore had out-touched him 10-4 to that point, anyhow. Coach Adam Gase has made it clear he wants to keep Gore involved on early downs, simultaneously (and somehow) keeping Drake featured in the Fins' lackluster passing game. It's ultimately resulted in Gore out-touching Drake 36-17 over the last two games. Gore remains a low-upside usage-based play in deeper leagues until further notice.
report: Frank Gore rushed 13 times for 90 yards, adding two catches for 12 yards in the Dolphins' Week 10 loss to the Packers.

impact: It was a much better second outing for Graham, but he could have had an even bigger fantasy day. He just missed on two deep targets including one in which he was clearly interfered, and he had a touchdown called back on a questionable holding call. He had another chance deep down the field on a free play, but the ball was knocked away. Even so, this was a promising performance for Graham’s rest-of-season outlook. He will be a solid TE1 next week in Washington.
report: Jimmy Graham hauled in 6-of-8 targets for 95 yards in the Packers' Week 2 tie with the Vikings.

impact: The Packers had trouble getting into the red zone thanks to drops and penalties. Hence, a quiet day for Graham. At some points today, Graham looked like he was playing in full armor. He's going to need near-weekly touchdowns to be a true top-eight TE1.
report: Jimmy Graham caught 5-of-7 targets for 45 yards in the Packers' Week 3 loss to the Redskins.

impact: The score was Graham's first in a Packers uniform. Graham was left uncovered on a three-yard rollout. Graham was also the target on Aaron Rodgers' interception, tipping the ball into the air for a pick. Graham is on pace for 64/676/4. With the exception of the touchdown rate increasing, that seems entirely plausible.
report: Jimmy Graham caught 3-of-6 targets for 21 yards and a touchdown in the Packers' Week 4 win over the Bills.

impact: The 11 targets were a new season-high and second on the team to Davante Adams (12).  Graham could have had a much bigger day, as he fell down on an end-zone fade pass at the goal line and then had a 21-yard touchdown go right through his hands later in the second half.  Graham left a lot of plays on the field.  He'll remain a top-four TE1 next week against the Niners.
report: Jimmy Graham caught 6-of-11 targets for 76 yards in the Packers' Week 5 loss to the Lions.

impact: Gordon saw a season-high in snaps after being eased in the last two weeks. He missed a few plays with a shoulder injury in the first half but was cleared to return. Gordon's nine targets led the Patriots, so this is an encouraging game despite the middling stats. Gordon's role should continue to grow as he gets acclimated to OC Josh McDaniels' system.
report: Josh Gordon caught 5-of-9 passes for 42 yards in the Patriots' Week 6 win over the Chiefs.

impact: The Patriots mostly focused on the short passing game early, but Gordon made his presence known with a great 20-yard catch in traffic on the final play of the first quarter. He dropped his second target on a low pass he probably should have worked back to, but he quickly made up for it by going high over a corner for a spectacular catch on fourth down. He was not able to repeat the feat on what would have been an impressive third-down catch in the third quarter, but he again made up for it with a 55-yard catch-and-run which ended just short of the goal line. The Patriots scored two plays later. Gordon now has 16 targets over the last two games, and while Rob Gronkowski is expected to return next week, it looks like he will have a big role moving forward. That makes him an upside WR3 next week in Buffalo.
report: Josh Gordon hauled in 4-of-7 targets for 100 yards in the Patriots' Week 7 win over the Bears.

impact: The Patriots went out of their way to try to attack Tennessee's previously vulnerable secondary, and Gordon delivered a 44-yard gain on their opening drive.  Unfortunately, he wound up losing too many one-on-one battles with Titans CB Adoree Jackson, while New England's offensive line struggled to protect Tom Brady against the Titans' blitzes.  The Patriots now have a Week 11 bye to sort out their offensive issues.  Gordon will remain an every-week WR2 when he comes back from the open date.
report: Josh Gordon managed four catches for 81 yards on 12 targets in the Patriots' Week 10 loss to the Titans.

impact: The Chargers were committed to exploiting the Chiefs' awful inside linebackers with Gordon and Austin Ekeler's receiving. Gordon's receptions matched a career high while the 100-yard day through the air was the first of his career. Whether it was via land or sky, Gordon was looking smooth and powerful, albeit against one of the league's worst defenses. Gordon did serious damage after first contact. Gordon will have a chance to get a hot streak going against the pathetic Bills in Week 2.
report: Melvin Gordon rushed 15 times for 64 yards in the Chargers' Week 1 loss to the Chiefs, adding a ridiculous nine receptions for 102 additional yards.

impact: Gordon did all of his damage in the first half. He went untouched on 20-yard run for his first score before beating the Bills for two red-zone TDs. Gordon was held in check on the ground, but his pass game usage continues to be encouraging. The Chargers rested Gordon most of the fourth quarter after picking up a minor injury. Gordon will remain a locked-in RB1 for Week 3 against the Rams.
report: Melvin Gordon rushed nine times for 28 yards and a touchdown and caught 6-of-7 passes for 38 yards and two touchdowns in the Chargers' Week 2 win over Buffalo.

impact: Gordon was fine on the ground -- 5.3 YPC and had an 11-yard touchdown -- but his receiving volume took an unexpected hit, even with the Chargers trailing for most of the game. Gordon had 15 receptions in his first two games, but only hauled in two passes against the Rams. Chargers coach Anthony Lynn has made it public that he wants to use Gordon as a receiver, so expect his receiving volume to rebound next Sunday against the 49ers. Gordon remains a locked-in RB1.
report: Melvin Gordon rushed 15 times for 80 yards and one touchdown and caught 2-of-4 targets for four yards in the Chargers' Week 3 loss to the Rams.

impact: Gordon broke 100 rushing yards for the first time since Week 8 of 2017, but it's his workload as a receiver that makes Gordon so valuable. Gordon is essentially matching Keenan Allen's receiving production -- they both have 24 receptions on the year -- on top of his rushing stats. Gordon is averaging 118.75 total yards, 1.25 total touchdowns, and six receptions per game with the season 25 percent over. Gordon will be an elite RB1 next Sunday against the Raiders, who are currently getting shredded by Nick Chubb and Carlos Hyde.
report: Melvin Gordon rushed 15 times for 104 yards, and also added seven receptions for 55 yards and a touchdown in the Chargers' Week 4 win over the 49ers.

impact: Gordon's across-the-board usage continued into Sunday as he hauled in all four of his targets for 62 yards. It wasn't pretty, but Gordon also mustered 58 yards rushing on a team-high 19 carries, out-touching teammate Austin Ekeler 23-7 on the day. With the Chargers leading big in the fourth quarter, Los Angeles rested Gordon on the team's final drive. Arguably the club's No. 2 receiver at this time, Gordon's weekly floor makes him as safe as any top option. He's now averaging 14.6 carries, 7.6 targets, and 119 total yards through five games this year. He'll remain an RB1 in Cleveland in Week 6.
report: Melvin Gordon rushed 19 times for 58 yards and one touchdown, adding four catches for 62 yards in the Chargers' week 5 victory over the Raiders.

impact: Gordon started the day with a 4-yard touchdown run on the Chargers' first possession of the game that got the ball rolling and the offense never looked back. He added touchdowns runs of 10 and 11 yards in the second half to bury the game. Gordon is off the best start of his career, rushing for 5.1 yards per carry through six games with nine total touchdowns. Gordon will be a set-and-forget option when the Chargers head to London in Week 7 versus the Titans.
report: Melvin Gordon rushed 18 times for 132 yards with three touchdowns while catching 2-of-4 targets for 18 yards in Sunday's Week 6 win over the Browns.

impact: Gordon steamrolled what had been a stout run defense to the tune of 7.06 yards per carry. Gordon was breaking into the open field on nearly every rush. The hamstring issue that held him out in Week 7 was ancient history. Gordon has now cleared 100 yards from scrimmage in 5-of-7 appearances. He has the sort of matchup dreams are made of in the embarrassing, tanking, given-up-on-the-season Raiders in Week 10.
report: Melvin Gordon rushed 16 times for 113 yards and a touchdown in the Chargers' Week 9 win over the Seahawks, adding a 10-yard reception.

impact: Gordon looked like he might bust in a great spot early in this game, but he started to get things cooking in the second quarter before blowing the game open on the first drive of the second half. After catching a dump off from Philip Rivers, Gordon made two defenders miss and beat everyone else to the end zone for a 66-yard touchdown. He was mostly unstoppable from that point on, and he stacked rushing yardage as the Chargers ran down the clock late. With a great matchup against the Broncos on deck, Gordon will remain a high-end RB1.
report: Melvin Gordon rushed 18 times for 93 yards and hauled in 5-of-6 targets for 72 yards and a touchdown in the Chargers' Week 10 win over the Raiders.

impact: Gordon was mostly stymied in the run game, averaging a meager 3.8 yards per carry on his 18 totes. He excelled as a pass-catcher, however, topping 80 yards receiving for the second time this season. Gordon did his best Beast Mode impression on a spectacular 32-yard catch-and-run during the second quarter, shedding multiple tacklers en route to his biggest gain of the afternoon. Sunday snapped a seven-game touchdown streak for the fourth-year ball-carrier. He'll look to start a new streak next week when the Chargers host Arizona.
report: Melvin Gordon chipped in with 69 yards on 18 carries while also producing six catches for 87 yards on six targets Sunday in Los Angeles’ Week 11 loss to the Broncos.

impact: Goodwin entered the game questionable with a quad injury, but he did not look hampered on the field. His touchdown came when he was left wide open in the third quarter, and Jimmy Garoppolo found him for an 11-yard score. Unfortunately, Garoppolo suffered what appears to be a season-ending injury in the fourth quarter. That is a concern for Goodwin, who broke out with Garoppolo under center late last season, but he also had some big games with C.J. Beathard on the field. He should stick in the WR3 tier.
report: Marquise Goodwin hauled in 3-of-4 targets for 30 yards and a touchdown in the 49ers' Week 3 loss to the Chiefs.
