report: Chris Hogan caught 3-of-5 targets for 42 yards and two touchdowns in the Patriots' Week 2 loss to the Jaguars.

impact: Hogan was invisible on a night Tom Brady threw for only 133 yards. He saw fewer targets than both Rob Gronkowski and Phillip Dorsett. Hogan's ROS outlook is trending down after the Patriots' trade for Josh Gordon. New England also gets Julien Edelman back in Week 5.
report: Chris Hogan caught 3-of-4 passes for 31 yards in Week 3 against the Lions.

impact: Hogan's baffling downward trend continues. Today was the first time all season he drew fewer than four looks. Josh Gordon returned, but he played just 18 snaps. Hogan has not been on the same page with Tom Brady over the middle, and Brady is struggling mightily deep. With Julian Edelman set to return for Week 5, a Hogan breakout will get that much more difficult. Sitting on 8/109/2 for the season, Hogan can't be trusted as a WR4 until he shows something more.
report: Chris Hogan caught 1-of-1 targets for 25 yards in the Patriots' 38-7, Week 4 win over the Dolphins.

impact: Hogan was a non-factor before a 45-yard catch late in the fourth quarter. This ended up being one of his better games, but Hogan is no higher than the No. 4 pass-game option. Hogan shouldn’t be in Week 7 fantasy lineups.
report: Chris Hogan caught four passes for 78 yards in Week 6 against the Chiefs.

impact: Hogan appeared to suffer a leg injury on the opening drive, but he quickly returned to the game. He was not heavily involved early, catching his first pass midway through the second quarter, but he surprisingly notched three quick catches in the third quarter and added a 19-yard grab on a fourth-quarter touchdown drive. He now has two solid games in a row, but it will be tough for him to build on this mini-breakout with Rob Gronkowski expected back next week. That said, it was still a step in the correct direction.
report: Chris Hogan hauled in 6-of-7 targets for 63 yards in the Patriots' Week 7 win over the Bears.

impact: Hogan appeared to suffer a leg injury on the opening drive, but he quickly returned to the game. He was not heavily involved early, catching his first pass midway through the second quarter, but he surprisingly notched three quick catches in the third quarter and added a 19-yard grab on a fourth-quarter touchdown drive. He now has two solid games in a row, but it will be tough for him to build on this mini-breakout with Rob Gronkowski expected back next week. That said, it was still a step in the correct direction.
report: Chris Hogan hauled in 6-of-7 targets for 63 yards in the Patriots' Week 7 win over the Bears.

impact: Hogan also appeared to draw the ire of Tom Brady following an in-game miscue.  Catch-less in back-to-back contests, Hogan can safely be sent to the waiver wire with New England entering its Week 11 bye.
report: Chris Hogan was held catch-less on one target in Week 10 at Tennessee.

impact: He finished second among Indy backs in touches behind Jordan Wilkins (17).  Hines was used heavily on screens and also gained 17 yards on a route where he lined up at wide receiver.  Even when Marlon Mack (hamstring) returns, Hines has a chance to carve out PPR flex value in this catch-first role.  The Colts are playing dink-and-dunk passing offense, and Hines' game suits that style of play.
report: Nyheim Hines rushed five times for 19 yards and caught 7-of-9 targets for 33 yards in the Colts' Week 1 loss to the Bengals.

impact: Hines impressed with a spinning, eight-yard touchdown dash in the second quarter but was a non-factor otherwise. All but two of his touches came in the first half. Hines spent most of the afternoon working behind Jordan Wilkins and Marlon Mack and that will likely be the case again next week against the Eagles. The fourth-round rookie is just a bench stash at this point.
report: Nyheim Hines contributed seven yards and a touchdown on four carries while catching his lone target for a loss of two yards Sunday in the Colts’ Week 2 win over the Redskins.

impact: Hines "led" the Colts backfield in Week 3, but hardly was noteworthy. Through three games, Hines has carried 14 times for 44 yards while catching 13 passes for 56 yards. He is not a fantasy option Week 4 against the Texans.
report: Nyheim Hines rushed five times for 18 yards while catching 5-of-5 targets for 25 yards in Sunday's Week 3 loss to the Eagles.

impact: Hines' 11 targets tied with Chester Rogers for the team lead on a day Andrew Luck uncorked a career-high 62 pass attempts.  With no Jack Doyles (hip) and T.Y. Hilton in and out of the game with chest and hamstring injuries, Hines became Luck's most trustworthy option.  Both of his scores were red-zone successes, from 14 and nine yards out.  The 14-yarder was an incredible leaping catch over the top of Tyrann Mathieu.  With the Colts having zero run game, Hines is essentially the extension of their nonexistent rushing offense.  He needs to be owned in all formats.
report: Nyheim Hines rushed four times for 10 yards and caught 9-of-11 targets for 63 yards and two touchdowns in the Colts' Week 4 loss to the Texans.

impact: Hines dropped an early would-be touchdown on third-and-goal to force a field goal, and he wasn't heard from much after that.  Marlon Mack led the backfield in Week 6 touches and sparked the rushing attack with 89 yards on 12 carries.  In a multi-headed RBBC, Hines is suddenly back in the shaky PPR-flex-option mix.
report: Nyheim Hines rushed three times for 14 yards and caught 2-of-3 targets for 21 yards in the Colts' Week 6 loss to the Jets.

impact: Hines played well when called upon, which wasn't often with Marlon Mack in the midst of a career game. Mack wound up out-touching Hines by a substantial 21-6 margin while also losing the snap battle 38-17. Hines will continue to have a role, especially when Indy is playing from behind, but he's now a distant second to Mack in the Colts' backfield pecking order. The fourth-round rookie gets the Raiders on the road in Week 8.
report: Nyheim Hines tallied 47 yards on five carries while adding one catch for -5 yards on two targets Sunday in the Colts’ Week 7 victory over the Bills.

impact: Hines played well when called upon, which wasn't often with Marlon Mack in the midst of a career game. Mack wound up out-touching Hines by a substantial 21-6 margin while also losing the snap battle 38-17. Hines will continue to have a role, especially when Indy is playing from behind, but he's now a distant second to Mack in the Colts' backfield pecking order. The fourth-round rookie gets the Raiders on the road in Week 8.
report: Nyheim Hines tallied 47 yards on five carries while adding one catch for -5 yards on two targets Sunday in the Colts’ Week 7 victory over the Bills.

impact: The Colts have been among the league's pass-heaviest teams this year but they abandoned that strategy against the Raiders, running it 40 times while attempting just 31 passes. Marlon Mack handled the lead role but Hines performed well in a change-of-pace capacity, setting a career-high with 78 rushing yards in the win. Hines benefited from positive game script Sunday against a one-win Raiders team, but that's not something he can count on every week. The Colts get Jacksonville at home after their bye.
report: Nyheim Hines rushed for 78 yards on 11 carries while adding two catches for seven yards on two targets Sunday in the Colts’ Week 8 victory over the Raiders.

impact: This game did not set up well for Hines as the Colts jumped out to an early lead, but he still did not take advantage of his opportunities. As well as averaging one yard per carry, Hines dropped what would have been a long gain in the third quarter. Hines should have better days -- he ran for 78 yards on 11 carries before the bye -- but he is not a must-hold in shallower leagues.
report: Nyheim Hines rushed three times for three yards and hauled in 3-of-4 targets for 19 yards in the Colts' Week 10 win over the Jaguars.

impact: The Colts won going away, but it was a rough game for the rookie change-of-pace back. He committed a brutal drop and later put the ball on the ground. Thankfully, the Colts managed to recover. Hines has failed to provide PPR FLEX value since Marlon Mack got rolling, though the Dolphins will be an appetizing Week 12 matchup.
report: Nyheim Hines rushed five times for 14 yards in the Colts' Week 11 win over the Titans, adding a 20-yard reception.

impact: Hilton was injured after a 40-yard catch on the opening series.  He was quickly escorted to the locker room where X-rays presumably showed no damage.  Hilton returned with a little less than two minutes left in the first quarter.
report: T.Y. Hilton (chest) returned to Week 4 against the Texans.

impact: This was Hilton's first game back after missing the previous two weeks with hamstring and chest injuries. CBS analyst Adam Archuleta may have put it best when he said Tre'Davious White was on Hilton like a pair of skinny jeans. Despite the tough matchup, Hilton still gave fantasy owners a lift with his two touchdowns including a five-yarder with time winding down in the second quarter. His other touchdown was even shorter, coming on a one-yard strike from Andrew Luck with Indy up big in the fourth quarter. Sunday marked the 28-year-old's first multi-touchdown game since Week 9 of last season. Hilton will try to keep the train rolling next week against a leaky Raiders secondary.
report: T.Y. Hilton contributed four catches for 25 yards and two touchdowns on four targets Sunday in the Colts’ Week 7 victory over the Bills.

impact: This was Hilton's first game back after missing the previous two weeks with hamstring and chest injuries. CBS analyst Adam Archuleta may have put it best when he said Tre'Davious White was on Hilton like a pair of skinny jeans. Despite the tough matchup, Hilton still gave fantasy owners a lift with his two touchdowns including a five-yarder with time winding down in the second quarter. His other touchdown was even shorter, coming on a one-yard strike from Andrew Luck with Indy up big in the fourth quarter. Sunday marked the 28-year-old's first multi-touchdown game since Week 9 of last season. Hilton will try to keep the train rolling next week against a leaky Raiders secondary.
report: T.Y. Hilton contributed four catches for 25 yards and two touchdowns on four targets Sunday in the Colts’ Week 7 victory over the Bills.

impact: He took a goose egg into the fourth quarter before finally coming up with his first catch. Hilton has largely been a non-factor since coming back from a hamstring injury, managing just five grabs for 59 yards over his last two outings, though he did find the end zone twice in last week's victory over Buffalo. Hilton will face the struggling Jaguars at home when the Colts return from their upcoming bye week.
report: T.Y. Hilton was held to one catch for 34 yards on five targets Sunday in the Colts’ Week 8 win over the Raiders.

impact: Hilton did not have much to do early with the Colts’ tight ends dominating, but he did get wide open for a 35-yard catch in the first quarter. That was basically it for Hilton for most of the game, but he showed back up when it mattered most. With the Colts clinging to a three-point lead, Hilton again got wide open for another 35-yard gain to help run down more clock. He should have an easier time next week against the Titans.
report: T.Y. Hilton hauled in 3-of-7 targets for 77 yards in the Colts' Week 10 win over the Jaguars.

impact: Hilton entered the afternoon with just eight catches in three games since returning from his hamstring injury but proceeded to go bonkers for his biggest game of the season despite a tough matchup with Adoree' Jackson. The highlight was Hilton's 68-yard touchdown in the second quarter. Hilton got a step on Jackson and Andrew Luck delivered a perfect deep ball in stride. Hilton's second score was "only" 14 yards but was nearly as impressive thanks to some fancy sideline footwork. Hilton will have a chance to get a hot streak going in a mouthwatering Week 12 home matchup with the Dolphins.
report: T.Y. Hilton caught 9-of-9 targets for 155 yards and two touchdowns in the Colts' Week 11 demolition of the Titans.

impact: Hill also rushed twice for four yards. It was a completely ridiculous performance, with Hill's punt return score the Chiefs' first touch of the season. He added a 58-yard receiving touchdown just seven minutes later. Hill's second passing strike was a one-yard shovel from Patrick Mahomes. There was a scary moment in the first quarter when Hill was evaluated for both a concussion and shoulder injury after an awkward landing, but he was cleared to remain in the game. The dream chemistry Hill displayed with Mahomes in the preseason carried over against the Chargers' (supposedly) elite defense. Hill gets the Steelers in Week 2.
report: Tyreek Hill caught 7-of-8 targets for 169 yards and a pair of touchdowns in the Chiefs' Week 1 win over the Chargers, adding a 91-yard punt return score.

impact: Hill wasn't even targeted in the first half, so 5/90/1 was quite an accomplishment, even if that's quiet by Hill's standards. Hill's score was a 29-yarder where he got several steps on Artie Burns down the left sideline. Hill will try to torment the 49ers in the Chiefs' Week 3 home opener.
report: Tyreek Hill caught 5-of-6 targets for 90 yards and a touchdown in the Chiefs' Week 2 win over the Steelers.

impact: With Patrick Mahomes spreading the ball around, Hill did not have a blow-up game, but he still made his presence known by going up high to reel in a 42-yard catch in the second quarter. He also should have had a 49-yard touchdown, but Mahomes just underthrew him, allowing the defender to catch up. Hill will have some down games, but his upside is as high as any receiver in the league. He will remain a locked-in WR1 next week against the Broncos.
report: Tyreek Hill hauled in 2-of-5 targets for 51 yards in the Chiefs' Week 3 win over the 49ers.

impact: He "added" two yards on one carry.  The Broncos did a really good job of containing Hill, but Travis Kelce and Kareem Hunt were able to pick up the slack, combining for 253 yards and a couple scores.  Hill has had a quiet last two games with no touchdowns and will be a WR2 next week vs. Jacksonville.
report: Tyreek Hill caught 9-of-13 targets for 54 yards in the Chiefs' Week 4 win over the Broncos.

impact: Jalen Ramsey's shadow should be Hill's toughest test of the season, but that did not stop him from making big plays. He opened the game with a 40-yard run on Kansas City's first offensive play, although it was reduced to 21 yards because of a penalty. He added a 36-yard catch in the third quarter on a great throw by Patrick Mahomes. Always a threat for a big play, Hill should have a much easier time next week in New England.
report: Tyreek Hill hauled in 4-of-7 targets for 61 yards and rushed twice for 26 yards in the Chiefs' Week 5 win over the Jaguars.

impact: Even the huge stats don't do justice to how good of a night Hill had. Hill’s first two touchdowns came in the red-zone, and he smoked the Patriots on a blown assignment for a 75-yard TD to tie the game with under four minutes. Hill got most of his yardage on chunk plays, but his speed was too much for New England's zone schemes. It’s a needed breakout for Hill after he'd been held to 166 scoreless yards over the last three games. Hill is in a great spot against the Bengals in another Sunday night matchup next week.
report: Tyreek Hill caught 7-of-12 targets for 142 yards and three touchdowns in the Chiefs' Week 6 loss to the Patriots.

impact: Hill was featured heavily but didn’t break any huge plays. He should've had a 35-yard touchdown but dropped a wide open pass in the end-zone. Hill made up for it a few plays later with a goal-line TD. He's now scored touchdowns in consecutive games after a three-week scoring drought. Hill has a matchup with the Broncos in Week 8.
report: Tyreek Hill caught 7-of-10 passes for 68 yards and a touchdown in Week 7 against the Bengals.

impact: Hill was featured heavily but didn’t break any huge plays. He should've had a 35-yard touchdown but dropped a wide open pass in the end-zone. Hill made up for it a few plays later with a goal-line TD. He's now scored touchdowns in consecutive games after a three-week scoring drought. Hill has a matchup with the Broncos in Week 8.
report: Tyreek Hill caught 7-of-10 passes for 68 yards and a touchdown in Week 7 against the Bengals.

impact: Most of his output came on a 40-yard catch-and-run during the second quarter. Aside from that highlight, it was a quiet week for Hill, who mostly took a backseat to teammates Sammy Watkins (8-107-2) and Travis Kelce (6-79-1). Hill left the game with a groin injury during the fourth quarter and didn't return. There wasn't much time left, so maybe the Chiefs were just playing it safe with their star receiver. Obviously his health will be something fantasy owners need to monitor ahead of next week's game at Cleveland.
report: Tyreek Hill absorbed three-of-four targets for 70 yards Sunday in KC’s Week 8 win over the Broncos.

impact: After dealing with a groin injury throughout the week, Hill was largely quiet outside of a 40-yard reception in the first half. Hill now has 70-yards or fewer in six of his past seven games. Next week, Hill heads home, where he has averaged 62.5 yards per game over four games. Despite his dip in yardage and home splits, Hill is still a locked-in starting wide receiver option in Week 10 against the Cardinals.
report: Tyreek Hill caught 4-of-5 targets for 69 yards in Sunday's Week 9 win over the Browns.

impact: He also had a 20-yard run. Hill was forced touches with Sammy Watkins sidelined, going for 75 yards on Kansas City's opening drive. He later added a 14-yard score, but wasn't needed much after that. It's a nice rebound for Hill after getting held to 69 scoreless yards last week. With Watkins not a lock to return in Week 11, Hill will be a top-10 receiver play against the Rams.
report: Tyreek Hill caught 7-of-10 targets for 117 yards and two touchdowns in Week 10 against the Cardinals.

impact: Gerald Everett also got his first catch of the season in this one, taking a late target 17 yards. Despite Sean McVay's history, the tight end position has simply not been a focal point of the Rams' passing game. Neither player is worth rostering in redraft formats.
report: Tyler Higbee hauled in 1-of-2 targets for three yards and a touchdown in the Rams' Week 2 win over the Cardinals.

impact: The Rams other tight end Gerald Everett also had two targets against the Chargers. Higbee found the end zone last week against the Cardinals, but he's not worthy of a roster spot with just four targets on the year. Sean McVay will continue to ride Gurley, Cooks, Woods, and Kupp.
report: Tyler Higbee caught both of his targets for 35 yards in the Rams' Week 3 win over the Chargers.

impact: One of Higbee's catches bounced off Cooper Kupp and into his hands for a 17-yard gain. He added another grab in the second quarter, but Gerald Everett was the tight end of choice in the second half. Normally the Rams do not heavily utilize Higbee's position, but that could change with both Brandin Cooks and Kupp dealing with concussions. Even so, Higbee is not even a good desperation option in standard formats.
report: Tyler Higbee hauled in 2-of-4 targets for 26 yards in the Rams' Week 5 win over the Seahawks.

impact: One of Higbee's catches bounced off Cooper Kupp and into his hands for a 17-yard gain. He added another grab in the second quarter, but Gerald Everett was the tight end of choice in the second half. Normally the Rams do not heavily utilize Higbee's position, but that could change with both Brandin Cooks and Kupp dealing with concussions. Even so, Higbee is not even a good desperation option in standard formats.
report: Tyler Higbee hauled in 2-of-4 targets for 26 yards in the Rams' Week 5 win over the Seahawks.

impact: Higbee is not usually a big part of the offense, but he opened this game with a big 33-yard gain to help set up the Rams’ first touchdown. He almost came up with another big play on the opening drive of the second half, but he dropped what should have been a touchdown. Despite the solid outing, Higbee is not a fantasy option.
report: Tyler Higbee caught 2-of-4 targets for 40 yards in the Rams' Week 9 loss to the Saints.

impact: Higbee has suddenly cleared three targets and 25 yards in back-to-back games. It might actually remain a theme if Cooper Kupp (knee) is facing an extended absence. Higbee will have dart throw TE2 appeal for Week 11 against the Chiefs.
report: Tyler Higbee caught 3-of-3 targets for 25 yards and a touchdown in the Rams' Week 10 win over the Seahawks.

impact: Higgins led Cleveland in receiving yards in a game where Baker Mayfield spread the ball around.  David Njoku's five catches led the team.  Higgins has a secure role in three-receiver sets alongside Jarvis Landry and Antonio Callaway but lacks fantasy value outside of Dynasty leagues.
report: Rashard Higgins caught 4-of-5 targets for 61 yards in the Browns' Week 4 loss to the Raiders.

impact: Higgins was absent since Week 5 as he dealt with a knee injury. Five players received more targets than Higgins in his return. He is not a fantasy option in Week 10 against the Falcons.
report: Rashard Higgins caught 3-of-4 targets for 19 yards in Sunday's Week 9 loss to the Chiefs.

impact: Heuerman was hardly heard from despite the Broncos teeing up a season-high 51 pass attempts, which is concerning for Heuerman's streamer viability going forward.  He will be a low-end TE2 in Week 6 against the Rams.
report: Jeff Heuerman caught 2-of-4 targets for 18 yards in the Broncos' Week 5 loss.

impact: The yards were Heuerman's second most of the season. He's done little to suggest he will be anything more than a last-gasp TE2 in fantasy leagues.
report: Jeff Heuerman caught 3-of-6 targets for 23 yards in the Broncos' Week 6 loss to the Rams.

impact: Heuerman was the recipient of a four-yard touchdown early in the fourth quarter, though he and Case Keenum were rarely on the same page. The end-zone visit was Heuerman's first since Week 15 of last season and only the third of his career. Even as a contrarian DFS punt play, using Heuerman would probably be a stretch. The fourth-year tight end faces Houston in Week 9.
report: Jeff Heuerman netted one grab for four yards and a touchdown on five targets Sunday in Denver’s Week 8 loss to Kansas City.

impact: In Denver's first game without Demaryius Thomas, it was unexpectedly Heuerman who led the team across the board in targets, catches, and receiving yards. He was hogging red zone usage all along, leading the team in targets inside the 10-yard line (7) prior to Sunday, but he was averaging just 3.8 targets on the year. His 11 looks Sunday were a season high. Given the landscape and desecration at his position, Heuerman is a viable season-long flier just in case this amount of volume unexpectedly continues to be thrown his way.
report: Jeff Heuerman hauled in 10 catches for 83 yards and one score on a team-high 11 targets in the Broncos' Week 9 defeat to the Texans.

impact: Playing for the first time since his 10-catch, 83-yard breakout in Week 9, Heuerman mostly disappointed, managing a long gain of just six yards. He also committed a head-scratching drop in the fourth quarter, though luckily it didn't cost the Broncos, who stole a 23-22 win on a last-second field goal by Brandon McManus. The 25-year-old won't be an appealing streamer when the Steelers come to town for Week 12.
report: Jeff Heuerman came down with four catches for 20 yards on five targets Sunday in the Broncos’ Week 11 win over the Chargers.

impact: Henry got eight touches before Dion Lewis even touched the ball at all, but the Titans switched gears thereafter.  Lewis wound up out-touching Henry by a whopping 21 to 3 margin from that point on.  Henry's lack of effectiveness is a major concern in a competitive situation where he must perform to earn carries over his counterpart.  Henry did have a long touchdown run negated by a Delanie Walker holding penalty.  Nevertheless, Henry can only be viewed as a TD-or-bust flex option for Week 2 against the Texans.
report: Derrick Henry rushed ten times for 26 yards and caught his lone target for five yards in the Titans' Week 1 loss to Miami.

impact: It was a tremendous game script for Henry, who will typically be called upon to ice games when the Titans are trying to secure a lead. He out-carried Dion Lewis 18-14, but both struggled mightily for breathing room without starting tackles Jack Conklin and Taylor Lewan available. Henry merely averaged 3.1 YPC, slightly better than Lewis' 3.0 Sunday. With only one target under his belt through two weeks of play, Henry (albeit immensely talented and an able receiver out of Tennessee's backfield) can't be considered anything more than a touchdown-dependent RB4 until further notice.
report: Derrick Henry rushed 18 times for 56 yards in the Titans' Week 2 win over the Texans.

impact: He was targeted once and didn't catch it.  Henry did out-touch Dion Lewis 18 to 12, but he remains scoreless on the year and has no passing-game role.  Henry will remain a touchdown-or-bust flex option in Week 4 against the Eagles.
report: Derrick Henry rushed 18 times for 57 yards in the Titans' Week 3 win over the Jaguars.

impact: Henry opened the day on a positive note with a 13-yard catch and a 14-yard run, but that was about it for the struggling running back. He did have a nice eight-yard run in overtime, but he played far fewer snaps than Dion Lewis in a game the Titans were trailing throughout the second half. On the bright side, Marcus Mariota looked healthy in this one, which should open up the running game and create more scoring opportunities. Henry will be an interesting DFS play in a bounce-back spot next week against the Bills.
report: Derrick Henry rushed eight times for 24 yards and caught two passes for seven yards in the Titans' Week 4 win over the Eagles.

impact: Dion Lewis out-touched him 15 to 11.  Henry drew just one target and missed it, and he is averaging one target per game five weeks in.  He is also scoreless on the year.  Henry will be a poor flex option in Week 6 versus Baltimore.
report: Derrick Henry rushed 11 times for 56 yards in the Titans' Week 5 loss to Buffalo.

impact: The only positive to takeaway is that Henry out-carried teammate Dion Lewis 7-5. He still averaged just 3.0 YPC on the day and has seen one target per game this season. As a touchdown-dependent back who hasn't scored a touchdown, he's droppable if a roster spot is needed.
report: Derrick Henry rushed seven times for 21 yards and caught his only target for five yards in the Titans' dreadful Week 6 loss to the Ravens.

impact: This was one of the better games of the season for Henry. He saw fewer touches than Dion Lewis but converted a goal-line carry for his touchdown. Henry added 30 yards on two catches and looked good when the Titans got him in open space. With Marcus Mariota getting closer to full health, Henry's ROS value is slightly trending up.
report: Derrick Henry had 12 carries for 33 yards and a touchdown in Week 7 against the Chargers.

impact: This was one of the better games of the season for Henry. He saw fewer touches than Dion Lewis but converted a goal-line carry for his touchdown. Henry added 30 yards on two catches and looked good when the Titans got him in open space. With Marcus Mariota getting closer to full health, Henry's ROS value is slightly trending up.
report: Derrick Henry had 12 carries for 33 yards and a touchdown in Week 7 against the Chargers.

impact: He also caught both of his targets for five yards, his seventh and eighth catches of the season.  The six carries marked a new season-low, as Dion Lewis set a new season-high with his 19 and 23 touches in total.  Lewis has flipped the script the past few weeks and taken over as the No. 1 back by a wide margin.  Henry has scored touchdowns in back-to-back games, but it's clear he's now nothing more than a short-yardage guy.  Henry is a bottom-barrel RB3/4.
report: Derrick Henry rushed six times for 27 yards and one touchdown in the Titans' Week 9 win over the Cowboys.

impact: Scoreless for nearly the entire first half of the season, Henry's TDs are now coming in bunches with four over his last three games.  He hit pay dirt on a goal-line score late in the first half, then danced in from a Wildcat formation in the fourth before icing the game with multiple clock-killing runs.  Henry was still out-touched by Dion Lewis 22 to 11 and has no passing-game role.  Henry will remain a touchdown-or-bust flex option when the Titans visit Indianapolis next.
report: Derrick Henry rushed 11 times for 58 yards and two touchdowns in the Titans' Week 10 rout of the Patriots.

impact: Most of Henry's yardage came in the second half of a non-competitive game. The Titans' offense was completely off the rails today, especially once Marcus Mariota departed with an elbow injury. With only two teams on bye for Week 12, Henry will be a last-gasp FLEX option against the Texans.
report: Derrick Henry rushed nine times for 46 yards in the Titans' Week 11 loss to the Colts.

impact: Bryant was mostly invisible except for a fourth quarter end zone target that resulted in Derek Carr's second interception of the day. Bryant was completely blanketed by Xavien Howard. It was an ill-advised throw. Despite his well-known upside, Bryant has given zero indication through two games he will be usable in fantasy leagues as a Raider.
report: Martavis Bryant caught 2-of-5 targets for 30 yards in the Raiders' Week 3 loss to the Dolphins.

impact: Bryant dropped two passes -- including one that would have gone for a touchdown bomb after he got clean behind Cleveland's secondary -- but did contribute positively with a downfield run block on Marshawn Lynch's 59-yard dash.  Oakland's situational deep threat and third receiver behind Amari Cooper and Jordy Nelson, Bryant will be a low-floor WR4/flex option in Week 5 against the Chargers.
report: Martavis Bryant caught 3-of-7 targets for 51 yards in the Raiders' Week 4 win over the Browns.

impact: In just his fourth game with the team, Bryant led the Raiders with 91 receiving yards. A majority of his production admittedly came in the fourth quarter with his team trailing late. Bryant has stayed involved as an over-the-top burner, though, averaging an outstanding 16.8 yards per catch. If involved more down the road, you don't have to squint to spot a legitimate path in which he overtakes Cooper as the team's No. 1 receiver. He's on a FLEX-deemable pace of 45-757 this season.
report: Martavis Bryant hauled in all three of his targets for a team-high 91 yards in the Raiders' Week 5 loss to the Chargers.

impact: Bryant has struggled with drops and turnovers this season, and he failed to capitalize on Seth Roberts (concussion) and Amari Cooper's (concussion) early Week 6 exits.  A situational deep threat on a team whose quarterback doesn't enjoy pulling the trigger to go deep, Bryant is all but worthless in fantasy leagues.
report: Martavis Bryant caught 2-of-3 targets for 18 yards in the Raiders' Week 6 loss to Seattle.

impact: Burton had caught just five passes for 35 yards through two weeks, so this could be considered an explosion by the marks he set through the first two weeks. Through three weeks, Burton has just nine catches for 90 yards and a touchdown as Mitchell Trubisky has struggled to generate little tangible production for the pass catchers in this offense. Despite his down production, Burton will still be in the TE1 mix at a dreadful fantasy position Week 4 when the Bears host the Buccaneers.
report: Trey Burton caught 4-of-5 passes for 55 yards in Sunday's Week 3 win over the Cardinals.

impact: After plodding through subpar performances during Chicago's first three games, Burton went as Mitchell Trubisky went, corralling one of the second-year pro's career-high six touchdowns on the day. To this point, Burton had merely posted a season-high of 55 yards and had yet to get into the end zone. Burton's lone touchdown on the day admittedly occurred during a complete breakdown in the Bucs' hapless secondary. It won't always be this easy for the Bears' offense, but it was good to see Burton finally get off the schneid and flash the rapport he showed with Trubisky in the preseason. He'll remain a low-end TE1 moving forward given the position's dreadful drop-off from years past.
report: Trey Burton hauled in 2-of-4 passes for 86 yards and one score in Sunday's Week 4 win over the Bucs.

impact: It was a quiet afternoon for Burton, though he salvaged the day somewhat by turning a Mitchell Trubisky shovel pass into a nine-yard touchdown during the third quarter. Burton has now scored in three of his last four games while catching 14-of-17 targets (82.4 percent) during that span. The 26-year-old will remain a borderline TE1 when he faces the Patriots in Week 7. Burton was involved in one of the most iconic plays in NFL history—the Philly Special—the last time he squared off against New England in Super Bowl LII.
report: Trey Burton handled all four of his targets for 23 yards and a touchdown Sunday in Chicago’s Week 6 loss to Miami.

impact: Burton was the only player Mitchell Trubisky could trust early in this game. He was the target on four of the quarterback’s eight first-half completions including a fourth-down conversion on a second-quarter touchdown drive. He kept it going after the break, catching five more passes for another 70 yards and a late touchdown. Although he has scored in four of the last five games, this was easily Burton’s best outing of the season, and he did it with Tarik Cohen the only other player making plays in the passing game. He will remain a back-end TE1 next week against the Jets.
report: Trey Burton hauled in 9-of-11 targets for 126 yards and a touchdown in the Bears' Week 7 loss to the Patriots.

impact: Burton was the only player Mitchell Trubisky could trust early in this game. He was the target on four of the quarterback’s eight first-half completions including a fourth-down conversion on a second-quarter touchdown drive. He kept it going after the break, catching five more passes for another 70 yards and a late touchdown. Although he has scored in four of the last five games, this was easily Burton’s best outing of the season, and he did it with Tarik Cohen the only other player making plays in the passing game. He will remain a back-end TE1 next week against the Jets.
report: Trey Burton hauled in 9-of-11 targets for 126 yards and a touchdown in the Bears' Week 7 loss to the Patriots.

impact: It's a letdown game for Burton, who saw fewer targets than Anthony Miller and Taylor Gabriel. Burton got all of his yards on one catch, with his other receptions coming at the line of scrimmage. Burton had at least 50 yards or a touchdown in five straight games going into Sunday. He has a rebound matchup with Buffalo in Week 9.
report: Trey Burton caught 3-of-4 targets for 18 yards in Week 8 against the Jets.

impact: Mitchell Trubisky needed to complete only 12 passes in Sunday's easy win, so no individual Chicago pass catcher so much as reached 50 yards.  Burton was lucky to escape with a fourth-quarter touchdown deep in garbage time.  Expect Burton to see more targets when the Bears host the Lions next.
report: Trey Burton caught 2-of-3 targets for 28 yards and a touchdown in the Bears' Week 9 win over the Bills.

impact: Burton did what was asked of him on a day where the Bears received giant contributions from both Allen Robinson (6-133-2) and Anthony Miller (5-122-1). The 27-year-old has mostly been held in check since his breakout Week 7 against New England (9-126-1), averaging a lethargic 28.7 yards with one touchdown over his last three games. Despite his lack of recent contributions, Burton will still be worthy of TE1 consideration next week when the Bears do battle with Minnesota on Sunday Night Football.
report: Trey Burton chipped in with four catches for 40 yards on four targets Sunday in the Bears’ Week 10 win over Detroit.

impact: Burkhead was targeted just three times in the passing game but was the Patriots' clear-cut lead rusher, especially after Jeremy Hill departed early in the third quarter with a knee injury. Whether that remains the case for Week 2 will depend on Sony Michel's (knee) health. Going up against the Jaguars next week, Burkhead could be featured more as a pass catcher against an elite defense where the Pats will need to counteract the rush.
report: Rex Burkhead rushed 18 times for 64 yards in the Patriots' Week 1 win over the Texans, adding a five-yard reception.

impact: Burkhead wasn't targeted in the passing game. Bafflingly, Burkhead "started" but then touched the ball zero times in the second or third quarter. Sony Michel was the only show in town on early downs with James White taking the lead in passing situations. It's possible Burkhead's multiple recent injuries played a part. Through two games, Burkhead has touched the ball just 25 times, with 19 of those coming in Week 1. With Michel healthy, Burkhead's RB2 status is up in the air. The Pats play the Lions in Week 3. The Lions have gotten mauled by pass-catching running backs early on.
report: Rex Burkhead rushed six times for 22 yards in the Patriots' Week 2 loss to the Jaguars.

impact: Todd Gurley was dealing with cramps, so Brown got all the work in the fourth quarter. He played well and seems like he would be a reliable starter if something were to happen to Gurley. The Rams also have rookie John Kelly, who has been inactive the first two weeks.
report: Malcolm Brown rushed 12 times for 46 yards in the Rams' Week 2 win over the Cardinals.

impact: Rookie John Kelly was a healthy scratch for the third straight week meaning Malcolm Brown is the handcuff to Todd Gurley. With Gurley healthy, Brown is solely a change-of-pace back for the Rams, and he can't be started in fantasy.
report: Malcolm Brown rushed five times for 42 yards in the Rams' Week 3 win over the Chargers.

impact: Rookie John Kelly was a healthy scratch for the third straight week meaning Malcolm Brown is the handcuff to Todd Gurley. With Gurley healthy, Brown is solely a change-of-pace back for the Rams, and he can't be started in fantasy.
report: Malcolm Brown rushed five times for 42 yards in the Rams' Week 3 win over the Chargers.

impact: Brown does not get many touches behind Todd Gurley, but he has been effective when given a shot this year. He was even better than that on the first drive of the second half. After making a catch in the flat, Brown somehow avoided a tackler, acrobatically tip-toed down the sideline, and went in for an 18-yard score. Brown remains the best handcuff in the game, and he could get a start or two late in the year if the Rams lock things up early
report: Malcolm Brown turned his only target into an 18-yard touchdown in the Rams' Week 9 loss to the Saints.

impact: Brown was the No. 2 option behind Michael Crabtree. He got open in the red-zone for his touchdown, scoring from seven yards out. Brown was talked up all training camp and looks to have a good rapport with Joe Flacco. He's on the WR4 radar for a Week 2 matchup with the Bengals.
report: John Brown caught 3-of-4 targets for 44 yards and a touchdown in Week 1 against Buffalo.

impact: He finished with one fewer target than Michael Crabtree, but he easily led the team in receiving yardage on a day which could have been bigger. Brown just missed a couple long catches down the sideline in the first half before Joe Flacco hit him with a beautiful pass for a 44-yard gain in the second quarter. At worst the 1B receiver in a quietly solid passing attack, Brown will be an upside WR3 next week against the Steelers.
report: John Brown hauled in 5-of-9 targets for 86 yards in the Ravens' Week 3 win over the Broncos.

impact: Brown led the Ravens in targets on Sunday, but failed to turn all of those looks into much as he and Flacco were not on the same page frequently. Brown's long gain of the day was a 28-yard catch and run, giving him a 25-yard plus reception in all five games this season. Brown has established himself as the Ravens' best playmaker through five weeks and will enter Week 6 as a WR2 option against the Titans.
report: John Brown caught 5-of-14 passes for 58 yards in Sunday's Week 5 loss to the Browns.

impact: Brown's two-catch day wouldn't have been so bad had he not seen 14 targets just last week. Instead it was Michael Crabtree (6/93/1) who finally broke out, with Willie Snead (7/60) quietly leading all in targets (10) and catches (7). There are better days on the horizon for Brown, who's still the team's primary deep threat and second on the Ravens with a 17% target share. Consider both he and Crabtree simultaneous WR2's against New Orleans' porous secondary in Week 7.
report: John Brown hauled in 2-of-3 targets for 28 yards in the Ravens' Week 6 win over the Titans.

impact: Coming off back-to-back quiet games, Brown set new season highs in catches and yards. 56 of his yards came on a dig route where Brown was allowed to run free. He got tackled at the two-yard line. Despite the big day, Brown did get out-targeted by Michael Crabtree. Brown's big-play volatility keeps him on the WR2/3 borderline. The Panthers are on deck for Week 8.
report: John Brown caught 7-of-7 targets for 134 yards and a touchdown in the Ravens' Week 7 loss to the Saints.

impact: Coming off back-to-back quiet games, Brown set new season highs in catches and yards. 56 of his yards came on a dig route where Brown was allowed to run free. He got tackled at the two-yard line. Despite the big day, Brown did get out-targeted by Michael Crabtree. Brown's big-play volatility keeps him on the WR2/3 borderline. The Panthers are on deck for Week 8.
report: John Brown caught 7-of-7 targets for 134 yards and a touchdown in the Ravens' Week 7 loss to the Saints.

impact: It was a big step back from Brown after going 7-134-1 last week against the Saints.  He's sandwiched that day with a pair of 28-yard games.  Brown gets the Steelers in Week 9, who he went 3-116-1 against in Week 4.
report: John Brown caught 3-of-7 targets for 28 yards in the Ravens' Week 8 loss to the Panthers.

impact: Brown balled out when these teams squared off back in Week 4 (3-116-1) but a repeat effort wasn't in the cards. He didn't break off any big plays, managing a long gain of just six yards. His largest contribution came in the second quarter when he drew a 33-yard pass interference flag on safety Terrell Edmunds. This won't go down as one of Brown's better weeks, though by now, fantasy owners should be well-aware of his boom-or-bust tendencies. The struggling Ravens—losers of three straight—will have the bye week to figure things out.
report: John Brown managed only three catches for 17 yards on six targets Sunday in Baltimore’s Week 9 loss to Pittsburgh.

impact: Regardless of matchups, Brown is going to be extremely volatile with low floors going forward.  The Ravens completed only 13 passes for 150 yards with Lamar Jackson at quarterback, and Jackson is expected to start again in Week 12.
report: John Brown caught his lone target for 23 yards in the Ravens' Week 11 win over Cincinnati.

impact: Brown had a lackluster start, catching just two passes for 14 yards in the first half against a very strong performance versus rookie Denzel Ward. In the second half, Brown got going, catching a 22-yard touchdown strike in blanket coverage from Ward that out the Steelers up 21-7 in the 3rd quarter. Brown remains the premier fantasy wideout and will be the consensus WR1 next week at home versus the Chiefs.
report: Steelers WR Antonio Brown caught 9-of-16 targets for 93 yards and touchdown in Sunday's Week 1 game versus the Browns.

impact: Although he was never officially announced with an injury, Brown spent most of the second half gutting through a right calf issue. It was his calf that bothered him late last season. Brown was slowed in the summer by a quad ailment. Brown was spotted bickering with coaches multiple times on the sideline. It was a frustrating day despite the monster usage. JuJu Smith-Schuster and the Steelers' tight ends were getting the end zone looks. Brown gets the Bucs' burnable secondary in Week 3.
report: Antonio Brown caught 9-of-17 targets for 67 yards in the Steelers' Week 2 loss to the Chiefs.

impact: Ben Roethlisberger was forcing the ball to his No. 1 receiver in the first half, but Brown entered the break just 2-of-8 for 15 yards. The duo finally got in sync in the second half, with the highlight being Brown's 47-yard score down the left sideline. Brown soundly beat Robert Alford and Roethlisberger hit him in stride. It was off to the races after that. The 100-yard game was Brown's first of the season. He will have a shot at getting a hot streak going against the Bengals in Week 6.
report: Antonio Brown caught 6-of-13 targets for 101 yards and two touchdowns in the Steelers' Week 5 win over the Falcons.

impact: Brown was quiet most of the day before going 49 yards on a second-half catch-and-run for his longest play of the season to date.  He then scored from 31 yards out with 10 seconds left and the Steelers trailing by one point.  The six targets were third on the team behind JuJu Smith-Schuster (10) and Vance McDonald (8).  The Steelers are entering their bye week and will host the Browns in Week 8.  Brown went 9-93-1 on 16 targets versus Cleveland in Week 1.
report: Antonio Brown caught 5-of-6 targets for 105 yards and one touchdown in the Steelers' 28-21, Week 6 win over the Bengals.

impact: Brown was quiet most of the day before going 49 yards on a second-half catch-and-run for his longest play of the season to date.  He then scored from 31 yards out with 10 seconds left and the Steelers trailing by one point.  The six targets were third on the team behind JuJu Smith-Schuster (10) and Vance McDonald (8).  The Steelers are entering their bye week and will host the Browns in Week 8.  Brown went 9-93-1 on 16 targets versus Cleveland in Week 1.
report: Antonio Brown caught 5-of-6 targets for 105 yards and one touchdown in the Steelers' 28-21, Week 6 win over the Bengals.

impact: Brown did all of his damage in the first half, catching a 43-yard touchdown for the Steelers first score of the game on a blown coverage in the second quarter and then catching a 1-yard quick hitting screen pass for a score with eight seconds before halftime. The Steelers took the air out of the ball in the second half as Brown added just one catch 19 yards after the break, but the damage was already done. Brown now has scored a touchdown in five straight games and has eight touchdowns through seven games on the season. The Steelers head to Baltimore in Week 9.
report: Antonio Brown caught 6-of-8 targets for 74 yards and two touchdowns in Sunday's Week 8 game versus the Browns.

impact: This wasn't one of Brown's better weeks, which was probably to be expected playing on the road against a stingy Ravens defense. But he still provided his weekly touchdown, punching it in from six yards out on a screen from Ben Roethlisberger with just over seven minutes remaining in the second quarter. AB showed expert elusiveness, making two defenders miss on the play. Brown had his hand/finger stepped on early in the game but the injury didn't seem to affect him. The Steelers stud now has nine touchdowns for the year, the same number he had all of last season. He'll take a six-game touchdown streak into Thursday night's Week 10 showdown with Carolina.
report: Antonio Brown notched five catches for 42 yards and a touchdown on 11 targets Sunday in the Steelers’ Week 9 win over Baltimore.

impact: Most of Brown's damage came on his 53-yard touchdown in the second quarter. Matched up 1-on-1 with second-rounder Donte Jackson down the right sideline, Brown simply overpowered the rookie on his way to the end zone. Jackson wanted an OPI call, but it was just a little hand fighting. Brown is now up to 10 scores on the season after visiting the end zone "just" nine times in all of 2017. He should see a heavy dose of Jalen Ramsey against the Jaguars in Week 11.
report: Antonio Brown caught 6-of-6 targets for 96 yards and a touchdown in the Steelers' Week 10 win over the Panthers.

impact: Brown was erased by Jalen Ramsey through nearly three quarters with just one catch, then his entire day changed on one play. On a play in which Ben Roethlisberger extended the play in the pocket, Brown found a hole in zone coverage upfield and raced 78 yards to the end zone. It was the eighth consecutive game in which Brown has caught a touchdown pass, the longest streak since Wes Welker over the 2012-2013 seasons. Brown will look to keep the streak going next week in Denver.
report: Antonio Brown caught 5-of-13 targets for 117 yards and a touchdown in Sunday's Week 11 win over the Jaguars.

impact: As has become too common, Breida aggravated his ankle injury early in this game. He quickly came back after getting re-taped, but he limped off the field again during the two-minute touchdown drive at the end of the first half and did not touch the ball again. Perhaps the 49ers were just playing it safe in the blowout loss. Breida has a great matchup next week against the Cardinals, but his injury history will make him a risky play even if he is able to suit up.
report: Matt Breida rushed five times for 15 yards in the 49ers' Week 7 loss to the Rams.

impact: Breida played through his questionable tag and was reportedly "limited" in this one, then went and out-touched Alfred Morris, Raheem Mostert, and Kyle Juszczyk by a combined 16-10. Oddly enough, none of the lot were involved in the Niners' passing game. Breida deserves credit for toughing through these last few weeks, but he still averaged only 2.6 YPC Sunday due in part to his ailing ankle. Despite leading the backfield in carries, Breida's status should be monitored given the Niners' quick turnaround in Oakland on Thursday.
report: Matt Breida rushed a team-high 16 times for 42 yards in the Niners' Week 8 heartbreaking loss to the Cardinals.

impact: Breida was able to play through his nagging ankle injury, but the 49ers pulled him in the second half with the 49ers out to a huge lead. Breida's outlook is slightly more promising with Raheem Mostert likely out for the season with a broken arm, but even if he sees a few more touches per game with Mostert out, Breida is still a low floor RB2/3 for the 49ers' Week 10 game against the Giants. Breida hasn't eclipsed 65 rushing yards in six straight games.
report: Matt Breida rushed for 41 yards on 12 carries and caught his lone target for three yards in the 49ers' Week 9 win over the Raiders.

impact: The 20 touches marked a new season-high for Breida.  After having 11 days to rest his ailing ankle between games, this was as healthy as Breida has looked since Week 3 when he suffered a knee injury only to hurt his ankle in Week 5.  Breida dominated the backfield work with Raheem Mostert (arm, I.R.) out of the picture, ceding nine ineffective carries to Alfred Morris.  Breida was limping at times in this one but showed way more burst than we've seen from him over the last month or so.  He'll now get the Niners' bye to get fully healthy before hosting the Bucs in Week 12.
report: Matt Breida rushed 17 times for 101 yards and one touchdown and caught 3-of-4 targets for 31 yards and a second touchdown in the 49ers' 27-23, Week 10 loss to the Giants on Monday night.

impact: The second-year UDFA was sprung into extra snaps with Marquise Goodwin and Dante Pettis both leaving the game with leg injuries. Bourne was able to convert the extra looks into a two-yard touchdown for his second touchdown of the year. He will return to his backup role once Goodwin and Pettis return to action.
report: Kendrick Bourne caught 3-of-4 targets for 34 yards and a touchdown in the 49ers' Week 4 loss to the Chargers.

impact: The second-year UDFA was sprung into extra snaps with Marquise Goodwin and Dante Pettis both leaving the game with leg injuries. Bourne was able to convert the extra looks into a two-yard touchdown for his second touchdown of the year. He will return to his backup role once Goodwin and Pettis return to action.
report: Kendrick Bourne caught 3-of-4 targets for 34 yards and a touchdown in the 49ers' Week 4 loss to the Chargers.

impact: Bourne started in place of Pierre Garcon (knee) and responded with a team-high 71 receiving yards on 10 targets. The second-year UDFA has quietly pieced together a WR3-worthy performance when given the opportunity, most recently finishing with 3/34/1 in Week 4 when thrusted into surprise reps with both Marquise Goodwin and Dante Pettis hobbled. With trade rumors suddenly circling Pierre Garcon leading up to Tuesday's deadline, Bourne is worth a speculative add in season-long leagues in the event Garcon is shipped out.
report: Kendrick Bourne trapped 7-of-10 targets for a team-high 71 yards in the 49ers' Week 8 loss to the Cardinals.

impact: Brees was sacked once for a seven-yard loss. Even though it came in a losing effort, the 39-year-old was absolutely brilliant, slinging touchdowns to Michael Thomas, Ted Ginn and Alvin Kamara in Sunday’s slugfest. Brees and Thomas were nearly unstoppable together, connecting 16 times for an incredible 180 yards. Neither defense showed up on Sunday as the two teams combined for an insane 1,004 yards of total offense. We’ll see what the future Hall of Famer does for an encore when he faces the Browns in Week 2.
report: Drew Brees completed 37-of-45 passes for 439 yards with three touchdowns and no interceptions Sunday in the Saints’ Week 1 loss to Tampa Bay.

impact: Despite completing 80 percent of his passes, Brees got off to a slow start in the first when he rushed a throw to a wide open Ben Watson in the end zone and underthrew a wide open Ted Ginn for potential scores. He bounced back in the second half to connect for two touchdowns to Michael Thomas and lead back-to-back drives for scores to give the Saints the lead in the 4th quarter. Brees will have his first road game in Week 3 visiting Atlanta, but will remain in the QB1 mix for fantasy.
report: Drew Brees completed 28-of-35 passes for 243 yards and two touchdowns in Sunday's Week 2 win over the Browns.

impact: He lost five yards on his lone sack. Brees got off to a blistering start, completing all four of his passes for 55 yards and a touchdown to Ted Ginn on the opening drive. He never took his foot off the gas, connecting on all 10 of his throws to Michael Thomas while also completing an exhausting 15 passes to running back Alvin Kamara. As he often does, Brees saved his best for last. The 39-year-old tied the game on a rare rushing touchdown, beating two defenders on a spin move for a seven-yard score with 1:15 left in the fourth quarter. He sealed the game in overtime with another rushing TD, leaping over the pile on a QB keeper. Brees passed Brett Favre Sunday to become the NFL’s all-time completion leader. He should keep the train rolling next week against a burnable Giants secondary.
report: Drew Brees completed 39-of-49 passes for 396 yards and three touchdowns while also adding three carries for seven yards and another two touchdowns Sunday in New Orleans’ Week 3 win over the Falcons.

impact: It was the Saints' first game outside of a dome this season, and we've seen this pass offense struggle in these outdoor environments over the years.  It continued on Sunday, but Brees being removed at certain times in the red zone in favor of gadget QB Taysom Hill was mind-boggling.  There's no reason Hill should be playing over Brees in those situations, and the Saints did it more than once.  At the end of the day, they still won easily.  Brees will head back home next week for a date with the Redskins on Monday night.
report: Drew Brees completed 18-of-32 passes for 217 yards and no touchdowns in the Saints' Week 4 win over the Giants.

impact: Brees entered the night in third place on the league's all-time passing yards list.  He quickly passed Brett Favre for the No. 2 spot and then eclipsed Peyton Manning at No. 1 with a 62-yard touchdown pass to Tre'Quan Smith late in the second quarter.  There was nobody within 10 yards of Smith on a blown coverage, and Brees picked apart this little-league pass defense all night, as evidenced by just the three incompletions and 12.5 YPA average.  Brees' other two scores went to Josh Hill and a second to Smith.  The Saints are now heading into their bye before traveling to Baltimore in Week 7.
report: Drew Brees completed 26-of-29 passes for 363 yards and three touchdowns in the Saints' 43-19, Week 5 blowout win over the Redskins on Monday night.

impact: The scores were Nos. 500 and 501 of Brees' Hall-of-Fame career. He is just the fourth member of the 500-touchdown club. The Saints were methodical in the road victory, rushing 39 times while trying to gobble up clock. No. 2 quarterback Taysom Hill remained extremely involved as a red zone gadget player. Hill is little more than a nuisance, though he is curbing both Brees and Alvin Kamara's ultimate upside. The Saints are headed on the road to Minnesota's dome for Week 8.
report: Drew Brees completed 22-of-30 passes for 212 yards and two touchdowns in the Saints' 24-23, Week 7 win over the Ravens.

impact: The scores were Nos. 500 and 501 of Brees' Hall-of-Fame career. He is just the fourth member of the 500-touchdown club. The Saints were methodical in the road victory, rushing 39 times while trying to gobble up clock. No. 2 quarterback Taysom Hill remained extremely involved as a red zone gadget player. Hill is little more than a nuisance, though he is curbing both Brees and Alvin Kamara's ultimate upside. The Saints are headed on the road to Minnesota's dome for Week 8.
report: Drew Brees completed 22-of-30 passes for 212 yards and two touchdowns in the Saints' 24-23, Week 7 win over the Ravens.

impact: The Vikings did a good job of limiting Brees to check downs and short throws. His only TD was a shovel pass to Alvin Kamara on the opening drive. Brees threw his first interception of the season but was highly accurate —completing 78 percent of his passes. He wasn’t asked to do much with the Saints protecting a two-score lead in the second half. This will likely go down as one of Brees’ worst statistical games of the year. Brees will be one of  the top quarterback plays for a Week 9 matchup with the Rams.
report: Drew Brees completed 18-of-23 passes for 120 yards with a touchdown and an interception in Week 8 against the Vikings.

impact: Brees did not do much of anything wrong in the first half. He got some help with some great catches by Michael Thomas and Ben Watson, but he was exceptionally sharp in his own right. He found Alvin Kamara for a touchdown late in the first quarter, hit Tre’Quan Smith for a short score in the second, and found Watson for his third score from 13-yards out just before halftime. At one point in the first half, he was 15-for-18 for 194 yards and those three scores, as many touchdowns as incompletions. The offense fell into a lull in the second half, allowing the Rams to tie it up, but Brees was able to hit Thomas for a 72-yard score, his fourth touchdown toss of the day, to put the game on ice. Brees' attempt total could be a concern in non-competitive games, but that should not be an issue next week in Cincinnati. He will be a rock-solid QB1 in a great matchup.
report: Drew Brees completed 25-of-36 passes for 346 yards and four touchdowns in the Saints' Week 9 win over the Rams.

impact: Brees also added a 1-yard rushing touchdown for good measure. Against the league's worst pass defense, Brees found no resistance on Sunday. He started the game off with a 7-yard touchdown to Michael Thomas and never looked back, completing passes to seven different receivers. Brees has now thrown 21 touchdowns to just one interception on the season while completing 77 percent of his passes. Brees will be at home against the Eagles in Week 11.
report: Drew Brees completed 22-of-25 passes for 265 yards and three touchdowns in Sunday's Week 10 win over the Bengals.

impact: Spreading the ball around, Brees hit five different receivers on his first seven completions including a bullet to Austin Carr for a touchdown near the end of the first quarter, and that was just the start of a spectacular performance. Facing very little pressure, Brees picked apart the Eagles’ undermanned secondary all game. His 15-yard touchdown to Tre’Quan Smith was a pinpoint throw into a small window, and he threw a beautiful pass to Michael Thomas down the sideline for his third touchdown. Brees capped his day with another great throw to Alvin Kamara for a 37-yard touchdown early in the fourth quarter. Playing as well as any quarterback in the league, Brees will have an argument to be the overall QB1 next week against the Falcons, who he dusted for 396 yards and three scores in Week 3.
report: Drew Brees completed 22-of-30 passes for 363 yards and four touchdowns in the Saints' Week 11 win over the Eagles.

impact: Brady got off to a Foles-ian start, generating just 92 yards on his first 18 attempts. Of course, two of those completions were touchdowns, one a 21-yard strike to Rob Gronkowski who showed off some fancy footwork near the goal line. Brady and the Pats' offense woke up as the day progressed, with Brady sticking some important throws late. The Pats' weapons-limited offense could lack for elite rate stats while Julian Edelman is sidelined, but overwhelming volume will continue to take the day. That being said, Brady has as daunting of a matchup as possible for Week 2, as the Pats will be venturing to Jacksonville.
report: Tom Brady completed 26-of-39 passes for 277 yards, three touchdowns and an interception in the Patriots' 27-20, Week 1 win over the Texans.

impact: Brady added three rushes for 10 yards. Brady did about what was expected against the Jaguars' elite defense. It was the Patriots' D that let the team down on the road. The game was decided in the third quarter, where the Pats couldn't get the Jags off the field as they took up half the quarter on a field goal drive. Brady couldn't connect with Rob Gronkowski but did rekindle his connection with Chris Hogan, finding him for two scores. Brady is going to find much smoother sailing in Week 3 against the Lions, especially if No. 1 CB Darius Slay (concussion) can't play.
report: Tom Brady completed 24-of-35 passes for 234 yards and two touchdowns in the Patriots' 31-20, Week 2 loss to the Jaguars.

impact: Brady got off to a slow start with the Lions dominating time of possession. The Patriots couldn't get anything going in second-half comeback mode, but he still managed to throw a perfect 10-yard touchdown to James White. Brady made some mental errors, picking up a drive killing intentional grounding in the fourth quarter followed by a forced interception into double coverage. This will likely go down as one of Brady's worse games. New England has a matchup with the division-leading Dolphins in Week 4.
report: Tom Brady completed 14-of-26 passes for 133 yards with a touchdown and an interception in the Patriots' Week 3 loss to the Lions.

impact: Brady got off to a slow start, relying on the running game and Dolphins mistakes to get the Patriots some momentum. He heated up, finding Cordarrelle Patterson for a 55-yard screen score before delivering some real touchdown dimes to Phillip Dorsett and James White. It was Brady's best performance of the season, though he still appeared to be lacking arm drive at times, including both his interceptions. The first was a bad decision to a blanketed Dorsett. The second was a (late) blind heave into traffic. Brady needs Julian Edelman back, which he will receive in Week 5 against the Colts on Thursday Night Football. Of concern is that Rob Gronkowski checked out against the Dolphins with an ankle injury.
report: Tom Brady completed 23-of-35 passes for 274 yards, three touchdowns and two interceptions in the Patriots' 38-7, Week 4 demolition of the Dolphins.

impact: The scores were the 498th, 499th and 500th of Brady's incomparable career. Despite an egregious Julian Edelman drop on a potential long completion, Brady entered the break 23-of-27 for 203 yards and two of his scores. The Pats' offense was not nearly as crisp after halftime, though Brady tallied score 500 on what you could argue was an ill-advised end zone jump ball to Josh Gordon. Brady has yet to hit on all cylinders for an entire game this season, but he is getting closer. Edelman's return was an immediate hit. A Week 6 shootout against the Chiefs on Sunday Night Football awaits.
report: Tom Brady completed 34-of-44 passes for 341 yards, three touchdowns and two interceptions in the Patriots' 38-24, Week 5 win over the Colts.

impact: This was a gritty one for Brady, who had just 113 yards at half. The Patriots went with a run-heavy attack early, but were forced to throw in a second-half boat race with the Chiefs. Brady made up for his lack of touchdowns with a rushing score in the fourth quarter. His only real mistake was a late third-quarter fumble, but he engineered a game-winning field goal drive for the win. Brady has looked much better over the last three weeks with an improved supporting cast. He'll get a matchup with Chicago in Week 7.
report: Tom Brady completed 24-of-35 passes for 340 yards and a touchdown in the Patriots' Week 6 win over the Chiefs.

impact: Focusing on the short-passing game, Brady peppered his running backs and Julian Edelman with targets on his way to an opening touchdown drive. Edelman caught that touchdown, and he found James White for his other two scores -- a short pass into the flats in the second quarter and a shovel pass on a jet sweep in the fourth. He did push the ball down the field later in the game, finding Josh Gordon with a tight-window pass for 20 yards on the final play of the first quarter and then hitting the receiver again for a fourth-down conversion. He found Gordon again for a 55-yard gain in the second half to set up his third touchdown. Brady now has three touchdowns in three of his last four games, and he has topped 300 yards in two of those. He will be a high-end QB1 in Buffalo next Monday night.
report: Tom Brady completed 25-of-36 passes for 277 yards, three touchdowns, and an interception in the Patriots' Week 7 win over the Bears.

impact: Focusing on the short-passing game, Brady peppered his running backs and Julian Edelman with targets on his way to an opening touchdown drive. Edelman caught that touchdown, and he found James White for his other two scores -- a short pass into the flats in the second quarter and a shovel pass on a jet sweep in the fourth. He did push the ball down the field later in the game, finding Josh Gordon with a tight-window pass for 20 yards on the final play of the first quarter and then hitting the receiver again for a fourth-down conversion. He found Gordon again for a 55-yard gain in the second half to set up his third touchdown. Brady now has three touchdowns in three of his last four games, and he has topped 300 yards in two of those. He will be a high-end QB1 in Buffalo next Monday night.
report: Tom Brady completed 25-of-36 passes for 277 yards, three touchdowns, and an interception in the Patriots' Week 7 win over the Bears.

impact: This was another game-managing night from Brady, who had 121 scoreless at half. Brady’s only TD was a wide open 55-yard catch and run from Josh Gordon. He’s now had one or fewer touchdowns in three of the last four weeks, though he's been playing without a full supporting cast. Brady will be a lower end QB1 for Week 10 against the Titans.
report: Tom Brady completed 22-of-35 passes for 294 yards and a touchdown in the Patriots' Week 9 win over the Packers.

impact: The Pats threw in the towel with over six minutes left, sitting Brady in favor of Brian Hoyer.  Brady faced constant duress as multiple offensive linemen were in and out of the game, but he didn't help them by holding the ball for too long in the pocket.  Tennessee's defense was simply dominant, winning with a high blitz frequency and contesting everything to Brady's pass catchers.  The Patriots have a Week 11 bye to get healthy and things figured out.
report: Tom Brady completed 21-of-41 passes for 254 scoreless yards in the Patriots' Week 10 loss to the Titans.

impact: Not only did Brate put up a goose egg, but he was also out-snapped 43-24 by teammate and fellow tight O.J. Howard. Dating back to last season, the Harvard alum has totaled an embarrassing 186 yards over his last 10 games. Even at a thin fantasy position, the 27-year-old doesn’t carry much weight.
report: Cameron Brate failed to catch either of his two targets Sunday in the Buccaneers’ Week 1 victory over the Saints.

impact: Brate has either been Jekyll or Hyde through the Bucs' first four games, being held catchless in Tampa's first two contests only to cross pay dirt in the next two. O.J. Howard (knee) did get knocked out in the second quarter Sunday and wasn't able to return. Brate has historically performed much better with Jameis Winston under center, and he'll arguably be a TE1 against the Falcons' ailing secondary if Howard remains out after the bye.
report: Cameron Brate caught 3-of-4 targets for 29 yards and one touchdown in the Bucs' Week 4 loss to the Bears.

impact: Even with Howard back, Brate did his fantasy backers proud by catching a touchdown on the opening drive. Jameis Winston showed a lot of trust in his tight end on the throw, and Brate made it count by going up over De’Vondre Campbell for the score. Brate now has a touchdown in three straight games. Unfortunately for his value moving forward, that was his only target as O.J. Howard went for 62 yards. He will be just a TE2 next week against the Browns.
report: Cameron Brate hauled in his only target for a 15-yard touchdown in the Bucs' Week 6 loss to the Falcons.

impact: Brate lost a fumble on one of his three catches that the Bucs were fortunate to not have come back to haunt them. Brate has just 15 targets on the season and only has true fantasy value if something were to happen to O.J. Howard.
report: Cameron Brate caught 3-of-4 targets for 23 yards in Sunday's Week 7 win over the Browns.

impact: Brate lost a fumble on one of his three catches that the Bucs were fortunate to not have come back to haunt them. Brate has just 15 targets on the season and only has true fantasy value if something were to happen to O.J. Howard.
report: Cameron Brate caught 3-of-4 targets for 23 yards in Sunday's Week 7 win over the Browns.

impact: Brate is never a fantasy factor as long as O.J. Howard is healthy.
report: Cameron Brate caught 1-of-2 targets for 13 yards in Week 8.

impact: Brate could only watch as O.J. Howard scored two touchdowns. Brate has not been phased all the way out of the offense, but he is now merely a TE2 touchdown hope/prayer in fantasy.
report: Cameron Brate caught 3-of-3 targets for 15 yards in the Bucs' Week 9 loss to the Panthers.

impact: He dropped one of his other targets on a third down in the red zone before the Bucs then missed the field goal.  The Redskins stamped out the Tampa Bay tight ends, holding O.J. Howard to one catch for 15 yards.
report: Cameron Brate caught 1-of-3 targets for 14 yards in the Week 10 loss to the Redskins.

impact: Over the past four games, Brate has totaled seven catches for 58 yards. Yes, you read that right. Unless Jameis Winston is announced as starter and O.J. Howard sits out, we're one week away from not having to discuss Brate in this space for the remainder of the season.
report: Cameron Brate caught 2-of-3 targets for 16 yards in the Bucs' Week 11 loss to the Giants.

impact: He out-targeted John Ross 5 to 2.  Boyd is unlikely to be a fantasy factor behind A.J. Green, Joe Mixon, and Tyler Eifert, but he has a more secure role than the Bengals' hyped sophomore wideout as Cincy's locked-in slot man.
report: Tyler Boyd caught 3-of-5 targets for 26 yards in the Bengals' Week 1 win over the Colts.

impact: Boyd was a monster in Week 2 against the Ravens, and he stepped up to become Andy Dalton's favorite target on Sunday as A.J. Green (groin) exited early in the third quarter and never returned.  Dalton hit Boyd for a spectacular 27-yard rollout touchdown, then found Boyd open off a broken play in the second half for a 49-yard gain.  Dalton is looking for Boyd when he's in trouble.  Boyd has earned WR3 treatment entering Week 4 at Atlanta, and could push for WR2 value if Green can't play.
report: Tyler Boyd caught 6-of-7 targets for 132 yards and a touchdown in the Bengals' Week 3 loss to Carolina.

impact: An established factor in Cincinnati's offense at this point, Boyd was one of Andy Dalton's favorite targets all game, but he was spectacular on the game-winning touchdown drive, converting a third down and two fourth downs. He now has two 100-yard games in a row after zero in the first 28 games of his career. With Dalton playing great and Tyler Eifert likely out for the year, Boyd should return at worst WR3 value the rest of the way.
report: Tyler Boyd hauled in 11-of-15 targets for 100 yards in the Bengals' Week 4 win over the Falcons.

impact: It's a step back after Boyd went over 90 yards the last three weeks. The Bengals went run heavy against Miami, leaving just seven targets for Boyd behind A.J. Green. With Tyler Eifert on IR, there's a lot to like with Boyd's ROS outlook. He'll be a WR3 for a plus Week 6 matchup with the Steelers.
report: Tyler Boyd caught 4-of-7 passes for 44 yards in Week 5 against the Dolphins.

impact: His nine looks were second on the team to A.J. Green's dozen.  Boyd was the recipient of both of Andy Dalton's touchdowns, from two and 14 yards out, and Boyd had to make a diving catch on the two-yarder.  He made a number of difficult grabs in this one on a day Dalton was off the mark.  Boyd has been a steady WR2 for weeks and will stay that way next week against the Chiefs.
report: Tyler Boyd caught 7-of-9 targets for 62 yards and two touchdowns in the Bengals' 28-21, Week 6 loss to the Steelers.

impact: Boyd was invisible in the first half, getting held without a catch. He managed to get some targets late with the Bengals airing it out, but it's a disappointing game. Boyd has been held under 50 yards in two of the last three weeks. He'll be a low-end WR2 for Week 8 against the Bucs.
report: Tyler Boyd caught 2-of-4 passes for 27 yards in Week 7 against the Chiefs.

impact: Boyd was invisible in the first half, getting held without a catch. He managed to get some targets late with the Bengals airing it out, but it's a disappointing game. Boyd has been held under 50 yards in two of the last three weeks. He'll be a low-end WR2 for Week 8 against the Bucs.
report: Tyler Boyd caught 2-of-4 passes for 27 yards in Week 7 against the Chiefs.

impact: Boyd pulled a disappearing act in last week's loss at Arrowhead.  He rebounded in a major way on Sunday, repeatedly dusting the Bucs' leaky slot coverage and scoring from seven yards out in the second quarter.  Boyd has had some ups and downs, but he has also developed into one of the NFL's premier slot receivers.  He will be a WR2/3 when Cincinnati returns from its Week 9 bye.
report: Tyler Boyd caught 9-of-10 targets for 138 yards and a touchdown in the Bengals' Week 8 win over the Bucs.

impact: In his first game without A.J. Green, Boyd matched season lows in targets and receptions as he was torpedoed by the inept Cincinnati offense, something we've now seen happen twice over their past three games. Boyd started off on the right foot, catching a 23-yard pass on the second play of the game, but the Bengals offense just fell apart after that opening drive. Despite the down day, Boyd will still be a WR2 option in Week 11 against the Ravens.
report: Tyler Boyd caught 3-of-4 targets for 65 yards in Sunday's Week 10 loss to the Saints.

impact: The Ravens used numerous double teams to deal with Boyd, explaining his inefficiency.  He did deliver gains of 29 and 32 but is getting no help from Cincinnati's lack of alternative weapons.  Still a volume monster, Boyd will remain a playable WR3 with WR2 upside when the Bengals host the Browns next.
report: Tyler Boyd caught 4-of-11 targets for 71 yards in the Bengals' Week 11 loss to Baltimore.

impact: It was not a good performance from Bortles, who struggled to move the ball without Leonard Fournette. Jacksonville had three long scoring drives in the first half including a touchdown drive after Fournette exited, but their longest play of the second half lasted just six plays. They punted seven times after the break. With Fournette looking questionable, Bortles will have to show more next week against the Patriots.
report: Blake Bortles completed 18-of-33 passes for 176 yards, a touchdown, and an interception in the Jaguars' Week 1 win over the Giants.

impact: The 377 yards passing were the third most of Bortles' career. Aside from a second half pick on a questionable but not egregious decision, Bortles was as poised as he's ever been. He "took what the defense was giving him," alternating some big throws down the field with lots of checkdowns to his playmakers. Dede Westbrook turned one such play into a 61-yard touchdown, while RB Corey Grant was eating up yards on short targets. Bortles did not take a single sack. He will look to stay hot against the Titans' soft defense in Week 3.
report: Blake Bortles completed 29-of-45 passes for 377 yards, four touchdowns and an interception in the Jaguars' 31-20, Week 2 win over the Patriots, adding five rushes for 25 additional yards.

impact: After shredding New England for 377 yards and four touchdowns in last week's win, Bortles got nothing going beyond checkdowns in Sunday's ugly 9-6 home-game loss.  Tennessee got to Bortles three times for sacks, but his throws to the outside were too often off the mark, and the Leonard Fournette-less running game was nearly nonexistent.  Fournette figures to return from his hamstring injury for Week 4 versus the Jets.  Bortles will continue to be a high-variance QB2.
report: Blake Bortles went 20-of-33 passing for 158 yards and rushed five times for 27 yards in the Jaguars' Week 3 loss to the Titans.

impact: Bortles was sharp in this one, completing 15 of his first 16 passes. He put good touch on a 67-yard touchdown to Donte Moncrief, with his other TD a screen to T.J. Yeldon. Bortles has started to heat up with 300-plus yards and multiple touchdowns in two of his last three weeks. He has a streamable Week 5 matchup with the Chiefs.
report: Blake Bortles completed 29-of-38 passes for 388 yards with two touchdowns and an interception in Week 4 against the Jets.

impact: Bortles had a first half to forget. Despite some good throws down the field including a 36-yard pass to D.J. Chark, the early part of his game was marred by turnovers. He lost a fumble the play after the defense picked off Patrick Mahomes, had a horrific pick-six on an attempted screen pass the next drive, and threw an end-zone interception off his lineman's helmet. He made several great throws on a touchdown drive in the third quarter, but he came back with a bad interception overthrown to a double-covered tight end on the next drive. He added another meaningless interception at the end of the game. On the bright side, he threw for 430 yards and added a long rushing score deep in garbage time to pad his fantasy stats.
