Always a threat for a big game when Leonard Fournette is sidelined, Bortles will be on the streaming map next week in Dallas.
report: Blake Bortles completed 33-of-61 passes for 430 yards, a touchdown, and four interceptions in the Jaguars' Week 5 loss to the Chiefs, adding four carries for 34 yards and a touchdown.

impact: He took three sacks for a loss of 10 yards. Bortles threw for just 35 yards in the first half, which may explain why the Jags went into halftime with a 24-point deficit. Even with the benefit of garbage time, Bortles never got anything going, struggling all day against an underrated Cowboys defense. His lone touchdown came on a 34-yard bomb to Dede Westbrook early in the third quarter. Bortles has thrown five interceptions over his last two outings with both resulting in losses. He'll try to do better next time out against Houston.
report: Blake Bortles completed 15-of-26 passes for 149 yards with one touchdown and one interception while adding 22 yards on four carries Sunday in the Jaguars’ Week 6 loss to Dallas.

impact: Bortles failed to move the ball at all, completing just 6-of-12 passes for 61 yards with two lost fumbles that directly led to Texans touchdowns.  Put simply, it was time.  Bortles has been as erratic as ever this season, showing no signs of progression, taking too many sacks, and turning the ball over far too often.  Kessler is a weak-armed game manager, but he is a better option under center for the Jaguars at this point.
report: Losing 20-0, the Jaguars benched Blake Bortles for Cody Kessler in the second half of Sunday's Week 7 game against the Texans.

impact: A week after getting benched, Bortles appeared hesitant to let the ball go early. At one point in the second quarter, he had more carries (4) than passing attempts (3), and he threw just seven passes total in the first half. The offense opened up after the break, and Bortles was able to move the football. He completed seven of nine passes on a 75-yard touchdown drive in the third quarter including a great touch throw to Dede Westbrook for the touchdown, and he led a couple field goal drives the next two times the Jags had the ball. A couple of better throws could have earned him a touchdown on both of those possessions, however, and he was not able to lead a comeback drive despite picking up one fourth down with his legs. Bortles played well enough to keep the starting job against the Colts coming out of the bye, especially since he did not commit any turnovers, but he will remain on a short leash.
report: Blake Bortles completed 24-of-41 attempts for 286 yards and a touchdown in the Jaguars' Week 8 loss to the Eagles in London, adding 43 yards on the ground.

impact: Bortles’ day started on a high note. He threw a great pass to Donte Moncrief on their second drive of the game, and the former Colt broke a couple tackles on his way to an 80-yard score. He was limited to handoffs most of the rest of the first half, but he got things going a bit on a two-minute drive for a field goal just before the half. He kept things going after the break, throwing for 59 yards and a score on the opening drive and keeping the offense moving despite Jacksonville’s near insistence on putting him in third-and-long situations. He drove the offense down the field for what at worst should have been a game-tying field goal, but a Rashad Greene fumble ended the game. Bortles played well enough for the Jags to win this game, but he will have a tougher time next week against the Steelers.
report: Blake Bortles completed 26-of-38 passes for 320 yards and two touchdowns in the Jaguars' Week 10 loss to the Colts.

impact: Bortles added 17 yards rushing on the day, but was also sacked six times. The 18 pass attempts and 104 passing yards were season-lows for Bortles in a complete game this season as the Jaguars largely tried to keep the ball with their run game on the afternoon. That game plan could be something in play next week as Bortles and the Jaguars head to Buffalo in Week 12. Bortles will only be a lower-end QB2 option in that game.
report: Blake Bortles completed 10-of-18 passes for 104 yards with no touchdowns or interceptions in Sunday's Week 11 loss to the Steelers.

impact: Booker operated as the third-down back early in the game and saw passing-down work all day, but he appeared to fall down the depth chart in this one. Following a 29-yard touchdown catch in the first quarter, Phillip Lindsay worked as the No. 2 running back and even matched Royce Freeman in rushing attempts and yards. Looking like the third option in a committee backfield, Booker does not need to be rostered in standard-sized redraft leagues.
report: Devontae Booker rushed twice for four yards and hauled in both his targets for 11 yards in the Broncos' Week 1 win over the Seahawks.

impact: Denver's No. 3 back, Booker took on a bigger role in the second half after Phillip Lindsay was ejected just before halftime. He did not do much with it, and he should fall back behind Lindsay in the pecking order next week.
report: Devontae Booker hauled in 5-of-7 targets for 34 yards and rushed five times for 10 yards in the Broncos' Week 3 loss to the Ravens.

impact: He remains the third wheel in Denver's backfield, but still an active one.  And Booker's activity spiked a bit this week because the Broncos got destroyed by the Jets and played passing-game specialist Booker more than usual.  Booker would still need a Phillip Lindsay or Royce Freeman injury to become a legit flex option, but he is worth stashing in 14- and 16-team PPR leagues.
report: Devontae Booker caught 5-of-6 targets for 59 yards in the Broncos' Week 5 loss to the Jets.

impact: He remains the third wheel in Denver's backfield, but still an active one.  And Booker's activity spiked a bit this week because the Broncos got destroyed by the Jets and played passing-game specialist Booker more than usual.  Booker would still need a Phillip Lindsay or Royce Freeman injury to become a legit flex option, but he is worth stashing in 14- and 16-team PPR leagues.
report: Devontae Booker caught 5-of-6 targets for 59 yards in the Broncos' Week 5 loss to the Jets.

impact: With Royce Freeman (ankle) absent, the 26-year-old set season-highs in both touches and yards from scrimmage. He was especially productive in the second half, delivering 76 of his 101 yards after the break. He delivered the game's longest run (though not the longest play from scrimmage) on a 26-yard burst in the fourth quarter. Despite drawing eight fewer touches than teammate Phillip Lindsay (he won the touch battle 21-13), Booker is still worth owning in most leagues, at least while Freeman is out. He gets the Texans at home in Week 9.
report: Devontae Booker collected 78 yards on nine carries while also snagging four catches for 23 yards on four targets Sunday in the Broncos’ Week 8 loss to the Chiefs.

impact: Booker's touchdown was essentially a vulture-job as he was drastically out-touched by teammate Phillip Lindsay 19-5. It was a severe reduction in his workload sans Royce Freeman in Week 8, having totaled 13 touches against the Chiefs. Given the Broncos' timid and horrid play-calling, Lindsay (the apparent workhorse) need be the only back considered moving forward if Freeman misses any further time.
report: Devontae Booker rushed three times for 15 yards and one score, tacking on two catches for nine yards in the Broncos' Week 9 loss to the Texans.

impact: Booker spent most of the day spectating, playing just 11-of-56 offensive snaps. With Royce Freeman back from injury and Phillip Lindsay enjoying a breakout season, Booker's opportunities going forward will be few and far between. He can be ignored next week against Pittsburgh.
report: Devontae Booker corralled his lone target for four yards Sunday in the Broncos’ Week 11 win over Los Angeles.

impact: Blue was out-touched 21-5 in the Texans' season opener but closed the gap (16-7) in Week 2. Miller is still being used as an every-down workhorse, but he admittedly lacks explosiveness and hasn't shown a propensity to break tackles yet this season. Until Blue eats into Miller's opportunities, though, it's the latter who's still the back to own in Houston.
report: Alfred Blue rushed seven times for 36 yards in the Texans' Week 2 loss to the Titans.

impact: Meanwhile, Lamar Miller rushed 15 times for 49 yards, so neither runner had much success.  Blue was targeted three times in the pass game, catching none of them.  The 15-12 touch share is a bit concerning for Miller owners.
report: Alfred Blue rushed 12 times for 31 yards in the Texans' Week 4 win over the Colts.

impact: Blue started and had a workhorse role despite Lamar Miller (chest) being active. He was more of a factor in the passing game, but Blue had some nice runs. The Texans never let Blue get in a rhythm and he was passed over for multiple goal-line looks in favor of Deshaun Watson. Miller was close to playing this week, so Blue will likely return to a backup role in Week 6.
report: Alfred Blue rushed 20 times for 46 yards and caught eight passes for 73 yards in Week 5 against the Cowboys.

impact: With Lamar Miller back, Blue went right back into a secondary role against the Bills. He did flash with a 17-yard run early, but he was mostly held in check the rest of the way. D'Onta Foreman's potential return is a concern for Blue's handcuff value moving forward.
report: Alfred Blue rushed seven times for 26 yards and caught 2-of-3 targets for 17 yards in the Texans' Week 6 win over the Bills.

impact: With Lamar Miller back, Blue went right back into a secondary role against the Bills. He did flash with a 17-yard run early, but he was mostly held in check the rest of the way. D'Onta Foreman's potential return is a concern for Blue's handcuff value moving forward.
report: Alfred Blue rushed seven times for 26 yards and caught 2-of-3 targets for 17 yards in the Texans' Week 6 win over the Bills.

impact: Blue was completely inefficient, averaging just 2.6 YPC against the Broncos' front-seven. His 15 carries are notable, though, because it was three more than Lamar Miller (12/21) received on the day. With D'Onta Foreman eyeing a return in the next few weeks, Blue would only be viable following the Texans' Week 10 bye if he continues seeing at least half of their backfield touches.
report: Alfred Blue rushed 15 times for 39 yards in the Texans' Week 9 victory over the Broncos.

impact: It was a Lions debut to forget for Blount, who lost seven yards on his first carry and injured his knee on his last one.  The 31-year-old played just 13 snaps, trailing both Theo Riddick and Kerryon Johnson.  Blount might score some touchdowns, but he doesn't need to be owned in most spots.
report: LeGarrette Blount rushed four times for -3 yards in the Lions' Week 1 loss to the Jets.

impact: Blount came to the defense of Matthew Stafford after it appeared Lee hit him when he was already out of bounds early in the fourth quarter. The running back was flagged for unnecessary roughness and promptly tossed for shoving Lee to the ground. Blount fared better than he did in last week's opener, finishing the afternoon with 38 yards on eight carries while catching his lone target for a loss of three yards. With the Lions in catch-up mode, Blount's absence is unlikely to be felt.
report: LeGarrette Blount was ejected from the Lions' Week 2 game for shoving 49ers LB Elijah Lee.

impact: Blount had his best game of the season after getting injured in Week 1 and ejected last week. He started, but rotated with Kerryon Johnson and Theo Riddick. Blount had gameflow working in his favor with Detroit milking the clock in the second half. With Johnson breaking out for over 100 yards, Blount should see his workload scaled back in Week 4.
report: LeGarrette Blount rushed 16 times for 48 yards in Week 3 against the Patriots.

impact: There wasn’t a lot of rushing work to go around on Sunday as the Lions logged just 20 carries, but it’s still baffling that Blount saw nearly the same workload as impressive rookie Kerryon Johnson. Blount has value as a short-yardage grinder but Johnson is more versatile and should be playing close to an every-down role. Known for his scoring prowess, the 31-year-old has yet to find the end zone in 2018. Blount won’t be an appealing fantasy option next week against Green Bay.
report: LeGarrette Blount managed just seven yards on 12 carries Sunday in the Lions’ Week 4 loss to the Cowboys.

impact: Blount was the ultimate vulture in this one, scoring a pair of one-yard touchdown runs in the opening quarter.  The 12 carries were Blount's second-most of the season and matched Kerryon Johnson for the team lead; Johnson later had to leave with an ankle injury.  Blount looks just about done with the tank coming close to empty, but he remains a goal-line threat as the Lions head into their bye.  Blount doesn't need to be owned in most formats outside of standard leagues.
report: LeGarrette Blount rushed 12 times for 22 yards and two touchdowns in the Lions' Week 5 win over the Packers.

impact: Blount was not targeted in the passing game. Blount was untouched on his two-yard touchdown run in the second quarter. Kerryon Johnson was running wild, but coach Matt Patricia insisted on continuing to feed Blount. Johnson is playing extremely well, but Blount is not going away as a fantasy troll/vulture.
report: LeGarrette Blount rushed 10 times for 50 yards and a touchdown in the Lions' Week 7 win over the Dolphins.

impact: Blount was not targeted in the passing game. Blount was untouched on his two-yard touchdown run in the second quarter. Kerryon Johnson was running wild, but coach Matt Patricia insisted on continuing to feed Blount. Johnson is playing extremely well, but Blount is not going away as a fantasy troll/vulture.
report: LeGarrette Blount rushed 10 times for 50 yards and a touchdown in the Lions' Week 7 win over the Dolphins.

impact: Blount's reception came on a screen. Blount's four touches were his fewest since Week 1. It was game flow related, as the Lions spent most of the afternoon playing from behind. Blount won't be a recommended FLEX for Week 9 against the Vikings.
report: LeGarrette Blount rushed three times for three yards in the Lions' Week 8 loss to the Seahawks, adding a 23-yard reception.

impact: He caught one ball for two yards.  Blount is useless when he's not scoring short TDs.
report: LeGarrette Blount rushed five times for eight yards in the Lions' Week 9 loss to the Vikings.

impact: As usual, he had no involvement in the passing game. Blount got the first crack at goal-line work with Detroit driving in the second quarter but was stuffed on both of his attempts. Kerryon Johnson spelled Blount on third down and scored from a yard out. The 31-year-old has bottomed out during the Lions' three-game losing streak, averaging a pathetic 1.07 yards per carry with no touchdowns during that span. With Johnson emerging as the Lions' bell cow, Blount no longer carries any fantasy significance.
report: LeGarrette Blount delivered just four yards on six carries Sunday in the Lions’ Week 10 loss to Chicago.

impact: Even with Kerryon Johnson going down in this game, there is little reason to expect much fantasy value out of Blount, especially with the Bears up next. The Lions might be better off giving Zach Zenner carries.
report: LeGarrette Blount gained one yard on seven carries in the Lions' Week 11 win over the Panthers.

impact: Bibbs was the Redskins' No. 2/change of pace with Chris Thompson sidelined. Thompson seemed close to suiting up this week, so Bibbs is not a compelling waiver wire add.
report: Kapri Bibbs rushed twice for 11 yards in the Redskins' Week 6 win over the Panthers, adding a six-yard reception.

impact: Without Chris Thompson for the second straight week, Bibbs again stepped in as Washington's No. 2 change-of-pace back. He showed his worth on Washington's first drive when he stretched a screen in the flats into a 23-yard touchdown scamper. His 43 receiving yards tied Jordan Reed's for the team lead. Bibbs has been out-carried by Adrian Peterson 41-4 over the last two games, though, and would need more consistent usage to be deemed a potential streamer moving forward. He's worthy of stashing in the event both Peterson and Thompson are ruled out later on.
report: Kapri Bibbs rushed two times for 16 yards, adding four catches for 43 yards and one touchdown through the air in the Redskins' Week 7 win over the Cowboys.

impact: Without Chris Thompson for the second straight week, Bibbs again stepped in as Washington's No. 2 change-of-pace back. He showed his worth on Washington's first drive when he stretched a screen in the flats into a 23-yard touchdown scamper. His 43 receiving yards tied Jordan Reed's for the team lead. Bibbs has been out-carried by Adrian Peterson 41-4 over the last two games, though, and would need more consistent usage to be deemed a potential streamer moving forward. He's worthy of stashing in the event both Peterson and Thompson are ruled out later on.
report: Kapri Bibbs rushed two times for 16 yards, adding four catches for 43 yards and one touchdown through the air in the Redskins' Week 7 win over the Cowboys.

impact: Bibbs technically played the "Chris Thompson role," but he was barely a factor in the passing game on a day where Alex Smith looked almost strictly for tight ends and slot receivers rather than wideouts and running backs.  Bibbs' second-half rushing score came from three yards out.  Even if Thompson (ribs) sits again in Week 10, Bibbs would be a weak PPR-only flex play at Tampa Bay.
report: Kapri Bibbs rushed three times for 20 yards and a touchdown and caught his lone target for 15 yards in Washington's Week 9 loss to Atlanta.

impact: Bibbs has been filling in as Chris Thompson's replacement while he's out hurt.  He's a desperation FLEX in deeper PPR leagues when Thompson is out.
report: Kapri Bibbs rushed three times for 28 yards and caught 2-of-4 targets for 13 yards in the Redskins' Week 10 win over the Bucs.

impact: Benjamin left the game just minutes after kickoff after hauling in his first target of the game. He slammed his helmet on the sideline in frustration, as he knew he re-injured his nagging foot injury. Benjamin can be safely dropped with his foot injury and Mike Williams working against him.
report: Travis Benjamin (foot) has been ruled for the remainder of the Chargers' Week 4 game against the 49ers.

impact: He added 27 yards on four catches. Bernard did cede more work to Mark Walton than last week, but he still operated as the clear lead back. His first touchdown came on a 10-yard run in which he cut to the outside and easily got the corner, and he added another one from one-yard out in the second quarter. Despite the good performance, Bernard's run as an RB1 could be at an end with Joe Mixon looking likely to return next week.
report: Giovani Bernard rushed 15 times for 69 yards and two touchdowns in the Bengals' Week 4 win over the Falcons.

impact: This was Bernard's first game action since Week 4 after dealing with an MCL injury. In his three games played with Joe Mixon, Bernard now has totaled just 16 touches for 87 yards. Bernard is only a bench-stash option in the event Mixon were to miss time.
report: Giovani Bernard rushed two times for six yards while catching 2-of-3 targets for 30 yards in Sunday's Week 10 loss to the Saints.

impact: It was a rough game for Benjamin, who dropped a touchdown in the end-zone. Benjamin was held back by Nathan Peterman in the first half, but saw more looks after Josh Allen took over. Benjamin has one of the worst quarterback situations in the league, but his target share keeps him in the WR3 discussion.
report: Kelvin Benjamin caught 1-of-7 targets for 10 yards in Week 1 against Baltimore.

impact: Benjamin's touchdown came deep into garbage time. He didn't make his first catch until deep in the third quarter and continued to be the victim of bad quarterback play. Benjamin should have better weeks as Josh Allen acclimates, but he can't be trusted in fantasy lineups.
report: Kelvin Benjamin caught two passes for 19 yards and a touchdown in Week 2 against the Chargers.

impact: Josh Allen did most of his damage scrambling for his life outside of the pocket, and thus Benjamin wasn't looked to downfield much. He still leads the Bills' skill players in target share, but hasn't caught more than three passes or eclipsed the 30-yard mark in any game this season. He's droppable in all formats.
report: Kelvin Benjamin caught 3-of-5 targets for 29 yards in the Bills' Week 3 win over the Vikings.

impact: Josh Allen did most of his damage scrambling for his life outside of the pocket, and thus Benjamin wasn't looked to downfield much. He still leads the Bills' skill players in target share, but hasn't caught more than three passes or eclipsed the 30-yard mark in any game this season. He's droppable in all formats.
report: Kelvin Benjamin caught 3-of-5 targets for 29 yards in the Bills' Week 3 win over the Vikings.

impact: As inefficient as you've come to expect. Benjamin was also checked for a concussion but thankfully cleared the protocol. On pace for just 368 yards in the Bills' dysfunctional offense, Benjamin is miles from fantasy relevance.
report: Kelvin Benjamin caught 1-of-6 targets for 34 yards in the Bills' Week 4 loss to the Packers.

impact: As inefficient as you've come to expect. Benjamin was also checked for a concussion but thankfully cleared the protocol. On pace for just 368 yards in the Bills' dysfunctional offense, Benjamin is miles from fantasy relevance.
report: Kelvin Benjamin caught 1-of-6 targets for 34 yards in the Bills' Week 4 loss to the Packers.

impact: Josh Allen hasn't helped him, but Benjamin has been atrocious this year.  He has shown no ability to separate from defensive backs or so much as win contested catches. Benjamin has finished below 40 yards in each of the Bills' first five games and is averaging under four yards per target.  Benjamin will not be a fantasy option in Week 6 at Houston.
report: Kelvin Benjamin caught 1-of-5 targets for 11 yards in the Bills' Week 5 win over the Titans.

impact: Josh Allen hasn't helped him, but Benjamin has been atrocious this year.  He has shown no ability to separate from defensive backs or so much as win contested catches. Benjamin has finished below 40 yards in each of the Bills' first five games and is averaging under four yards per target.  Benjamin will not be a fantasy option in Week 6 at Houston.
report: Kelvin Benjamin caught 1-of-5 targets for 11 yards in the Bills' Week 5 win over the Titans.

impact: Benjamin was predictably quiet for most of this game, but he showed up with a couple big plays in the third quarter. The first was negated by an illegal formation penalty, but he came back on the next drive with a 39-yard catch. That catch went for more yards than he did in any of the first five games this season. He regressed right back to expectations after that, dropping a pass a couple plays later. He will not be an option next week against the Colts.
report: Kelvin Benjamin hauled in 2-of-6 targets for 43 yards in the Bills' Week 6 loss to the Texans.

impact: Benjamin was predictably quiet for most of this game, but he showed up with a couple big plays in the third quarter. The first was negated by an illegal formation penalty, but he came back on the next drive with a 39-yard catch. That catch went for more yards than he did in any of the first five games this season. He regressed right back to expectations after that, dropping a pass a couple plays later. He will not be an option next week against the Colts.
report: Kelvin Benjamin hauled in 2-of-6 targets for 43 yards in the Bills' Week 6 loss to the Texans.

impact: The 71 yards represented a new season-high for Benjamin, who made the most of his limited workload. He was the only receiver who showed anything resembling chemistry with Derek Anderson, who was making his first start in nearly two years. Despite a decent showing Sunday, it's still been a brutal year for the former first-round pick, who has converted just 37.8 percent of his targets this season. He'll take a five-game scoreless drought into next week's matchup against the Patriots.
report: Kelvin Benjamin secured four of his five targets for 71 yards Sunday in the Bills’ Week 7 loss to Indianapolis.

impact: The 71 yards represented a new season-high for Benjamin, who made the most of his limited workload. He was the only receiver who showed anything resembling chemistry with Derek Anderson, who was making his first start in nearly two years. Despite a decent showing Sunday, it's still been a brutal year for the former first-round pick, who has converted just 37.8 percent of his targets this season. He'll take a five-game scoreless drought into next week's matchup against the Patriots.
report: Kelvin Benjamin secured four of his five targets for 71 yards Sunday in the Bills’ Week 7 loss to Indianapolis.

impact: Nathan Peterman's insertion did not spark Benjamin despite his team high in targets.  Benjamin ran lackadaisical routes as usual and appeared to give up on an end-zone target where he strangely flopped to the ground despite not even being pushed.  At least until Derek Anderson (concussion) gets cleared, Benjamin will have no business in fantasy football lineups in Week 10 at the Jets.
report: Kelvin Benjamin caught 4-of-9 targets for 40 yards in the Bills' Week 9 loss to the Bears.

impact: Beathard wasn't so bad in the game with Kyle Shanahan only asking his quarterback to attempt two passes 20+ yards down the field. The 49ers might be able to dink-and-dunk their way down the field like they did today, but it's tough to imagine this offense being explosive with Beathard and a below average receiving group. He averaged 237 yards and only had three total touchdowns in five starts last season.
report: C.J. Beathard completed 23-of-37 passes for 298 yards, two touchdowns, and two interceptions in the 49ers' Week 4 loss to the Chargers.

impact: Beathard was also sacked four times for a loss of 49 yards. After playing surprisingly well in last week's loss to the Chargers, Beathard took a noticeable step back against the Cardinals. He was a turnover machine, throwing a pair of interceptions while also losing two fumbles. One of those fumbles was returned for a 23-yard touchdown in the fourth quarter, which essentially sealed the victory for Arizona. The 24-year-old benefited from garbage time, logging over 200 passing yards with San Francisco trailing in the second half. His lone rushing score came on a one-yard QB sneak. Outside of two-quarterback leagues, Beathard won't be someone fantasy owners can rely on next week at Green Bay.
report: C.J. Beathard completed 34-of-54 passes for 349 yards with two touchdowns and two interceptions while adding two carries for seven yards and another touchdown Sunday in the Niners’ Week 5 loss to the Cardinals.

impact: Beathard played so well for 58 minutes of this one.  He had a near-perfect passer rating and was carving up a banged-up Packers secondary, but a late interception with 1:07 left and the game tied at 30-30 set Aaron Rodgers up at his own 10-yard line.  The magic then happened, as Rodgers dropped dimes for 46 yards passing with a 21-yard scramble to finish the comeback.  Beathard's game can't go overlooked, though.  He threw 67- and 30-yard touchdowns to Marquise Goodwin, who roasted Kentrell Brice and Tramon Williams on each.  Beathard also showed big guts and toughness with 21 rushing yards, diving headfirst for first downs.  This was one of the most entertaining games of the year.  Beathard will do battle with the Rams in Santa Clara in Week 7.
report: C.J. Beathard completed 16-of-23 passes for 245 yards, two touchdowns, and one interception in the 49ers' 33-30, Week 6 loss to the Packers on Monday night.

impact: Beathard had a rough first half, turning the ball over twice including a lost fumble and failing to complete a pass to a receiver. He did find George Kittle for several big plays, however, including a 10-yard touchdown with just 10 seconds left to at least give the 49ers a chance. Unfortunately for San Francisco, he could not build on that drive in the second half, and he tossed another interception on a pass thrown slightly behind Kittle in the third quarter. Beathard has to take some blame for the showing, but he was constantly under pressure and ended up taking seven sacks. The road will not get any easier in Arizona against an underrated defense next week.
report: C.J. Beathard completed 15-of-27 passes for 170 yards, one touchdown, and two interceptions in the 49ers' Week 7 loss to the Rams.

impact: Beathard had a rough first half, turning the ball over twice including a lost fumble and failing to complete a pass to a receiver. He did find George Kittle for several big plays, however, including a 10-yard touchdown with just 10 seconds left to at least give the 49ers a chance. Unfortunately for San Francisco, he could not build on that drive in the second half, and he tossed another interception on a pass thrown slightly behind Kittle in the third quarter. Beathard has to take some blame for the showing, but he was constantly under pressure and ended up taking seven sacks. The road will not get any easier in Arizona against an underrated defense next week.
report: C.J. Beathard completed 15-of-27 passes for 170 yards, one touchdown, and two interceptions in the 49ers' Week 7 loss to the Rams.

impact: It's the second consecutive game Beathard's failed to eclipse 200 yards, and he's done so in cush matchups (Rams, at Cardinals). He's only trended down since exploding out of the gates in place of Jimmy Garoppolo due in part to constant injuries among the Niners' receiving corps and offensive line. With trade rumors circling Pierre Garcon, Beathard could take to the field Thursday with Marquise Goodwin, Kendrick Bourne, and Trent Taylor in three-wide sets. He'll still be a serviceable streamer in Week 9 against the Raiders.
report: C.J. Beathard completed 14-of-28 passes for 190 yards and one score in the 49ers' Week 8 loss to the Cardinals.

impact: Beasley led all Cowboys receivers in targets, catches, and receiving yards. Ex-Bills castoff Deonte Thompson finished second on the team with 27 yards. Beasley mustered just 314 yards last season but will likely lead Dallas in receiving until explosive rookie Michael Gallup gets up to speed in the league. Beasley should be on the radar as a low-ceiling PPR FLEX option.
report: Cole Beasley caught 7-of-8 targets for 73 in the Cowboys' Week 1 loss to the Panthers.

impact: Beasley sprained his ankle mid-week and was limited Friday. Even so, he'll be active for the Cowboys in Seattle. Beasley currently leads Dallas' skill players in targets (11) but has an extremely low ceiling given the team's propensity to run early and often. Ezekiel Elliott remains the only matchup-proof weekly starter among Dallas' offense.
report: Cole Beasley (ankle) will play in Week 3 against the Seahawks.

impact: The Cowboys’ supposed lead receiver was out-targeted by both Ezekiell Elliott and Geoff Swaim. Even with Dallas in catch-up mode for most of the second half, Beasley was unable to make a difference. He’ll be tough to trust against the Lions in Week 4.
report: Cole Beasley reeled in three-of-five targets for 46 yards Sunday in the Cowboys’ Week 3 loss to the Seahawks.

impact: Beasley was non-existent in the first half (one catch for 12 yards), but he fared much better after the break. He made a clutch grab on third-and-long in the third quarter, setting Dallas up with a fourth-and-one opportunity at the three-yard line, which Ezekiel Elliott converted for a first down. Beasley has drawn five or fewer targets in three of four games this year and with Dallas committing to a run-first offense, his workload is unlikely to increase. He shouldn’t be in any fantasy lineups for next week’s Sunday night matchup against Houston.
report: Cole Beasley brought in four catches for 55 yards on five targets Sunday in the Cowboys’ Week 4 win over Detroit.

impact: The first of Beasley's two touchdowns came on a play where he was left inexplicably wide open, taking it to the house for a 17-yard score in the second quarter. He followed that up with a nine-yarder just before halftime. Sunday's breakout ended a 12-game touchdown drought for Beasley. It was also the 29-year-old's first 100-yard receiving game in almost three years. Despite his success against Jacksonville, Beasley won't be of much fantasy interest next week at Washington.
report: Cole Beasley racked up nine catches for 101 yards and two touchdowns on 11 targets Sunday in the Cowboys’ Week 6 victory over the Jaguars.

impact: Beasley came crashing back to Earth following his outta-nowhere 9/101/2 performance against the Jaguars last week, catching his typical seven passes for a median amount of yards versus the Redskins. He reverted back into a possession receiver used strictly over the middle or near the sidelines, helping move the ball rather than erupt for explosive over-the-top plays. Expect a similar performance once the Cowboys return and face the Titans following next week's bye.
report: Cole Beasley recorded seven receptions on a team-high eight targets for 56 yards in the Cowboys' Week 7 heart-breaking loss to the Redskins.

impact: Beasley came crashing back to Earth following his outta-nowhere 9/101/2 performance against the Jaguars last week, catching his typical seven passes for a median amount of yards versus the Redskins. He reverted back into a possession receiver used strictly over the middle or near the sidelines, helping move the ball rather than erupt for explosive over-the-top plays. Expect a similar performance once the Cowboys return and face the Titans following next week's bye.
report: Cole Beasley recorded seven receptions on a team-high eight targets for 56 yards in the Cowboys' Week 7 heart-breaking loss to the Redskins.

impact: Beasley didn't see his first target until there was less than five minutes left in the game; he also threw a pass to Dak Prescott that was a hilarious fail in the red zone.  In Amari Cooper's debut with the team, Beasley went back to No. 3 duties as the slot man, playing fewer snaps than both Cooper and Michael Gallup.  Beasley will have popup games that will be totally unpredictable.
report: Cole Beasley caught 3-of-4 targets for 16 yards in the Cowboys' Week 9 loss to the Titans.

impact: Beasley's seven targets were second on the team to Ezekiel Elliott's eight.  Beasley committed an unusual drop in the end zone in the first half, botching a should-be four-yard touchdown.  This was still his best day since the Amari Cooper trade.  Beasley will be a WR4/5 for Week 12 vs. Washington.
report: Cole Beasley caught 5-of-7 targets for 51 yards in the Cowboys' Week 11 win over the Falcons.

impact: He added two catches for 22 yards on six targets. The rookie had absolutely nowhere to run for most of this game, gaining just 37 yards on his first 16 carries. He showed why he was the No. 2 overall pick on the 17th. He broke a tackle in the hole, broke another to bounce it outside, beat everyone to the corner, and then sprinted down the sideline for a 68-yard touchdown. Barkley could have some frustrating outings behind a questionable offensive line, but he has the ability to change a game in one play. He will hopefully be better utilized in the passing game next week – he did get going a bit in the screen game in the second half after not being targeted in the first – but he will be a solid RB1 against the Cowboys regardless.
report: Saquon Barkley rushed 18 times for 106 yards and a touchdown in the Giants' Week 1 loss to the Jaguars.

impact: Barkley couldn't get anything going with the Giants getting dominated up front. His pass game usage was encouraging after getting held to two catches last week, but it was a product of bad offensive line play. Barkley has lived up to his draft status, going over 100 total yards in his first two games. He's a mid-range RB1 for a matchup against a solid Houston run defense in Week 3.
report: Saquon Barkley rushed 11 times for 28 yards and caught 14-of-16 targets for 80 yards in the Giants' Week 2 loss to the Cowboys.

impact: Barkley remained the offensive centerpiece, but didn't get his first catch until the third quarter. He made one of his signature cutbacks behind the line before stiff-arming his way into the end-zone on his 15-yard touchdown. Barkley missed a few snaps with a knee bruise, but it's a non-issue for his Week 4 status. Barkley now has over 100 total yards in all three games this season. He's a locked-in RB1 for a matchup with the Saints.
report: Saquon Barkley rushed 17 times for 82 yards and a touchdown and caught five passes for 35 yards in Week 3 against the Texans.

impact: Barkley added 56 yards receiving while catching 6-of-8 targets.  Barkley went to the half with 28 yards on six touches but was able to find the end zone late.  It's going to be a struggle every week behind this horrendous offensive line, but Barkley is churning out enough numbers as a locked-in RB1.  Things won't be any easier next week on the road against the Panthers.
report: Saquon Barkley rushed 10 times for 44 yards and one touchdown in the Giants' 33-18, Week 4 loss to the Saints.

impact: The Giants' sluggish start continued with a heart-breaking, walk-off loss to Carolina in Week 5, but Barkley shouldn't be to blame. The second overall pick was his usual, productive self on Sunday, topping 100 yards from scrimmage for the fifth time in five games. Saquon delivered his first touchdown of the afternoon on a 57-yard pass from Odell Beckham, of all people. It was the easiest touchdown he'll ever score as there was nobody within 20 yards of him. Barkley found pay-dirt again in the fourth quarter, taking a 15-yard screen to the house to give New York a one-point lead with 1:08 remaining. The rookie came down awkwardly after hurdling a defender at the goal line but didn't seem to be showing any ill effects on the sideline. Barkley will remain in play as an RB1 when the Giants host Philadelphia on Thursday night.
report: Saquon Barkley went for 48 yards on 15 carries while adding four catches for 81 yards and two touchdowns on four targets Sunday in the Giants’ Week 5 loss to the Panthers.

impact: On a dismal night for the G-Men, Barkley was a bright spot, putting defenders on skates and routinely looking cannon shot as he hit the hole or found the edge. His score was a 50-yarder where he made a nimble cutback before exploding through the hole untouched. He fell just one yard shy of becoming the first Giants back to tally both 100 yards rushing and receiving in a game. Barkley has a gear few NFL players have, especially running backs. The Giants' line and passing game struggles haven't prevented Barkley from clearing 100 yards from scrimmage in each of his first six games. He's forcing himself into weekly top-three consideration. The burnable Falcons are on deck for Week 7.
report: Saquon Barkley rushed 13 times for 130 yards and a touchdown in the Giants' Week 6 loss to the Eagles, adding nine receptions for 99 additional yards.

impact: It's the first time this season Barkley has been held to fewer than 100 yards from scrimmage, but he made up for it with a boat load of catches, the short touchdown, and a two-point conversion at the end of the game.  Barkley just did not have much room to work with on the ground behind this pitiful offensive line and against a defense that got DT Grady Jarrett back from injury.  Barkley still remains an elite RB1 no matter the matchup and will get the Redskins in Week 8.
report: Saquon Barkley rushed 14 times for 43 yards and one touchdown and caught 9-of-10 targets for 51 yards in the Giants' 23-20, Week 7 loss to the Falcons on Monday night.

impact: It's the first time this season Barkley has been held to fewer than 100 yards from scrimmage, but he made up for it with a boat load of catches, the short touchdown, and a two-point conversion at the end of the game.  Barkley just did not have much room to work with on the ground behind this pitiful offensive line and against a defense that got DT Grady Jarrett back from injury.  Barkley still remains an elite RB1 no matter the matchup and will get the Redskins in Week 8.
report: Saquon Barkley rushed 14 times for 43 yards and one touchdown and caught 9-of-10 targets for 51 yards in the Giants' 23-20, Week 7 loss to the Falcons on Monday night.

impact: Washington entered this game playing elite run defense, and that remained the case as Barkley was bottled up on the ground.  He survived with 111 total yards and scored over 20 points in PPR leagues with heavy receiving involvement.  Barkley now gets to rest his rookie legs during New York's Week 9 bye.
report: Saquon Barkley rushed 13 times for 38 yards and caught 9-of-10 targets for 73 yards in the Giants' Week 8 loss to Washington.

impact: It's Barkley's eighth 100-yard game in nine contests as a pro.  There wasn't much running room to be found, and Barkley's biggest play was a 23-yard catch across the middle on a third down on the final game-winning drive with the Giants still down 23-20.  Bigger days are ahead obviously, and the Giants will head home on a short week to face the Bucs' bottom-barrel defense in Week 11.
report: Saquon Barkley rushed 20 times for 67 yards and caught 4-of-5 targets for 33 yards in the Giants' Week 10 win over the 49ers.

impact: Even Barkley's lack of involvement in the passing game can't be knocked since one of his three targets on the day resulted in a touchdown. A big outing was expected given that the Bucs were without stud defenders Kwon Alexander (torn ACL), Vinny Curry (ankle), and Lavonte David (knee), but Barkley exceeded all expectations in hitting season-high marks in carries, rushing yards, and touchdowns. The generational talent is now remarkably on pace for 253/1,164/11 on the ground and 102/864/5 receiving. He's obviously a matchup-proof commodity that should close the year in elite company.
report: Saquon Barkley rushed 27 times for a season-high 142 yards and two touchdowns, tacking on another receiving touchdown for good measure in the Giants' Week 11 victory over the Bucs.

impact: He wasn’t targeted in the passing game. Barber impressed in the first half, tallying 50 yards on eight carries before the break. His longest run of the afternoon came on a 23-yard burst with just over four minutes remaining in the first quarter. Tampa Bay built a big lead and tried to salt the clock by feeding it to Barber, though that approach mostly backfired as the Saints limited him to just 19 yards on 11 second-half carries (1.72 yards per attempt). Barber out-touched backup Jacquizz Rodgers by a commanding 19-3 margin in the victory while further establishing himself as the Bucs’ clear lead back. He’ll be a mere RB3 in a tough matchup with Philadelphia in Week 2.
report: Peyton Barber logged 69 yards on 19 carries Sunday in Tampa Bay’s Week 1 victory over the Saints.

impact: He has 91 yards on 35 carries this season; "good" for 2.6 yards per rush.  That isn't going to cut it for the Bucs' running game, making it imperative for them to give rookie Ronald Jones a longer look on the practice field this week.  Barber will remain a touchdown-or-bust flex option in Week 3 versus Pittsburgh.
report: Peyton Barber managed 22 yards on 16 carries and caught 1-of-2 targets for seven yards in the Bucs' Week 2 win over the Eagles.

impact: Second-round rookie Ronald Jones was also active, and promptly took his place at the table, out-touching Barber 11-8. Jones also led the Bucs in rushing yards (29) on an otherwise porous day from both. Tampa Bay will likely come out of their Week 5 bye with Jameis Winston and Ronald Jones as starters, seemingly making Barber droppable across all formats.
report: Peyton Barber rushed seven times for 24 yards in the Bucs' Week 4 loss to the Bears.

impact: There was some thought (hope) Ronald Jones would take on a bigger role coming out of the bye, but that did not materialize. Barber started and worked as the clear lead back. Jones seemed to be getting snaps in passing situations, but Barber was on the field late in the game and came down with a five-yard touchdown. Barber will face a tougher test next week against the Browns, but he will be a FLEX option.
report: Peyton Barber rushed 13 times for 82 yards and hauled in all four of his targets for 24 yards and a touchdown in the Bucs' Week 6 loss to the Falcons.

impact: Barber failed to secure either of his two targets in the passing game. He appeared to injure his ankle on his final target of the game in the third quarter and although the Bucs provided no update on his status in game, he never returned to the field the rest of the way. Barber's status will be one to monitor early in the week, but even if he is good to go in Week 8, he is at best a low-level FLEX option on the road against the Bengals.
report: Peyton Barber rushed 11 times for 30 yards in Sunday's Week 7 win over the Browns.

impact: Barber was not targeted in the passing game, where Jacquizz Rodgers came off the bench to make four catches. Barber was fortunate to score his goal-line touchdown after Adam Humphries was ruled down at the one the play before. Ronald Jones' hamstring injury does narrow the Bucs' backfield from three to two, raising Barber's floor as an RB2/flex option entering Week 9 at Carolina.
report: Peyton Barber rushed 19 times for 85 yards and a touchdown in the Bucs' Week 8 loss to the Bengals.

impact: Barber appeared to weak his ankle injury late, but there were no words of injury alarm after the fact. His practice status will be worth watching during the week. The Redskins are extremely stout against the run. With negative game script always a risk, Barber will not be a recommended RB2 for Week 10.
report: Peyton Barber rushed 11 times for 31 yards in the Bucs' Week 9 loss to the Panthers, adding two receptions for nine additional yards.

impact: He caught his lone pass-game target for five yards.  Barber had a couple runs of 12 and 13 yards back-to-back but did little else as the Bucs failed to score a touchdown.  Barber is a weekly TD-or-bust RB3.  The Giants are up next.
report: Peyton Barber rushed 13 times for 61 yards in the Bucs' Week 10 loss to the Redskins.

impact: He nearly scored a second touchdown on the goal line, but fumbled it forward into the cradling arms of Mike Evans. The Giants had actually been stout in the trenches despite trading away run-stuffing NT Damon Harrison at the deadline, so this outing is a bit of a shock. His 18 carries without rookie Ronald Jones (hamstring) available were certainly encouraging. Whether it's Jameis Winston or Ryan Fitzpatrick under center in Week 12, consider Barber a usage-based touchdown-dependent RB3/FLEX against San Francisco's front-seven.
report: Peyton Barber rushed 18 times for 106 yards and one touchdown in the Bucs' Week 11 loss to the Giants.

impact: Baldwin was playing in his first game since exiting Week 1 with a knee injury after he missed the entire preseason with a knee injury to his other knee. Baldwin lead the Seahawks in targets on Sunday and will enter Week 5 as a lower-end WR2 option against a Rams team that has been vulnerable to interior wideouts.
report: Doug Baldwin caught 5-of-7 passes for 41 yards in Sunday's Week 4 win over the Cardinals.

impact: Baldwin appeared to play his normal complement of snaps and did not look hampered by his knee injury as he blocked play after play. The real problem was Russell Wilson attempted just 21 passes as Seattle consistently gashed the Rams' defense on the ground. Baldwin should have better games moving forward, but Seattle's new emphasis on the running game is very concerning for his rest-of-season outlook. He should be considered a WR3 next week against the Raiders.
report: Doug Baldwin caught his only target for one yard in the Seahawks' Week 5 loss to the Rams.

impact: Baldwin's one-target Week 5 game sent the fantasy community into a tailspin, but he rebounded for a solid game against an Oakland defense that has struggled mightily to cover the slot.  Baldwin's eight targets were easily a team high; the next-closest Seahawks pass catcher had only four.  Despite his slow start, Baldwin will emerge from Seattle's Week 7 bye as an every-week fantasy WR2.  He is a recommended buy-low target in fantasy leagues.
report: Doug Baldwin caught 6-of-8 targets for 91 yards in the Seahawks' Week 6 win over the Raiders.

impact: Baldwin could only watch as Tyler Lockett once again found the end zone. Baldwin remains scoreless on the season as Lockett and David Moore find the painted area with regularity. If there's good news, it's that Baldwin has cleared four catches in 3-of-4 games. He will find himself on the WR3/4 borderline for Thursday's short-week matchup with the Packers.
report: Doug Baldwin caught 5-of-5 targets for 39 yards in the Seahawks' Week 10 loss to the Rams.

impact: Baldwin finally scored his first touchdown of the season, but it was not easy. Baldwin was wide open for a 21-yard score in the first quarter, but Russell Wilson flat missed him. The two then narrowly failed to connect in the end zone on a six-yarder in the second quarter before finally getting it right on the next play. Tonight was Baldwin's first 10-target game of the season. That won't happen often in the Seahawks' run-heavy offense, though Baldwin has now cleared five catches in back-to-back games. He will be a WR3 for Week 12 against the Panthers.
report: Doug Baldwin caught 7-of-10 targets for 52 yards and a touchdown in the Seahawks' Week 11 win over the Packers.

impact: With the offense struggling to move the ball, Miami introduced some wildcat looks featuring Ballage. His longest gain was called back by a penalty, however, and the plays did not amount to much. Despite this surprising usage, Ballage is only rosterable in Dynasty formats barring an injury to Frank Gore or Kenyan Drake.
report: Kalen Ballage rushed once for negative-two yards and caught both of his targets for 17 yards in the Dolphins' Week 9 win over the Jets.

impact: He got out-touched by Bilal Powell 16 to 15.  Crowell seemed to be missing a step after suffering an ankle injury last week and barely practicing.  Crowell has been a boom-bust weekly performer reliant on long runs and/or short TDs.  He will remain a high-variance RB2/flex option in Week 7 against the Vikings.
report: Isaiah Crowell rushed 13 times for 40 yards and caught 2-of-2 targets for 12 yards in the Jets' Week 6 win over the Colts.

impact: He caught a 21-yard pass on three targets while committing a bad drop on another pass.  Crowell has been battling ankle and foot issues in recent weeks but had to carry the load in this one with Bilal Powell leaving early in the first half with a neck injury.  Crowell gets the Bears on the road in Week 8.  Assuming he's healthy for it, Crowell will be a tough sell as an RB2/FLEX.
report: Isaiah Crowell rushed 11 times for 29 yards in the Jets' Week 7 loss to the Vikings.

impact: He added one catch for 13 yards. It was a negative gamescript for Crowell with the Jets trailing the entire game. They abandoned the run in the second half, leading to more work for Trenton Cannon. Crowell's ROS outlook is rising with Bilal Powell out for the year, but he's prone to bad games whenever the Jets play from behind.
report: Isaiah Crowell rushed 13 times for 25 yards in Week 9 against Chicago.

impact: Miami has struggled to stop the run all season, but Crowell could not get anything going as the Jets went nowhere early in the game. He finished the first half with just 16 yards on five carries. Crowell found more running room after the break, but he did not have much of a chance with the offense floundering. Crowell will be in a similar spot next week against the Bills, a lackluster run defense which does not have the offense to force the Jets into negative game script, but he will be tough to trust as more than a low-end RB2 with Sam Darnold struggling.
report: Isaiah Crowell carried the ball 13 times for 49 yards and caught one pass for 11 yards in the Jets' Week 9 loss to the Dolphins.

impact: His five-yard bunny score didn't occur until the Jets were already down by 30-plus points.  It was the team's lone touchdown all game in New York's embarrassing 41-10 home loss.  Behind one of the NFL's worst offensive lines, Gang Green's running game has gone in the absolute tank.  Crowell will remain a touchdown-or-bust flex option when the Jets return from their Week 11 bye.
report: Isaiah Crowell rushed seven times for 19 yards and a touchdown and caught 2-of-2 targets for 18 yards in the Jets' Week 10 loss to the Bills.

impact: The Redskins had little reason to air it out while leading comfortably, which would account for Crowder’s abbreviated workload. Obviously Crowder’s season debut was short on fantasy pyrotechnics, but the contract-year slot receiver should have a chance to rebound next week in a favorable matchup against Indy’s Swiss-cheese secondary.
report: Jamison Crowder managed three catches for 32 yards on four targets Sunday in Washington’s Week 1 victory over the Cardinals.

impact: He got the ball on Washington’s first play from scrimmage, chewing up 25 yards on a reverse. Crowder didn’t see much work after that, though he was involved with a controversial play in the second quarter. Darius Leonard appeared to strip the ball from Crowder following a four-yard catch, though the play was later overturned after replay showed Crowder was down by contact. The contract-year receiver is off to an underwhelming start with just five catches for 40 yards through his first two contests. We’ll see what the former Duke Blue Devil can cook up next week against the Packers.
report: Jamison Crowder absorbed two-of-four targets for eight yards while adding a team-leading 29 rushing yards on two carries Sunday in the Redskins’ Week 2 loss to the Colts.

impact: Crowder doubled his Weeks 1 and 2 production while catching his first touchdown pass from Alex Smith. We thought Crowder would mesh well with Smith's conservative skill-set, but Smith has been more locked onto Jordan Reed and Chris Thompson. Crowder has yet to make a viable WR4 case. He does have a juicy for Week 5 when the Redskins come off their bye against the Saints.
report: Jamison Crowder caught 4-of-4 targets for 39 yards and a touchdown in the Redskins' Week 3 win over the Packers.

impact: Coutee came out of the gates quickly, catching two passes in the first quarter. He had another target in that quarter which should have been a long catch-and-run touchdown, but it was thrown behind him and broken up. Unfortunately, he only caught one more pass the rest of the game as Deshaun Watson struggled. That could happen a lot next week against the Jaguars, making Coutee a risky FLEX option.
report: Keke Coutee hauled in 3-of-5 targets for 33 yards in the Texans' Week 6 win over the Bills.

impact: Coutee showed no ill effects from his months-long hamstring injury and severely out-targeted Demaryius Thomas, 9 to 1.  Coutee is likely to remain up and down as a complementary receiver on a run-first team, but at least we can say he is healthy again.  He'll be a high-risk WR3/flex in Week 12 against Tennessee.
report: Keke Coutee caught 5-of-9 targets for 77 yards in the Texans' Week 11 win over the Redskins.

impact: Cousins came out peppering Dalvin Cook with early targets, beating an aggressive Niners defense for chunk gains.  He later threw a dime over the top of CB Ahkello Witherspoon to hit Stefon Diggs for a 22-yard touchdown down the left sideline.  It was a perfectly-placed ball.  Cousins' second score was an 11-yard hookup to Kyle Rudolph.  He was also cooking with Adam Thielen, who had 102 yards on six grabs, killing the Niners out of the slot.  Cousins' debut couldn't have gone much better.  The 1-0 Vikings will head on the road to Green Bay in Week 2.
report: Kirk Cousins completed 20-of-36 passes for 244 yards and two touchdowns in the Vikings' 24-16, Week 1 win over the 49ers.

impact: It was a tie, but Cousins did everything he could to win this game despite facing an underrated defense. He threw a laser to Laquon Treadwell for his first score of the day, and his third was a beautiful pass to Stefon Diggs for a 75-yard touchdown, almost all of that coming in the air. He was even better with the game on the line. Despite an interception which went right through Treadwell’s hands, Cousins was able to lead the Vikings back with an eight-play touchdown drive he finished with an outstanding tight-window throw to Adam Thielen and a two-point conversion to Diggs to tie the game. He led what should have been two scoring drives in overtime, but Daniel Carlson missed both field goals including one as time expired. With Buffalo up next, Cousins will be a locked-in QB1 next week.
report: Kirk Cousins completed 35-of-48 passes for 425 yards, four touchdowns, and an interception in the Vikings' Week 2 tie with the Packers.

impact: The Vikings' offensive line didn't help matters, allowing Cousins to be blindsided and strip-sacked on the team's first two possessions. Minnesota's passing offense was playing catch-up from that point forward as Cousins was forced to attempt 55 passes under duress for the remainder of the afternoon. Cousins' lone touchdown came in garbage time when he found Kyle Rudolph in the end zone down 27-0 with less than two minutes to play. The Vikings have another tough test on the road against the Rams Thursday night.
report: Kirk Cousins completed 40-of-55 passes for 296 yards, one touchdown, and an interception in the Vikings' Week 3 loss to the Bills.

impact: Cousins also lost a fumble on a botched sideways pass. As has become a theme, Cousins was attempting and converting heat check throws in the first half. His touchdown was a three-yarder where only Adam Thielen could catch it in the end zone. Cousins has made as many "wow" passes as anyone in football so far this season. The Vikings' offense was far less effective after halftime but got back into rhythm in time to close the game out in the fourth quarter. Cousins is making hay with his elite receiver duo of Thielen and Stefon Diggs. He'll be a high-end QB1 for next week's home date with the abysmal Cardinals.
report: Kirk Cousins completed 30-of-37 passes for 301 yards and a touchdown in the Vikings' 23-21, Week 5 win over the Eagles.

impact: He added a touchdown on a seven-yard run. Cousins fumbled on a sack that was returned for a touchdown, but he was sharp in this one, completing 71 percent of his passes. Cousins' only passing TD was a perfect throw over the middle to Adam Thielen. He's now led the Vikings to consecutive wins after losing to Buffalo and the Rams. Cousins gets a matchup with the Jets in Week 7.
report: Kirk Cousins completed 24-of-34 passes for 233 yards with a touchdown and an interception in the Vikings' Week 6 win over the Cardinals.

impact: It was a struggle much of the day as both offenses really had trouble moving the ball.  At one point, both teams were a combined 0-for-12 on third downs.  Cousins, however, did throw a 34-yard touchdown to Adam Thielen on the opening drive before then hitting Aldrick Robinson for a second 34-yard score in the fourth quarter.  Both were dimes from Cousins in tight coverage.  Cousins will look to get back on track with big numbers next week against the Saints at home.
report: Kirk Cousins completed 25-of-40 passes for 241 yards and two touchdowns in the Vikings' Week 7 win over the Jets.

impact: It was a struggle much of the day as both offenses really had trouble moving the ball.  At one point, both teams were a combined 0-for-12 on third downs.  Cousins, however, did throw a 34-yard touchdown to Adam Thielen on the opening drive before then hitting Aldrick Robinson for a second 34-yard score in the fourth quarter.  Both were dimes from Cousins in tight coverage.  Cousins will look to get back on track with big numbers next week against the Saints at home.
report: Kirk Cousins completed 25-of-40 passes for 241 yards and two touchdowns in the Vikings' Week 7 win over the Jets.

impact: Cousins got off to a fast start with a touchdown to Stefon Diggs. He put up huge stats despite the loss, but the Vikings couldn’t overcome a pair of turnovers. Cousins threw a game-changing pick-six in the second half and had multiple passes knocked down at the line of scrimmage. He salvaged his night with a late touchdown to Adam Thielen. Cousins will remain a QB1 for Week 9 against Detroit.
report: Kirk Cousins completed 30-of-40 passes for 351 yards with two touchdowns and an interception in Week 8 against the Saints.

impact: Cousins was without Stefon Diggs (ribs) and really struggled, forcing his interception into double-coverage trying to go to Adam Thielen.  Cousins also was credited with a lost fumble deep in Detroit territory, but Dalvin Cook was to blame who dropped the pitch on a run play.  Cousins hasn't had big numbers on the stat sheet in weeks really but now gets the bye for the Vikings to try and get healthy before going to Chicago in Week 11.  Cousins will be a back-end QB1.
report: Kirk Cousins completed 18-of-22 passes for 164 yards, one touchdown, and one interception in the Vikings' Week 9 win over the Lions.

impact: This was a rough game for Cousins, who played worse than his stats. He had just 57 yards and an interception at halftime, but salvaged his night with a touchdown on the final drive. One of Cousins' interceptions was a late fourth quarter pick-six that crushed the Vikings' comeback attempt. Cousins has had a downswing the last two weeks, but he's in a rebound spot against the Packers in Week 12.
report: Kirk Cousins completed 30-of-46 passes for 262 yards with two touchdowns and a pair of interceptions in the Vikings' Week 11 loss to Chicago.

impact: Crabtree bounced back from two drops on his first three targets. He showed good body control to on his touchdown, getting his feet down in the back of the end-zone from 12 yard out. Crabtree could've had more yards but was rested in the second half. He'll be a high-floor WR2 for Thursday night's game with the Bengals.
report: Michael Crabtree caught 3-of-6 passes for 38 yards and a touchdown in Week 1 against Buffalo.

impact: John Brown has been the explosive option in the passing game, but Crabtree continues to be a reliable set of hands for Joe Flacco. He made a couple big catches when the game was in doubt including a third-down conversion in the second quarter. His possession role is not going to result in much fantasy upside when he does not find the end zone, but Crabtree is at worse a solid option in PPR formats. He will be even better than that in a good matchup against the Steelers next week.
report: Michael Crabtree hauled in 7-of-10 targets for 61 yards in the Ravens' Week 3 win over the Broncos.

impact: Crabtree's 66 yards were a season-high, but it was the 11th consecutive game that he failed to reach 70-yards receiving in a game. He dropped multiple passes on the day, including a potential game-winning touchdown in the final seconds of regulation. Crabtree will be a WR3 in Week 6 against the Titans.
report: Michael Crabtree caught 6-of-12 targets for 66 yards in Sunday's Week 5 loss to the Browns.

impact: The volume had been there all along, but Crabtree still hadn't recorded more than 70 yards in a single game prior to Sunday. He finally turned in a terrific outing against Tennessee, hauling in the team's only receiving score on the day. John Brown (2/28) still profiles as the Ravens' deep threat, but both wideouts are capable of WR2-type outings on any given week. Pending who the Saints stick Marshon Lattimore on, both wideouts have a chance for monumental performances against New Orleans' shoddy secondary next week.
report: Michael Crabtree caught 6-of-9 targets for 93 yards and one touchdown in the Ravens' Week 6 victory over the Titans.

impact: Crabtree got out-caught and out-gained by John Brown today, but Crabtree has out-targeted Brown four of the past five games. He's also cleared 60 yards four of the past five games. Crabtree has vanishingly-little upside but continues to maintain one of the safest WR3 floors in fantasy football. The Panthers are on tap for Week 8.
report: Michael Crabtree caught 5-of-9 targets for 66 yards in the Ravens' Week 7 loss to the Saints.

impact: Crabtree got out-caught and out-gained by John Brown today, but Crabtree has out-targeted Brown four of the past five games. He's also cleared 60 yards four of the past five games. Crabtree has vanishingly-little upside but continues to maintain one of the safest WR3 floors in fantasy football. The Panthers are on tap for Week 8.
report: Michael Crabtree caught 5-of-9 targets for 66 yards in the Ravens' Week 7 loss to the Saints.

impact: The five targets mark a new season-low for Crabtree after he saw at least eight Weeks 2-7.  Crabtree will look to bounce back against the Steelers next week.  He went 3-29-0 in Week 4 against Pittsburgh.
report: Michael Crabtree caught 3-of-5 targets for 31 yards in the Ravens' Week 8 loss to the Panthers.

impact: It was another listless outing for the drop-prone veteran. Crabtree had the end zone in his sights on a second-quarter pass from Joe Flacco, but couldn't come up with it. It wasn't the sharpest throw in the world but Crabtree still should have had it. Even with Baltimore in catch-up mode in the second half, Crabtree did almost nothing to move the needle. The 31-year-old has committed an embarrassing 10 drops this year, which leads the league. Crabtree and the rapidly-fading Ravens will face the Raiders at home after their bye week.
report: Michael Crabtree corralled two-of-six targets for 25 yards Sunday in the Ravens’ Week 9 loss to the Steelers.

impact: Crabtree won't be a fantasy option in the Ravens' new run-dominant attack.
report: Michael Crabtree caught 1-of-3 targets for seven yards in the Ravens' Week 11 win over the Bengals.

impact: Cooper had just 17 receptions for 160 yards in six career games versus the Broncos prior to today, so this was an extremely positive game for Cooper after catching just one pass for nine yards in Week 1. No other Oakland player had more than four targets as Cooper played inside and outside during the game and was the clear number one target in the offense. Being a boom-or-bust option to this point in his career, Cooper will look to build off this game Week 3 versus the Dolphins.
report: Amari Cooper caught 10-of-10 targets for 116 yards in Sunday's Week 2 loss to the Broncos.

impact: It was back into hiding for Cooper, who appeared to run the wrong route on Derek Carr's first interception and committed an inexplicable second half drop. Cooper, an NFL receiver, let the ball go right through his hands without touching it. His quiet day came as Jordy Nelson exploded and Martavis Bryant drew as many targets. Cooper is simply too volatile to be counted on as an every-week WR3. He has a tough Week 4 matchup in the Browns.
report: Amari Cooper caught 2-of-5 targets for 17 yards in the Raiders' Week 3 loss to the Dolphins.

impact: All of the Raiders' pass catchers got "theirs" in this overtime shootout as Derek Carr threw for 447 yards.  Browns CBs Denzel Ward and T.J. Carrie were no match for Amari, who now has topped 100 yards in two of the Raiders' first four games but was held below 20 yards in the other two.  Cooper will remain a volatile WR3/flex play when Oakland draws Casey Hayward's Chargers next.
report: Amari Cooper caught 8-of-12 targets for 128 yards and a touchdown in the Raiders' Week 4 win over the Browns.

impact: In his defense, Cooper's one catch was his only target on the day. Even so, it's been a rollercoaster of a season (career?) thus far for Average Amari, as he's either recorded less than 20 yards or exploded for 110-plus in all five games this season. He'll stay a boom-bust WR3 moving forward.
report: Amari Cooper thankfully caught his only target for 10 yards in the Raiders' Week 5 loss to the Chargers.

impact: It's an unfortunate but unsurprising outcome after Cooper was knocked unconscious by Seahawks S Bradley McDougald.  McDougald was not flagged for the helmet-to-helmet hit, but he will almost certainly draw a significant fine.  Cooper finished catch-less on one target.  The Raiders have a Week 7 bye.
report: Amari Cooper is done for the day in Week 6 with a concussion.

impact: His eight targets led the team as Cooper was making his Cowboys debut following his acquisition from the Raiders.  He beat Malcolm Butler for a four-yard score in the first quarter.  OC Scott Linehan was clearly trying to scheme him the ball early, but the offense went off the rails in the second half and didn't score after the break.  Still, it's pretty clear the Cowboys plan to force the ball to Cooper, and Dak Prescott's one interception was a forced ball into double-coverage in the end zone to Cooper.  Cooper will be a WR3 next week against the Eagles.
report: Amari Cooper caught 5-of-8 targets for 58 yards and one touchdown in the Cowboys' 28-14, Week 9 loss to the Titans on Monday night.

impact: Cooper got off to a fast start with 50 yards in the first half. He had just one catch after that, but it's another encouraging game after Cooper scored in his Cowboys' debut. Cooper was open on multiple downfield plays, but was overthrown by Dak Prescott. His rest-of-season value is up in Dallas, where Cooper is the clear featured wideout. Cooper is a WR2 for a Week 11 matchup with the Falcons.
report: Amari Cooper caught 6-of-10 targets for 75 yards in the Cowboys' Week 10 win over the Eagles.

impact: It was a step back for Cooper in his third game with the team after amassing an 11-133-1 line in his first two appearances against the Titans and Eagles.  Cooper averaged nine targets per game in those contests.  The matchup against Atlanta was ripe, but Ezekiel Elliott was just cruising all afternoon, totaling 201 yards and a score on 30 touches.  Cooper was held catch-less in the first half but made a couple contested grabs in the third quarter.  Cooper will look to rebound against the Redskins on Thanksgiving.
report: Amari Cooper caught 3-of-5 targets for 36 yards in the Cowboys' 22-19, Week 11 win over the Falcons.

impact: Making his return from a five-week hamstring injury, Cook didn't get the start but did out-snap and out-touch Latavius Murray, who managed 47 yards on 11 touches but also scored a goal-line touchdown.  Cook looked good on his big 70-yard run before getting dragged down at the five-yard line.  He now has the bye to get even healthier ahead of Week 11 against the Bears.
report: Dalvin Cook rushed 10 times for 89 yards and caught all four of his targets for 20 yards in the Vikings' Week 9 win over the Lions.

impact: He also lost a fumble in the first quarter. The Vikings run game was completely shut down by Chicago and they were forced to go pass heavy in the second half. Cook looked over his hamstring issues coming off Minnesota's bye and likely would have been more involved if not for gameflow. Cook has a get-right matchup with a Packers defensive line that will be without DE Mike Daniels in Week 12.
report: Dalvin Cook had nine carries for 12 yards in Week 11 against Chicago.

impact: Cooks seems to be perfectly comfortable in Los Angeles. After going for 87 yards in the season opener, he was even better in this game. He probably should have had a long touchdown, but Jared Goff underthrew him, forcing him to come back to the ball and the defender. Cooks made another big play in the fourth quarter, going high for a catch to convert a third down. The Rams should have a tougher time against the Chargers next week, but Cooks will be a top-20 option all season.
report: Brandin Cooks hauled in 7-of-9 targets for 159 yards in the Rams' Week 2 win over the Cardinals.

impact: Cooks fell just one foot short of his first touchdown in a Rams uniform when he pulled in a tightly covered target across the middle. Despite not having a touchdown yet, Cooks looks very comfortable with Jared Goff and coach Sean McVay is crafting up a lot of plays to get Cooks involved. The speedster will look to find the end zone next Thursday against the Vikings as a WR2.
report: Brandin Cooks caught 7-of-8 targets for 90 yards in the Rams' Week 3 win over the Chargers.

impact: Cooks caught a 44-yard pass on the Rams' third play from scrimmage and went into witness protection thereafter. The Rams' passing attack never really got in gear as it dealt with injury to Cooper Kupp and watched Todd Gurley go bonkers on the ground. Cooks should bounce back as a high-end WR2 for Week 7 against the 49ers.
report: Brandin Cooks caught 2-of-6 targets for 53 yards in the Rams' Week 6 win over the Broncos.

impact: The Rams' passing game did not have to do much in this one, but Cooks still had a good day. His best play was a 19-yard touchdown in the second quarter in which he ran a great route to get open. The offense should have more to do next week against the Packers, and Cooks will be a borderline WR1 in that good matchup.
report: Brandin Cooks hauled in 4-of-5 targets for 64 yards and a touchdown in the Rams' Week 7 win over the 49ers.

impact: The Rams' passing game did not have to do much in this one, but Cooks still had a good day. His best play was a 19-yard touchdown in the second quarter in which he ran a great route to get open. The offense should have more to do next week against the Packers, and Cooks will be a borderline WR1 in that good matchup.
report: Brandin Cooks hauled in 4-of-5 targets for 64 yards and a touchdown in the Rams' Week 7 win over the 49ers.

impact: Both the targets and yards were Cooks' most in four games, but he found himself dealing with some sticky coverage from Packers rookie CB Jaire Alexander. Cooks has not cleared 100 yards since September, but there has been nothing concerning about his usage. He's just dealing with the typical statistical ups and downs of a fantasy season. Especially with six teams on bye, Cooks will remain in the WR1 mix for next week's showdown with the Saints.
report: Brandin Cooks caught 3-of-8 targets for 74 yards in the Rams' Week 8 win over the Packers.

impact: Cooks’ "revenge" game could not have started much better. After coming up with a 48-yard catch to help spark the second drive, Cooks finished it off with a grab in the back of the end zone for a four-yard score, his third of the season. He opened up the second half with a 15-yard catch on the opening scoring drive, made a great diving catch on a tipped pass the next series, and had another 15-yard gain to top 100 yards on a game-tying touchdown drive in the fourth. The Rams offense sputtered from there, but it was still a good outing for Cooks. He will be a borderline WR1 next week against the Seahawks.
report: Brandin Cooks caught 6-of-8 targets for 114 yards and a touchdown in the Rams' Week 9 loss to the Saints.

impact: Cooks' rushing score came on a jet sweep. The Rams spent the better part of four quarters setting it up. Both the targets and catches were new season highs. Cooks could begin seeing 10 looks with greater regularity if Cooper Kupp (knee) is lost for the season. He will be a WR1 for next Monday's guaranteed shootout with the Rams in Mexico City.
report: Brandin Cooks caught 10-of-12 targets for 100 yards in the Rams' Week 10 win over the Seahawks, adding a nine-yard rushing touchdown.

impact: Conley's score was a bullet on a first quarter post route. Conley got the inside track on Artie Burns. It was a nice play, but Conley has just three targets through two games. Patrick Mahomes is working miracles, but he can't make Conley fantasy relevant.
report: Chris Conley caught 2-of-2 targets for 17 yards and a touchdown in the Chiefs' Week 2 win over the Steelers.

impact: Conner had one blip on his resume with a fumble in the 4th quarter that let the Browns back in the game, but other than that, had a dominant game as a dual purpose back. Conner had an untouched 4-yard rushing score in the 2nd quarter and then a 22-yard touchdown run in the 3rd quarter. On top of his performance, no other Steeler RB even registered a touch in the game. As long as Le'Veon Bell continues his hold out, Conner is a RB1 for fantasy purposes.
report: Steelers RB James Conner rushed 31 times for 135 yards and two touchdowns while catching 5-of-6 targets for 57 yards in Sunday's Week 1 game versus the Browns.

impact: With the Steelers down 21-0 by the end of the first quarter, they never bothered to establish the run. Conner missed some time with an injury, but the Steelers never announced what was bothering him. Stevan Ridley ran in his place. Conner was on the field to finish the game. Provided Le'Veon Bell does not report this week, Conner will again be a usage-based RB1 for Week 3 against the Bucs.
report: James Conner rushed eight times for 17 yards and a touchdown in the Steelers' Week 2 loss to the Chiefs, adding five receptions for 48 additional yards.

impact: Conner fell victim to gameflow with the Ravens winning time of possesion. The Steelers went pass-heavy after getting behind early and didn't have any red-zone trips. Conner managed to catch a two-point conversion to save his night, but it was still his worst game to date. Conner will be an RB2 for Week 5 against the Falcons.
report: James Conner rushed nine times for 19 yards and caught 3-of-7 targets for 25 yards in Week 4 against the Ravens.

impact: Conner touched the ball seven times for 72 yards and a score on the opening drive and never looked back. He was piling on yards after first contact against the Falcons' injury-ruined defense. Conner has now hit 185 yards from scrimmage in 2-of-5 games, though he's totaled just 204 yards across his other three contests. Thankfully for his fantasy owners, the Bengals are an attackable Week 6 matchup. The Steelers then go on bye in Week 7. That is when Le'Veon Bell is expected to finally return.
report: James Conner rushed 21 times for 110 yards and two touchdowns in the Steelers' Week 5 win over the Falcons, adding four receptions for 75 additional yards.

impact: He added four catches for 18 yards on seven targets.  The NFL's leading tackle-shedder, Conner showed it in this one, consistently bulldozing would-be tacklers and injuring a couple along the way as S Shawn Williams was concussed on one of the long runs.  Conner's scores were both of the one-yard plunge variety.  He should have had a third touchdown but was ruled down at the one before getting stuffed on 1st- and 3rd-and-goal runs.  A premier RB1, Conner's workload will now be subject to question with Le'Veon Bell expected to report to the team during the Week 7 bye.
report: James Conner rushed 19 times for 111 yards and two touchdowns in the Steelers' 28-21, Week 6 win over the Bengals.

impact: He added four catches for 18 yards on seven targets.  The NFL's leading tackle-shedder, Conner showed it in this one, consistently bulldozing would-be tacklers and injuring a couple along the way as S Shawn Williams was concussed on one of the long runs.  Conner's scores were both of the one-yard plunge variety.  He should have had a third touchdown but was ruled down at the one before getting stuffed on 1st- and 3rd-and-goal runs.  A premier RB1, Conner's workload will now be subject to question with Le'Veon Bell expected to report to the team during the Week 7 bye.
