Of course, Darnold proved the Jets' caution correct when he immediately tossed a pair of late-game picks when forced into comeback mode. Darnold has now turned in back-to-back unimpressive performances after his Week 1 throttling of the Lions. He has 10 days to review tape before a foreboding Week 4 matchup with the Jaguars.
report: Sam Darnold completed 15-of-31 passes for 169 yards, zero touchdowns and two interceptions in New York's 21-17, Week 3 loss to the Browns.

impact: It's another rough game for Darnold after throwing two interceptions last week. Darnold managed to salvage his game with a late touchdown to Jordan Leggett, but the Jets offense continued to struggle. Darnold has went through some expected early-season growing pains, failing to throw multiple touchdowns since the season opener. He'll have another dificult matchup in Week 5 against the Broncis.
report: Sam Darnold completed 17-of-34 passes for 167 yards and a touchdown in Week 4 against the Jaguars.

impact: He only took one sack and three hits all game as the Jets neutralized Von Miller and leaned on their running game on a career day for Isaiah Crowell.  Darnold was terrific in his own right, though, finding Robby Anderson in stride on a 76-yard touchdown bomb, then showing pinpoint ball placement on Anderson's 35-yard score and Terrelle Pryor's 20-yard TD.  Darnold has struggled in tough matchups, unsurprising for a rookie.  He got a favorable one Sunday against Denver's overrated pass defense, and draws an above-average one at home against the Colts in Week 6.
report: Sam Darnold completed 10-of-22 passes for 198 yards, three touchdowns, and an interception in the Jets' Week 5 win over the Broncos.

impact: With the exception of a telegraphed pick Colts FS Malik Hooker easily jumped all over, Darnold was fantastic for the second straight week.  He carved up the Colts' interior defense on slant routes, took only two sacks, and made numerous plays with his feet outside the pocket.  Darnold had a predictable Weeks 3-4 rough patch in road trips to Cleveland and Jacksonville, but otherwise his performance has been highly promising for the NFL's youngest-ever Week 1 starting quarterback.  Darnold will be a two-QB-league play when Gang Green hosts the Vikings next.
report: Sam Darnold completed 24-of-30 passes for 280 yards, two touchdowns, and an interception in the Jets' Week 6 win over the Colts.

impact: Darnold was horrible with one of the worst quarterback performances of the season.  He missed open receivers, overthrew Robby Anderson on a potential 81-yard touchdown, and was also hurt by a couple drops.  The interceptions were a pass thrown right to CB Holton Hill, another tipped by Xavier Rhodes to Harrison Smith, and a drop-turned-INT by Charone Peake to Trae Waynes.  Darnold was able to score a one-yard rushing touchdown to boost his stats, but his 40.5% completion rate is ugly.  Darnold will be harassed next week in Chicago.
report: Sam Darnold completed just 17-of-42 passes for 206 yards, one touchdown, and three interceptions in the Jets' 37-17, Week 7 loss to the Vikings.

impact: The good news is Davis drew by far a team-high 13 targets.  The bad news is he didn't do much with them, lost Marcus Mariota to a shoulder/elbow injury, and couldn't beat Minkah Fitzpatrick on a touchdown opportunity inside the five-yard line in the first half.  Davis' going-forward outlook will very much depend on Mariota's health.  He'll be far less appealing if Gabbert is forced to start.
report: Corey Davis caught 6-of-13 targets for 62 yards in the Titans' Week 1 loss to Miami.

impact: Davis led Tennessee in targets for the second consecutive week, already putting him at the 20-target mark for the year. Though they weren't efficient targets, Davis used his athleticism to catch-and-run for additional yards throughout the day. His ceiling is much lower with Blaine Gabbert under center, but as long as Davis remains the focal point of Tennessee's passing offense, he'll stay a low-end WR2 for the rest of the year.
report: Corey Davis caught 5-of-7 targets for 55 yards in the Titans' Week 2 win over the Texans.

impact: Tennessee's passing game was nonexistent, managing 108 yards from Marcus Mariota and Blaine Gabbert combined.  Davis' 34 receiving yards actually led the team.  Davis gets a good Week 4 matchup against a beatable Eagles cornerback unit, but the state of this offense always renders him a high-risk WR3/flex option.
report: Corey Davis caught 2-of-4 targets for 34 yards in the Titans' Week 3 win over the Jaguars.

impact: Consistently getting targets, Davis always seemed likely to break out once Marcus Mariota returned to full health, and that is exactly what happened against the Eagles. He had already set a new season-high in yardage by midway through the second quarter, and that was with Mariota missing him for what would have been a long gain. Mariota found him for that long play in the fourth quarter, but that was not the end of the action. Following an Eagles field goal, the Titans needed a touchdown to win, and Davis delivered with a leaping grab with just five seconds left. With Mariota looking healthy, Davis will be a top-24 option next week against the Bills.
report: Corey Davis hauled in 9-of-15 targets for 161 yards and a touchdown in the Titans' Week 4 win over the Eagles.

impact: The Titans got Davis matched up with other defenders at times, but he mostly squared off with Bills top CB Tre'Davious White, who handily won their one-on-one draws.  As Tennessee's passing game has gone, Davis' box-score production has gone.  He gets an even tougher Week 6 matchup against Baltimore's shutdown pass defense.
report: Corey Davis caught 4-of-6 targets for 49 yards in the Titans' Week 5 loss to the Bills.

impact: Davis fell victim to the Titans' miserable pass protection, hauling in just one catch from Marcus Mariota, who was on his back 11 times throughout the afternoon. The only positive to come from this is that four of Mariota's 15 attempts were directed at Davis. As the Titans' O goes, Davis goes, and both went nowhere in a hurry Sunday. He'll remain a low-end WR2 in Week 7 against the Chargers' secondary.
report: Corey Davis vacuumed just one of his four targets for 24 yards in the Titans' Week 6 romping to the Ravens.

impact: It's another rough game from Davis, who was led to 24 yards last week. Davis was out-targeted by Tajae Sharpe and had couldn't come down with an end-zone look in the fourth quarter. He hasn't been on the same page with Marcus Mariota over the last few weeks. Davis will be a WR3 when the Titans come out of their bye in Week 9.
report: Corey Davis caught 3-of-7 passes for 10 yards in Week 7 against the Chargers.

impact: It's another rough game from Davis, who was led to 24 yards last week. Davis was out-targeted by Tajae Sharpe and had couldn't come down with an end-zone look in the fourth quarter. He hasn't been on the same page with Marcus Mariota over the last few weeks. Davis will be a WR3 when the Titans come out of their bye in Week 9.
report: Corey Davis caught 3-of-7 passes for 10 yards in Week 7 against the Chargers.

impact: The 10 targets were easily a team-high as Davis saw 34.5% of the target share in this one.  He's been dominating the looks all season for Tennessee, but the quality of those passes have been all over the map.  Davis should have had a 10-yard touchdown, but Marcus Mariota missed him wide open in the end zone on what was maybe one of his two bad throws on the night.  He also missed Davis for a short gain on his first pass on the game.  Davis will get the Patriots next in Week 10.  He went 5-63-2 against them in the playoffs last year.
report: Corey Davis caught 6-of-10 targets for 56 yards in the Titans' Week 9 win over the Cowboys.

impact: Held to 65 yards or fewer in seven of the Titans' first eight games, Davis owned this matchup from start to finish.  Stephon Gilmore entered Week 10 as the hottest cornerback in the league, but he couldn't hang with Davis' physicality and acrobatic in-the-air prowess.  Davis even drew three defensive pass interference flags against Patriots defenders.  With Davis dominating targets and Tennessee's passing game finally turning a corner, Davis will be an upside WR2 play in Week 11 at Indianapolis.
report: Corey Davis caught 7-of-10 targets for 125 yards and a touchdown in the Titans' Week 10 upset win over New England.

impact: The Titans' offense appeared derailed from the opening snap, with the Colts scrambling Marcus Mariota, especially on third down. Mariota then re-injured his throwing elbow late in the first half. It was game over for Davis' fantasy prospects once laughingstock Blaine Gabbert checked in. Davis' Week 12 prospects against the Texans will depend on who is under center for the Titans. If it's Mariota, Davis will maintain upside WR3 appeal despite his up-and-down season.
report: Corey Davis caught 2-of-4 targets for 30 yards in the Titans' Week 11 loss to the Colts.

impact: Dalton was mostly sharp, keeping his eyes downfield when pressured and hitting A.J. Green and John Ross for scores.  Green's TD came from 38 yards out on a bomb, and Ross' from three yards away on an end-zone fade.  This is the best supporting cast Dalton has been surrounded by since the 2015 season, when he finished as a top-seven quarterback in fantasy points per game.  Dalton will be a mid-range QB2 in a tough Week 2 matchup with Baltimore, however.
report: Andy Dalton completed 21-of-28 passes for 243 yards, two touchdowns, and an interception in the Bengals' Week 1 win over the Colts.

impact: It was one of the shakiest four-touchdown performances you will ever see. Dalton was excellent in the first half, piling up all four of his scores. After the break, he could barely get a first down and was lucky to escape without a turnover. Dalton relentlessly worked his connection with A.J. Green, finding him for three of his four TDs. Dalton also displayed strong chemistry with Tyler Boyd, a welcome development as the Bengals try to deepen their weapons arsenal. The Bengals head on the road to Carolina for Week 3.
report: Andy Dalton completed 24-of-42 passes for 265 yards and four touchdowns in the Bengals' 34-23, Week 2 win over the Ravens.

impact: The four picks make Dalton's game look worse than it was; one was tipped high into the air on a target Josh Malone couldn't haul in, and Dalton's fourth INT came on what amounted to a last-gasp Hail Mary heave.  Of more concern are the Bengals' mounting injuries; after Joe Mixon had his knee scoped in Week 2, A.J. Green left Sunday's loss with a groin pull and did not return.  Dalton's Week 4 fantasy upside at Atlanta will hinge largely on Green's availability.
report: Andy Dalton completed 29-of-46 passes for 352 yards, two touchdowns, and four interceptions in the Bengals' Week 3 loss to Carolina.

impact: Dalton was exceptional throughout this game -- he completed 14-of-16 passes for 211 yards and two touchdowns in the first half -- but he made his money with the win in the balance late in the fourth quarter. Down five, Dalton led a 16-play, 75-yard touchdown drive in which he found Tyler Boyd for two fourth-down conversions. The touchdown was a great throw to A.J. Green in the end zone. Dalton now has multiple touchdowns in every game and has topped 335 yards each of the last two weeks. He will be a back-end QB1 next week against the Dolphins.
report: Andy Dalton completed 29-of-41 passes for 337 yards, three touchdowns, and an interception in the Bengals' Week 4 win over the Falcons.

impact: Dalton's only touchdown was a broken play where he hit Joe Mixon in the end-zone on a back-shoulder throw. He was picked trying to force a pass in the red-zone, but otherwise managed the game effectively. It's a disappointing game from Dalton against a Miami pass rush that was missing multiple starters. Dalton has another plus matchup with the Steelers in Week 6.
report: Andy Dalton completed 20-of-30 passes for 248 yards with a touchdown and an interception in the Bengals' Week 5 win over the Dolphins.

impact: Dalton averaged a pitiful 5.5 yards per attempt and took three sacks.  He needed to play much better for the Bengals but was also hurt bad by a couple drops.  Dalton just didn't seem to be on his A-game in this one, misfiring on a couple throws.  Tyler Boyd had to make a pair of shoe-string, diving catches, with one coming on a two-yard touchdown.  Dalton's now had back-to-back mediocre outings ahead of a ripe Week 7 spot against the Chiefs.
report: Andy Dalton completed 26-of-42 passes for 229 yards and two touchdowns in the Bengals' Week 6 loss to the Steelers.

impact: The Bengals got off to a sluggish start, but Dalton managed a first-quarter touchdown to C.J. Uzomah. He telegraphed a pick-six on the first drive of second half and couldn’t get anything going after that. It’s one of the worst starts of the season for Dalton, who’s had multiple TDs in 5-of-7 games. Dalton has a rebound matchup with the Bucs in Week 8
report: Andy Dalton completed 15-of-29 passes for 148 yards with a touchdown and an interception in Week 7 against Kansas City.

impact: The Bengals got off to a sluggish start, but Dalton managed a first-quarter touchdown to C.J. Uzomah. He telegraphed a pick-six on the first drive of second half and couldn’t get anything going after that. It’s one of the worst starts of the season for Dalton, who’s had multiple TDs in 5-of-7 games. Dalton has a rebound matchup with the Bucs in Week 8
report: Andy Dalton completed 15-of-29 passes for 148 yards with a touchdown and an interception in Week 7 against Kansas City.

impact: He rushed three times for ten yards.  Dalton dominated in the first half with scoring throws to A.J. Green (17 yards) and Tyler Boyd (7 yards), then went in the tank in the final two quarters as Tampa Bay rallied back before Bengals K Randy Bullock clinched the win with a last-second field goal.  Dalton will come out of the Bengals' Week 9 bye as a streamer option but not a locked-in QB1.
report: Andy Dalton completed 21-of-34 passes for 280 yards and two touchdowns in the Bengals' Week 8 win over the Bucs.

impact: Without A.J. Green, the Bengals next to nothing on offense on Sunday in a blowout loss. Dalton's lone highlight was a 2-yard touchdown pass to John Ross in the first quarter. Dalton threw a crucial interception right before the first half that turned into a Saints touchdown and closed the door on the afternoon. Things don't get much better for Dalton in Week 11 when the Bengals head to Baltimore.
report: Andy Dalton completed 12-of-20 passes for 153 yards with one touchdown and two interceptions in Sunday's Week 10 loss to the Saints.

impact: Dalton took only one sack and five hits, but he is playing against a loaded deck without A.J. Green and Tyler Eifert.  His touchdowns on Sunday went to third-string TE Matt Lengel and John Ross, who managed 27 yards on seven targets in the game.  There is some hope that Green (toe) will return for Week 12 against the Browns, but either way Dalton is a mere two-quarterback-league option.
report: Andy Dalton completed 19-of-36 passes for 211 yards and two touchdowns and rushed twice for 29 yards in the Bengals' Week 11 loss to Baltimore.

impact: Game flow worked perfectly for Ivory, who was able to rumble his way to 20 carries while the Bills milked a 27-0 first half lead. The three catches (and 70 receiving yards) were unexpected, but it was just another thing that happened to go right in a day chalked with them for Buffalo on Sunday. At worst, Ivory set himself apart from third-down RB Marcus Murphy (8-33) and made his case as a potential FLEX option if LeSean McCoy (ribs) misses an extended period. Ivory remains volume-driven, though.
report: Chris Ivory rushed 20 times for 56 yards and hauled in 3-of-4 targets for 70 yards in the Bills’ Week 3 win over the Vikings.

impact: With LeSean McCoy (ribs) back, Ivory retreated to a supporting role, though he actually out-carried McCoy 6-5. McCoy out-touched him 8-6. Occasionally, both backs were on the field at the same time. Ivory has zero standalone fantasy value.
report: Chris Ivory rushed six times for 15 yards in the Bills' Week 4 loss to the Packers.

impact: Virtually every Ivory touch is a wasted one, but he's a favorite of the coaching staff for whatever reason.  His longest run of the season is nine yards.  Ivory is LeSean McCoy's handcuff but nothing more.
report: Chris Ivory rushed 14 times for 43 yards in the Bills' Week 5 win over the Titans.

impact: With LeSean McCoy back and dominating work, Ivory took a backseat in this one. He has some stash value in deeper leagues in case the Bills trade LeSean McCoy, but that is looking unlikely at this point.
report: Chris Ivory rushed six times for five yards and caught his only target for four yards in the Bills' Week 6 loss to the Texans.

impact: He came on in relief of LeSean McCoy, who left with a head injury early in the first quarter. Ivory handled most of the Bills' backfield responsibilities after that, though he did leave briefly during the third quarter after Colts cornerback Pierre Desir came down awkwardly on his left foot. The nine-year vet broke off a couple big runs for Buffalo including a 21-yard burst in the second quarter, though he never came close to finding the end zone. Ivory would lead the backfield again if McCoy can’t go next week when the Bills host New England on Monday Night Football. That makes him a worthy roster add in all formats.
report: Chris Ivory delivered 81 yards on 16 carries while adding three catches for 25 yards on six targets Sunday in Buffalo’s Week 7 loss to the Colts.

impact: Evans disappointed in his matchups against Marshon Lattimore last season but he flipped the script Sunday, owning the reigning Defensive Rookie of the Year from start to finish. The Bucs stud left the field with an injury early in the second half but showed no ill effects upon his return, dusting Lattimore on a 50-yard touchdown strike from red-hot Ryan Fitzpatrick. The 147 yards were Evans’ most in a game since Week 9 of 2016 against Atlanta. He’s now just one receiving touchdown away from tying Jimmie Giles’ team record of 34. Next week’s matchup with Philadelphia won’t be an easy one, though Evans is still worthy of WR1 consideration against the reigning World Champs.
report: Mike Evans tallied seven catches for 147 yards and a touchdown on seven targets Sunday in the Buccaneers’ improbable Week 1 win over the Saints.

impact: Evans didn't get loose for vertical bombs, but he out-physicaled the Eagles' defensive backs en route to a high-volume game.  His touchdown came on an easy four-yard route where Evans simply used his big body to shield himself from beleaguered Eagles CB Jalen Mills.  The Steelers' defense has been getting torched early on, and Evans will catch them on Monday Night Football in Week 3.
report: Mike Evans caught 10-of-12 targets for 83 yards and a touchdown in the Bucs' Week 2 win over the Eagles.

impact: Unlike last week, it was DeSean Jackson (5-112) who benefited immensely as the Bucs trailed 38-3 after two quarters. Evans' nine targets were still a team-high, with Adam Humphries (6-36) seeing seven. Evans has proved to be a true WR1 with Jameis Winston, who replaced Ryan Fitzpatrick at the half, under center and that should continue once the Bucs return from their Week 5 bye.
report: Mike Evans hauled in 6-of-9 targets for 59 yards in the Bucs' Week 4 loss to the Bears.

impact: It is an extremely disappointing result considering Jameis Winston threw for 395 yards and four touchdowns. That said, Evans did not make any glaring mistakes or play poorly. He just did not really get the opportunities. That should change next week against the Browns.
report: Mike Evans hauled in 4-of-5 targets for 58 yards in the Bucs' Week 6 loss to the Falcons.

impact: After two slow weeks with 107 yards combined through the air, Evans led the Bucs across the board in receiving on Sunday. With Denzel Ward following DeSean Jackson, Evans worked mostly on Damarious Randall on the afternoon. After scoring a touchdown in each of the opening three weeks of the season, Evans has failed to reach the end zone over the past three games. Despite that, he remains a high-end WR1 option in Week 8 on the road against the Bengals.
report: Mike Evans caught 7-of-10 targets for 107 yards in Sunday's Week 7 win over the Browns.

impact: After two slow weeks with 107 yards combined through the air, Evans led the Bucs across the board in receiving on Sunday. With Denzel Ward following DeSean Jackson, Evans worked mostly on Damarious Randall on the afternoon. After scoring a touchdown in each of the opening three weeks of the season, Evans has failed to reach the end zone over the past three games. Despite that, he remains a high-end WR1 option in Week 8 on the road against the Bengals.
report: Mike Evans caught 7-of-10 targets for 107 yards in Sunday's Week 7 win over the Browns.

impact: Evans entered halftime 0-of-6, and things did not get better after the break. Evans was the intended "target" on Ryan Fitzpatrick's first interception. Fitz sailed the ball 10 feet over his receiver's head. Evans had previously balled out with Fitz under center, but the quarterback had little time to throw today. The Bucs get Josh Norman and the Redskins in Week 10.
report: Mike Evans caught just 1-of-10 targets for 16 yards in the Bucs' Week 9 loss to the Panthers.

impact: It's an improvement off of Evans' 1-16 day on 10 targets last week, but Evans looked like he was going to have a bigger day when he had 28 yards on two grabs early in the first half.  The Bucs totaled nearly 500 yards of offense but didn't score a touchdown.  Ryan Fitzpatrick had Evans wide open for a two-yard score in the fourth quarter but spiked it right at his feet then fumbled on the very next play.  Evans will be a WR1 next week against the Giants.
report: Mike Evans caught 3-of-6 targets for 51 yards in the Bucs' Week 10 loss to the Redskins.

impact: Evans was well on his way to another disappointing afternoon before Ryan Fitzpatrick was benched in the second half. Jameis Winston came in and promptly peppered Evans with targets, including a 41-yard touchdown bomb that sailed over the watchful eye of CB Janoris Jenkins. He had caught just 4-of-16 targets for a lowly total of 67 yards in his previous two performances, so this outing was needed for both Evans and his owners. He'll have an extremely tough matchup on paper against the Niners and Richard Sherman in Week 12, but can't possibly be benched whether it's Winston or Fitzpatrick under center throwing to him.
report: Mike Evans hauled in 6-of-7 targets for 120 yards and one touchdown in the Bucs' near-comeback loss to the Giants.

impact: Making his 2018 debut after serving a four-game suspension to open the season, Ingram got the start and out-touched Alvin Kamara 18-9, adding two catches for 20 yards on three targets.  It was evident right from the get-go that coach Sean Payton wanted to get Ingram involved and keep him involved after sitting out the first four weeks.  It was also an opportunity for Kamara to get some extra rest heading into the bye.  Moving forward, we expect Kamara to be used much more than he was tonight, but there's obviously some serious concern here with all the weapons and mouths in the New Orleans offense.  Kamara is unlikely to match his 22.75 touches per game mark from Weeks 1-4.  He's going to need big plays to maintain elite RB1 status while Ingram is very much a mid-to-high RB2 the rest of the way.  The Saints get the Ravens on the road in Week 7.
report: Mark Ingram rushed 16 times for 53 yards and two touchdowns in the Saints' 43-19, Week 5 rout of the Redskins on Monday night.

impact: Ingram out-touched Kamara 18-9 in his Week 5 debut, but Kamara had a 19-14 upper hand in Baltimore. Ingram received carries from the Ravens' six- and five-yard line but could not cash either in. Kamara found the end zone from two yards out in the fourth quarter. This is more how we were expecting the Saints' backfield to look following Ingram's return but nothing is settled after only two games. Ingram will be a touchdown-dependent RB2 for Week 8 against the Vikings.
report: Mark Ingram rushed 12 times for 32 scoreless yards in the Saints' Week 7 win over the Ravens, adding two catches for 10 additional yards.

impact: Ingram out-touched Kamara 18-9 in his Week 5 debut, but Kamara had a 19-14 upper hand in Baltimore. Ingram received carries from the Ravens' six- and five-yard line but could not cash either in. Kamara found the end zone from two yards out in the fourth quarter. This is more how we were expecting the Saints' backfield to look following Ingram's return but nothing is settled after only two games. Ingram will be a touchdown-dependent RB2 for Week 8 against the Vikings.
report: Mark Ingram rushed 12 times for 32 scoreless yards in the Saints' Week 7 win over the Ravens, adding two catches for 10 additional yards.

impact: Ingram took a backseat to Alvin Kamara for the second straight week. He got almost all his work in the second half with the Saints running the clock. Ingram played behind Kamara in red-zone situations — a concern to his going-forward outlook. With a matchup against the Rams in Week 9, Ingram will be a touchdown-dependent RB3.
report: Mark Ingram rushed 13 times for 63 yards and caught three passes for 29 yards in Week 8 against the Vikings.

impact: Ingram’s game did not start as well as his backfield partner’s. He was limited to just five yards on his first three carries, and he coughed up the ball on the last of those attempts, although the Rams bailed him out with a failed fake field goal. Ingram might have been able to save his day if the Saints had held their lead in the second half, but he ended up touching the ball just four times after the break. Ingram has not scored since finding the end zone twice in his first game back, and he has averaged just 57 total yards since the bye. He will be back-end RB2 despite a good matchup next week in Cincinnati.
report: Mark Ingram rushed nine times for 33 yards and caught 1-of-2 targets for three yards in the Saints' Week 9 win over the Rams.

impact: Sunday was Ingram's first 100-yard rushing game since Week 11 of last season as he found gaping room all afternoon against a non-existent Bengals defense. Ingram found the end zone on a 28-yard screen pass in which is almost appeared as the Bengals defense was trying to let him score. Ingram still took a back seat to Alvin Kamara at the goal line. Ingram's big day was largely a product of the opponent and game script, leaving him as a sketchy fantasy option next week against the Eagles strong rushing defense.
report: Mark Ingram rushed 13 times for 104 yards while catching three passes for 58 yards and a touchdown in Sunday's Week 10 win over the Bengals.

impact: Ingram set the tone on his opening carry, going for 38 yards to help spark a field-goal drive, and continued to eat until he was pulled from the blowout in the fourth quarter. His first touchdown came on a 14-yard rush early in the second quarter, and he scored from one yard out in the third. Ingram's carry totals are a bit of a concern, but he has now topped 100 yards in each of the last two games. He will be a solid RB2 on Thanksgiving against the Falcons.
report: Mark Ingram rushed 16 times for 103 yards and two touchdowns in the Saints' Week 11 win over the Eagles.

impact: He led the team in targets, just ahead of Nelson Agholor (12).  Ertz has been the Eagles' most-targeted pass catcher with Nick Foles under center dating back to last season.  Carson Wentz (knee) is tentatively due back for Week 3 against the Colts, however, and Wentz's return would boost Ertz's touchdown probability.  Ertz has yet to reach pay dirt on 23 targets through two games.
report: Zach Ertz caught 11-of-13 targets for 94 yards in the Eagles' Week 2 loss to Tampa Bay.

impact: Ertz and Wentz more than less picked up where they left off as Ertz lead the Eagles across the board in targets, receptions and yards. Despite failing to score through three games, Ertz leads the Eagles in targets (33), receptions (21) and receiving yardage (215). He will be a set-and-forget option next week against the Titans.
report: Zach Ertz caught 5-of-10 targets for 73 yards in Sunday's Week 3 win over the Colts.

impact: It is about what we have come to expect from Ertz, who now has at least 10 targets in every game this season. The Titans simply had no answer for him as he consistently made plays across the middle on the way to his first 100-yard game of the season. With Wentz looking better every week, Ertz will remain a high-end TE1 as long as he is healthy.
report: Zach Ertz hauled in 10-of-14 targets for 112 yards in the Eagles' Week 4 loss to the Titans.

impact: Ertz has now caught 10 passes in 3-of-5 games this season. He's on pace for 1,398 yards after entering 2018 with a career high of 853. His production has come with both Nick Foles and Carson Wentz under center and withstood the return of Alshon Jeffery. Ertz will jockey with Rob Gronkowski and Travis Kelce for the TE1 rank going forward.
report: Zach Ertz caught 10-of-11 targets for 110 yards and a touchdown in the Eagles' Week 5 loss to the Vikings.

impact: Ertz was legitimately unstoppable, relentlessly beating the Panthers’ linebackers and safeties on slants and exploiting every hole known to man in Carolina’s zone coverage. Ertz came oh-so close to a second-quarter touchdown, but he was tackled just short of the goalline.  As the NFL’s premier route-running tight end, Ertz has also been fantasy football’s most-consistent TE1. Even against the Jaguars in London in Week 8, Ertz will be a top-three option at the position at worst.
report: Zach Ertz caught 9-of-11 targets for 138 yards in the Eagles’ Week 7 loss to the Panthers.

impact: Ertz was legitimately unstoppable, relentlessly beating the Panthers’ linebackers and safeties on slants and exploiting every hole known to man in Carolina’s zone coverage. Ertz came oh-so close to a second-quarter touchdown, but he was tackled just short of the goalline.  As the NFL’s premier route-running tight end, Ertz has also been fantasy football’s most-consistent TE1. Even against the Jaguars in London in Week 8, Ertz will be a top-three option at the position at worst.
report: Zach Ertz caught 9-of-11 targets for 138 yards in the Eagles’ Week 7 loss to the Panthers.

impact: Ertz was having a quiet day, especially by his standards, entering the final quarter, but he took care of his fantasy backers in the final stanza. With the Eagles up by just two, Ertz ran a good route to get a step in the end zone, and Carson Wentz found him for the five-yard touchdown. This was Ertz’s first game of the season with fewer than nine targets, but he has now caught a touchdown in three of his last four games. He will be a high-end TE1 against the Cowboys after the bye week.
report: Zach Ertz caught 4-of-6 targets for 26 yards and a touchdown in the Eagles' Week 8 win over the Jaguars.

impact: This was easily Ertz's worst fantasy game of the season -- he at least caught a touchdown when he went for just 26 yards against the Jaguars. Like every Eagles pass catcher, Ertz was seemingly unable to get open, and he went for just eight and seven yards on his two catches. He should find more success against the Giants next week.
report: Zach Ertz hauled in just 2-of-3 targets for 15 yards in the Eagles' Week 11 loss to the Saints.

impact: Engram was walking around with a brace on his knee after the game. He told reporters he expects to be "fine." It sounds like Engram avoided a serious injury, but he may still be looking at MCL damage. More will be known after Monday's MRI.
report: Evan Engram (knee) will undergo an MRI on Monday.

impact: It was Engram's first game back from a sprained MCL suffered in Week 3.  His four targets were a distant fourth on the team behind Odell Beckham (11), Saquon Barkley (10), and Sterling Shepard (8).  Engram has better days ahead and will remain a default TE1 next week against the Redskins.
report: Evan Engram caught 2-of-4 targets for 16 yards in the Giants' Week 7 loss to the Falcons.

impact: It was Engram's first game back from a sprained MCL suffered in Week 3.  His four targets were a distant fourth on the team behind Odell Beckham (11), Saquon Barkley (10), and Sterling Shepard (8).  Engram has better days ahead and will remain a default TE1 next week against the Redskins.
report: Evan Engram caught 2-of-4 targets for 16 yards in the Giants' Week 7 loss to the Falcons.

impact: Engram's TD came in what amounted to garbage time of New York's 20-13 loss; the Giants were down two scores with :17 left when Engram hit pay dirt.  Both of Engram's touchdowns this year have come in garbage time.  Engram will remain a fringe TE1 when the Giants return from their Week 9 bye.
report: Evan Engram caught 5-of-9 targets for 25 yards and a touchdown in the Giants' Week 8 loss to Washington.

impact: He did all of his damage in the second half after catching one ball for no gain prior to the break.  Engram's longest gain of 31 was a shot down the sideline where he was tackled inside the 10-yard line late in the fourth quarter.  Engram has been a distant third or fourth option when healthy this season but does get a promising Week 11 date with the Bucs and will be a locked-in TE1.
report: Evan Engram caught 4-of-5 targets for 46 yards in the Giants' Week 10 win over the 49ers.

impact: He only saw two targets on the day, but Engram made one in particular count 54-yards downfield. Typically the Giants' third receiving option behind Odell Beckham and Saquon Barkley, Engram is at least slated with another good matchup against the Eagles' ailing secondary in Week 12. Lock him in.
report: Evan Engram hauled in both of his targets for 66 yards in the Giants' Week 11 victory over the Bucs.

impact: Running as the No. 2 for the Texans' undermanned receiver corps, Ellington's touchdown was just the sixth of his career. He will offer some desperation appeal for as long as Will Fuller (hamstring) is sidelined. The Texans get the Titans in Week 2.
report: Bruce Ellington caught 4-of-8 targets for 37 yards and a touchdown in the Texans' Week 1 loss to the Patriots.

impact: With Keke Coutee and Sammie Coates out, Ellington continued his run as Houston's clear-cut No. 3 receiver. Unfortunately, that position serves little to no value with Will Fuller (8-113-1) and DeAndre Hopkins (6-110-1) manning the outside. Coutee, who has a much higher ceiling than Ellington, should mix-in as the team's primary slot receiver once he's healthy.
report: Bruce Ellington caught all three of his targets for 45 yards in the Texans' Week 2 loss to the Titans.

impact: Active for the first time as a Lion, Ellington was involved early, catching two passes in the first quarter, but that was it for him in the first half. He took a big hit to the back on a target just before halftime, but he returned following the break. He started fast again following the half, catching two quick passes including a nice 21 yarder to help set up a field goal, and he finished the game second on the team in targets. With Marvin Jones’ availability uncertain, Ellington could have a big role on Thanksgiving against the Bears. He is worth a look in deeper leagues.
report: Bruce Ellington hauled in 6-of-9 targets for 52 yards in the Lions' Week 11 win over the Panthers.

impact: The 126 yards from scrimmage were a new career high. The Chargers were intent on featuring Ekeler and Melvin Gordon as pass catchers against the Chiefs' suspect linebacker corps. The mission was accomplished. Ekeler is still little more than an RB5/handcuff for fantasy purposes, though he would be an instant RB2 were Gordon to go down with injury.
report: Austin Ekeler caught 5-of-5 targets for 87 yards and a touchdown in the Chargers' Week 1 loss to the Chiefs, adding five carries for 39 additional yards.

impact: Ekeler was heavily involved for the second straight week. His touches were inflated with Melvin Gordon checking out with an injury in the fourth quarter, but it's becoming clear the Chargers have a role for Ekeler in their weekly gameplan. Ekeler is on the radar as a PPR FLEX for Week 3 against the Rams.
report: Austin Ekeler rushed 11 times for 77 yards and caught three passes for 21 yards in Week 2 against Buffalo.

impact: The Chargers have given Ekeler a small, defined role in the offense, and he is certainly making the most of his opportunities. Through three games, the change-of-pace back is averaging 8.15 yards per carry and 12 yards per reception. Ekeler is a weak PPR FLEX for Week 4 against the 49ers, but he would be an instant RB2 if Gordon ever misses time.
report: Austin Ekeler rushed four times for 44 yards and caught all three of his targets for 24 yards in the Chargers' Week 3 loss to the Rams.

impact: The Chargers have been giving Ekeler some looks every week behind Melvin Gordon, and he's been able to make the most of them. Today, Ekeler hauled in a 22-yard touchdown on a beautiful pass from Philip Rivers to save his fantasy day. It's nothing special, but Ekeler is a low-end FLEX option during the bye week season in 12-team leagues.
report: Austin Ekeler rushed eight times for 25 yards but caught 2-of-3 targets for 31 yards and touchdown in the Chargers' Week 4 win over the 49ers.

impact: Ekeler continued his 70-30 timeshare with teammate Melvin Gordon Sunday, being out-touched 23-7 on the day. Ekeler's carries primarily occurred in the team's final drive with the game already put to bed. His lone score was a terrific effort from both he and Philip Rivers, the latter who quickly recouped after bobbling the initial snap, looked to his right, and fired a laser to Ekeler, who broke ankles on his way into the end zone, in the flats. This performance puts Ekeler on pace for a standalone valuable 108-649 rushing and 44-662-9 receiving year.
report: Austin Ekeler rushed six times for 15 yards, additionally scampering for a 44-yard touchdown catch in the Chargers' Week 5 win over the Raiders.

impact: This was the first game in which Ekeler wasn't targeted in the passing game, but the Chargers threw just five passes in the second half. Ekeler is now averaging a gaudy 6.4 yards per carry now on the season in relief of Melvin Gordon. He will enter Week 7 as a FLEX option when the Chargers face the Titans in London.
report: Austin Ekeler rushed seven times for 60 yards in Sunday's Week 6 win over the Browns.

impact: Ekeler got the start with Melvin Gordon out. This was one of his worse games of the year despite the expanded role. The Chargers scored both of their touchdowns on deep shots, so there wasn't a ton of red-zone opportunities for Ekeler. With Los Angeles on a bye, Ekeler looks destined to resume a change-up role in Week 9.
report: Austin Ekeler rushed 12 times for 42 yards and caught 5-of-7 passes for 26 yards in the  Chargers' Week 7 win over the Titans.

impact: Ekeler got the start with Melvin Gordon out. This was one of his worse games of the year despite the expanded role. The Chargers scored both of their touchdowns on deep shots, so there wasn't a ton of red-zone opportunities for Ekeler. With Los Angeles on a bye, Ekeler looks destined to resume a change-up role in Week 9.
report: Austin Ekeler rushed 12 times for 42 yards and caught 5-of-7 passes for 26 yards in the  Chargers' Week 7 win over the Titans.

impact: The 34 yards from scrimmage were Ekeler's fewest of the season. Ekeler is usually going to get more than four touches, but he has plateaued behind Melvin Gordon, struggling to offer standalone FLEX value. He does have a gorgeous setup for Week 10, when there should be quarters of garbage time against the Raiders.
report: Austin Ekeler rushed three times for 21 yards in the Chargers' Week 9 win over the Seahawks, adding a 13-yard reception.

impact: After not touching the ball in the first half, Ekeler looked like he had saved his fantasy day with just one play, but his 42-yard touchdown was called back because of a holding call. Ekeler has now touched the ball just seven times in the last two games. He is just a handcuff at this point.
report: Austin Ekeler carried the ball three times for 19 yards in the Chargers' Week 10 win over the Raiders.

impact: Ekeler saw 16 fewer touches than teammate Melvin Gordon, but obviously he made the most of his limited workload. Both of his catches came during the fourth quarter. Ekeler didn't re-enter the game after suffering a minor injury on special teams, though he remained on the sidelines with his helmet, suggesting he could have gone back in if needed. Assuming he's healthy, the second-year Western State product will face the Cardinals at home in Week 12.
report: Austin Ekeler rolled up 29 yards on six carries while also snagging two catches for 40 yards on two targets Sunday in Los Angeles’ Week 11 loss to Denver.

impact: His total rushing yards were nice, but Zeke ultimately fell victim to OC Scott Linehan's mundane early-down rushing scheme behind an offensive line missing C Travis Frederick in the middle. He handled 15 of Dallas' 17 backfield carries, though, reassuring his bell-cow status. Zeke will have to overcome loaded boxes with all the touches he's bound to receive if he's going to finish as a top-three back.
report: Ezekiel Elliott rushed for 69 yards and one score on 15 carries while adding three catches for 17 yards on four targets in the Cowboys’ Week 1 loss to the Panthers.

impact: Elliott had a quiet night before scoring a six-yard fourth quarter touchdown. He was the Cowboys entire offense aside from a 64-yard Tavon Austin touchdown on the third play of the night. Despite playing behind an offensive line missing Travis Frederick, Elliott has managed 80 total yards and a touchdown in both games to start the year. He'll remain a locked-in top-five option for Week 3 against Seattle.
report: Ezekiel Elliott rushed 17 times for 78 yards and a touchdown and caught 5-of-6 passes for nine yards in the Cowboys' Week 2 win over the Giants on Sunday night.

impact: After opening the year with a pair of so-so games, Elliott played legitimately well on Sunday, particularly in the second half when he broke loose for 76 yards on only seven carries. Zeke’s longest gain came on a 26-yard burst in the fourth quarter, though Bradley McDougald spoiled it by stripping him at the end of his run, resulting in a turnover. Elliott has averaged 16 carries per game this year, which is well below the 24.2 he averaged last season. We’ll see what the 23-year-old can cobble up next week against the Lions.
report: Ezekiel Elliott totaled 127 yards on 16 carries while securing three-of-eight targets for 11 yards Sunday in the Cowboys’ Week 3 loss to the Seahawks.

impact: Zeke's 240 yards from scrimmage—140 of which came after halftime—set a career-high. Elliott was, for large stretches of the afternoon, the Cowboys' only source of offense. The third-year back got to stepping with a 38-yard touchdown off a screen pass late in the second quarter. He rumbled to a 41-yard run, his longest of the game, in the third quarter. Elliott made arguably his biggest contribution when he hauled in a 34-yard deep bomb from Dak Prescott, putting the Cowboys in field-goal range with under two minutes left in the fourth quarter. The Cowboys' offensive line has mostly struggled this year, but they went all out for Zeke in Week 4. Elliott, who currently leads the NFL with 426 rushing yards, will look to stay hot when he faces the Texans next week on Sunday Night Football.
report: Ezekiel Elliott exploded for 152 yards on 25 carries while also contributing four catches for a team-high 88 yards and a touchdown Sunday in Dallas’ Week 4 win over the Lions.

impact: Coming off a brutal outing against Houston in Week 5 (54 yards on 21 carries), Zeke was much better Sunday, shredding the Jags for 61 rushing yards in the second half. Elliott tallied his fourth touchdown of the year on a 15-yard scamper early in the fourth quarter. The Cowboys' offense isn't what it was a few years ago but Elliott has remained productive, leading the NFL with 586 rushing yards through six games. Even with his clunker against the Texans, Zeke has still cleared 100 yards rushing in three of his last four contests. He'll look to make it four out of five when he takes on the Redskins in Week 7.
report: Ezekiel Elliott rumbled to 106 yards and a touchdown on 24 carries while gaining 11 yards on his lone catch Sunday in Dallas’ Week 6 win over the Jaguars.

impact: Washington's defense kept Elliott bottled at the line of scrimmage, permitting just 2.2 YPC. He was in position to score on the goal line late in the fourth quarter, but Dak Prescott kept the ball and scampered over the middle and crossed the plain himself instead. Although his six targets were encouraging, it's the second straight week Zeke has been held under 12 yards receiving, and already the fourth time he's failed to reach that mark this season. His on-field usage and involvement remains that of a true bell-cow, though, keeping him as a weekly top-five option despite porous results in Dallas' passing game. The Cowboys are on bye in Week 8.
report: Ezekiel Elliott handled 15 carries for 34 yards, tacking on two catches for the nine yards in the Cowboys' Week 7 loss to the Redskins.

impact: Washington's defense kept Elliott bottled at the line of scrimmage, permitting just 2.2 YPC. He was in position to score on the goal line late in the fourth quarter, but Dak Prescott kept the ball and scampered over the middle and crossed the plain himself instead. Although his six targets were encouraging, it's the second straight week Zeke has been held under 12 yards receiving, and already the fourth time he's failed to reach that mark this season. His on-field usage and involvement remains that of a true bell-cow, though, keeping him as a weekly top-five option despite porous results in Dallas' passing game. The Cowboys are on bye in Week 8.
report: Ezekiel Elliott handled 15 carries for 34 yards, tacking on two catches for the nine yards in the Cowboys' Week 7 loss to the Redskins.

impact: Elliott was the lone bright spot of the offense and was cooking early, running through gaping holes.  He also made things happen in the pass game with a 37-yard pickup on a screen down to the four-yard line to set up Amari Cooper's score in the first quarter.  The Cowboys got away from Elliott in the second half, though, and they didn't score a single point after the break.  Elliott will again be a locked-in RB1 next week on the road in a tough date against the Eagles.
report: Ezekiel Elliott rushed 17 times for 61 yards and caught 4-of-5 targets for 51 yards in the Cowboys' 28-14, Week 9 loss to the Titans on Monday night.

impact: It was a monster game for Elliott, who provided most of the Cowboys' offense. Elliott had the highlight of the night on a 32-yard run when he hurdled over Tre Sullivan -- his second-longest run of the season. He later converted a goal-line carry for his rushing touchdown, with his receiving touchdown coming on a third down red-zone pass from Dak Prescott. Elliott looks to have benefitted from the Dallas firing their offensive line coach during their bye. He's a locked-in top-10 running back play against Atlanta in Week 11.
report: Ezekiel Elliott rushed 19 times for 151 yards and a touchdown and caught 6-of-7 targets for 36 yards and a touchdown in the Cowboys' Week 10 win over the Eagles.

impact: He put the offense on his back, scoring from 23 yards out in the fourth quarter to put the Cowboys up 19-9.  Atlanta came back to tie it, but Elliott muscled up for chunk yards on the final drive to put Brett Maher in position for the winning 42-yard field goal as time expired.  Elliott also led the team in receiving on a day Dak Prescott had just 208 passing yards.  Since the Week 8 bye, Elliott has three straight games of 100-plus total yards, amassing 500 yards and three scores in that span against the Titans, Eagles, and Falcons.  He gets the Redskins on Thanksgiving.
report: Ezekiel Elliott rushed 23 times for 122 yards and one touchdown in the Cowboys' 22-19, Week 11 win over the Falcons, adding seven catches for 79 yards on eight targets.

impact: The Ravens used a "hot-hand" approach and settled on featuring Edwards after Alex Collins struggled to create early-game yardage on his own.  Buck Allen had one touch, and Ty Montgomery didn't touch the ball at all.  Edwards now has a chance to become Baltimore's lead back ahead of their Week 12 date with the Raiders.  A plus-sized bulldozer type, Edwards never so much as ran for 750 yards in a college season, but opportunity is trending toward his favor ahead of one of the softest stretch-run rush-defense schedules in the league.
report: Undrafted rookie Gus Edwards rushed 17 times for 115 yards and a touchdown in the Ravens' Week 11 win over the Bengals.

impact: He was used as a part-time player, but it was nice to see him out there nonetheless considering his injury history.  Eifert's playing time figures to rise as he shows the coaching staff he can be trusted from a durability standpoint.  Eifert will be a touchdown-or-bust streamer in Week 2 versus Baltimore.
report: Tyler Eifert caught 3-of-3 targets for 44 yards in the Bengals' Week 1 win over the Colts.

impact: After drawing only three and four targets in the first two games, Eifert was a much bigger factor in this one, making his trademark tough catches in traffic and helping Andy Dalton move the sticks on third down.  A.J. Green (groin) went down at the start of the third quarter and never returned.  If Green can't play in Week 4 at Atlanta, Eifert's passing-game role will further expand.
report: Tyler Eifert caught 6-of-8 targets for 74 yards in the Bengals' Week 3 loss to Carolina.

impact: All of his work came in the second half. It was an encouraging debut for the fourth-rounder, though it’s doubtful he’ll see enough work to really register in the fantasy realm. It would probably take an injury to David Johnson for him to be relevant.
report: Chase Edmonds rushed four times for 24 yards while also pulling in four catches for 24 yards on four targets Sunday in the Cardinals’ Week 1 loss to the Redskins.

impact: Edmonds came into the game questionable with a back injury. He looked healthy, but it's possible the Cardinals scaled his snaps back at less than 100 percent. Edmonds didn't have any setbacks. He'll be fine for his change-up role in Week 7.
report: Chase Edmonds had one carry for four yards in Week 6 against the Vikings.

impact: Edmonds came into the game questionable with a back injury. He looked healthy, but it's possible the Cardinals scaled his snaps back at less than 100 percent. Edmonds didn't have any setbacks. He'll be fine for his change-up role in Week 7.
report: Chase Edmonds had one carry for four yards in Week 6 against the Vikings.

impact: A seventh-round, 24-year-old rookie out of Oklahoma State, Ateman was promoted from the practice squad ahead of this week's game. With Martavis Bryant (knee) and Jordy Nelson (knee) both on the shelf, Ateman was pressed into heavy duty after Brandon LaFell went down midway through the third quarter with an Achilles' injury. Even if all three players miss Week 12 against the Ravens, Ateman will not be on the fantasy radar.
report: Raiders WR Marcell Ateman caught 4-of-5 targets for 50 yards in the team's Week 11 victory over the Cardinals.

impact: Ebron did most of his damage on the opening possession, snaring two grabs for 20 yards including a seven-yard touchdown strike from Andrew Luck on third-and-three. He put up a goose egg after halftime, failing to reel in his lone second-half target. That play could have been called for pass interference on Montae Nicholson, but the refs let it slide. Ebron’s Lions tenure was mostly a disappointment, but he’s gotten off to a strong start in Indy with a touchdown in each of his first two contests. He’ll look to keep that streak going next week against Philadelphia.
report: Eric Ebron corralled three-of-four targets for 26 yards and a touchdown Sunday in the Colts’ Week 2 win over the Redskins.

impact: With Jack Doyle out of the lineup, Ebron led the Colts in targets, but was able to turn them into just pedestrian yardage. His afternoon was filled near misses, failing to reel in any of his three end zone targets. Ebron will be the lower-TE1 mix if Doyle remains sidelined next week against the Texans.
report: Eric Ebron caught 5-of-11 targets for 33 yards in Sunday's Week 3 loss to the Eagles.

impact: Ebron has been a steady presence in the red zone for the Colts, catching three touchdowns through four games.  His one on Sunday was a five-yarder where the Texans simply forgot to cover him outside.  With the Colts throwing so much and Ebron catching touchdowns, he's on the TE1 map moving forward.  The Patriots are up next in Week 5.  Expect plenty of Ebron in a likely blowout.
report: Eric Ebron caught 5-of-10 targets for 40 yards and one touchdown in the Colts' Week 4 loss to the Texans.

impact: Operating as the No. 1 receiver for the Colts' epically banged up offense — to say nothing of the hollowed-out defense — Ebron posted a new career high for targets while notching his first 100-yard game. True to form, Ebron also committed a drop or two, but he was finding space against the second and third levels of the Patriots' defense. His Week 6 fantasy status against the Jets will depend on Jack Doyle and T.Y. Hilton's health.
report: Eric Ebron caught 9-of-15 targets for 105 yards and two touchdowns in the Colts' Week 5 loss to the Patriots.

impact: Ebron wasn't targeted quite as heavily as usual in this one -- he came in averaging 12 per game over the previous three weeks -- but he hit pay dirt for the sixth time in six games and continues to produce as top-five fantasy TE1.  Ebron's hot stretch will be threatened whenever Jack Doyle (hip) returns, but there are no indications Doyle is close.  The Colts host the Bills next.
report: Eric Ebron caught 4-of-7 targets for 71 yards and a touchdown in the Colts' Week 6 loss to the Jets.

impact: Sunday erased a three-game touchdown streak for Ebron, who also tallied his fewest receiving yards since Week 2, which was the last time he shared the field with Jack Doyle. Ebron wasn't really needed in this one as the Colts got ahead early and coasted to an easy win behind a career day from running back Marlon Mack. Despite Sunday's clunker, Ebron should remain in play as a TE1 next week in Oakland, assuming Doyle remains sidelined.
report: Eric Ebron absorbed three-of-seven targets for 31 yards Sunday in the Colts’ Week 7 win over the Bills.

impact: Sunday erased a three-game touchdown streak for Ebron, who also tallied his fewest receiving yards since Week 2, which was the last time he shared the field with Jack Doyle. Ebron wasn't really needed in this one as the Colts got ahead early and coasted to an easy win behind a career day from running back Marlon Mack. Despite Sunday's clunker, Ebron should remain in play as a TE1 next week in Oakland, assuming Doyle remains sidelined.
report: Eric Ebron absorbed three-of-seven targets for 31 yards Sunday in the Colts’ Week 7 win over the Bills.

impact: Ebron has now had to back-to-back quiet weeks, though he salvaged the day somewhat by scoring his seventh touchdown of the year. That ties him with Kansas City's Tyreek Hill for the league lead. Ebron will likely see fewer looks now that Jack Doyle is back from his hip injury, but at a thin fantasy position, he still merits starting consideration. He'll have the week off before facing Jacksonville after the bye.
report: Eric Ebron gathered three catches for 37 yards and a touchdown on three targets Sunday in the Colts’ Week 8 victory over Oakland.

impact: On the opening drive, the Jaguars simply lost Ebron down the field, and Luck hit him for an easy 53-yard touchdown, although Ebron flashed his athleticism by tip-toeing the sideline before diving for the pylon. That was just the start of a big game. A couple drives later, Ebron took an end around, got the edge, and waltzed into the end zone from two yards out for the second rushing score of his career. He was left wide open again for a 12-yard score in the second quarter to cap his massive day. With Jack Doyle back, volume could be a concern for Ebron, but he plays for a coach and with a quarterback who both like to target tight ends in the red zone. That keeps him in the TE1 mix.
report: Eric Ebron hauled in all three of his targets for 69 yards and two touchdowns and rushed once for a two-yard touchdown in the Colts' Week 10 win over the Jaguars.

impact: The only time Ebron touched the ball was a on trick play pass attempt. He and Andrew Luck could not quite hook up in the end zone. Ebron's role-player usage finally caught up to him in fantasy today. He is wholly dependent on his red zone targets, and Luck was looking elsewhere inside the 20. Ebron does have a lovely Week 12 matchup in the Dolphins, who have gotten absolutely gutted by tight ends this season. He will be a top-16 option.
report: Eric Ebron was not targeted in the Colts' 38-10, Week 11 win over the Titans.

impact: It was a similar game to last week for Edelman, who had 57 yards in his debut. He got behind Kendall Fuller for a 17-yard touchdown but was quiet after that. Even with the addition of Josh Gordon, Edelman has remained Tom Brady’s most trusted target. He’s a low-end WR2 for Week 7 against Chicago.
report: Julian Edelman caught 4-of-7 passes for 54 yards and a touchdown in Week 6 against the Chiefs.

impact: Edelman earned his early touchdown, making a man miss and going through a couple others on his way to a nine-yard score on a screen pass on the opening drive of the game. He was not able to build on his hot start, however. He was targeted just once after halftime, and he did not record a catch in the second half. He has yet to top 57 yards since returning. Edelman will always be a touchdown threat in this offense, but there is at least some reason for concern, especially with Rob Gronkowski expected back next week.
report: Julian Edelman hauled in 5-of-8 targets for 36 yards and a touchdown in the Patriots' Week 7 win over the Bears.

impact: Edelman earned his early touchdown, making a man miss and going through a couple others on his way to a nine-yard score on a screen pass on the opening drive of the game. He was not able to build on his hot start, however. He was targeted just once after halftime, and he did not record a catch in the second half. He has yet to top 57 yards since returning. Edelman will always be a touchdown threat in this offense, but there is at least some reason for concern, especially with Rob Gronkowski expected back next week.
report: Julian Edelman hauled in 5-of-8 targets for 36 yards and a touchdown in the Patriots' Week 7 win over the Bears.

impact: It was Edelman's first 100-yard game of the season since returning four weeks ago.  The targets and catches are also new season-bests.  He was dominating the middle of the field, as both Edelman and James White seemingly couldn't be stopped by the Bills.  The only thing missing was pass-game touchdowns.  Tom Brady didn't throw one.  Edelman will be a solid WR2 next week against the Packers at home with obvious big upside in a likely shootout.
report: Julian Edelman caught 9-of-10 targets for 104 yards in the Patriots' 25-6, Week 8 win over the Bills on Monday night.

impact: Edelman entered the game with an ankle injury.  In the fourth quarter, he may have aggravated the injury, went to the sideline, and eventually the locker room at the end of New England's blowout loss.  Edelman took an unruly number of shots over the middle from physical Titans CB Logan Ryan.  Edelman was able to walk on his own power.  We suspect he'll be good to go after the Pats' Week 11 bye.
report: Julian Edelman caught 9-of-12 targets for 104 yards in the Patriots' Week 10 loss to Tennessee.

impact: Andrews got his day started with a 30-yard catch in the first quarter in which he hurdled a defender, and he had another long catch in the third. Andrews is not getting enough work in the Ravens' tight end committee, but he could become a fantasy option if that changes.
report: Mark Andrews caught 2-of-3 targets for 59 yards in the Ravens' Week 3 win over the Broncos.

impact: Andrews got his day started with a 30-yard catch in the first quarter in which he hurdled a defender, and he had another long catch in the third. Andrews is not getting enough work in the Ravens' tight end committee, but he could become a fantasy option if that changes.
report: Mark Andrews caught 2-of-3 targets for 59 yards in the Ravens' Week 3 win over the Broncos.

impact: Andrews led all Ravens tight ends with five targets, but fellow rookie Hayden Hurst caught a late garbage-time touchdown from Lamar Jackson.  Andrews is a bottom-barrel TE2 heading into Week 9 against the Steelers.
report: Mark Andrews caught 4-of-5 targets for 31 yards in the Ravens' Week 8 loss to the Panthers.

impact: Even with Hayden Hurst back from injury, Andrews has kept his role. The former Oklahoma Sooner—and college teammate of Baker Mayfield—has now drawn 11 targets over his last two contests. He's not quite on the streaming radar yet, but perhaps he'll get there by the end of the season.
report: Mark Andrews collected three catches for 50 yards on six targets Sunday in Baltimore’s Week 9 loss to the Steelers.

impact: The one target is real concerning for Anderson owners, but the good news is Anderson scored, and Sam Darnold only attempted 21 passes in the lopsided win.  Anderson also had to deal with CB Darius Slay much of the night.  His touchdown was a pass-off to S Tavon Wilson, who didn't stand a chance.  But with Quincy Enunwa back from his neck injury and seeing 10 targets in this one, Anderson's volume might take a sizable hit.  Move forward with Anderson as a big-play WR3 for next week's home opener against the Dolphins.
report: Robby Anderson caught his lone target for a 41-yard touchdown in the Jets' Week 1 win over the Lions.

impact: He's been out-targeted 21 to 6 by Quincy Enunwa through two games.  Anderson's big-play potential gives him theoretical upside each week, but his usage has been very disappointing in an offense that features shorter passing and not necessarily deep shots down the sideline.  Anderson will remain a boom-bust WR3/flex option when Gang Green visits Cleveland next.
report: Robby Anderson caught 3-of-5 targets for 27 yards in the Jets' Week 2 loss to the Dolphins.

impact: Anderson's early-season struggles continued. He has just eight catches for 108 yards and a score through the Jets' first four games while dealing with fumbles and drops. It's shaping as a lost year for Anderson.
report: Robby Anderson caught 2-of-6 passes for 18 yards in Week 4 against Jacksonville.

impact: Anderson dusted Bradley Roby relentlessly in this one, first beating him for a 12-yard catch on a nasty out route, then blowing past Roby for a 76-yard touchdown bomb, then rinsing Roby again for a 35-yard score on a pinpoint-placement throw by Sam Darnold.  Anderson's lack of volume has rendered him highly untrustworthy from a fantasy standpoint, but his big-play potential is undeniable.  He will remain a boom-bust WR3/flex option in Week 6 versus the Colts.
report: Robby Anderson caught 3-of-5 targets for 123 yards and two touchdowns in the Jets' Week 5 win over the Broncos.

impact: Five to six targets has become Anderson's weekly expectation, and he needs to connect on low volume in order to produce usable fantasy results.  Sam Darnold tried to go to Anderson for a big play in the first half of Sunday's win, but Darnold underthrew the pass and it was picked off easily by Malik Hooker.  Anderson will remain a boom-bust WR3/flex option in Week 7 against the Vikings.
report: Robby Anderson caught 3-of-5 targets for 39 yards in the Jets' Week 6 win over the Colts.

impact: His 10 targets were a team-high, but Sam Darnold was not good while completing just 40.5% of his passes and overthrowing Anderson on a potential 81-yard touchdown bomb over the top when Anderson had separation.  Anderson appeared to be shaken up in the second as he got tangled up with CB Xavier Rhodes, but he came back in the game.  Anderson will try to rebound next week on the road against the Bears, but that's a tough matchup with a rookie quarterback.
report: Robby Anderson caught 3-of-10 targets for 44 yards in the Jets' Week 7 loss to the Vikings.

impact: Anderson took two sacks for a loss of seven yards. The 35-year-old looked like he'd rather be on a golf course somewhere than playing football, committing as many turnovers (four) as Andrew Luck had touchdown passes. Anderson mostly kept it together in the first half, completing 11-of-14 throws for 90 yards and an interception. He went into self-destruct mode after that, however, continually forcing difficult throws into tight windows. That's an ill-advised strategy when your best receivers are a noticeably checked-out Kelvin Benjamin and draft bust Zay Jones. The fact that Anderson, a street free agent who barely knows the playbook, seemed like a markedly better option than Nathan Peterman shows just how bleak Buffalo's quarterback situation has gotten. With Josh Allen's elbow still healing, Anderson could draw another start next week against the Patriots, winners of four straight, on Monday Night Football.
report: Derek Anderson completed 20-of-31 passes for 175 yards with no touchdowns, three interceptions and one lost fumble Sunday in the Bills’ Week 7 loss to the Colts.

impact: It was an improvement from last week when Anderson tossed no touchdowns with three picks against the Colts.  Unfortunately, his pick this week was a long pick-six by Devin McCourty late in the game with the Bills threatening to cover the 14-point spread.  Anderson then got pulverized with a hit to the midsection on his final drive and had to leave for the locker room before Nathan Peterman came on to throw the final two passes.  This offense hasn't scored a touchdown in weeks.  They'll get the Bears at home next Sunday.  Who knows who will be under center.
report: Derek Anderson completed 22-of-39 passes for 290 yards, no touchdowns, and one interception in the Bills' 25-6, Week 8 loss to the Patriots on Monday.

impact: Finally over his hamstring issue, Allison was making his first appearance since Week 4. Although he was a ghost in the box score, Pro Football Focus charted Allison as playing as many snaps as Marquez Valdes-Scantling. Of course, a dead heat with MVS would be bad for Allison's fantasy prospects. With Randall Cobb also back, Allison is looking like a WR4/5 in the Packers' crowded receiver corps.
report: Geronimo Allison caught 1-of-1 targets for 14 yards in the Packers' Week 8 loss to the Rams.

impact: Standard operating procedure for one of the league's truly elite wide receivers. Allen is so quick in and out of his breaks and spent much of the afternoon toying with the Chiefs' replacement-level defensive backs. For Week 2 he gets a Bills secondary that got ripped by the Ravens on Sunday.
report: Keenan Allen caught 8-of-11 targets for 108 yards and a touchdown in the Chargers' Week 1 loss to the Chiefs.

impact: Allen led the Chargers in receiving in a spread-it-out game from Philip Rivers. The Chargers got up big early and didn't need to pass much in the second half, so Allen didn't get a ton of chances to exploit Buffalo's secondary. Allen is averaging seven catches and 88 yards through two games. He gets a matchup with the Rams in Week 3.
report: Keenan Allen caught 6-of-8 passes for 67 yards in the Chargers' Week 2 win over Buffalo.

impact: Allen was bottled up by the Rams defense despite Marcus Peters and Aqib Talib leaving the game early with injuries. Instead it was Mike Williams -- he also had seven targets -- who did the damage for the Chargers. Near the end of the game, Allen limped over to the sideline in some pain, but it appeared to not be very serious. Assuming the injury is minor, Allen will be a WR1/2 in a home matchup against the Garoppolo-less 49ers.
report: Keenan Allen caught 3-of-7 targets for 44 yards in the Chargers' Week 3 loss to the Rams.

impact: Allen missed some practice time this week with knee and tooth soreness, but he was able to play through it. The 49ers were down two starting players in the secondary, but Allen was held in check in a game that featured Melvin Gordon. Allen is still on pace for a 96-1,128-4 season receiving line on 144 targets despite three straight average games. Look for Allen to return to low-end WR1 form against the Raiders next Sunday.
report: Keenan Allen caught 7-of-10 targets for 63 scoreless yards in the Chargers' Week 4 win over the 49ers.

impact: Allen has now seen at least seven targets in every game, and at least nine in three-of-five. Although he's recorded just one touchdown on the year, his massive volume (nine targets per game) will inevitably lead to more fireworks-style outings for owners in the near future. His red zone usage has admittedly taken a hit with Melvin Gordon so heavily involved out of the backfield this year, but Allen's weekly floor still makes him one of the safest plays going in fantasy. He's on pace for a usage-hog 102-1,190-3 season, and remains a safe WR1 in Week 6 against the Browns.
report: Keenan Allen vacuumed 8-of-9 targets for 90 yards in the Chargers' Week 5 rout over the Raiders.

impact: Allen got his day started off strong with two catches for 33 yards on the opening drive of the game. The Chargers took the air out of the ball in the second half, but his rushing performance made his day a respectable one as his four carries were a career-high. In fact, for his career, Allen had just three rushes for 11 yards entering Sunday's game. Allen hasn't been the WR1 fantasy owners drafted to begin the season, but got off to a slow statistical start a year ago before turning it on over the back half of the year. Allen will be a high-end WR2 option Week 7 when the Chargers face the Titans in London.
report: Keenan Allen caught 4-of-6 targets for 62 yards while rushing four times for 41 yards in Sunday's Week 6 win over the Browns.

impact: Allen didn't get a ton of volume with Philip Rivers only attempting 26 passes. He had an on-field outburst after not getting targeted in the end-zone late in the fourth quarter. Allen has hit his floor all year but has only one touchdown. He's due for some positive regression in the second half.
report: Keenan Allen caught five passes for 72 yards in the Chargers' Week 7 win over the Titans.

impact: Allen didn't get a ton of volume with Philip Rivers only attempting 26 passes. He had an on-field outburst after not getting targeted in the end-zone late in the fourth quarter. Allen has hit his floor all year but has only one touchdown. He's due for some positive regression in the second half.
report: Keenan Allen caught five passes for 72 yards in the Chargers' Week 7 win over the Titans.

impact: The 100-yard day through the air was Allen's first since Week 1. Allen had little issue separating against what has been a fairly-sticky Seahawks secondary this season. Allen has a dream matchup in the sub-expansion level Raiders in Week 10, but the risk will be that things get out of hand too quickly. That seems to be the way Jon Gruden's tanking team wants it. Either way, Allen will be a locked-in WR1 in the ranks.
report: Keenan Allen caught 6-of-10 targets for 124 yards in the Chargers' Week 9 win over the Seahawks, adding two rushes for 28 additional yards.

impact: Allen did not catch a pass until there was less than a minute left in the second quarter, but he finished the first half in style. With the game tied, Allen got open in the end zone, and Philip Rivers hit him for an 11-yard score right at the end of the half. There was not much to do after the break, but Allen added another four catches including an 18-yarder to help set up a field goal. He will face a tougher test next week in Denver, but Allen will remain in the WR2 tier.
report: Keenan Allen hauled in 6-of-9 targets for 57 yards and a touchdown in the Chargers' Week 10 win over the Raiders.

impact: Allen came out firing on all cylinders, delivering three grabs for 38 yards on the Chargers' opening drive. A week after ending a seven-game touchdown drought, Allen returned to the end zone Sunday by scoring on a four-yard strike from Philip Rivers with 2:39 left in the second quarter. He celebrated that score by putting on a championship belt provided by a fan, which predictably drew a flag for unsportsmanlike conduct. The 26-year-old saw plenty of Chris Harris on Sunday, but it didn't matter as Allen delivered yet another big game. He'll face another tough assignment next week against Cardinals stud Patrick Peterson, though Allen is still good enough to warrant WR2 consideration in all formats.
report: Keenan Allen tacked on nine catches for 89 yards and a touchdown on 12 targets Sunday in L.A.’s Week 11 loss to the Broncos.

impact: Kenny Stills was Miami's big-play weapon, while Amendola (six targets), Jakeem Grant (seven), and Albert Wilson (four) essentially shared time.  Beyond Stills, this will be a tough situation to invest in for fantasy purposes.
report: Danny Amendola caught 4-of-6 targets for 26 yards in the Dolphins' Week 1 win over Tennessee.

impact: He has drawn 6 and 4 targets through two games in Miami's low-volume passing offense, where Ryan Tannehill has yet to attempt 30 throws.  Amendola is capable of flirting with PPR value in games where Tannehill is forced to throw more, but the Dolphins' game plans are consistently balanced to run heavy.
report: Danny Amendola caught 4-of-4 targets for 32 yards in the Dolphins' Week 2 win over the Jets.

impact: That's about what Amendola has done all three games in a Dolphins uniform. He's the chain-mover in a receiver corps full of big-play threats. Even in PPR leagues, it is not going to translate to fantasy value.
report: Danny Amendola caught 3-of-3 targets for 42 yards in the Dolphins' Week 3 win over the Raiders.

impact: The two-catch afternoon came even with DeVante Parker (quad) sitting. Amendola has 13 grabs for 121 yards through his first four games as a Dolphin, putting him on pace for 52/484. If Amendola appears in all 16 games, it would be the first time he has done so since 2014.
report: Danny Amendola caught 2-of-3 targets for 21 yards in the Dolphins' Week 4 loss to the Patriots.

impact: Amendola led the Dolphins in targets with Ryan Tannehill checking down all game. His biggest play was a 16-yard contested catch on third down in second quarter, but he wasn't much of a factor. With DeVante Parker on track to return next week, Amendola's target share is going to take a hit.
report: Danny Amendola caught 3-of-4 passes for 30 yards in Week 5 against the Bengals.

impact: Amendola saw plenty of work in the win, though he averaged just 7.1 yards per reception with a long gain of 11 yards. Leonard Floyd pulled a wrestling move on Amendola in the first quarter but luckily the diminutive slot receiver was able to shake it off. Amendola's season-long touchdown drought continued against Chicago, though he saw more targets in this game than he had in his previous three combined. The veteran will go against Matt Patricia, another former Patriot, when the Dolphins host Detroit in Week 7.
report: Danny Amendola absorbed eight-of-11 targets for 59 yards Sunday in the Dolphins’ Week 6 win over Chicago.

impact: With DeVante Parker inactive and Albert Wilson (hip) banged up early, Amendola posted a new season-high for yardage. He now has 14 grabs on 18 targets over his past two games. With Kenny Stills joining Wilson on the shelf late against the Lions, Amendola could have some Week 8 relevance against the Texans.
report: Danny Amendola caught 6-of-7 targets for 84 yards and a touchdown in the Dolphins' Week 7 loss to the Lions.

impact: It was a bit of a frustrating fantasy day for Amendola. He did open the game with a 26-yard catch, but Brock Osweiler badly overthrew him on what should have been a long gain later in the first half. He did keep a drive alive with a fourth-down conversion and easily led the team in receiving, but there was not much room for fantasy success with the offense struggling to move the ball. Amendola will once again be a low-upside option next week against the Packers.
report: Danny Amendola hauled in 5-of-7 targets for 47 yards in the Dolphins' Week 9 win over the Jets.

impact: Amendola picked up a large chunk of his yards on a 39-yard catch-and-run over the middle of the field in the second quarter. His team-high 72 yards were certainly encouraging, but Amendola's ultimately nothing more than a desperate PPR floor play given that he has yet to eclipse 90 yards in any outing this season. He's actually averaged 8.2 targets since Brock Osweiler took over, so his dwindling value would only plummet further if Ryan Tannehill is able to return in Week 12 after Miami's bye.
report: Danny Amendola vacuumed 7-of-10 targets for a team-high 72 yards in the Dolphins' Week 10 loss to the Packers.

impact: Allen continues to struggle to produce positive yardage -- he now has 32 yards on 16 carries this season -- but he also continues to find the end zone. His first score came on a 12-yard pass in which he was able to get the corner and dive for the pylon, and he added a one-yard rushing touchdown in the third quarter. He is going to offer next to nothing when he fails to score, but Allen is a weekly FLEX consideration because of his red-zone role.
report: Javorius Allen rushed six times for seven yards and a touchdown and caught three passes for 19 yards and another score in the Ravens' Week 3 win over the Broncos.

impact: Allen played ahead of Alex Collins for most of the second quarter after Collins lost a goal-line fumble. He didn't have any highlights, but his workloads have been trending up. Allen will be a touchdown-dependent FLEX for Week 5 against the Browns.
report: Javorius Allen rushed 10 times for 30 yards and caught two passes for 17 yards in Week 4 against the Steelers.

impact: Allen also lost a fumble on one his six catches. He out-touched Alex Collins 14-to-13 and once again entered the game for goal line opportunities, though he failed to convert. Allen has at worst forced a committee with Collins and has a firm grasp on receiving work in the Baltimore offense. He's arguably a safer fantasy option at this stage since he is siphoning goal line snaps. Allen will enter Week 6 as an RB2/FLEX option against the Titans with a larger boost in PPR formats.
report: Javorius Allen rushed eight times for 34 yards while catching 6-of-8 targets for 44 yards in Sunday's Week 5 loss to the Browns.

impact: Only one week after out-touching (14-13) and out-snapping (50-27) teammate Alex Collins, Allen fell victim to Baltimore's early lead and ensuing run-heavy game script. Collins inevitably out-carried Buck 19-1 on the day. In a closer game, perhaps Allen would've been used more, but his week-to-week usage is a legitimate dice roll at this point given coach Jon Harbaugh's recent statement about just "keeping Collins fresh." Allen has a higher floor (and will be needed) as the team's only pass-catching back in Week 7 against the Saints.
