report: Javorius Allen rushed just one time for one yard and caught all three of his targets for 18 yards in the Ravens' Week 6 mauling of the Titans.

impact: Allen has four carries for four yards over his past two games. Alex Collins is hardly setting the world on fire, but Allen is not making a meaningful push for more work. Allen is a bottom-of-the-barrel, bye week fill-in RB3. The Ravens get the Panthers in Week 8.
report: Javorius Allen rushed three times for three yards in the Ravens' Week 7 loss to the Saints, adding three receptions for 21 additional yards.

impact: Allen has four carries for four yards over his past two games. Alex Collins is hardly setting the world on fire, but Allen is not making a meaningful push for more work. Allen is a bottom-of-the-barrel, bye week fill-in RB3. The Ravens get the Panthers in Week 8.
report: Javorius Allen rushed three times for three yards in the Ravens' Week 7 loss to the Saints, adding three receptions for 21 additional yards.

impact: He didn't record a carry and was out-touched 13-3 by Alex Collins, who ran the ball 11 times for 49 yards and a score.  Collins lost a fumble again, but the coaches stuck by him.  Allen has registered touch counts of four, six, and three the last three weeks.  Allen is no longer a reliable fantasy option.
report: Javorius Allen caught 3-of-5 targets for 18 yards and one touchdown in the Ravens' Week 8 loss to the Panthers.

impact: The Ravens all but abandoned their running game in the second half, which obviously limited Allen's rushing opportunities. With Ty Montgomery likely to debut after the Ravens' bye week, Allen's days of being a relevant fantasy producer could be coming to an end. Outside of deeper leagues, it's probably time to cut bait.
report: Javorius Allen rushed once for a six-yard pick-up while snaring five catches for nine yards on five targets Sunday in Baltimore’s Week 9 loss to the Steelers.

impact: Allen was demoted to the Ravens' No. 3 back behind Gus Edwards and Alex Collins and can be dropped beyond the deepest of PPR leagues.
report: Javorius Allen rushed once for two yards in the Ravens' Week 11 win over the Bengals.

impact: Allen replaced a faceplanting Nathan Peterman in the third quarter. It wasn't much of a debut, but he moved the offense better than Peterman. Allen should've had a touchdown that was dropped by Kelvin Benjamin in the end-zone. The Bills are likely to continue to go with Allen as their starter going forward. He'll get a tough test in the Chargers in Week 2.
report: Josh Allen completed 6-of-15 passes for 74 yards in Buffalo's Week 1 game against Baltimore.

impact: Allen moved the offense better than Nathan Peterman, but there were some rough stretches in his first start. He didn't get much help from an offense that allowed five sacks, but Allen held on to the ball too long at times and made some reckless throws, resulting in the two picks. Allen showed off his arm on a 57-yard bomb to Zay Jones, and his garbage-time touchdown to Kelvin Benjamin was threaded in a tight window. The Bills are committed to Allen as their starter for the rest of the year. He'll get another tough matchup with the Vikings in Week 3.
report: Josh Allen completed 18-of-33 passes for 245 yards with a touchdown and two interceptions in Sunday's Week 2 loss to the Chargers.

impact: Despite dealing with constant pressure throughout the afternoon, Allen made play after play with both his arm and legs in Buffalo's dominating win over Minnesota. The Bills' trenches did little to help Allen, but the No. 7 overall pick's ability to scramble and throw on the run allowed him to extend plays outside of the pocket and consistently find open receivers in the flats. Allen has quietly become Buffalo's red zone back, scoring two touchdowns inside the 10-yard line on Sunday. Allen and the Bills travel to Lambeau Field to face the Packers in Week 4.
report: Josh Allen completed 15-of-22 passes for 196 yards and one touchdown, adding 10 carries for 39 yards and two touchdowns on the ground in the Bills' Week 3 victory over the Vikings.

impact: Everything the Bills were in Week 3 against the Vikings, that's what they weren't today. Allen entered halftime just 5-of-19 for 58 yards and a pick. He was scarcely better after the break, where he specialized in taking thundering sacks as he spun backwards. His picks were amateur hour decisions. This kind of wild inconsistency is going to be Allen's hallmark as he gets his NFL sea legs amidst scarily-little surrounding talent in Buffalo. He will not be a recommended streamer against the Titans' upstart defense in Week 5.
report: Josh Allen completed 16-of-33 passes for 151 yards, zero touchdowns and two interceptions in the Bills' 22-0, Week 4 loss to the Packers, also losing a fumble and taking seven sacks.

impact: Buffalo pulled this upset without any hint of a passing game, instead relying on Allen's 14-yard rushing touchdown on their opening drive and two Steven Hauschka field goals, including the 46-yard game winner as time expired.  The Bills are now a surprising 2-3 after upset victories over Tennessee and Minnesota.  Allen will remain a high-variance QB2 when Buffalo visits Houston next.
report: Josh Allen completed 10-of-19 passes for 82 yards and an interception in the Bills' Week 5 win over the Titans, 13-12.

impact: Ajayi did not show any ill effects from his back injury in this one, running hard and consistently creating yards after contact. He did briefly leave the game with trainers in the fourth quarter, but he was back on the field after a couple plays. His health will remain a concern, but Ajayi will be an RB2 as long as he is healthy.
report: Jay Ajayi rushed 15 times for 70 yards and hauled in 3-of-4 targets for 11 yards in the Eagles' Week 4 loss to the Titans.

impact: Ajayi also lost a goal line fumble early in the third quarter as the Eagles were trying to get back into a 17-3 affair. To top it all off, he was announced as questionable with a knee injury, though he did remain in the game. Wendell Smallwood out-gained Ajayi 71-34 on the afternoon. Yet to see truly elite usage or eclipse 81 yards from scrimmage, Ajayi is settling in as a low-end RB2. His health will be worth monitoring for Week 6, as the Eagles are playing in the Thursday night game.
report: Jay Ajayi rushed eight times for 29 yards in the Eagles' Week 5 loss to the Vikings, adding a five-yard reception.

impact: Agholor has double-digit targets in each of the first two weeks, and there is some belief Carson Wentz (knee) could return for Week 3 versus Indianapolis.  With Alshon Jeffery (shoulder) slated to miss at least one more game, Agholor will remain a volume monster.  He's earned WR2 treatment for the foreseeable future.
report: Nelson Agholor caught 8-of-12 targets for 95 yards and a touchdown in the Eagles' Week 2 loss at Tampa Bay.

impact: For the second time in three games, Agholor received all of his targets near the line of scrimmage and failed totally tangible receiving yardage. Through three games, Agholor has 20 receptions for a 145 yards (7.3 yards per reception). With Alshon Jefferey nearing a return, Agholor may quickly find himself third in line for targets. As for now, Agholor is a WR3/FLEX option in PPR formats in Week 4 against the Titans.
report: Nelson Agholor caught 4-of-5 targets for 24 yards in Sunday's Week 4 game versus the Colts.

impact: It was a day to forget for Agholor. He dropped at least two passes including one which would have converted a third-and-long, and he committed a bad fumble which luckily for him rolled out of bounds. On the bright side, he still saw 12 targets in Alshon Jeffery's first game back and had a couple chances at big plays. He will look to bounce back against a scuffling Vikings defense next week.
report: Nelson Agholor hauled in 5-of-12 targets for 22 yards in the Eagles' Week 4 loss to the Titans.

impact: The four targets were a new season low. Agholor is sitting on one touchdown and has cleared 50 yards once in five games. Since Carson Wentz's return, he is averaging seven targets. Agholor will be a low-end WR3 for Thursday night's game against the Giants.
report: Nelson Agholor caught 4-of-4 targets for 45 yards in the Eagles' Week 5 loss to the Vikings.

impact: This is what happens when you start the game with -1 yard on your first four targets. Quick hitters to Agholor simply did not work in this one, as the Panthers’ speedy linebackers tracked him down quickly each time. As a slot receiver, Agholor will theoretically have the Eagles’ best Week 8 pass-catcher matchup against Jacksonville, but his usage and production warrant WR4 treatment at this point.
report: Nelson Agholor caught 6-of-7 targets for 20 yards in the Eagles’ Week 7 loss to the Panthers.

impact: This is what happens when you start the game with -1 yard on your first four targets. Quick hitters to Agholor simply did not work in this one, as the Panthers’ speedy linebackers tracked him down quickly each time. As a slot receiver, Agholor will theoretically have the Eagles’ best Week 8 pass-catcher matchup against Jacksonville, but his usage and production warrant WR4 treatment at this point.
report: Nelson Agholor caught 6-of-7 targets for 20 yards in the Eagles’ Week 7 loss to the Panthers.

impact: With Alshon Jeffery being shadowed by Jalen Ramsey, Agholor saw heavy usage the first half. He was able to come down with a 39-yard catch, and he was just inches away from what would have been another long gain and potentially touchdown. Unfortunately, he disappeared in the second half with his only catch coming on a screen late in the fourth quarter. Agholor has failed to top 50 yards in five of his last six games and has not found the end zone since Week 2. He is not a must-hold through the bye week.
report: Nelson Agholor hauled in 3-of-6 targets for 49 yards in the Eagles' Week 8 win over the Jaguars.

impact: It breaks a downward trend for Agholor, who was held under 50 yards in six of the last nine games. Agholor missed a few plays with a stinger but was able to return. Most of his damage came on a 51-yard catch late in the fourth quarter. Agholor has a decent target share, but he's going to lose some targets when Golden Tate gets up to speed.
report: Nelson Agholor caught 5-of-7 targets for 83 yards in Week 10 against Dallas.

impact: Agholor turned seven targets into five catches and 83 yards in Golden Tate's first game with the Eagles, but he was more of an afterthought in this one. Agholor also appeared to injure himself on his final target, but nothing was announced. With Tate's role growing -- he led the team with eight targets -- Agholor will struggle for consistent fantasy value.
report: Nelson Agholor did not catch either of his two targets in the Eagles' Week 11 loss to the Saints.

impact: With the running game struggling, it made sense for Adams to get more opportunities, and he made the most of them on Sunday. He was fine on four carries in the first half, but he exploded for a 21-yard gain after the break to help spark a touchdown drive before going for 17 to set up another score in the fourth. The rookie has a scare when it looked like he fumbled with the Eagles attempting to run out the clock, but he was ruled down on review. Looking like the best runner on the roster, Adams has a good chance to see more work coming out of the bye. He is an add in all formats.
report: Josh Adams rushed nine times for 61 yards and caught his only target for six yards in the Eagles' Week 8 win over the Jaguars.

impact: Adams was the Eagles' leading rusher and saw more carries than Wendell Smallwood and Corey Clement. After outplaying Smallwood before the bye, he's cemented his role ahead of Smallwood as the primary early-down back. Adams is worth picking up in leagues where available. He has an attackable matchup against the Saints in Week 11.
report: Josh Adams rushed seven times for 47 yards in Week 10 against the Cowboys.

impact: He added 19 yards on three catches. Adams was the lone bright spot in a pitiful display from the Eagles, consistently gaining yards against one of the tougher run defenses in the league. His 28-yard touchdown run was Philly's only score of the game. Adams now has 178 yards on just 27 carries (6.6 YPC) over the last four games. His role should continue to expand down the stretch.
report: Josh Adams rushed seven times for 53 yards and a touchdown in the Eagles' Week 11 loss to the Saints.

impact: Despite shadow coverage from Xavier Rhodes, Adams was able to consistently get open on Sunday. His touchdown came on a quick out in which he was able to cut back and beat a couple defenders to the goal line. Unfortunately, he dropped one of his targets, had a long catch called back on a spurious offensive pass interference call, and had a touchdown knocked out of his hands, but he still put together a solid fantasy day in one of his toughest matchups of the season. Assuming Aaron Rodgers’ knee continues to cooperate, Adams will be a solid WR1 next week in Washington.
report: Davante Adams hauled in 8-of-12 targets for 64 yards and a touchdown in the Packers' Week 2 tie with the Vikings.

impact: Adams also drew a 21-yard DPI. Adams has yet to have a 90-yard game this season — he's averaging 68 — but has scored all three times out. He's the preferred red zone weapon for the best quarterback in football. Adams will have a good shot at making it 4-of-4 on TDs in Week 4 against the Bills.
report: Davante Adams caught 7-of-9 targets for 52 yards and a touchdown in the Packers' Week 3 loss to the Redskins.

impact: Adams was dealing with Tre'Davious White but aside from not finding the end zone, he had his typical game. With 25 percent of the season in the books, Adams is on pace for 112/1,140/12. That's certainly within his range of outcomes. Adams will remain a back-end WR1 for Week 5 against the Lions.
report: Davante Adams caught 8-of-14 targets for 81 yards in the Packers' Week 4 win over the Bills.

impact: What calf injury?  Adams was a late addition to the injury report during the week but looked no worse for the wear as he chewed up chunk gains all day against Darius Slay and others.  The 12 targets led the team on a day Randall Cobb and Geronimo Allison were out and injured.  Adams seemed to be the only target Aaron Rodgers could trust fully on a day he attempted 52 passes.  Adams should work over Richard Sherman and the Niners next Monday night.
report: Davante Adams caught 9-of-12 targets for 140 yards and one touchdown in the Packers' 31-23, Week 5 loss to the Lions.

impact: Adams has been on a tear the past couple weeks with Randall Cobb and Geronimo Allison sidelined with injuries.  In the two games, Adams has reeled in 19-of-28 targets for 272 yards and three touchdowns against the Lions and Niners.  Things didn't really pop off for him until the second half when Adams scored a 16-yard touchdown to tie the game at 30-30 with 1:55 left.  He then made multiple catches on the final drive to get the Packers into field goal range for the win.  This all came after he caught a nine-yard TD in the first quarter.  Cobb and Allison should be back after the Week 7 bye, but Adams will remain an obvious WR1 the rest of the way.
report: Davante Adams caught 10-of-16 targets for 132 yards and two touchdowns in the Packers' come-from-behind 33-30, Week 6 win over the 49ers.

impact: Adams has been on a tear the past couple weeks with Randall Cobb and Geronimo Allison sidelined with injuries.  In the two games, Adams has reeled in 19-of-28 targets for 272 yards and three touchdowns against the Lions and Niners.  Things didn't really pop off for him until the second half when Adams scored a 16-yard touchdown to tie the game at 30-30 with 1:55 left.  He then made multiple catches on the final drive to get the Packers into field goal range for the win.  This all came after he caught a nine-yard TD in the first quarter.  Cobb and Allison should be back after the Week 7 bye, but Adams will remain an obvious WR1 the rest of the way.
report: Davante Adams caught 10-of-16 targets for 132 yards and two touchdowns in the Packers' come-from-behind 33-30, Week 6 win over the 49ers.

impact: With the Packers back to full strength at receiver, Adams drew fewer than 10 targets for the first time since Week 3 but still managed to post his third-straight 130-yard game. Adams was routinely left completely wide open by the Rams' struggling secondary. The Pack should be headed for a shootout with the Patriots in Week 9, though Adams will likely find himself shadowed by Stephon Gilmore.
report: Davante Adams caught 5-of-7 targets for 133 yards in the Packers' Week 8 loss to the Rams.

impact: Adams got open in the end-zone on a broken play for his touchdown. It was mostly a quiet night for Adams after that, though he still paced the Packers with nine targets. Adams has over 80 yards or a touchdown in every game this season. Even in a matchup with Xavien Howard, he's a top-10 play against the Miami next week.
report: Davante Adams caught 6-of-9 targets for 40 yards and a touchdown in Week 9 against the Patriots.

impact: It was an all-around lowly day for the Packers' passing game, partly because it wasn't needed. Aaron Jones pummeled Miami's front-seven for 15/145/2, allowing Aaron Rodgers and Co. to sip Mai Tais throughout the afternoon. Adams still made the most of his seven targets, crossing up Fins' top corner Xavien Howard for one score, and beating backup DB Bobby McCain off the line on a slant for his second of the day. There's no denying the Packers still have a lot to sort out as it pertains to their aerial attack, but Adams remains one of the safest WR1's in the league no matter game script.
report: Davante Adams hauled in 4-of-7 targets for 57 yards and two scores in the Packers' easy Week 10 win over the Dolphins.

impact: The 166 yards were a career high. Adams' mind meld with Aaron Rodgers was on full display this evening, never more so than on his 57-yard reception in the fourth quarter. With the rush in his face, Rodgers unleashed a perfectly-thrown dime to hit Adams in stride. With six games to go, Adams is now just 47 yards shy of his first 1,000-yard campaign. The Vikings are on tap for Week 12.
report: Davante Adams caught 10-of-12 targets for 166 yards in the Packers' Week 11 loss to the Seahawks.

impact: All of his catches came after halftime as the Cardinals were forced to air it out trailing by 21. Seals-Jones was the intended receiver on Sam Bradford’s interception in the second half, which seemed to be a miscommunication. He also dropped a would-be touchdown in the fourth quarter, though Bradford could have placed the ball better. It was a rough opener for the second-year tight end, though his workload was somewhat encouraging. RSJ should probably be avoided next week in a difficult matchup against the Rams.
report: Ricky Seals-Jones chipped in with three catches for 19 yards on six targets Sunday in the Cardinals’ Week 1 loss to the Redskins.

impact: It is a disappointing line for Seals-Jones, but it is not his fault. Arizona's passing game is comatose with Sam Bradford under center. Unfortunately, Seals-Jones will not be a fantasy option until that changes, especially with Jermaine Gresham on the way back.
report: Ricky Seals-Jones hauled in 4-of-6 targets for 17 yards in the Cardinals' Week 2 loss to the Rams.

impact: Seals-Jones made his presence felt early with a 35-yard score down the left side where he was left all alone by the Chicago defense and walked into the end zone. His failed to convert his other two targets for receptions. Jermaine Gresham made a return on Sunday and drew a pair of targets as he will cut into a small portion of Seals-Jones' opportunity, which wasn't exactly strong to begin with. Seals-Jones now has eight catches for 61 yards through three games.
report: Ricky Seals-Jones caught 1-of-3 targets for 35 yards and a touchdown in Sunday's Week 3 loss to the Bears.

impact: The highlight of his day came on a 31-yard catch down the right sideline in which Josh Rosen put right on the money. It was second consecutive game in which Seals-Jones had a 30-yard reception. Through four weeks, Seals-Jones has reeled in 10-of-19 targets for 123 yards and a touchdowns. He will enter Week 5 as a TE2 option against the 49ers.
report: Ricky Seals-Jones caught 2-of-4 targets for 52 yards in Sunday's Week 4 loss to the Seahawks.

impact: Just brutal. RSJ still carries mild streaming appeal at an injury-ravaged fantasy position, though obviously the early returns for him have not been encouraging. The second-year tight end will look to rebound from Sunday's 0-for next time out against the Vikings.
report: Ricky Seals-Jones didn’t catch any of his six targets Sunday in the Cardinals’ Week 5 win over San Francisco.

impact: It's a solid rebound after Jones was held without a catch on six targets last week. He did almost all of his damage early before the Cardinals offense stalled out in the second half. Seals-Jones' highlight was a jump ball over Harrison Smith for 40 yards. He's a TE2 for Thursday night's matchup against the Broncos.
report: Ricky Seals-Jones caught 5-of-6 passes for 69 yards in Week 6 against the Vikings.

impact: New OC Byron Leftwich's scheme benefitted nearly everyone except Seals-Jones, who stayed splitting time with incumbent starter Jermaine Gresham. To add insult to injury, Gresham even out-gained RSJ 22-12 on the day. Unless Gresham is ruled out, Seals-Jones can't be trusted as a starting tight end moving forward.
report: Ricky Seals-Jones caught 2-of-4 targets for 12 yards in the Cardinals' Week 8 victory over the Niners.

impact: Seals-Jones took on a larger role with Chad Williams out. His nine targets were behind only Larry Fitzgerald. Williams looks likely to miss another week, so Seals-Jones will be on the Week 11 streaming radar against the Raiders.
report: Ricky Seals-Jones caught 5-of-9 targets for 51 yards in Week 10 against the Chiefs.

impact: It was a rough game for the 23-year-old converted wideout, as he dropped a pass and committed a devastating holding penalty that nullified a late 57-yard David Johnson touchdown. The five yards were his second fewest of the season, though he's been held below 15 in 3-of-4. RSJ will be a high-risk TE2 for Week 12 against the Chargers.
report: Ricky Seals-Jones caught 1-of-3 targets for five yards in the Cardinals' Week 11 loss to the Raiders.

impact: Snead didn't make much noise in the preseason, but he worked as the clear No. 3 wideout behind Michael Crabtree and John Brown. His role looks larger than expected in Baltimore's offense, but this may end up one of his better games. Playing on a short week, Snead would be a low-upside waiver-wire flyer.
report: Willie Snead caught 4-of-6 targets for 49 yards and a touchdown in Baltimore's Week 1 win over Buffalo.

impact: This was actually Snead's worst game of the season, but he still managed a couple big plays including a third-down conversion in the third quarter. Snead does not offer much upside as the No. 3 option in the passing game, but he can provide value in deeper PPR leagues.
report: Willie Snead hauled in 3-of-5 targets for 39 yards in the Ravens' Week 3 win over the Broncos.

impact: Snead was fourth on the team in targets as he's established himself as the possession receiver for the Ravens. Snead has four or more catches in four of five games this season, but has yet to reach 60-yards in any game to this point. The Ravens play at Tennessee in Week 6.
report: Willie Snead caught 5-of-7 targets for 55 yards in Sunday's Week 5 loss to the Browns.

impact: His catches and targets were both team-highs, with Michael Crabtree (6/93/1) leading the Ravens with 93 receiving yards. Snead has established himself as the club's possession wideout, but even finished with the second-most air yards (123) among Baltimore's receivers Sunday. It was all at the expense of John Brown, who recorded just two catches for 23 yards. Crabtree and Brown will still rank higher in Week 7 against the Saints.
report: Willie Snead hauled in a team-high 7-of-10 targets for 60 yards in the Ravens' Week 6 victory over the Titans.

impact: Amazingly, this was Snead's worst game of the season. He's averaging a solid 48 weekly yards but not really doing much with them in the way of catches or scores. He hasn't found the end zone since Week 1. Snead is just a desperation PPR fill-in.
report: Willie Snead caught 3-of-7 targets for 23 yards in the Ravens' Week 7 loss to the Saints.

impact: Amazingly, this was Snead's worst game of the season. He's averaging a solid 48 weekly yards but not really doing much with them in the way of catches or scores. He hasn't found the end zone since Week 1. Snead is just a desperation PPR fill-in.
report: Willie Snead caught 3-of-7 targets for 23 yards in the Ravens' Week 7 loss to the Saints.

impact: The 11 targets led the team and were four more than John Brown.  Snead has drawn double-digit looks in two of the last three games, but he hasn't scored since Week 1.  Five catches for roughly 50 yards has become what to expect from Snead.  He'll be a low-upside WR4 next week versus Pittsburgh.
report: Willie Snead caught 5-of-11 targets for 54 yards in the Ravens' Week 8 loss to the Panthers.

impact: Snead padded his stats in garbage time with six second-half catches, though none of them were for big gains. The fourth-year Ball State alum continues to see a heavy workload—he's drawn seven or more targets in each of his last six games. Unfortunately he hasn't scored a touchdown since the Ravens' opener and has only reached 60 yards once this season. Snead will get the Raiders at home after Baltimore's bye week.
report: Willie Snead came down with seven catches for 58 yards on eight targets Sunday in the Ravens’ Week 9 loss to Pittsburgh.

impact: Snead led Baltimore in targets, but as a team they only threw for 150 yards.  With Lamar Jackson expected to continue starting in a run-focused attack, Snead will be a low-upside WR4 specific to PPR leagues going forward.
report: Willie Snead caught 5-of-8 targets for 51 yards in the Ravens' Week 11 win over Cincinnati.

impact: Swoope played behind Mo Alie-Cox in the Colts' backup tight end timeshare with Eric Ebron out in front.  Swoope is a Dynasty stash but nothing more.
report: Erik Swoope caught 1-of-2 targets for a two-yard touchdown in the Colts' Week 6 loss to the Jets.

impact: Wright went 3-23 on five targets in Week 1 and seems to have carved out the slot job for the Panthers.  Cam Newton really had an affinity for him on third down, especially with no Greg Olsen (foot) in the lineup.  Wright's touchdown came on third down from five yards out.  There are worse players to roster in deep PPR leagues.  The Panthers get the Bengals in Week 3.
report: Jarius Wright caught 5-of-7 targets for 62 yards and one touchdown in the Panthers' Week 2 loss to the Falcons.

impact: Wright went 3-23 on five targets in Week 1 and seems to have carved out the slot job for the Panthers.  Cam Newton really had an affinity for him on third down, especially with no Greg Olsen (foot) in the lineup.  Wright's touchdown came on third down from five yards out.  There are worse players to roster in deep PPR leagues.  The Panthers get the Bengals in Week 3.
report: Jarius Wright caught 5-of-7 targets for 62 yards and one touchdown in the Panthers' Week 2 loss to the Falcons.

impact: Woods did not take advantage of his opportunities in the opener, but he rectified the problem against the Cardinals. He caught three passes for 30 yards in the first quarter, and he kept making plays the rest of the way. His fantasy day could have been much better, but Jared Goff missed him when he was wide open in the end zone in the fourth. The Rams will have a tougher time with the Chargers next week, but Woods will still be a solid WR3.
report: Robert Woods hauled in 6-of-9 targets for 81 yards in the Rams' Week 2 win over the Cardinals.

impact: Going into the game, Woods was a breakout candidate as he was leading the team in targets and air yards but only had 118 scoreless yards to show for it. Today was a different story. The Chargers had no answers for Jared Goff and Woods, who scored two times on the same red zone play and ended with over 100 receiving yards. With at least nine targets in all three games, Woods is a WR2/3 even against the Vikings on Thursday night.
report: Robert Woods caught 10-of-11 targets for 104 yards and two touchdowns in the Rams' Week 3 win over the Chargers.

impact: With both Brandin Cooks and Cooper Kupp sidelined by concussions, Woods was the No. 1 receiver for most of this game, and he delivered. He made a great move after the catch to pick up third down and a lot more in the second quarter, and he sparked a touchdown drive with a 56-yard gain on a jet sweep in the third quarter. He drew a defensive pass interference on fourth down later that drive to keep it alive. Woods now has at least 100 yards from scrimmage in each of his last three games while Cooks and Kupp are question marks for next week. If they do not play, Woods will be a WR1 against the Broncos.
report: Robert Woods hauled in 5-of-7 targets for 92 yards and rushed twice for 53 yards in the Rams' Week 5 win over the Seahawks.

impact: Woods also drew an end zone DPI that set the Rams up at the one-yard line in the third quarter. With Cooper Kupp (knee) ailing, Woods gobbled up more than half of the Rams' receiving yards. Woods has now cleared 90 yards in four-straight games, and 100 in three of his past four. He's been operating as a poor man's Adam Thielen in the Rams' three-headed attack at wideout. The 49ers are a plus matchup for Week 7.
report: Robert Woods caught 7-of-10 targets for 109 yards in the Rams' Week 6 win over the Broncos, adding a 12-yard rush.

impact: The Rams' passing attack did not have to do much in the easy win, but Woods still managed to top 75 for the sixth game in a row. He helped set up a field goal with a 21-yard gain on third down in the first quarter, and he went for 32 yards to spark another scoring drive in the second. With the Packers likely to offer more resistance, Woods will once again be a high-end WR2 next week.
report: Robert Woods hauled in 5-of-7 targets for 78 yards in the Rams' Week 7 win over the 49ers.

impact: The Rams' passing attack did not have to do much in the easy win, but Woods still managed to top 75 for the sixth game in a row. He helped set up a field goal with a 21-yard gain on third down in the first quarter, and he went for 32 yards to spark another scoring drive in the second. With the Packers likely to offer more resistance, Woods will once again be a high-end WR2 next week.
report: Robert Woods hauled in 5-of-7 targets for 78 yards in the Rams' Week 7 win over the 49ers.

impact: Woods has now cleared 70 yards in seven-straight games, though he has not found the end zone since Week 4. It has been disappointing in fantasy, but Woods' usage and opportunity remain elite. The volume will remain and the scores will come. The Saints are on deck for a likely Week 9 shootout.
report: Robert Woods caught 5-of-7 targets for 70 yards in the Rams' Week 8 win over the Packers.

impact: Woods did not match Brandin Cooks' big game, but he consistently helped Jared Goff move the chains. He made a diving 12-yard grab on the second drive to keep the scoring march moving, came up with another 13-yard gain in the second quarter, and made a great sideline grab to help set up a field goal just before halftime. He picked up right where he left off after the break, catching two passes for 29 yards on the opening touchdown drive. He took a bit of backseat to Cooper Kupp the rest of the way, but it was still another solid outing from Woods, who has at least 70 yards in every game since Week 1. Woods will be a high-end WR2 next week against the Seahawks.
report: Robert Woods hauled in 5-of-9 targets for 71 yards in the Rams' Week 9 loss to the Saints.

impact: Woods has now cleared 70 yards receiving in every game since Week 1. One of the league's most consistent players, Woods' floor will be jacked even higher if Cooper Kupp (knee) is forced to miss significant time. Woods will be a WR1 for Week 11 when the Rams journey to Mexico City to take on the equally high-flying Chiefs.
report: Robert Woods caught 4-of-5 targets for 89 yards in the Rams' Week 10 win over the Seahawks, adding three rushes for 17 additional yards.

impact: Trailing 38-3 during the first half due to Mitchell Trubisky's career performance, the Bucs had no choice but to turn one dimensional and telegraph their play-calling. Fitzpatrick, who threw for 126 yards and one interception before exiting, didn't stand a chance against the Bears' pass rush. Winston will finish the game under center.
report: Jameis Winston replaced Ryan Fitzpatrick to start the third quarter.

impact: An 80% completion rate is actually impressive given that Winston was suspended and away from football during the first three weeks. He replaced Ryan Fitzpatrick, who tossed an interception in his own right, at the half and will seemingly stay under center (barring injury) for the remainder of the season. Winston will have the entire bye week to become acclimated to football again and will return in Week 6 as a sneaky low-end QB1 against the Falcons' injury-riddled secondary.
report: Jameis Winston completed 16-of-20 passes for 145 yards, one touchdown, and two picks in the Bucs' Week 4 loss to the Bears.

impact: Winston made a couple mistakes in this game, but he delivered the big fantasy performance everyone was expecting. He was sharp early, completing four of his five passes on the opening drive including a good throw to Cameron Brate for a 15-yard touchdown, but the offense fell into a lull after that. Following an interception in the second quarter, Winston bounced back to lead a big touchdown drive he capped with a 10-yard throw to O.J. Howard, and the offense was in sync from that point on. Winston did throw an end-zone interception on the first drive of the second half -- a forced pass was tipped into the air -- but he led three straight scoring drives after that to make it a game. He got Tampa in position for a potential game-winner, but a wild final play in which he took a draw up the middle before attempting a lateral fell short. Winston faces a tougher matchup next week against the Browns, but he should be in the QB1 conversation the rest of the season.
report: Jameis Winston completed 30-of-41 passes for 395 yards, four touchdowns, and two interceptions in the Bucs' Week 6 loss to the Falcons.

impact: Winston turned in one his specials where he showcased all of the positives that made him the first overall selection in the 2015 draft and all of the mistakes that keep his status as a franchise quarterback in question. Winston threw two telegraphed interceptions and a lost a fumble on a scramble, but also shook off multiple sacks and extended drives in the run game consistently all afternoon. The highlight of his day was a 14-yard touchdown run where he sacrificed his body and dove for the end zone in the second quarter. Winston has now turned in games of 395 and 365 passing yards in his two starts. 300-yard passing games are just about something we should expect weekly in this Tampa Bay passing game. Despite his propensity for turnovers each week, Winston will be a high-floor fantasy option in Week 8 on the road against the Bengals.
report: Jameis Winston completed 32-of-52 passes for 365 yards with an interception while rushing 10 times for 55 yards and a touchdown in Sunday's Week 7 win over the Browns.

impact: Winston turned in one his specials where he showcased all of the positives that made him the first overall selection in the 2015 draft and all of the mistakes that keep his status as a franchise quarterback in question. Winston threw two telegraphed interceptions and a lost a fumble on a scramble, but also shook off multiple sacks and extended drives in the run game consistently all afternoon. The highlight of his day was a 14-yard touchdown run where he sacrificed his body and dove for the end zone in the second quarter. Winston has now turned in games of 395 and 365 passing yards in his two starts. 300-yard passing games are just about something we should expect weekly in this Tampa Bay passing game. Despite his propensity for turnovers each week, Winston will be a high-floor fantasy option in Week 8 on the road against the Bengals.
report: Jameis Winston completed 32-of-52 passes for 365 yards with an interception while rushing 10 times for 55 yards and a touchdown in Sunday's Week 7 win over the Browns.

impact: And all four of the picks were on him.  The fourth did in Winston, as it was pick sixed by Bengals rookie S Jessie Bates to put Cincinnati up 34-16.  Winston has been continually careless with the ball, and at this point coach Dirk Koetter had only one choice which was to hold Winston accountable.  The Bucs will have to decide this week whether to go back to Jameis for Week 9 against Carolina.
report: Jameis Winston was benched for Ryan Fitzpatrick after throwing his fourth interception of Sunday's Week 8 game against the Bengals.

impact: Winston came off the bench in the second half and engineered four consecutive touchdown drives, including a long 41-yard bomb to get Mike Evans on the board. His only offensive possession that didn't result in the Bucs hitting pay dirt just happened to include his game-ending interception -- his only turnover on the day. Fitzpatrick began with 167 yards and three picks before promptly being benched, so one has to think this is probably Winston's job moving forward (or at least until he rides the pine again). Whomever gets the nod in Week 12 gets an extremely juicy matchup against the Niners' leaky secondary.
report: Jameis Winston completed 12-of-16 passes for 199 yards, two touchdowns, and one pick in the Bucs' Week 11 loss to the Giants.

impact: It was a frustrating yet familiar day for Wilson. His offensive line struggled to protect him, and his receivers struggled to get open. Even so, he managed to create several big plays and keep Seattle in the game until the end. Wilson could face a similar script next week against the Bears and Khalil Mack, but he will remain a solid QB1.
report: Russell Wilson completed 19-of-33 passes for 298 yards, three touchdowns, and two interceptions in the Seahawks' Week 1 loss to the Broncos.

impact: He rushed for just 17 yards and fumbled twice, losing one.  Wilson entered the fourth quarter with 69 passing yards and went into halftime with 68 through the air.  He took six sacks for the second-straight week to open the season and continues to hold onto the ball far too long in an attempt to create offense for a talentless unit that also can't block.  Wilson had far fewer than 200 pass yards before the meaningless final drive with under a minute left where the Bears played no defense, allowing a short Will Dissly touchdown at the end.  Wilson is an incredible quarterback but is being suffocated in Seattle under OC Brian Schottenheimer, playing behind a peewee league offensive line, along with a running game that still does nothing.  Wilson gets the Cowboys at home in Week 3.  Good luck to fantasy owners.  Wilson finished just ahead of Blaine Gabbert and Josh Allen in the Week 2 fantasy standings at quarterback.
report: Russell Wilson completed 22-of-36 passes for 226 yards, two touchdowns, and one interception in the Seahawks' 24-17, Week 2 loss to the Bears on Monday night.

impact: He was sacked twice for a loss of 10 yards. Playing without top receiver Doug Baldwin for the second straight week, Wilson was a game manager on Sunday, spending most of his afternoon handing off to running back Chris Carson. It was a workmanlike effort for Wilson, though he did supply one big play, uncorking a 52-yard touchdown to Tyler Lockett late in the second quarter. Wilson gets the winless Cardinals on the road in Week 4.
report: Russell Wilson completed 16-of-26 passes for 192 yards and a pair of touchdowns while losing a yard on two carries Sunday in the Seahawks’ Week 3 win over the Cowboys.

impact: Wilson added 21 yards on four rushes on the ground. Wilson played a clean game, but once again failed to add much fantasy production. He has now finished in the bottom-half of quarterback scoring in three consecutive games since opening the season as QB1 on the road. Wilson will enter Week 2 as a high-QB2 option Week 5 at home against the Rams.
report: Russell Wilson completed 19-of-26 passes for 172 yards with no touchdowns or interceptions in Sundays Week 4 win over the Cardinals.

impact: The Seahawks continue to lean on the running game, limiting Wilson to just 73 attempts in the last three games, but the quarterback was able to help his fantasy backers out with big plays and touchdowns. Wilson found Tyler Lockett for two long plays including a touchdown, and he hit David Moore for 30-yard and three-yard scores. The three-yarder was vintage as Wilson created time in the backfield and found Moore in the back of the end zone just before going out of bounds. Wilson has a great matchup next week against the Raiders in London, but he will be nothing more than a low-end QB1 because of his attempt concerns.
report: Russell Wilson completed 13-of-21 passes for 198 yards and three touchdowns in the Seahawks' Week 5 loss to the Rams.

impact: Wilson rushed six times for 20 yards, but he looked relatively sluggish on his carries while dealing with a hamstring injury.  The good news is Wilson got it done through the air, and Seattle has a forthcoming Week 7 bye for Wilson to rest his ailing leg.  Even while missing his early-season dual threat due to the hamstring, Wilson has flirted with QB1 production.  It would not be surprising if Wilson delivered one of his trademark second-half explosions.
report: Russell Wilson completed 17-of-23 passes for 222 yards, three touchdowns, and one interception in the Seahawks' Week 6 drubbing of the Raiders.

impact: Wilson rushed six times for 20 yards, but he looked relatively sluggish on his carries while dealing with a hamstring injury.  The good news is Wilson got it done through the air, and Seattle has a forthcoming Week 7 bye for Wilson to rest his ailing leg.  Even while missing his early-season dual threat due to the hamstring, Wilson has flirted with QB1 production.  It would not be surprising if Wilson delivered one of his trademark second-half explosions.
report: Russell Wilson completed 17-of-23 passes for 222 yards, three touchdowns, and one interception in the Seahawks' Week 6 drubbing of the Raiders.

impact: The Seahawks were decking the Lions with the run and jump balls, so Wilson needed to throw even less than usual. He entered the break 11-of-12 for 151 yards and all three of his scores. It was Wilson's first game with fewer than 20 attempts since Nov. 9, 2014. David Moore owned Teez Tabor's soul, making life easy for his quarterback. Wilson has been providing fantasy owners with 2-3 touchdowns every week, but his lack of volume makes him a risky QB1. Working in his roto favor is what should be a high-scoring game with the Chargers in Week 9.
report: Russell Wilson completed 14-of-17 passes for 248 yards and three touchdowns in the Seahawks' 28-14, Week 8 win over the Lions.

impact: Today was the first time since Week 2 Wilson attempted more than 30 throws. He should have had a third touchdown on the game's final play, but a lightly-tipped ball clanged off David Moore's hands in the end zone. The Seahawks would have still needed a two-point conversion to tie. Wilson was under a ton of pressure in this one and made some highly-questionable decisions in the face of it, none more so than a late dump-off with time ticking away. His interception was also a pick six, his second of 2018 but just the third of his career. Although it won't be the Seahawks' preference, Wilson will undoubtedly blow by 30 attempts again in Week 10 as the Seahawks try to keep up with the Rams. He will be in the QB1 mix.
report: Russell Wilson completed 26-of-39 passes for 235 yards, two touchdowns and one interception in the Seahawks' 25-17, Week 9 loss to the Chargers.

impact: The 92 rushing yards were Wilson's most since Nov. 2014. With the Rams declining to spy, Wilson was tucking and running often in the second half. It nearly propelled the Seahawks to a road upset, but Wilson could not convert a potential game-winning drive. Wilson's lack of passing volume was surprising in a see-saw, back-and-forth game but not in the context of his 2018 usage. This is who the Seahawks are now. Thankfully for fantasy owners, Wilson continues to supply a bonkers touchdown rate. That's not sustainable, of course. The Seahawks host the Packers for Thursday Night Football in Week 11.
report: Russell Wilson completed 17-of-26 passes for 176 yards and three touchdowns in the Seahawks' 36-31, Week 10 loss to the Rams, adding nine carries for 92 additional yards.

impact: Wilson added five carries for 17 additional yards. It never felt like the Seahawks were playing particularly well, but the Packers proved to be even more mistake prone. It was a shaky effort from Wilson, who badly missed a gimme 21-yard touchdown to Doug Baldwin in the first quarter and made some awful decisions — including a Matthew Stafford-style lateral that killed a drive near the end of the first half — with the ball in his hands outside the pocket. Thankfully none of them turned into disasters like his Week 9 pick six against the Chargers. Wilson is oscillating between game manager and playmaker for an offense coach Pete Carroll is obsessed with funneling through the run game. The Seahawks head to Carolina for Week 12.
report: Russell Wilson completed 21-of-31 passes for 225 yards and two touchdowns in the Seahawks' 27-24, Week 11 win over the Packers.

impact: One of Williams' missed connections was a dropped 39-yard touchdown in the end zone. There was no one in Williams' area code and he simply put the ball on the ground. It was a bad moment in a game full of them for the Chargers' offense. Rotating with Travis Benjamin and Mike Williams behind Keenan Allen, Williams doesn't have much of a WR5 case right now.
report: Tyrell Williams caught 2-of-5 targets for eight yards and a touchdown in the Chargers' Week 1 loss to the Chiefs.

impact: It was a quiet game for Williams, though he improved on his eight yards for Week 1. Williams has been dealing with a groin injury, but looked fully healthy. The Chargers' deep threat remains off the fantasy radar.
report: Tyrell Williams caught three passes for 48 yards in Week 2 against Buffalo.

impact: Williams' grip as the Chargers No. 2 receiver is really loosening with Mike Williams taking a second-year leap. Mike Williams had as many touchdown grabs (2) today as Tyrell Williams had receptions. Tyrell Williams is just a deep threat for Rivers and is off the fantasy radar.
report: Tyrell Williams caught two passes for 22 yards in the Chargers' Week 3 loss to the Rams.

impact: Williams had more targets than Mike Williams in a game where Travis Benjamin (foot) left in the first quarter. Tyrell can bring in an occasional long touchdown for Rivers, but his weekly floor is really low since he's averaging just four targets per game. Williams will look for his first 50+ yard game next week against the burnable Raiders.
report: Tyrell Williams caught 3-of-5 targets for 48 scoreless yards in the Chargers' Week 4 win over the 49ers.

impact: None of his catches resulted in a touchdown, of course. It was the third time this season that Williams has seen just three targets, which now puts him at just 19 on the year. If searching for positives, it was his first 50-plus yard outing of the year and he did manage to finish second on the team in receiving yards. At this point, The Gazelle should only be owned in deeper leagues.
report: Tyrell Williams hauled in all three of his targets for 66 yards in the Chargers' Week 5 victory over the Raiders.

impact: Williams did all of his damage in the first half. His day got started on a two-play, 85-yard drive in which he caught a 40-yard pass over the top of the defense and then a 45-yard touchdown pass in which he took the ball from Damarious Randall on a simultaneous reception in the end zone. Williams then added a 29-yard touchdown strike with 51 seconds remaining in the first half to put the Chargers ahead 21-6 at the half. Williams entered Sunday with 192 yards and one touchdown, so he won't be an option next week when the Chargers head to London to face the Titans.
report: Tyrell Williams caught 3-of-4 targets for 118 yards and two touchdowns in Sunday's Week 6 win over the Browns.

impact: Williams roasted Logan Ryan for a 75-yard touchdown on the Chargers’ first play. He had a quiet second half with the Chargers losing the time-of-possesion battle. Williams is a one-trick deep threat, but he's had a high floor this season, with at least 40 yards or a touchdown in 6-of-7 games. Williams gets a matchup with Seattle in Week 9.
report: Tyrell Williams caught four passes for 118 yards and a touchdown in Week 7 against the Titans.

impact: Williams roasted Logan Ryan for a 75-yard touchdown on the Chargers’ first play. He had a quiet second half with the Chargers losing the time-of-possesion battle. Williams is a one-trick deep threat, but he's had a high floor this season, with at least 40 yards or a touchdown in 6-of-7 games. Williams gets a matchup with Seattle in Week 9.
report: Tyrell Williams caught four passes for 118 yards and a touchdown in Week 7 against the Titans.

impact: Williams' 12-yard score came as the first quarter expired. Unfortunately, it was not the harbinger of a big day. Williams' 23 yards were his fewest since Week 3. Williams offers plenty of big-play appeal, but it can be all he offers. He will have a chance to tap into it against the historically-bad Raiders in Week 10.
report: Tyrell Williams caught 2-of-3 targets for 23 yards and a touchdown in the Chargers' Week 9 win over the Seahawks.

impact: It was not a big game for Williams, but his usage was promising on Sunday. The six targets are actually the most he has seen this season, and he has clearly vanquished Mike Williams in the battle for the No. 2 receiver job. He will face a tougher test next week in Denver, but Williams will remain the FLEX conversation.
report: Tyrell Williams hauled in 4-of-6 targets for 46 yards in the Chargers' Week 10 win over the Raiders.

impact: The six targets matched a season-high for Williams, though obviously he didn't take advantage of his increased workload. Tyrell came down with a 19-yard catch off play-action to begin the second half, but was leveled by Darian Stewart on the play. Williams went to the sideline after that, but would eventually return. He was the intended receiver on the first of Philip Rivers' two interceptions. The 26-year-old enjoyed back-to-back 100-yard games earlier this year, but has slumped recently, averaging just 30.3 yards over his last three outings. We'll see how The Gazelle fares next week when the Chargers host Arizona.
report: Tyrell Williams was held to two catches for 22 yards on six targets Sunday in the Chargers’ Week 11 loss to the Broncos.

impact: He beat Buster Skrine for a 29-yard score but was otherwise quiet.  Operating as Miami's No. 3/4 receiver in a rotation with Danny Amendola, Kenny Stills, and Jakeem Grant, Wilson has drawn 4 and 5 targets through two weeks.  The Dolphins' low-volume passing offense limits the upside of all its members.  Wilson led the team in receiving yards with just 37 on Sunday.
report: Albert Wilson caught 3-of-5 targets for 37 yards and a touchdown in the Dolphins' Week 2 win over the Jets.

impact: For the passing touchdown, Wilson got the ball on a double reverse then delivered a perfect strike down the right sideline to Jakeem Grant. For the receiving, Wilson took a shovel pass from Ryan Tannehill, found the edge, hit the hole and exploded through the Raiders' entire defense for a 74-yard score. Electrifying stuff. Of course, Wilson has just eight grabs through three games. He will make big plays in the Dolphins' creative offense, but the road to re-draft value is too long and winding.
report: Albert Wilson caught 2-of-2 targets for 74 yards and a touchdown in the Dolphins' Week 3 win over the Raiders, adding a 52-yard touchdown pass.

impact: Wilson how has five touches in 3-of-4 games, though he's on pace for a modest 712 yards from scrimmage. Wilson seems like a classic "better in real life than fantasy" player.
report: Albert Wilson caught 4-of-6 targets for 19 yards in the Dolphins' Week 4 loss to the Patriots, adding a two-yard rush.

impact: This was only the second 100-yard receiving game of Wilson's career. The first-year Dolphin did nearly all of his damage in the second half, blowing up for 150 yards after the break. Wilson showed game-breaking speed in the fourth quarter by turning a simple dump-off from Brock Osweiler into a 43-yard touchdown. He bettered that with a 75-yard touchdown later in the quarter, which tied the game at 28 with just over three minutes remaining. With so many mouths to feed in Miami, Wilson won't be someone fantasy owners can consistently rely on, though his touchdown prowess—he's now visited the end zone four times this season—puts him in play as a bye-week fill-in/DFS dart throw. We'll see what he does for an encore next week against the Lions.
report: Albert Wilson delivered six catches for 155 yards and two touchdowns on nine targets Sunday in Miami’s Week 6 victory over the Bears.

impact: Nearly all of Williams' production came with the Chargers in fourth quarter comeback mode. That was also after Tyrell Williams and Travis Benjamin burned the team with horrible drops. If nothing else, the Chargers are going to need Williams in the red zone. Today did nothing to change his status as an upside WR5 you can start in a pinch. Hopefully that pinch comes later in the season.
report: Mike Williams caught 5-of-6 targets for 81 yards in the Chargers' Week 1 loss to the Chiefs.

impact: Williams stayed involved on offense after playing 54 percent of snaps in the season opener. His touchdown came on an opening drive red-zone strike from Philip Rivers, but he faded over the second half. With Travis Benjamin dealing with a foot injury, Williams should continue to see his role grow.
report: Mike Williams caught two passes for 27 yards and a touchdown Week 2 against Buffalo.

impact: Williams took advantage of Travis Benjamin's absence by securing two touchdown grabs. The first score came on a beautiful 42-yard diving catch in the end zone where he showed why the Chargers selected him with the No. 7 overall pick in 2017. Williams appears to be over his back issues that plagued him all last year and his role should continue to grow. Even if Benjamin returns next week, Williams has earned WR3/4 status with his performance today.
report: Mike Williams caught 4-of-7 targets for 81 yards and two touchdowns in the Chargers' Week 3 loss to the Rams.

impact: Williams came crashing down back to earth after a career-best game last week. He tied for the sixth-most targets on the team even with Travis Benjamin (foot) exiting the game early in the first quarter. The No. 7 overall pick will have his ups-and-downs, but the talent is there if he can put it all together. Williams has a golden matchup against the Raiders next week, but he is just an upside WR4 until his usage levels out.
report: Mike Williams caught 1-of-3 targets for 15 scoreless yards in the Chargers' Week 4 win over the 49ers.

impact: After flourishing through the first three weeks of the season, Williams has recorded just 4-60 and no touchdowns on seven targets in his last two games. There will be better days ahead, but Philip Rivers' touchdowns tosses have seemingly been spread out this year due to the added layer of Melvin Gordon's and Austin Ekeler's usage in the passing game. Williams will remain a WR3 in Week 6 versus the Browns.
report: Mike Williams caught 3-of-4 targets for 45 yards in the Chargers' Week 5 win over the Raiders.

impact: Williams added one rush for 10 yards Philip Rivers missed Williams wide open on his first two targets and then he was hardly involved afterwards. Despite having three touchdowns on the season, Williams is a clear ancillary option in the Charger passing attack. He has totaled five catches for 64 yards over the past three weeks on 11 targets. He is a touchdown-dependent WR4 next week versus the Titans.
report: Mike Williams caught 1-of-4 targets for four yards in Sunday's Week 6 win over the Browns.

impact: Williams scored his touchdown on the Chargers' first drive of the second half. He had two end-zone targets, but couldn't come up with either of them. Williams briefly exited after getting shaken up late in the fourth quarter but didn't miss any time. He'll have the Chargers' Week 8 bye to get healthy.
report: Mike Williams caught a 55-yard touchdown in Week 7 against the Titans.

impact: Williams scored his touchdown on the Chargers' first drive of the second half. He had two end-zone targets, but couldn't come up with either of them. Williams briefly exited after getting shaken up late in the fourth quarter but didn't miss any time. He'll have the Chargers' Week 8 bye to get healthy.
report: Mike Williams caught a 55-yard touchdown in Week 7 against the Titans.

impact: Williams' fifth score of the season was his second in as many games. He destroyed Tre Flowers on the sideline. Williams was actually quite lucky, as replay seemed to show him conclusively stepping out of bounds. For whatever reason, the call was not overturned. Although he's scored in back-to-back games, Williams has done so on just two catches. The Raiders are the softest of matchups for Week 10.
report: Mike Williams caught 1-of-3 targets for a 30-yard touchdown in the Chargers' Week 9 win over the Seahawks.

impact: He did not gain anything on one carry. Philip Rivers attempting just 25 passes did not help, but Williams made almost no impact in this game. He has now seen four or fewer targets in six straight contests, and he has caught one or fewer passes in five of those. He is not worth rostering in redraft formats.
report: Mike Williams was not targeted in the Chargers' Week 10 win over the Raiders.

impact: Williams' biggest contribution of the day came when he beat Tramaine Brock for a 29-yard reception on third down, setting up a first-and-goal from the four-yard line. That was about it for Williams, who continues to function as a boom-or-bust deep threat. The 2017 first-rounder has drawn a combined nine targets over his past four games. He won't be of much use to fantasy owners next week against the Steelers.
report: Mike Williams collected two catches for 56 yards on three targets Sunday in the Chargers’ Week 11 loss to Denver.

impact: It was a nondescript night for Williams. He had a long run of 11 yards and fell out of the gameplan with the Packers airing it out in the second half. Williams is locked in as Green Bay's featured back for at least another week with Aaron Jones suspended, but he's going to face competition for carries when Jones returns.
report: Jamaal Williams rushed 15 times for 47 yards in Sunday night's Week 1 win over Chicago.

impact: Williams did not get much going against a tough defense, but he once again worked as the clear lead back ahead of Ty Montgomery. That could change moving forward, however, with Aaron Jones due back from suspension. Williams is a more reliable option in the passing game who had a two-week headstart on Jones, so he will likely retain the lead job. Even so, he will be a risky FLEX play next week in Washington.
report: Jamaal Williams rushed 16 times for 59 yards and hauled in 3-of-4 targets for 12 yards in the Packers' Week 2 tie with the Vikings.

impact: Williams got the start, but Aaron Jones drew as many touches in his 2018 debut. Jones out-gained Williams 47-45. Ty Montgomery out-produced both (64). Jones looked cannon shot whenever he was asked to change the pace. Williams' pass protection is going to keep him on the field, but the Packers — who need play-making targets — figure to start looking Jones and Ty Montgomery's way more and more. Williams' RB2 candidacy is on thin ice. The Pack host the Bills in Week 4.
report: Jamaal Williams rushed five times for 29 yards in the Packers' Week 3 loss to the Redskins, adding two receptions for 16 additional yards.

impact: Williams wasn't targeted in the passing game. Williams once again got the "start," but was once again out-gained by Aaron Jones, this time handily (82-27). Jones scored the Packers' lone ground touchdown. Williams is now averaging 3.44 yards per carry compared to 6.29 for Jones. The Pack like Williams' pass protection, but that production gulf can only go on for so long. Williams won't be a recommended FLEX against the Lions in Week 5.
report: Jamaal Williams rushed 11 times for 27 yards in the Packers' Week 4 win over the Bills.

impact: He added two catches for 19 yards on four targets.  Williams and Aaron Jones (seven carries, two catches) essentially split the run-down work, but the Packers fell behind big on the scoreboard and were down 24-0 at halftime.  It was mostly Ty Montgomery after the break.  Williams has been a big disappointment through five weeks.  Jones should get more chances to earn increased snaps moving forward.  Williams will be a low-upside RB3 next week against the 49ers.
report: Jamaal Williams rushed six times for 33 yards in the Packers' Week 5 loss to the Lions.

impact: Williams was once again comprehensively out-played by Aaron Jones, but he cashed in a one-yard goal line look on the Packers' second drive. Williams has just 127 yards rushing in five games since Jones came off suspension in Week 3. You need to do better than chasing Williams' one-off touchdowns in fantasy.
report: Jamaal Williams rushed four times for nine yards and a touchdown in the Packers' Week 8 loss to the Rams.

impact: Williams was the distant No. 2 back behind Aaron Jones. He got a few series, but Williams continues to get outplayed by Jones. He's just a touchdown-dependent change-of-pace.
report: Jamaal Williams rushed seven times for 34 yards in Week 9 against the Patriots.

impact: Williams took a backseat to Aaron Jones, who was finally let loose for 15/145/2. Williams' three carries were a season-low in what appears to be a passing-of-the-torch moment in Green Bay's backfield. Drop him if you haven't already.
report: Jamaal Williams rushed for three yards on just three carries in the Packers' Week 10 win over Miami.

impact: He'll face a Bengals run defense that is missing WLB Vontaze Burfict (hamstring) but remains largely stout up front.  Of more concern for Wilkins' fantasy outlook is his RBBC with Christine Michael and Nyheim Hines.  New Colts coach Frank Reich was a committee-backfield proponent during his time in Philadelphia.
report: Jordan Wilkins will be the Colts' starting running back in Week 1.

impact: The good news is Wilkins led Indy's backfield with 17 touches compared to Nyheim Hines' 12 and Christine Michael's two.  The bad news is the Colts continued to struggle to run block, and Wilkins struggled for effiency on his opportunities.  Marlon Mack (hamstring) could also return as soon as Week 2, which would further muddy up the running back distribution.  At best, Wilkins will be a low-end flex option at Washington in the second game.
report: Jordan Wilkins rushed 14 times for 40 yards and caught 3-of-3 targets for 21 yards in the Colts' Week 1 loss to the Bengals.

impact: Wilkins left briefly after tweaking his ankle in the second quarter but the injury didn’t seem to bother him in the second half. The fifth-round rookie failed to impress in last week’s debut against Cincinnati (2.9 yards per carry) but he did a nice job of moving the chains in this one. His 18-yard scamper with under five minutes remaining in the fourth quarter essentially sealed the win for Indy. Wilkins out-touched teammate Marlon Mack by a slim 12-11 margin, though he held a decisive edge in yards from scrimmage (64-36). The Colts seem committed to using a timeshare at running back, so we’d expect similar usage for both players next week against the Eagles.
report: Jordan Wilkins tallied 61 yards on 10 carries while collecting two catches for three yards on two targets Sunday in the Colts’ Week 2 win over Washington.

impact: Wilkins started in place of Marlon Mack, but found little room to run as the Eagles dominated on the defensive front. Wilkins now has rushed 30 times for 120 yards with seven catches for 25 yards through three games. He is not a starting-caliber option heading into Week 4 versus the Texans.
report: Jordan Wilkins rushed six times for 19 yards while catching two passes for one yard in Sunday's Week 3 loss to the Eagles.

impact: Wilkins got another start with Marlon Mack injured, but he again did nothing of note.  Over the past two weeks, Wilkins has 35 yards on 14 carries.  Wilkins wasn't active in the pass game, either, failing to catch his lone target against Houston.  Wilkins doesn't belong in fantasy lineups Week 5 at New England.
report: Jordan Wilkins rushed eight times for 16 yards in the Colts' Week 4 loss to the Texans.

impact: With Robert Turbin (shoulder) sidelined, Wilkins saw his first touches in three weeks. He got the last series all to himself with Indy up big in the fourth quarter. Wilkins had some fantasy relevance early on, but now that Marlon Mack is back from his hamstring injury, he's no longer worth rostering.
report: Jordan Wilkins collected 46 yards on six carries while securing his lone target for an eight-yard gain Sunday in the Colts’ Week 7 win over Buffalo.

impact: With Robert Turbin (shoulder) sidelined, Wilkins saw his first touches in three weeks. He got the last series all to himself with Indy up big in the fourth quarter. Wilkins had some fantasy relevance early on, but now that Marlon Mack is back from his hamstring injury, he's no longer worth rostering.
report: Jordan Wilkins collected 46 yards on six carries while securing his lone target for an eight-yard gain Sunday in the Colts’ Week 7 win over Buffalo.

impact: Wilkins' score was an 18-yarder where he took a toss and found the seam. It was the first touchdown of his career. Wilkins is providing some big plays off the bench, but he is not cutting into Marlon Mack's workload. Wilkins lacks standalone fantasy value.
report: Jordan Wilkins rushed four times for 30 yards and a touchdown in the Colts' Week 11 win over the Titans.

impact: White actually led the Patriots in targets, though he predictably got out-carried 18-5 by Rex Burkhead. He had a free release on his 12-yard touchdown catch in the second quarter, getting left completely unaccounted for. White is going to feature in games where the Patriots feel they need to get the ball out quickly. That should definitely be the case in Week 2 against the Jaguars' elite defense.
report: James White caught 4-of-9 targets for 38 yards and a touchdown in the Patriots' Week 1 win over the Texans, adding five rushes for 18 yards.

impact: Unsurprisingly, White led the Patriots in targets as they looked to counteract the Jaguars' pass rush. White now has 11 grabs through two games. Great for the Patriots but replacement-level in fantasy football. White does have a solid Week 3 matchup in the Lions, but he is ideally treated as a bye week fill-in.
report: James White caught 7-of-8 targets for 73 yards in the Patriots' Week 2 loss to the Jaguars, adding four rushes for 11 additional yards.

impact: White scored his touchdown on a perfect throw from Tom Brady in the third quarter. He split passing reps with Rex Burkhead and was limited to third downs behind feature back Sony Michel. White got most of his rushing yardage against prevent coverage on the final drive of the game. With Burkhead dealing with a neck injury, White could have passing downs to himself in Week 4.
report: James White rushed four times for 37 yards and caught three passes for 14 yards and a touchdown in Week 3 against the Lions.

impact: The carries, rushing yards and receptions were all new season highs. With Rex Burkhead (neck) on injured reserve, White's fantasy production will be more bankable. He is a legitimate FLEX option in every format of fantasy.
report: James White caught 8-of-10 targets for 68 yards and a touchdown in the Patriots' Week 4 win over the Dolphins, adding eight carries for 44 yards and an additional score.

impact: White's seven targets were behind only Josh Gordon (9). He benefitted from a run-heavy approach from the Patriots and had a larger role in the run game than normal. White was held out of the end-zone for the first time since Week 3, but he continues to have a bankable floor. He's and RB2/FLEX for Week 7 against Chicago.
report: James White rushed six times for 39 yards and caught 5-of-7 passes for 53 yards in Week 6 against the Chiefs.

impact: Already being heavily utilized, it did not seem like White had much room to grow in this offense, but that changed when Sony Michel exited with a knee injury in the second quarter. Kenjon Barner mixed in, but White was the primary back the rest of the way. He parlayed that role into yet another receiving touchdown in the second quarter, cooking an overmatched Leonard Floyd to get wide open near the goal line, and he found the end zone again in the fourth quarter on a jet flip in which he beat the defense to the corner. He now has six receiving scores on the season. Most impressively, he was able to grind out two first downs to help kill the clock in the fourth quarter. With Michel looking likely to miss some time, White could return RB1 value the next several weeks.
report: James White rushed 11 times for 40 yards and hauled in 8-of-10 targets for 57 yards and two touchdowns in the Patriots' Week 7 win over the Bears.

impact: Already being heavily utilized, it did not seem like White had much room to grow in this offense, but that changed when Sony Michel exited with a knee injury in the second quarter. Kenjon Barner mixed in, but White was the primary back the rest of the way. He parlayed that role into yet another receiving touchdown in the second quarter, cooking an overmatched Leonard Floyd to get wide open near the goal line, and he found the end zone again in the fourth quarter on a jet flip in which he beat the defense to the corner. He now has six receiving scores on the season. Most impressively, he was able to grind out two first downs to help kill the clock in the fourth quarter. With Michel looking likely to miss some time, White could return RB1 value the next several weeks.
report: James White rushed 11 times for 40 yards and hauled in 8-of-10 targets for 57 yards and two touchdowns in the Patriots' Week 7 win over the Bears.

impact: White's 13 targets led the team as he was again the offensive focal point with Sony Michel (knee) sitting this one out.  It was all White and Julian Edelman, who amassed 117 yards on 11 touches, including nine grabs of his own.  White is likely to see a dip in usage once Michel is back, but he's going to remain an RB1 the remainder of the way, making a killing in the short passing game.  White is second to only Saquon Barkley in catches among running backs.  Giddy up for next Sunday night when the Patriots host the Packers at Foxboro.
report: James White rushed eight times for 15 yards and one touchdown and caught 10-of-13 targets for 79 yards in the Patriots' 25-6, Week 8 win over the Bills on Monday night.

impact: White scored on a eight-yard toss on the opening drive of the game. He missed seven plays with a leg injury, but returned after halftime. White got most of his receiving yards on a gadget screen pass from Julian Edelman. He was stuffed on multiple goal-line chances, but finally converted from the one-yard line in the fourth quarter. White's usage has been up with Sony Michel sidelined, but his value is going to take a hit if Michel returns next week.
report: James White rushed 12 times for 31 yards and two touchdowns and caught 6-of-7 targets for 72 yards in Week 9 against the Packers.

impact: The Patriots forced the issue unsuccessfully with Sony Michel early, then got nothing going offensively against Tennessee's blitz-heavy pressure after falling behind.  This was easily White's weakest fantasy performance all season.  Fantasy owners need to keep their trust in White following New England's Week 11 bye.  He has flirted with every-week RB1 viability all season.
report: James White rushed once for a loss of five yards and caught 5-of-8 targets for 31 yards in the Patriots' Week 10 loss to the Titans.

impact: Westbrook did not get the start, but he looked like Blake Bortles' No. 1 option for stretches of this game including on back-to-back big catches in the second quarter. Westbrook's six targets were the second-most on the team and the most among the receiving corps. It is only a matter of time before he jumps Donte Moncrief on the depth chart.
report: Dede Westbrook hauled in 5-of-6 targets for 51 yards in the Jaguars' Week 1 win over the Giants.

impact: Westbrook also lost six yards on a rush. It would have been a lost day for Westbrook, but he managed to turn a fourth quarter dumpoff into a 61-yard touchdown. Westbrook shed a tackle, found the sideline and was off to the races. Those are the kinds of plays he's capable of. Westbrook's upside is tantalizing, but the Jags' receiver rotation currently has him stuck in WR4 land for fantasy purposes.
report: Dede Westbrook caught 4-of-5 targets for 83 yards and a touchdown in the Jaguars' Week 2 win over the Patriots.

impact: Westbrook has been expectedly inconsistent in the early going as a rotational receiver on a run-first team.  He will get a better matchup in Week 4 against the Jets, who have struggled mightly to contain slot receivers.
report: Dede Westbrook caught 3-of-4 targets for 31 yards in the Jaguars' Week 3 loss to Tennessee.

impact: Westbrook started fast, racking up six catches for 89 yards in the first half. He led Jacksonville in targets, ahead of both Keelan Cole (3) and Donte Moncrief (5). Westbrook did most of his damage on short passes but was explosive in the open field and picked up most of his yards after the catch. He's now went over 80 yards in two of his last three games. Westbrook will be a WR3/FLEX for Week 5 against the Chiefs.
report: Dede Westbrook caught 9-of-13 targets for 130 yards in Jacksonville's Week 4 win over the Jets.

impact: Held off the box score in the first half, Westbrook opened the third quarter with a 30-yard catch and converted a third down with a great 23-yard grab on the next drive. That was about it for the receiver, however, who still served as the No. 3 despite his breakout game last week. Westbrook will be a weak WR4 dart throw next week in Dallas.
report: Dede Westbrook hauled in 3-of-5 targets for 55 yards in the Jaguars' Week 5 loss to the Chiefs.

impact: Like the rest of Jacksonville's sluggish offense, Westbrook was mostly held in check, though he did find an opening in the Cowboys' defense during the third quarter when he scored on a 34-yard touchdown pass from Blake Bortles. Even with Sunday's clunker thrown in, the second-year wideout is still on pace for over 1,000 yards receiving. He'll get the Texans at home in Week 7.
report: Dede Westbrook secured three catches for 38 yards and a touchdown on five targets Sunday in the Jaguars’ Week 6 loss to Dallas.

impact: Westbrook got loose for no big plays as the Jaguars switched quarterbacks, benching Blake Bortles for Cody Kessler early in the third quarter. Donte Moncrief, T.J. Yeldon, Keelan Cole, and rookie D.J. Chark all drew more targets than Westbrook, who will be a dicey WR4/flex option when the Jaguars head to London to face the Eagles next.
report: Dede Westbrook caught 4-of-4 targets for 17 yards in the Jaguars’ Week 7 loss to the Texans.

impact: Westbrook got loose for no big plays as the Jaguars switched quarterbacks, benching Blake Bortles for Cody Kessler early in the third quarter. Donte Moncrief, T.J. Yeldon, Keelan Cole, and rookie D.J. Chark all drew more targets than Westbrook, who will be a dicey WR4/flex option when the Jaguars head to London to face the Eagles next.
report: Dede Westbrook caught 4-of-4 targets for 17 yards in the Jaguars’ Week 7 loss to the Texans.

impact: There was not much to go around in the first half as Blake Bortles attempted just seven passes, but Westbrook made his mark after the break, using a great double move to get open in the back of the end zone for an 11-yard score. It was his second touchdown in the last three games and third of the season. He earned another end-zone target on the next drive, but the pass was batted away. He later added a 20-yard gain in which he cooked the defensive back on the line of scrimmage, but he gave most of it back with a taunting penalty at the end of the catch. With Keelan Cole struggling, Westbrook could see his role expand following the bye.
report: Dede Westbrook hauled in 2-of-6 targets for 31 yards and a touchdown in the Jaguars' Week 8 loss to the Eagles.

impact: He added two carries for 13 yards. Donte Moncrief made the big play, but Westbrook was Blake Bortles’ favorite target on Sunday. He easily led the team with five targets in the first half, and he saw four more than any other Jag on the day. Unfortunately, he struggled to do much with the work. His fantasy day would have looked much better if he had found the end zone, but he was tackled at the one-half-yard line in the third quarter. He also could not come up with what would have been a long gain along the sideline. With a tough Steelers defense on deck, Westbrook will be nothing more than a WR4 next week.
report: Dede Westbrook hauled in 5-of-10 targets for 30 yards in the Jaguars' Week 10 loss to the Colts.

impact: Westbrook was second on the team in targets on Sunday, but the Jaguars threw a season-low 18 times. Westbrook has now been held under 40-yards receiving in five straight games. Now that we are through the heavy bye weeks, he is not truly on the fantasy radar. The Jaguars head to Buffalo in Week 12.
report: Dede Westbrook caught 2-of-4 targets for 19 yards in Sunday's Week 11 loss to the Steelers.

impact: White had not caught a pass coming into this game, but he got a bit more run with Allen Robinson hobbled by a groin injury. That playing time almost led to a spectacular moment when White came down with the potential game-tying Hail Mary on the final play of the game, but he made the catch just short of the goal line and was pushed back by a group of defenders. Despite the big play and Robinson's injury, White is not a fantasy option.
report: Kevin White hauled in both of his targets for 64 yards in the Bears' Week 7 loss to the Patriots.

impact: White had not caught a pass coming into this game, but he got a bit more run with Allen Robinson hobbled by a groin injury. That playing time almost led to a spectacular moment when White came down with the potential game-tying Hail Mary on the final play of the game, but he made the catch just short of the goal line and was pushed back by a group of defenders. Despite the big play and Robinson's injury, White is not a fantasy option.
report: Kevin White hauled in both of his targets for 64 yards in the Bears' Week 7 loss to the Patriots.

impact: Playing in his first game since Week 14 of last season, Wentz worked with a skeleton crew on offense in the driving rain.
