Wentz battled through enormous pressure, getting sacked five times, losing a fumble on one for his second turnover deep in Eagles territory. His day started off strong, completing 5-of-7 passes for 48 yards on his first possession, capped by a 13-yard touchdown strike to Dallas Goedert. The Eagles may get Alshon Jeffery back soon for Wentz, but their offense has struggled out of the gates to open the season as a byproduct of all their injuries. Wentz will enter Week 4 as a high-QB2 option on the road against the Titans.
report: Carson Wentz completed 25-of-37 passes for 255 yards with one touchdown and one interception while rushing three times for 10 yards in Sunday's Week 3 win over the Colts.

impact: It was a disappointing loss for the Eagles, but Wentz performed well in his second game back despite his receivers letting him down a few times. He consistently threw lasers from the pocket including on Alshon Jeffery's touchdown catch and looked healthy when on the move. With Minnesota's defense scuffling, Wentz will be in the QB1 conversation next week.
report: Carson Wentz completed 33-of-50 passes for 348 yards and two touchdowns in the Eagles' Week 4, overtime loss to the Titans.

impact: Wentz added five carries for 26 additional yards. Wentz's second quarter fumble provided the difference in the score, as a scarily-fast Linval Joseph housed it for a 64-yard touchdown. Otherwise, Wentz took another incremental step into the season, producing 300 yards and two scores for the second-straight game while posting an 8.89 YPA after entering the week with a 6.93 mark. Wentz could have had a better day but was hurt by some drops. Wentz is passing both the eye and box score tests. He will be a borderline QB1 for Thursday night's game with the Giants.
report: Carson Wentz completed 24-of-35 passes for 311 yards and two touchdowns in the Eagles' 23-21, Week 5 loss to the Vikings, also losing a fumble.

impact: This one was an extended scrimmage for the Eagles, who dominated an overmatched Giants team from the opening whistle. The three-score effort was Wentz's first in four 2018 starts. Wentz showed excellent mobility, especially on his first touchdown. Wentz vacated the pocket and rolled to his right before throwing across his body to Alshon Jeffery in the end zone. After some rusty play in Weeks 3 and 4, Wentz has started to resemble his would-have-been-if-not-for-injury 2017 MVP self over the past two weeks. He has 10 days to rest up for a Week 7 matchup with the Panthers.
report: Carson Wentz completed 26-of-36 passes for 278 yards, three touchdowns and zero interceptions in the Eagles' 34-13, Week 6 demolition of the Giants.

impact: Wentz was very nearly perfect, but Cam Newton could not be stopped in the second half, and Philadelphia’s defense melted down after Doug Pederson’s offense built a 17-0 first-half lead. Wentz has played at a QB1-level in four straight games. Although his Week 8 matchup looks difficult on paper against Jacksonville in London, the Jaguars appear to be a crumbling team. Wentz will be a fringe fantasy starter.
report: Carson Wentz completed 30-of-37 passes for 310 yards and two touchdowns in the Eagles’ Week 7 loss to the Panthers.

impact: Wentz had an eventful opening drive. He caught a batted-down pass and scampered for a third-down conversion, he converted another third down with a circus throw to Jordan Matthews, and then he lost a fumble on the very next play. The up-and-down play continued on the next drive when he marched the Eagles down the field only to throw a bad interception in the end zone, his first since Week 3. He settled down after that on his way to a big game. He found Dallas Goedert open deep down the middle of the field for a 32-yard score just before the break for his first score. His second touchdown was a much-easier screen pass to Wendell Smallwood, but Wentz converted two third downs on that drive. His final touchdown was a laser to Zach Ertz from five yards out to put the game out reach. Fully recovered from his injury, Wentz has been on fire over the last month. He will be a solid QB1 against the Cowboys following the bye.
report: Carson Wentz completed 21-of-30 passes for 286 yards, three touchdowns, and an interception in the Eagles' Week 8 win over the Jaguars in London, adding 28 yards on the ground.

impact: The Eagles didn't even try to run in this one, with the 44 attempts Wentz's second most of the year. Wentz rebounded from an early pick, but couldn't rally the Eagles to a fourth quarter comeback. Both of his touchdowns came on red-zone throws to Zach Ertz. Wentz has been locked in with at least two TDs in six straight games. He gets a likely shootout with the Saints in Week 11.
report: Carson Wentz completed 32-of-44 passes for 360 yards with two touchdown and an interception in Week 10 against the Cowboys.

impact: Wentz entered this game on a hot streak, completing 71.6 percent of his passes with 14 touchdowns to just two interceptions over his previous six games, but he was completely shut down in this one. With the Saints blanketing his receivers, Wentz struggled to move the offense all game, and all three of his interceptions were essentially give-up throws deep down the field. Wentz should have better luck next week against the Giants, who he tossed three touchdowns against in Week 6.
report: Carson Wentz completed 19-of-33 passes for 156 yards, zero touchdowns, and three interceptions in the Eagles' Week 11, blowout loss to the Saints.

impact: Watson had an ugly first half, but salvaged his game with two late scoring drives. Both his touchdowns were on dumpoffs, with his second one not coming until the final play. Watson added a team-leading 36 rushing yards on five carries. After a shaky Week 1, Watson has 300-plus total yards in consecutive games. He'll be a top-five option for a matchup with the Colts next week.
report: Deshaun Watson completed 24-of-40 passes for 385 yards, two touchdowns, and an interception in the Texans' Week 3 loss to the Giants.

impact: Watson rushed six times for an additional 41 yards and a third touchdown.  This was a true up-and-down shootout that kind of lulled through the first half before exploding after the break.  The Texans blew a 28-10 lead and had to go to overtime for the win.  Watson's two touchdowns were three- and five-yard hookups to Will Fuller and DeAndre Hopkins, respectively, and his rushing score was a five-yard scamper to cap a 15-play drive.  Watson has now topped 300 yards passing in three-straight games ahead of a Week 5 date with the Cowboys where he'll remain a QB1.
report: Deshaun Watson completed 29-of-42 passes for 375 yards, two touchdowns, and one interceptions in the Texans' Week 4 win over the Colts.

impact: It was an uneven game from Watson, but he bounced back from a late fourth-quarter interception to rally the Texans to an overtime win.  Watson had a larger role in the running game with Alfred Blue sidelined, rushing for 40 yards on 10 carries. He took some huge hits and was stuffed on multiple goal-line runs, but managed to avoid injury. After a slow start, Watson has looked much closer to the quarterback he was in 2017. He gets a plus matchup with Buffalo in Week 6.
report: Deshaun Watson completed 33-of-44 passes for 375 yards with a touchdown and an interception in Houston's Week 5 win over Dallas.

impact: Watson also fumbled three times, losing one, and was sacked seven times in a game he almost certainly wants to forget. Things started out perfectly for the quarterback, who was five-for-five with 62 yards and a touchdown to start the game, but it all went downhill from there. Houston's only meaningful offense in the second half came when Will Fuller drew a defensive pass interference play in the end zone. Houston could not get convert that into a touchdown, but the defense bailed them out with a pick-six to close out the game. Watson can point to a tough matchup, but the road will not get any easier next week in Jacksonville. He will be just a borderline QB1 in that matchup.
report: Deshaun Watson completed 15-of-25 passes for 177 yards, one touchdown, and two interceptions in the Texans' Week 6 win over the Bills.

impact: "He’s playing hurt," coach Bill O’Brien conceded after the game. Watson is believed to be dealing with lung and ribs injuries, which are why he’s been listed with a "chest" ailment on weekly injury reports. The Texans committed to their rushing attack in Sunday’s victory rather than leaning on Watson to drop back to pass against Jacksonville’s talented-if-underachieving front. Watson now has a quick turnaround in Week 8 against the Dolphins on Thursday Night Football. Due to the injuries, Watson has become an increasingly risky fantasy bet coming off consecutive sub-par box-score games.
report: Deshaun Watson completed 12-of-24 passes for 139 yards and a touchdown and rushed seven times for 13 yards in the Texans’ Week 7 win over the Jaguars.

impact: Watson added a 14-yard scramble. As you can see, Watson had more touchdowns than incompletions against a truly embarrassing Dolphins defense. Matt Burke's unit was leaving star players like DeAndre Hopkins and Will Fuller completely uncovered for touchdowns, while little-featured rookie TE Jordan Thomas was able to break free for two scores. Watson was extending plays all night with his legs. Watson and the Texans have now won five straight after opening the year 0-3. The Broncos are on tap for Week 9. A concern for Watson is Fuller's health after he left Thursday's game with a knee issue.
report: Deshaun Watson completed 16-of-20 passes for 239 yards and five touchdowns in the Texans' 42-23, Week 8 win over the Dolphins.

impact: Watson added a 14-yard scramble. As you can see, Watson had more touchdowns than incompletions against a truly embarrassing Dolphins defense. Matt Burke's unit was leaving star players like DeAndre Hopkins and Will Fuller completely uncovered for touchdowns, while little-featured rookie TE Jordan Thomas was able to break free for two scores. Watson was extending plays all night with his legs. Watson and the Texans have now won five straight after opening the year 0-3. The Broncos are on tap for Week 9. A concern for Watson is Fuller's health after he left Thursday's game with a knee issue.
report: Deshaun Watson completed 16-of-20 passes for 239 yards and five touchdowns in the Texans' 42-23, Week 8 win over the Dolphins.

impact: Without Will Fuller (torn ACL) and Keke Coutee (hamstring) available, Watson pressed half of his throws in DeAndre Hopkins' direction. The Texans' play-caller may have been efficient again, but it was the fourth consecutive outing he's attempted fewer than 26 passes and, in turn, recorded less than 240 passing yards. He practiced in full all week, but It's a wonder whether or not he's still battling a collapsed lung given his consistent lack of volume. Consider this a warning as he should be fully healed when the Texans return from extended rest and face the Redskins in Week 11.
report: Deshaun Watson completed 17-of-24 passes for 213 yards and two touchdowns in the Texans' Week 9 win over the Broncos.

impact: The Texans won their seventh straight game despite a rough day for Watson, who managed seven yards on three rushing attempts and failed to engineer a sustained passing game.  Houston plays its next game on Monday Night Football against the Titans, who got shredded by Andrew Luck on Sunday but have otherwise played stout pass defense this year.  On lowered volume with the Texans leaning on their defense for wins, Watson will be a mid-range to low-end QB1 play.
report: Deshaun Watson completed 16-of-24 passes for 208 yards, one touchdown, and two interceptions in Houston's Week 11 win over Washington.

impact: The 12 carries doubled Washington's previous season total. He was involved because Doug Martin injured his ankle late in the first half. Washington will be in for plenty of work if Martin misses Week 12, but he will not be a recommended FLEX option against the Ravens' lockdown defense.
report: DeAndre Washington rushed 12 times for 32 yards in the Raiders' Week 11 win over the Cardinals.

impact: Watkins was targeted on Patrick Mahomes' first pass of the game but ended up getting out-targeted by both Tyreek Hill and Travis Kelce. That's not surprising, of course. Watkins had to contend with a few poor throws from Mahomes, though he did catch a blazing, low fastball for his second reception. Watkins is going to have big games in the Chiefs' high-octane offense, but they will be harder to see coming than Hill or Kelce's. He is best treated as a WR4 in fantasy.
report: Sammy Watkins caught 3-of-5 targets for 21 yards in the Chiefs' Week 1 win over the Chargers.

impact: The Chiefs made a point of getting Watkins going after his quiet Week 1, targeting him five times in the first 16 minutes. Despite the obvious intent, Watkins' usage did not feel forced. He was running fluidly in the Chiefs' high-octane attack. Watkins is going to be a feast-or-famine player behind Tyreek Hill and Travis Kelce, but today serves as a good reminder of his unusual upside for a WR3/4.
report: Sammy Watkins caught 6-of-7 targets for 100 yards in the Chiefs' Week 2 win over the Steelers, adding 31 yards on an end around.

impact: He added another 20 yards on two carries. Watkins' role in the passing game expanded last week, and he hauled in his first touchdown with the Chiefs in this game. The score was a 12-yard reception late in the second quarter in which Watkins ran through a few tacklers. An emerging part of the best offense in the league, Watkins will be an upside WR3 next week in Denver.
report: Sammy Watkins hauled in 5-of-8 targets for 55 yards and a touchdown in the Chiefs' Week 3 win over the 49ers.

impact: Watkins entered the game nursing a hamstring injury, but he looked healthy on Sunday. His biggest play of the day came when he found a hole in zone coverage for a 33-yard gain on third down in the first half. Clearly healthy and a major cog in the best offense in the league, Watkins will be an upside WR3 play next week in New England.
report: Sammy Watkins hauled in 6-of-8 targets for 78 yards in the Chiefs' Week 5 win over the Jaguars.

impact: Watkins was on his way to another quiet game, but he salvaged his night with a 50-yard catch to open the second half. He wasn't much of a factor, though his seven targets were behind only Tyreek Hill. Watkins got banged up late in the fourth quarter but wasn't announced with an injury. He'll have a tough matchup with Denver's secondary in Week 8.
report: Sammy Watkins caught 4-of-7 passes for 74 yards in Week 7 against the Bengals.

impact: That means a bigger role for rookie James Washington after Hunter played 51-of-84 snaps against the Browns in Week 1. Washington was on the field for just 11 plays. That will change against the Chiefs in what could be an extremely high-scoring game. If you're already in the deepest of binds, there's a case for Washington as a blindfold, dart throw WR5.
report: Steelers WR Justin Hunter is a healthy scratch for Week 2 against the Chiefs.

impact: Washington played just 11 snaps in Week 1 but was far more involved today with Justin Hunter a healthy scratch. Washington was targeted on the Steelers' first play from scrimmage and drew four looks in the first quarter, one of which was nullified by a Steelers penalty. The Steelers went away from the strategy as Washington's looks proved fruitless, though he did score a 14-yard touchdown late in the second quarter where a scrambling Ben Roethlisberger was almost entirely across the line of scrimmage. Washington is going to bust some big plays, but he's not currently re-draft relevant.
report: James Washington caught 1-of-5 targets for 14 yards and a touchdown in the Steelers' Week 2 loss to the Chiefs.

impact: The Bengals were expected to get Walton more touches this week. He played sparingly behind Joe Mixon, failing to get a single carry. Walton has flashed when given chances, but he's just a handcuff until Giovani Bernard returns.
report: Mark Walton caught 2-of-3 passes for three yards in Week 5 against Miami.

impact: The Bengals were expected to get Walton more touches this week. He played sparingly behind Joe Mixon, failing to get a single carry. Walton has flashed when given chances, but he's just a handcuff until Giovani Bernard returns.
report: Mark Walton caught 2-of-3 passes for three yards in Week 5 against Miami.

impact: Ryan and the offense got off to a sleepy start, scoring three points in the first quarter and trailing 10-3 at one point, but Atlanta went on to score three unanswered touchdowns.  Ryan sneaked in from one yard away on his first score, and then helicoptered in from eight yards out on his second rushing score.  His two via the pass went to Calvin Ridley and Austin Hooper.  All four scores were of the red-zone variety, a huge improvement from Week 1 when the offense went 0-of-5 in the red area.  Ryan will be a back-end QB1 next week against the Saints.
report: Matt Ryan completed 23-of-28 passes for 272 yards, two touchdowns, and one interception in the Falcons' 31-24, Week 2 win over the Panthers, adding 18 yards and two additional touchdowns on four carries.

impact: He took three sacks for a loss of 15 yards. Halloween isn’t for another month but Ryan was handing out touchdowns like candy on Sunday, dropping dimes all over the gridiron. Three of his touchdowns went to rookie Calvin Ridley, who broke out for 146 yards on seven catches. Matty Ice probably should have had a sixth touchdown but slightly underthrew Julio Jones on what ended up being a 58-yard catch. As dominant as he was, Ryan’s afternoon ended on a low note when Atlanta's last drive stalled out, forcing a punt with 16 seconds left in regulation. That would be the last time Atlanta touched the football as New Orleans walked it off on a Drew Brees touchdown in overtime. Ryan has redeemed himself since his meltdown against the Eagles in Week 1 and is once again safe to pencil in as an every-week QB1. He’ll get the Bengals at home in Week 4.
report: Matt Ryan completed 26-of-35 passes for five touchdowns while adding 12 rushing yards on four carries Sunday in Atlanta’s Week 3 loss to the Saints.

impact: Atlanta ended up losing this game, but Ryan should not shoulder much of the blame. He did miss a few passes which perhaps could have iced things late in the fourth quarter, but he consistently answered a Bengals offense which Atlanta's defense struggled to stop all game. Two of his touchdowns were wide-open throws to Logan Paulsen and Calvin Ridley, but he made a great tight-window throw on Ridley's other score. Ryan now has 793 yards and eight touchdowns in his last two games. He will be a high-end QB1 in a great matchup against the Steelers next week.
report: Matt Ryan completed 29-of-39 passes for 419 yards and three touchdowns in the Falcons' Week 4 loss to the Bengals.

impact: Ryan also lost a fumble that the Steelers returned for a touchdown. Under siege — he took six sacks and was pressured countless other times — Ryan played really poorly in this one, going three full quarters before finally finding Julio Jones for a reception. He was addicted to checking down to Austin Hooper. Ryan was lucky to escape with only one turnover. Ryan has now struggled mightily in each of his road starts while having big days at home. The Falcons host the Bucs in Week 6. That's an obvious smash spot in fantasy.
report: Matt Ryan completed 26-of-38 passes for 285 yards, one touchdown and zero interceptions in the Falcons' 41-17, Week 5 loss to the Steelers.

impact: Ryan came out firing, completing all five of his passes on the opening drive for 74 yards and a touchdown and 11-of-11 for 125 yards in the first quarter, and he did not slow down from there. The offense did have a lull in the third quarter, but Ryan was hitting open receivers all game and answered Tampa's comeback attempt with two scoring drives of his own. Ryan has now thrown for at least 350 yards in three of his last four games. He will be a high-end QB1 next week against the Giants.
report: Matt Ryan completed 31-of-41 passes for 354 yards and three touchdowns in the Falcons' Week 6 win over the Bucs.

impact: Ryan took three first-half sacks but wasn't sacked after the break; anytime he had time to throw, Ryan was dicing up this defense with relative ease.  He hit deep reserve WR Marvin Hall for a 47-yard touchdown over the top.  Ryan should have had a 60-yard touchdown to Julio Jones on top of that but underthrew the ball as he hit his hand on a helmet on the follow-through.  Atlanta had to settle for a trio of Giorgio Tavecchio field goals tonight.  Ryan and the Falcons are going into their bye week ahead of a road date with the Redskins in Week 9.
report: Matt Ryan completed 31-of-39 passes for 379 yards and one touchdown in the Falcons' Week 7 win over the Giants.

impact: Ryan took three first-half sacks but wasn't sacked after the break; anytime he had time to throw, Ryan was dicing up this defense with relative ease.  He hit deep reserve WR Marvin Hall for a 47-yard touchdown over the top.  Ryan should have had a 60-yard touchdown to Julio Jones on top of that but underthrew the ball as he hit his hand on a helmet on the follow-through.  Atlanta had to settle for a trio of Giorgio Tavecchio field goals tonight.  Ryan and the Falcons are going into their bye week ahead of a road date with the Redskins in Week 9.
report: Matt Ryan completed 31-of-39 passes for 379 yards and one touchdown in the Falcons' Week 7 win over the Giants.

impact: Atlanta's pass protection was a major problem before their Week 8 bye, but Ryan had clean pockets all day with only two sacks and four hits absorbed among 40 dropbacks.  He hit Tevin Coleman twice for scores, Calvin Ridley for a 40-yard TD on a crossing route, and Julio Jones on a 35-yard screen pass for touchdown No. 4.  Ryan will continue to offer elite QB1 upside in Week 10 at Cleveland, whose secondary has been decimated by injuries.
report: Matt Ryan completed 26-of-38 passes for 350 yards and four touchdowns in Atlanta's Week 9 win at Washington.

impact: With the game already in hand late, Ryan lost a fumble. Ryan could have had a bigger day, but the Falcons had some dysfunction in the red zone after weeks of red-hot play inside the 20. Ryan did manage to find Julio Jones for a score for the second time in as many games. This time it was a Jones bubble screen from the one. It wasn't a bad day for Ryan, it was just a better day for Baker Mayfield and the Browns. Ryan gets the Cowboys at home for Week 11.
report: Matt Ryan completed 38-of-52 passes for 330 yards and two touchdowns in the Falcons' 28-16, Week 10 loss to the Browns.

impact: It was Ryan's first sub-300 yards day since Week 5.  The Falcons didn't get into the red zone until the second half as the teams traded field goals the first three quarters.  Ryan's interception was a drop by Calvin Ridley that clanged up into the air for Leighton Vander Esch.  His one touchdown was a 34-yard strike to Julio Jones down the right sideline to tie the game at 19-19 late in the fourth quarter.  Ryan will battle the Saints on Thanksgiving.  He had 374 yards and five touchdowns against the Saints in Week 3.
report: Matt Ryan completed 24-of-34 passes for 291 yards, one touchdown, and one interception in the Falcons' Week 11 loss to the Cowboys.

impact: Rudolph didn't see his first target until there was about five minutes left in the third quarter.  Both Vikings backup TEs David Morgan and Tyler Conklin caught a pass before Rudolph was targeted, but Rudolph saved his day with the red-zone touchdown.  His lack of targets is still alarming, especially after Rudolph was targeted just once in the preseason despite playing a full game's worth of snaps.  Rudolph will be a TD-or-bust TE1 next week in Green Bay.
report: Kyle Rudolph caught 1-of-2 targets for an 11-yard touchdown in the Vikings' Week 1 win over the 49ers.

impact: It was the quietest 72 yards in history. Rudolph did get loose for 23 yards in the third quarter, but that was his only catch of more than 12. Still, it was a welcome bounceback after Rudolph went for just 11 yards total in Week 1. He will be a back-end TE1 next week against the Bills.
report: Kyle Rudolph hauled in 7-of-8 targets for 72 yards in the Vikings' Week 2 tie with the Packers.

impact: Rudolph was one of the primary beneficiaries from the Vikings' 27-0 first half deficit. His lone score came in garbage time with less than two minutes to play while Minnesota was still getting blanked. Even so, the touchdown alone was enough to vault him into the top-three at his position in Week 3. The Rams have been exploited by tight ends in the middle of the field so far this season, so expect another juicy outing from Rudolph Thursday night.
report: Kyle Rudolph hauled in 5-of-6 targets for 48 yards and one touchdown in the Vikings' Week 3 loss to the Bills.

impact: That's as standard issue as a Rudolph game gets. Rudolph has two scores through five games. He's an uninspiring, but consistent and locked in, TE1. The Cardinals are on tap for Week 6.
report: Kyle Rudolph caught 5-of-5 targets for 41 yards in the Vikings' Week 5 win over the Eagles.

impact: It's another standard Rudolph game. Rudolph has just two touchdowns this season and hasn't scored since Week 3. He'll be a back-end TE1 against the Jets in Week 7.
report: Kyle Rudolph caught four passes for 37 yards in Week 6 against the Cardinals.

impact: Rudolph has been held below 50 yards in 5-of-7 games and hasn't scored since Week 3.  However, he remains a TE1 at a weak position going into a potential shootout next week at home against a bad Saints defense.
report: Kyle Rudolph caught just 1-of-4 targets for 16 yards in the Vikings' Week 7 win over the Jets.

impact: Rudolph has been held below 50 yards in 5-of-7 games and hasn't scored since Week 3.  However, he remains a TE1 at a weak position going into a potential shootout next week at home against a bad Saints defense.
report: Kyle Rudolph caught just 1-of-4 targets for 16 yards in the Vikings' Week 7 win over the Jets.

impact: Rudolph had a pair of red-zone targets he couldn’t come down with. He was ruled out of bounds on a touchdown that was overturned. Rudolph has been an afterthought in a Vikings pass offense the goes through Adam Thielen and Stefon Diggs. He hasn't scored since Week 3.
report: Kyle Rudolph caught 4-of-7 targets for 39 yards in Week 8 against the Saints.

impact: Rudolph hasn't scored since Week 3 and has been held below 50 yards in 7-of-9 games.  He has zero upside.  Fantasy owners can find more tight ends capable of breakout weeks rather than continuing to use Rudolph.
report: Kyle Rudolph caught both of his targets for 28 yards in the Vikings' Week 9 win over the Lions.

impact: His yardage totals through three games are 3, 8, and 16.  Two of Andy Dalton's four interceptions on Sunday came on throws directed at Ross.  Ross has a ton of straight-line speed, but he is a work in progress as a route runner and catcher of the ball.  Even if A.J. Green (groin) can't play in Week 4 at Atlanta, Ross will be a high-risk WR4/flex option at best.
report: John Ross caught 3-of-7 targets for 16 yards in the Bengals' Week 3 loss to the Panthers.

impact: Ross' touchdown was a 39 yarder in which Andy Dalton put the ball just out of reach from the safety down the seam. Unfortunately, Ross appeared to suffer a pulled hamstring or groin on that play, and while he was able to keep playing into the second half -- he had a nice sideline catch in the third quarter -- that injury eventually forced him from the game. He should be considered questionable to face the Dolphins next week.
report: John Ross hauled in 2-of-2 targets for 52 yards and a touchdown in the Bengals' Week 4 win over the Falcons.

impact: Despite, catching just two passes, Ross led the Bengals in targets in their first game without A.J. Green. Ross provided the lone touchdown for the Bengals on their opening drive of the game, securing a 2-yard touchdown when he came across the back of the end zone. He added a 37-yard catch and run later in the game, but suffered the same fate as the entire Bengals offense as Cincinnati did next to nothing for the rest of the game. Ross has just nine catches on the season, but will be needed to step up with Green expected to miss at least Week 11 at minimum. Ross will only be a desperation option next week at Baltimore.
report: John Ross caught 2-of-6 targets for 39 yards and a touchdown in Sunday's Week 10 loss to the Saints.

impact: The stat line is similar to last week's, when Ross managed 2/39/1 against the Saints. On Sunday, Ross beat Ravens CB Marlon Humphrey on his 22-yard score. Ross has been highly inefficient all season, he has found the end zone just often enough to be fringe WR3/flex worthy.  Ross will be the likeliest Bengals to draw impressive Browns rookie CB Denzel Ward's coverage in Week 11.
report: John Ross caught 2-of-7 targets for 27 yards and a touchdown in the Bengals' Week 11 loss to the Ravens.

impact: Rosen was thrown into the game 4:31 left in the game and the Cardinals trailing by two points. Things started off positively as the Cardinals moved the ball into Bears territory, but then Rosen threw an interception in which he was late and behind Christian Kirk on an out route down the right sideline. This was a tough spot to place Rosen in for his first game action, but with Sam Bradford turning the ball over three more times Sunday, Rosen should finally get a look to start next week at home versus the Seahawks.
report: Josh Rosen completed 4-of-7 passes for 36 yards with an interception in Sunday's Week 3 loss to the Bears.

impact: Rosen played well enough to win and lost multiple touchdowns on the day as Larry Fitzgerald and J.J. Nelson each dropped touchdown passes on the day. Rosen's first touchdown pass of his career came on a 22-yard pass to Chad Williams which he managed the pocket and tied the game in the 4th quarter. Despite the positive start, Rosen will not be an option Week 5 against the 49ers outside of deeper 2-QB leagues.
report: Josh Rosen completed 15-of-27 passes for 180 yards and one touchdown in Sunday's Week 4 loss to the Seahawks.

impact: He was sacked once for a loss of six yards. Rosen got his first win as an NFL starter in this one, though he wasn't asked to do very much and even when he did, the rookie was rarely on the same page with his receivers. The 21-year-old got his highlight out of the way early, hitting the mark on a 75-yard deep bomb to Christian Kirk on the Cardinals' very first play from scrimmage. He essentially took the rest of afternoon off, though he was also done in by a number of bad drops. Rosen will have his work cut out for him next week in a tough road matchup against the Vikings.
report: Josh Rosen completed 10-of-25 passes for 170 yards and a touchdown while losing three yards on his three carries Sunday in the Cardinals’ Week 5 win over the 49ers.

impact: Rosen had some success early but flatlined in the second half. He was under constant pressures, taking four sacks. Rosen continued to lock on to Christian Kirk, who led the Cardinals with 77 yards. It was a tough spot for Rosen on the road against the Vikings. He'll get another tough matchup with the Broncos on Thursday night.
report: Josh Rosen completed 21-of-31 passes for 240 yards with an interception in the Cardinals' Week 6 loss to the Vikings.

impact: Two of Rosen's picks were housed for scores. Rosen also tweaked his toe on the final play of the game but said he was "fine." This was one of the worst starts you will ever see from an NFL quarterback. Although he was getting zero help from his play-calling, Rosen was inexcusably bad, delivering passes late and not feeling pressure. He was lucky to escape with "only" five turnovers. Rosen does not have the biggest arm for a first-round quarterback, and it showed this evening. Which brings us back to the play-calling. OC Mike McCoy seems to have zero awareness of Rosen's strengths and weaknesses, dialing up one sideline out after another while all but ignoring play action. There's a strong chance he's fired during the Cardinals' "mini bye" and replaced by QBs coach Byron Leftwich.
report: Josh Rosen completed 21-of-39 passes for 194 yards, one touchdown and three interceptions in the Cardinals' 45-10, Week 7 loss to the Broncos, also losing two fumbles.

impact: Rosen's passing yards and attempts both qualified as season-highs, an encouraging sign in OC Byron Leftwich's new offensive scheme. Rosen fired the game-winner with just 0:34 left over the middle to fellow rookie Christian Kirk (3/42/1), helping secure the Cardinals' second win of the season. With Larry Fitzgerald (8/102/1) additionally honed in on throughout the afternoon, there's suddenly reason to believe in Rosen and the Cardinals' passing attack as a whole. The offense will get its second test in Kansas City following the team's Week 9 bye.
report: Josh Rosen completed 23-of-40 passes for 252 yards, two touchdowns, and one interception in the Cardinals' Week 8 win over the 49ers.

impact: This was another small step forward for Rosen, but he continued to take too many sacks. Rosen's only touchdown was a red-zone strike to David Johnson. The Cardinals have looked better under OC Byron Leftwich, but they're still a bottom-tier offense. Rosen has an attackable matchup with Oakland in Week 11.
report: Josh Rosen completed 22-of-39 passes for 208 yards with a touchdown and two interceptions in Week 10 against the Chiefs.

impact: If you were forced to start Rosen in a two-quarterback league in a week with six teams on bye you are not complaining, but he struggled mightily in this one. Both of Rosen's picks were terrible decisions into crowded areas, and he was consistently a beat or two slow with his decision making. Even a critical late completion to Christian Kirk to set up a touchdown should have been intercepted. Rosen's biggest play was a 59-yard screen score where Kirk did all the work. Having difficulty adjusting to NFL game speed with a thin supporting cast, Rosen will not be stuffing any stat sheets down the stretch. The Cardinals are headed on the road to Los Angeles to face the Chargers in Week 12.
report: Josh Rosen completed 9-of-20 passes for 136 yards, three touchdowns and two interceptions in the Cardinals' 23-21, Week 11 loss to the Raiders.

impact: Rogers entered Sunday with eight catches for 49 yards on 10 targets.  He was far more active in this one after T.Y. Hilton had to leave multiple times with chest and hamstring injuries.  Rogers' 11 targets matched Nyheim Hines for the team lead on a day Andrew Luck attempted 62 passes.  With Hilton expected to miss Thursday night's Week 5 game against the Patriots, Rogers will again be relied upon.  He may have some WR5 appeal in deeper leagues in a likely catchup-mode game.
report: Chester Rogers caught 8-of-11 targets for 85 yards in the Colts' Week 4 loss to the Texans.

impact: Rogers got off to an excruciating start with multiple dropped passes.  He salvaged his fantasy bottom line on a 17-yard garbage-time touchdown with Indianapolis down multiple scores.  Nevertheless, Rogers is suddenly in prime fantasy position as the Colts lost several more pass catchers to injury on Sunday, including Ryan Grant (ankle).  With double-digit targets in three straight games, Rogers will be a fantasy starter in Week 7 versus Buffalo.
report: Chester Rogers caught 4-of-10 targets for 55 yards and a touchdown in the Colts' Week 6 loss to the Jets.

impact: The bulk of his yards came on one catch, a 29-yard grab on a play where the defense forgot about him during the second quarter. That was the Colts' longest play from scrimmage. Rogers couldn't take advantage of Ryan Grant's absence, though that was mostly because the Colts stopped throwing after getting ahead early. The 25-year-old could be in play as a DFS dart throw if Grant remains sidelined for Week 8 against the Raiders.
report: Chester Rogers came down with four catches for 40 yards on four targets Sunday in Indianapolis’ Week 7 win over the Bills.

impact: The bulk of his yards came on one catch, a 29-yard grab on a play where the defense forgot about him during the second quarter. That was the Colts' longest play from scrimmage. Rogers couldn't take advantage of Ryan Grant's absence, though that was mostly because the Colts stopped throwing after getting ahead early. The 25-year-old could be in play as a DFS dart throw if Grant remains sidelined for Week 8 against the Raiders.
report: Chester Rogers came down with four catches for 40 yards on four targets Sunday in Indianapolis’ Week 7 win over the Bills.

impact: After drawing double-digit targets in three straight games between Weeks 4-6, Rogers has vanished, seeing just five looks from Andrew Luck over the past two weeks. The 24-year-old hasn't moved the needle much, even with Ryan Grant (ankle) sidelined. Even as a cheap DFS punt play, you can probably do better than Rogers.
report: Chester Rogers came up empty on his lone target Sunday in the Colts’ Week 8 win over Oakland.

impact: Roethlisberger also lost two fumbles on sacks as he compiled five turnovers on the afternoon in heavy rain. Outside of the bulk yardage, his lone bright spot was a 22-yard touchdown strike to Antonio Brown in the 3rd quarter. Roethlisberger has now thrown one or fewer touchdown passes in 16 of his past 22 games on the road in early starts. Despite his poor start, Roethlisberger will be a starting fantasy option at home next week against the Chiefs.
report: Ben Roethlisberger completed 23-of-41 passes for 335 yards with one touchdowns and three interceptions in Sunday's Week 1 tie versus the Browns.

impact: With the Steelers down 21-0 after 13 minutes, Roethlisberger had nearly an entire afternoon of comeback mode/garbage time. The Steelers were unwatchable early on, beginning the game with two three-and-outs. Ben then got cooking, targeting Antonio Brown and JuJu Smith-Schuster a combined 36 times. He also consistently found TE Jesse James for big plays. Rookie big-play threat James Washington was heavily involved early after a Week 1 mothballing. The Steelers actually came close to pulling off the comeback, but the early deficit was too much to overcome on an afternoon where Patrick Mahomes piled up six touchdowns. Roethlisberger has an attackable matchup in the Bucs for Week 3.
report: Ben Roethlisberger completed 39-of-60 passes for 452 yards and three touchdowns in the Steelers' 42-37, Week 2 loss to the Chiefs, adding a rushing score.

impact: Roethlisberger and the Steelers' offense shook off a quick three-and-out and interception during their first two possessions to eventually take a 30-10 lead into the half. Big Ben's first touchdown was a YAC-filled 75-yard touchdown pass over the middle to emerging starter Vance McDonald, followed by touchdowns to Antonio Brown and Ryan Switzer before heading to the locker room. Pittsburgh was shutout in the second half, but Roethlisberger did enough damage early on to finish as the week's QB10. The Steelers have a divisional showdown next Sunday night against a Ravens defense that could be without both CB Jimmy Smith and LB C.J. Mosley.
report: Ben Roethlisberger completed 30-of-38 passes for 353 yards, three touchdowns, and one interception in the Steelers' Week 3 victory over the Buccaneers.

impact: Roethlisberger had a solid first half, but the Steelers' offense went in the tank over the final two quarters. His only touchdown came on an extended play to Antonio Brown from 26 yards out. It's the first game of the season Roethlisberger hasn't passed for at least 300 yards. Roethlisberger is on pace for 32 touchdowns and  21 interceptions through the first month of the season. He'll get a matchup with the Falcons in Week 5.
report: Ben Roethlisberger completed 27-of-47 passes for 274 yards with one touchdown and an interception in the Steelers' Week 5 loss to the Ravens.

impact: Roethlisberger was on track for a disappointing day before he finally got his Antonio Brown connection going in the second half. After entering the break 2-of-8 for eight yards and an interception targeting his No. 1 wideout, Ben found Brown six times for 93 yards and two scores over the final two quarters. The second was the highlight. Brown got a step on Robert Alford down the left sideline and Roethlisberger hit him in stride for a 47-yarder. Roethlisberger gets the Bengals on the road for Week 6.
report: Ben Roethlisberger completed 19-of-29 passes for 250 yards, three touchdowns and an interception in the Steelers' 41-17, Week 5 win over the Falcons.

impact: Big Ben had a clean pocket all day, not getting sacked at all, and was pretty unlucky to only have one touchdown pass.  JuJu Smith-Schuster was ruled down at the one-yard line on a play where it appeared he actually did score.  The Steelers also failed to convert a 1st-and-goal situation from the one-yard line, settling for a field goal.  Ben's lone score was a 31-yard quick slant, game-winner to Antonio Brown with 10 seconds left.  The Steelers now head into their bye week.
report: Ben Roethlisberger completed 32-of-46 passes for 369 yards and one touchdown in the Steelers' Week 6 win over the Bengals.

impact: Big Ben had a clean pocket all day, not getting sacked at all, and was pretty unlucky to only have one touchdown pass.  JuJu Smith-Schuster was ruled down at the one-yard line on a play where it appeared he actually did score.  The Steelers also failed to convert a 1st-and-goal situation from the one-yard line, settling for a field goal.  Ben's lone score was a 31-yard quick slant, game-winner to Antonio Brown with 10 seconds left.  The Steelers now head into their bye week.
report: Ben Roethlisberger completed 32-of-46 passes for 369 yards and one touchdown in the Steelers' Week 6 win over the Bengals.

impact: Roethlisberger found Antonio Brown for both scores in the second quarter. The first was a 43-yard play in which Roethlisberger climbed the pocket and Brown got behind the Cleveland defense. The second was a 1-yard screen right before the first half came to a close. With the Steelers up big, Roethlisberger wasn't asked to do much in the second half as the Steelers ran wild after the break. Roethlisberger will find himself in a tough road matchup against the Ravens in Week 9.
report: Ben Roethlisberger completed 24-of-36 passes for 257 yards and two touchdowns with one interception in Sunday's Week 8 win over the Browns.

impact: Ben was sacked once for a loss of 10 yards. Roethlisberger looked more tentative than usual playing through a broken finger on his non-throwing hand but still managed a pair of touchdowns including one to Antonio Brown, his ninth of the season. He took an enormous hit from Darius Smith after taking off on a fourth-quarter scramble, coming down hard on his right shoulder. Roethlisberger looked to be in serious pain but returned after missing just one snap. Believe it or not, this was actually Roethlisberger's first career three-touchdown game in Baltimore. The veteran will probably be feeling it after this one, so don't expect him to practice much ahead of Thursday night's showdown with Carolina.
report: Ben Roethlisberger completed 28-of-47 passes for 270 yards and two touchdowns while adding four yards and another touchdown on two carries Sunday in the Steelers’ Week 9 win over the Ravens.

impact: For the fourth time in his career, Roethlisberger finished with a perfect passer rating. He set the tone with a 75-yard touchdown to JuJu Smith-Schuster on the Steelers' first play from scrimmage. He also found Antonio Brown for a 53-yard score. The rest of the scores went to Vance McDonald, Jesse James and Jaylen Samuels (yes, really). The performance was extra impressive since Ben was playing banged up on a short week. Roethlisberger is not going to fare as well in Week 11, where the Steelers are venturing on the road to Jacksonville.
report: Ben Roethlisberger completed 22-of-25 passes for 328 yards and five touchdowns in Pittsburgh's Week 10 game against the Panthers, taking a seat with the Steelers winning 52-14 in the fourth quarter.

impact: Roethlisberger also added the game-winning 1-yard touchdown run with five seconds left to give the Steelers a come from behind victory after being behind 16-0 with 2:09 left in the third quarter. Things got off to a disastrous start as Roethlisberger had just 53 passing yards at the half with two interceptions. He found Antonio Brown on a 78-yard busted coverage to get the Steelers on the board and then added an 11-yard score to Vance McDonald late in the fourth quarter. Roethlisberger will be a QB1 option next week on the road in Denver.
report: Ben Roethlisberger completed 27-of-47 passes for 314 yards with two touchdowns and three interceptions in Sunday's Week 11 win over the Jaguars.

impact: It was a dreary, dull affair against an overmatched Bills team. Rodgers was steamed in his post-game press conference about the Packers' lack of production. A positive was Rodgers' increased mobility. Although still nowhere close to 100 percent, Rodgers did look healthier and more willing to run. Rodgers' pick was a tip drill from Jimmy Graham, who also caught Rodgers' score. It was the duo's first end zone connection. The Packers venture to Detroit for Week 5.
report: Aaron Rodgers completed 22-of-40 passes for 298 yards, one touchdown and an interception in the Packers' 22-0, Week 4 win over the Bills, adding five carries for 31 additional yards.

impact: Rodgers has been critical of the Packers' offense this year, calling the team's play in last week's win over Buffalo "not acceptable." There have been rumblings of a rift between Rodgers and his head coach, but Murphy isn't buying it. "I think they've had a great relationship," said Murphy. "The most important thing, they both want the same thing—they want us to win and obviously score as many points as possible." Part of the problem for Green Bay is that their receiving corps has been running on fumes with injuries to Randall Cobb (hamstring) and Geronimo Allison (concussion, hamstring), among others. Luckily Rodgers' health has improved significantly as the two-time MVP was finally removed from the injury report this week after struggling with knee issues early in the year.
report: Packers CEO and president Mark Murphy downplayed the tension between Aaron Rodgers and coach Mike McCarthy.

impact: He added 10 rushing yards on three attempts and also lost a pair of fumbles on strip-sacks.  The Packers fell in a huge hole early in the game and pretty much had to abandon the run game by the second quarter.  With Randall Cobb and Geronimo Allison out and injured for this one, Rodgers was working with Marquez Valdes-Scantling and Equanimeous St. Brown behind Davante Adams.  The rookies had some trouble getting open and staying on the same page with Rodgers, who was visibly frustrated at times.  Adams piled up 140 yards and a touchdown as the lead dog.  Rodgers gets to feast on the 49ers at Lambeau Field next Monday night.
report: Aaron Rodgers completed 32-of-52 passes for 442 yards and three touchdowns in the Packers' 31-23, Week 5 loss to the Lions.

impact: To borrow the words from ESPN analyst Jason Witten, Rodgers pulled a "rabbit out of his head" in the incredible fourth-quarter comeback.  (Yes, Witten said head.)  Rodgers and the Packers came out piping hot to open the game, with 60- and 54-yard completions to Marquez Valdes-Scantling and Jimmy Graham, respectively.  49ers DC Robert Saleh started dialing up the blitzes the rest of the way, causing Rodgers serious problems much of the second, third, and fourth quarters, but Rodgers turned it up and absolutely diced the Niners in the final two-plus minutes with a 16-yard touchdown strike to Davante Adams to tie the game at 30-30.  (Witten used the rabbit reference here.)  Rodgers then got the ball back at his own 10-yard line with 1:07 left and threw for 46 yards and added a 21-yard run to give Mason Crosby a walkoff 27-yard field goal for the win.  The Packers are now on their bye ahead of a gargantuan Week 8 date in L.A. with the Rams.
report: Aaron Rodgers completed 25-of-46 passes for 425 yards and two touchdowns in the Packers' 33-30, Week 6 comeback win over the 49ers on Monday night.

impact: Rodgers should have had a 300-yard day, but a devastating Ty Montgomery kickoff fumble with 1:56 remaining robbed him of a comeback attempt. Rodgers had the two minutes and a timeout to work with as the Pack eyed flipping a 29-27 Rams lead. Rodgers also should have had a two-score day, but Jimmy Graham was narrowly taken down at the one in the first half. Even as he's battled knee issues and receiver injuries, Rodgers has played genuinely elite football all year. The Packers are headed to New England for Sunday Night Football in Week 9.
report: Aaron Rodgers completed 18-of-30 passes for 286 yards and one touchdown in the Packers' 29-27, Week 8 loss to the Rams.

impact: Rodgers played without a knee brace for the first time since Week 1. He struggled to move the offense for most of the night, with his touchdowns coming on goal-line throws to Davante Adams and Jimmy Graham. Rodgers is on pace for 5,084 yards and a 30:1 TD/INT ratio at the season’s halfway point, so he's due for some positive touchdown progression. He’ll remain a locked-in QB1 for Week 10 against Miami.
report: Aaron Rodgers completed 24-of-43 passes for 259 yards and two touchdowns in the Packers' Week 9 loss to the Patriots.

impact: Both touchdown tosses went to Davante Adams, who's now tallied nine scores on the year. The Packers' passing attack admittedly appeared shaky at times, but it wasn't needed on this day. Aaron Jones led the way with 15/145/2 on the ground, allowing Rodgers and crew to coast for most of the afternoon. There will be better days ahead for Rodgers, who's now on pace for 4,872 yards and a 30:1 TD:INT ratio. He remains a matchup-proof QB1 in Seattle in Week 11.
report: Aaron Rodgers completed 19-of-28 passes for 199 yards and two touchdowns in the Packers' Week 10 walk in the park over the Dolphins.

impact: Rodgers played a perfect first half — the highlights, including a 54-yard, cross-body touchdown to "Robert Tonyan," are worth checking out — but the Packers fell apart after the break. Coach Mike McCarthy was dialing up truly awful play-calling, with long-developing third down plays that resulted in sacks the favorite. Rodgers also made a few decisions he will want back. The talk will be McCarthy's job status. Struggling more than ever this season, McCarthy was straight bad this evening, botching play calls, wasting timeouts and choosing to punt back to the Seahawks with four minutes remaining even though the Pack's defense was injury ravaged and running on fumes. At 4-5-1, the Pack are in grave trouble in the NFC North. They are headed to Minnesota for Week 12.
report: Aaron Rodgers completed 21-of-30 passes for 332 yards and two touchdowns in the Packers' 27-24, Week 11 loss to the Seahawks.

impact: The Bucs’ backup played sparingly and was ineffective in the few instances when he was called upon, managing a long gain of just three yards. Peyton Barber served as Tampa’s workhorse in the opener, leading the Bucs’ backfield with 19 touches. We’d expect that trend to continue next week against the Eagles.
report: Jacquizz Rodgers rushed twice for only one yard while catching his lone target for a two-yard gain Sunday in the Buccaneeers’ Week 1 win over the Saints.

impact: The Bucs’ backup played sparingly and was ineffective in the few instances when he was called upon, managing a long gain of just three yards. Peyton Barber served as Tampa’s workhorse in the opener, leading the Bucs’ backfield with 19 touches. We’d expect that trend to continue next week against the Eagles.
report: Jacquizz Rodgers rushed twice for only one yard while catching his lone target for a two-yard gain Sunday in the Buccaneeers’ Week 1 win over the Saints.

impact: He carried the ball just one time for no gain.  The eight targets and 102 yards were both team-highs for Rodgers as the third-down and passing back behind Peyton Barber.  Rodgers made a critical mistake in the second half, however, losing a fumble at the Washington 20-yard line that ended up in the end zone and recovered by the Redskins.  This is a fluke line; Rodgers isn't a fantasy option.
report: Jacquizz Rodgers caught all eight of his targets for 102 yards in the Bucs' 16-3, Week 10 loss to the Redskins.

impact: Only one week after leading his team in receiving, Rodgers touched the ball three times and failed to record a single catch against the Giants. Apologize to your league for wasting their time if you spent any amount of FAAB on him.
report: Jacquizz Rodgers rushed three times for 15 yards in the Bucs' Week 11 loss to the Giants.

impact: Robinson has now led the Bears in receiving and targets in both games to open the season, averaging 10.5 targets per in that span.  The yards haven't been great (61 in Week 1), and Robinson has yet to find the end zone.  However, it's pretty obvious Robinson is Mitchell Trubisky's No. 1 option.  Robinson will have a tough battle with Patrick Peterson on the road in Week 3.
report: Allen Robinson caught 10-of-14 targets for 83 yards in the Bears' 24-17, Week 2 win over the Seahawks.

impact: Calling them targets is being generous as the bulk of his opportunity came from uncatchable passes and 50/50 jump balls. His lone highlight was a 39-yard connection where Robinson beat the defender at the line of scrimmage and Mitchell Trubisky put on the money. Robinson is dominating passing-game opportunity with the Bears, receiving 28 targets through three games, but has turned all of those targets into a modest 194 yards through three games with no scores. Things get much better in Week 4, however, as the Bears host a porous Tampa Bay secondary on a short week.
report: Allen Robinson caught 3-of-7 targets for 50 yards in Sunday's Week 3 win over the Cardinals.

impact: Robinson's 20 yards and ensuing touchdown wouldn't ordinarily be a letdown, but it came on a day in which Mitchell Trubisky threw for career-highs in yards (354) and touchdowns (6). Normally the recipient during the majority of his drop backs, Trubisky instead fed backup RB Tarik Cohen (7-121-1), Taylor Gabriel (7-104-2), and Trey Burton (2-86-1) rather than A-Rob. Robinson should still be the primary beneficiary moving forward now that the Bears' offense appears to be clicking on all cylinders. Unless he's shadowed by premier CB Xavien Howard after the bye, Robinson will stay a low-end WR2 against the Dolphins.
report: Allen Robinson caught 2-of-4 targets for 23 yards and one touchdown in the Bears' Week 4 victory over the Buccaneers.

impact: Robinson found himself on the receiving end of a 12-yard touchdown strike from Mitchell Trubisky in the third quarter, which came immediately following Kyle Fuller's interception of Brock Osweiler. That marked his second touchdown in as many games. Robinson's other contributions included a nice back-shoulder catch for a 21-yard gain in the fourth quarter and drawing a pass interference flag that eventually led to a Bears touchdown. A-Rob gets a date with New England in Week 7.
report: Allen Robinson pulled in five catches for 64 yards and a touchdown on six targets Sunday in Chicago’s Week 6 loss to the Dolphins.

impact: Robinson did not have anything to show for his early opportunities in this one. He was unable to get loose on a deep target on the opening drive, and he dropped what would have been a third-down conversion on the second series. His only catch of the first half went for just four yards, and he was somehow worse in the second half. He was targeted just once in the third quarter – an errant end-zone target – and he was not heard from after that. It is possible he aggravated his groin injury in the second half, but the Bears never announced an injury. The Jets are a good matchup next week, but Robinson’s health and Mitchell Trubisky’s play are concerns moving forward.
report: Allen Robinson hauled in 1-of-5 targets for four yards in the Bears' Week 7 loss to the Patriots.

impact: A-Rob absolutely roasted the Lions in his return from a two-game absence (he had been out with a groin injury), contributing his first multi-touchdown game since Week 3 of 2016 back when he was still a member of the Jaguars. Robinson did most of his damage before halftime, hanging 99 first-half yards on the visiting Lions. Robinson made DeShawn Shead his first victim, beating him for a 36-yard touchdown with time winding down in the first quarter. He made another end-zone cameo in the third quarter, this time breaking off a 24-yard catch-and-run to put the Bears ahead 32-10. Detroit’s secondary looked shot without stud corner Darius Slay (knee) and Robinson took full advantage on Sunday. We’ll see what he does for an encore next week against the Vikings.
report: Allen Robinson nabbed six catches for 133 yards and two touchdowns on eight targets Sunday in Chicago’s Week 10 victory over Detroit.

impact: It's a letdown for Robinson coming off last week's 6/133/2 line. Robinson finished behind only Taylor Gabriel in targets but wasn't much of a factor with Mitchell Trubisky checking down all night. Robinson has been highly inconsistent, with six games under 70 yards. He's a WR4 for a tough Week 12 matchup against Detroit.
report: Allen Robinson caught 3-of-7 targets for 39 yards in Week 12 against the Vikings.

impact: After losing Amari Cooper (concussion), the Raiders are down to Jordy Nelson, Martavis Bryant, and Dwayne Harris at wide receiver.  Roberts immediately went to the locker room after suffering his fourth-quarter brain injury.  The slot receiver had five catches for 31 yards on six targets before departing.
report: Raiders WR Seth Roberts left Sunday's Week 6 game with a concussion.

impact: Some theorized that Roberts' role would expand following Amari Cooper's trade to Dallas, but that obviously didn't come to fruition Sunday as the 27-year-old drew his fewest targets since Week 4. His touchdown came in the second quarter on a 31-yard heave from Derek Carr. That was both the longest catch of the day for Oakland as well as Roberts' longest play this year. Roberts won't be of much fantasy interest Thursday against the Niners.
report: Seth Roberts nabbed two of four targets for 42 yards and a touchdown Sunday in the Raiders’ Week 8 loss to the Colts.

impact: The seven targets matched a season high. Roberts was heavily involved because both Martavis Bryant (knee) and Jordy Nelson (knee) were on the shelf. Brandon LaFell then joined them there with an Achilles' issue. Despite all that, Roberts will be tough to recommend as a WR4 option for next week's trip to Baltimore. The Raiders' passing offense simply is not good enough.
report: Seth Roberts caught 4-of-7 targets for 38 yards in the Raiders' Week 11 win over the Cardinals.

impact: Backfield mate Marshawn Lynch handled just nine carries since the game was out of hand early. Richard was involved late, finishing second on the team in receiving yards. Richard has shown a propensity to produce when involved — the issue being he's never involved. If Lynch ever misses time, there's no doubt Richard will sneak into strong RB3/FLEX consideration.
report: Jalen Richard caught all six of his targets for 53 yards and one touchdown in the Raiders' Week 5 stomping to the Chargers.

impact: When the Raiders play from behind, Richard's usage spikes as a frequent checkdown target for checkdown-loving Derek Carr.  The team's leading receiver in Sunday's blowout loss, Richard will remain a negative-game-script-dependent, PPR-only flex option when Oakland emerges from its Week 7 bye.
report: Jalen Richard caught 7-of-8 targets for 48 yards and rushed twice for three yards in the Raiders' Week 6 loss to Seattle.

impact: When the Raiders play from behind, Richard's usage spikes as a frequent checkdown target for checkdown-loving Derek Carr.  The team's leading receiver in Sunday's blowout loss, Richard will remain a negative-game-script-dependent, PPR-only flex option when Oakland emerges from its Week 7 bye.
report: Jalen Richard caught 7-of-8 targets for 48 yards and rushed twice for three yards in the Raiders' Week 6 loss to Seattle.

impact: With Marshawn Lynch (groin) sidelined, Doug Martin earned most of the Raiders' early-down work while ceding passing-down reps to Richard. Martin is the favorite for goal-line work in Lynch's absence, though Richard's receiving role should keep him on the flex radar in PPR leagues. He gets an enticing matchup Thursday against San Francisco.
report: Jalen Richard tallied 14 yards on two carries while pulling in all eight of his targets for 50 yards Sunday in the Raiders’ Week 8 loss to the Colts.

impact: Richard was quiet for most of this game, but as is usually the case, he padded his stats late in the loss. Four of his targets, three of his catches, and 37 of his yards came on a failed drive in garbage time. The good news is the 1-8 Raiders should provide plenty of those opportunities, keeping him in the FLEX conversation.
report: Jalen Richard rushed three times for seven yards and hauled in 5-of-6 targets for 52 yards in the Raiders' Week 10 loss to the Chargers.

impact: With Doug Martin nursing an ankle injury, Richard took over as the Raiders' lead rusher after the break, though DeAndre Washington also mixed in for 12 carries. The three receptions were actually Richard's fewest in six games, which was highly surprising because of how thin the Raiders are at wideout. Regardless of Martin's Week 12 status, Richard will be a FLEX against the Ravens' stout defense.
report: Jalen Richard rushed 11 times for 61 yards in the Raiders' Week 11 win over the Cardinals, adding three receptions for 32 additional yards.

impact: Riddick led all Lions running backs playing 40 snaps with Detroit getting annihilated on the scoreboard and playing catchup most of the night.  Riddick still did nothing with his looks despite seeing a goal-line carry, where he was predictably stonewalled.  Riddick isn't fantasy starter material outside of deep PPR leagues where he'll have some bye-week value.
report: Theo Riddick rushed four times for 20 yards and caught 5-of-7 targets for 15 yards in the Lions' Week 1 loss to the Jets.

impact: He didn’t see any chances as a ball-carrier but was targeted heavily in the passing game with the Lions playing from behind in the second half. Riddick may not sleep well tonight after dropping a third-down pass from Matthew Stafford with the Lions driving late in the fourth quarter. Stafford went right back to Riddick, who was wide-open on the following play, but his pass fell incomplete. That ended Detroit’s comeback bid with 14 seconds remaining. Though he technically plays running back, Riddick is really more of a wide receiver. He gets the Patriots at home next week.
report: Theo Riddick secured nine-of-12 targets for 47 yards Sunday in Detroit’s Week 2 loss to the 49ers.

impact: As usual, Riddick worked mostly as a pass-catcher, seeing just one carry in the loss. All five of his touches came before halftime. With Kerryon Johnson and LeGarrette Blount getting most of the backfield work for Detroit, Riddick is just a bench stash in PPR leagues. He’ll get the Packers at home in Week 5.
report: Theo Riddick gained seven yards on his lone carry while nabbing four catches for 20 yards on five targets Sunday in the Lions’ Week 4 loss to Dallas.

impact: Since the Lions were the ones with a commanding lead, Riddick wasn't needed for his normal comeback mode role as the check-down option.  Matthew Stafford attempted just 26 passes on the day.  Riddick remains a basement-level RB3 in deeper PPR leagues as the Lions head into their bye.
report: Theo Riddick rushed three times for three yards and caught 2-of-3 targets for 20 yards in the Lions' Week 5 win over the Packers.

impact: Riddick missed the previous two games with a knee injury but came back to tie for the team lead in targets with Marvin Jones.  He didn't rush the ball, as Kerryon Johnson stayed the lead back with 15 touches.  Riddick essentially took over Golden Tate's role as the third receiver.  Those targets will put him on the map for desperate PPR owners, but there's little upside and a low floor.
report: Theo Riddick caught 7-of-8 targets for 36 yards in the Lions' Week 9 loss to the Vikings.

impact: Predictably, Riddick did almost all of his damage with Detroit trailing in the second half. Five of his six grabs came after halftime. The Lions aren't even pretending to use him as a running back anymore as evidenced by the zero carries he's logged over his last two games. Riddick's receiving usage gives him a reasonable PPR floor but his lack of touchdowns—he's yet to find the end zone in 2018—makes him a risky fantasy bet. He'll be back at it against the Panthers in Week 11.
report: Theo Riddick compiled six catches for 60 yards on seven targets Sunday in Detroit’s Week 10 loss to Chicago.

impact: Riddick has consistently been involved as a receiver since Golden Tate was traded, and that continued on Sunday. He did not do anything with the work in the first half, finishing with negative-five yards, but he opened the second by cooking Thomas Davis on an 18-yard catch.  He added another 17 on a shovel pass in the fourth to help spark the game-winning touchdown drive. With Kerryon Johnson's status uncertain, Riddick could play a big role against the Bears on Thanksgiving.
report: Theo Riddick hauled in 5-of-7 targets for 30 yards in the Lions' Week 11 win over the Panthers.

impact: A dream fantasy scenario unfolded once the Chargers fell behind 14-3 in the first quarter. Rivers is a legendary comeback-mode predator. He did not disappoint despite the best efforts of his receivers, who committed some truly horrifying drops. Tyrell Williams and Travis Benjamin both bungled certain touchdowns, while Rivers missed Benjamin on another. It was a thoroughly Chargers game, from the mistakes to the garbage time. Rivers gets the Bills on the road in Week 2. That's a long road trip.
report: Philip Rivers completed 34-of-51 passes for 424 yards, three touchdowns and an interception in the Chargers' 38-28, Week 1 loss to the Chiefs.

impact: It was a near-perfect game from Rivers, who didn't face any resistance from an injured Buffalo secondary. Rivers threw a touchdown to Mike Williams on the opening drive, with his other two coming on checkdowns to Melvin Gordon. This was another cupcake matchup for Rivers after shredding the Chiefs in the opener, but he's been locked in to start the year. The Chargers have a matchup with the Rams in Week 3.
report: Philip Rivers completed 23-of-27 passes for 256 yards and three touchdowns in the Chargers' Week 2 win over Buffalo.

impact: Coming off a three touchdown performance against the Bills, Rivers had a tougher matchup with the Rams this week, but he was still able to put together a respectable fantasy performance. Both touchdown passes went to Mike Williams who appears to have taken a second-year leap after being sidelined with injuries as a rookie. Rivers and the Chargers have an opportunity to get back in the win column next Sunday at home against the 49ers.
report: Philip Rivers completed 18-of-30 passes for 226 yards and two touchdowns in the Chargers' Week 3 loss to the Rams.

impact: Rivers passed John Elway for the eighth-most career passing yards in league history during the close home win. All three of his touchdown passes went to non-receivers, which will frustrate Keenan Allen and Mike Williams' fantasy owners, but Melvin Gordon and Austin Ekeler's receiving production is helping Rivers fill the stat sheet. Through four games, Rivers is averaging 289 passing yards and 2.75 touchdowns. He will be a QB1 next week against the Raiders.
report: Philip Rivers completed 25-of-39 passes for 250 yards, three touchdowns, and one interception in the Chargers' Week 4 win over the 49ers.

impact: It was an extremely efficient afternoon for Rivers, who totaled just five incompletions en route to his second 300-plus yard performance on the year. Both scores came on throws out to the flats, including one in which he bobbled the snap, quickly regrouped, and side-armed a laser in the direction of Austin Ekeler (7-59-1), who shuffled his way past two defenders and into the end zone. Keenan Allen's touchdown toll has taken a hit this season, but Rivers has still stood upright as a strong QB1 due in part to the added involvement of both Melvin Gordon and Ekeler in Los Angeles' passing attack. Rivers is currently averaging 299 yards and 2.6 touchdowns through five games this season. He'll be a strong QB1 again in Week 6 against the Browns.
report: Philip Rivers completed 22-of-27 passes for 339 yards and two touchdowns in the Chargers' Week 5 victory over the Raiders.

impact: The 11 completions were the fewest in a game for Rivers since Week 16 of 2012. With the Chargers up big, he just wasn't needed as he attempted just five total passes in the second half on Sunday. Both of Rivers' scores went to Tyrell Williams in the second quarter. Rivers is having a tremendous start to the season with 15 touchdown passes to just three interceptions and will be in the lower-end QB1 mix next week in London versus the Titans.
report: Philip Rivers completed 11-of-20 passes for 207 yards with two touchdowns and one interception in Sunday's Week 6 win over the Browns.

impact: Rivers hit Tyrell Williams on a 75-yard bomb on the Chargers’ first play from scrimmage. Both of his touchdowns were 50-plus yards, with Mike Williams beating the Titans deep to open the second half. Rivers attempted only 26 passes but he's been a lot more efficient this year with a 17:3 TD/INT ratio. The Chargers are on bye next week, but Rivers will be in the lower-end QB1 mix against Seattle in Week 9.
report: Philip Rivers completed 19-of-26 passes for 306 yards and two touchdowns in the Chargers' Week 7 win over the Titans.

impact: Rivers hit Tyrell Williams on a 75-yard bomb on the Chargers’ first play from scrimmage. Both of his touchdowns were 50-plus yards, with Mike Williams beating the Titans deep to open the second half. Rivers attempted only 26 passes but he's been a lot more efficient this year with a 17:3 TD/INT ratio. The Chargers are on bye next week, but Rivers will be in the lower-end QB1 mix against Seattle in Week 9.
report: Philip Rivers completed 19-of-26 passes for 306 yards and two touchdowns in the Chargers' Week 7 win over the Titans.

impact: It was another low-volume day, but Rivers compensated by averaging at least 8.77 yards per attempt for the fourth-straight contest. Rivers has not attempted 30 passes in a game since Week 4 but has still managed to produce at least two scores every week out. His offense is outfitted with playmakers and running threats. Despite his light throwing workloads, Rivers will be a QB1 for Week 10 against the Raiders' expansion-level defense.
report: Philip Rivers completed 13-of-26 passes for 228 yards and two touchdowns in the Chargers' 25-17, Week 9 win over the Seahawks.

impact: This was not a highlight-reel game for Rivers, but he did enough against the Raiders’ barely-there offense. At the end of a quiet first half, Rivers led a quick scoring drive capped by an 11-yard touchdown to Keenan Allen to give the Chargers the lead. He had little to do with his next score as Melvin Gordon took a dump off, avoided two tacklers, and beat everyone down the field for a 66-yard touchdown, but it still counts. From that point, Rivers mostly turned around and handed off the ball. Rivers will face a tougher test next week against the Broncos, but he should also be asked to throw more.
report: Philip Rivers completed 18-of-26 passes for 223 yards, two touchdowns, and an interception in the Chargers' Week 10 win over the Raiders.

impact: He took three sacks for a loss of 17 yards. Sunday marked the veteran's first multi-interception game of the season. His first pick came on a pass intended for Tyrell Williams while Von Miller came up with the second and almost took it back for a pick-six. Rivers' touchdown throws went to Keenan Allen and veteran tight end Antonio Gates, who had his best game of the season by far with five catches for 80 yards on seven targets. The 37-year-old NC State product made an inexplicable mistake late in the fourth quarter by throwing the ball away on third down instead of taking a sack, which would have kept the clock running. The incompletion essentially gave the Broncos a free timeout and allowed them to drive down the field for a game-winning field goal in the closing seconds. The loss snapped a six-game winning streak for the Bolts. They'll try to get back in the win column next week against the Cardinals.
report: Philip Rivers completed 28-of-43 passes for 401 yards with two touchdowns and two interceptions while losing four yards on his lone carry Sunday in the Chargers' Week 11 loss to the Broncos.

impact: His 64 yards tied Julio Jones for the team lead, while Ridley scored the Falcons' first touchdown through the air from 11 yards out, beating fellow rookie CB Donte Jackson.  Ridley put up a goose egg on two targets in the opener, but coach Dan Quinn said he wanted Ridley more involved, and OC Steve Sarkisian made it happen.  His five targets were three more than Mohamed Sanu for second on the team behind Jones (nine).  Ridley is worth watching on the waiver and perhaps nabbing in 12- and 14-team leagues as a WR4/5 ahead of Week 3 against New Orleans.
report: Calvin Ridley caught 4-of-5 targets for 64 yards and one touchdown in the Falcons' Week 2 win over the Panthers.

impact: This won’t happen every week, but on Sunday, Ridley was the better of Atlanta’s two Alabama receivers. Ridley went absolutely hog-wild in the first half, cruising to 129 yards and two touchdowns including a 75-yard jailbreak in the second quarter. The rookie embarrassed P.J. Williams to such an extent that he was actually benched for Ken Crawley for a portion of the second half. In addition to his three touchdowns (the same number teammate Julio Jones had all of last season), Ridley also drew a pass interference flag that moved the Falcons up 45 yards in the third quarter. After seeing just two looks from Matt Ryan in the opener, the 23-year-old has been the recipient of 13 targets over his last two outings. He’ll be an acceptable WR3/flex option against the Bengals next week and needs to be picked up in all formats.
report: Calvin Ridley corralled seven-of-eight targets for 146 yards and three touchdowns while gaining nine yards on his lone carry Sunday in the Falcons’ Week 3 loss to the Saints.

impact: Ridley disappointingly saw just six targets, but he made the most of his work. His first touchdown was a good slant route to give Matt Ryan a throwing window, and he cooked Dre Kirkpatrick on a double move for a 30-yard score in the fourth quarter. The two scores made him the first rookie receiver in NFL history to have six touchdowns in his first four games. Ridley seeing three fewer targets than Mohamed Sanu is a bit of a concern, but he is a highly-talented receiver getting consistent work in a red-hot passing attack. He will be an upside WR3 in a great matchup against the Steelers next week.
report: Calvin Ridley hauled in 4-of-6 targets for 54 yards and two touchdowns in the Falcons' Week 4 loss to the Bengals.

impact: It was Ridley's first game without a score since Week 1. Ridley, who leads the Falcons in red zone looks, did draw a target from the Steelers' 21-yard line. Ridley will remain a solid WR3 for next week's matchup with the Bucs' awful defense.
report: Calvin Ridley caught 4-of-5 targets for 38 yards in the Falcons' Week 5 loss to the Steelers.

impact: Ridley's ankle didn't seem to be a problem at all.  His six targets were second-most on the team to Julio Jones' 12, but Ridley was unable to do anything big with them.  Ridley will get the bye week to get back to 100 percent ahead of a Week 9 road date with the Redskins where he'll again be a WR2/3.
report: Calvin Ridley caught 5-of-6 targets for 43 yards in the Falcons' Week 7 win over the Giants.

impact: Ridley's ankle didn't seem to be a problem at all.  His six targets were second-most on the team to Julio Jones' 12, but Ridley was unable to do anything big with them.  Ridley will get the bye week to get back to 100 percent ahead of a Week 9 road date with the Redskins where he'll again be a WR2/3.
report: Calvin Ridley caught 5-of-6 targets for 43 yards in the Falcons' Week 7 win over the Giants.

impact: Ridley got checked for a concussion late in the game, but returned.  His touchdown came on a crossing route from 40 yards out with multiple big downfield blocks via Mohamed Sanu.  Ridley's week-to-week target volume has not been bankable, but he has clearly passed Sanu as Atlanta's No. 2 passing-game option.  Keep Ridley rolling as a WR2/3 in Week 10 at Cleveland.
report: Calvin Ridley caught 6-of-9 targets for 71 yards and a touchdown in Atlanta's Week 9 win at Washington.

impact: The five targets were a major disappointment on a day where Matt Ryan attempted 52 passes. Through nine games, Ridley is still averaging just five weekly looks. That would barely be WR3 usable if not for Ridley's red zone usage. The Falcons are hosting the Cowboys for Week 11.
report: Calvin Ridley caught 3-of-5 targets for 37 yards in the Falcons' Week 10 loss to the Browns, adding a three-yard rush.

impact: The one missed connection was a drop by Ridley that popped into the air for an interception deep in Atlanta territory that led to a Cowboys touchdown.  Ridley has just one touchdown since September and has topped 50 yards only once since Week 4.  Ridley gets the Saints in a likely shootout on Thanksgiving.  Ridley eviscerated the Saints in Week 3 for a 7-146-3 line.
report: Calvin Ridley caught 3-of-4 targets for 32 yards in the Falcons' Week 11 loss to the Cowboys.

impact: Richardson added a two-yard rush. Richardson's score came as he got loose at the back of the end zone as Alex Smith scrambled around for time. The high-dollar free agent addition has 13 catches for 212 yards through five games as a Redskin. That's not going to cut it in fantasy leagues.
report: Paul Richardson caught 3-of-5 targets for 31 yards and a touchdown in the Redskins' Week 6 win over the Panthers.

impact: With Alex Smith at quarterback, none of Washington's perimeter pass catchers have fantasy value in a low-volume passing attack.
report: Paul Richardson caught 2-of-5 targets for 34 yards in Washington's Week 8 win over the Giants.

impact: He saw an end-zone target in fourth-quarter garbage time but Alex Smith's pass was essentially uncatchable in heavy traffic.  Richardson has been a complete dud in fantasy, yet next week's matchup with Tampa Bay will at least put him on the WR4/flex radar.
report: Paul Richardson caught 2-of-6 targets for 16 yards in Washington's Week 9 loss to the Falcons.

impact: Filling in for Brandin Cooks and Cooper Kupp, who both left the game with concussions, Reynolds came out hot following halftime. He had a 22-yard catch on the second offensive play of the half, a 17-yard grab the next play, and he rushed for 10 yards the play after that. He did not touch the ball again the rest of the game, but Reynolds is a talented young receiver who might be forced into playing time with Cooks and Kupp questionable.
