He should be added in most formats.
report: Josh Reynolds hauled in 2-of-3 targets for 39 yards and rushed once for 10 yards in the Rams' Week 5 win over the Seahawks.

impact: The story of Reynolds' Week 6 was Cooper Kupp's knee injury. It appeared Kupp's season was over before he miraculously returned for the second half (and barely played). Provided Kupp continues to get good news, Reynolds will remain on the outside looking in of fantasy value for Week 7 against the 49ers.
report: Josh Reynolds caught 1-of-2 targets for -2 yards in the Rams' Week 6 win over the Broncos.

impact: Even with Cooper Kupp sidelined, Reynolds did not see a big boost. He did set up a touchdown with a 19-yard catch down to the one-yard line in the third quarter, but that was his only involvement. Even with uncertainty about Kupp’s availability, Reynolds can be sent back to the wire.
report: Josh Reynolds caught his only target for 19 yards in the Rams' Week 7 win over the 49ers.

impact: Even with Cooper Kupp sidelined, Reynolds did not see a big boost. He did set up a touchdown with a 19-yard catch down to the one-yard line in the third quarter, but that was his only involvement. Even with uncertainty about Kupp’s availability, Reynolds can be sent back to the wire.
report: Josh Reynolds caught his only target for 19 yards in the Rams' Week 7 win over the 49ers.

impact: With the Packers doing an excellent job on Brandin Cooks and Robert Woods, Reynolds was open at critical moments. The scores were just the second and third of Reynolds' career, and first of 2018. Even if Cooper Kupp (knee) remains sidelined for Week 9, Reynolds won't be a recommended fill-in option against the Saints.
report: Josh Reynolds caught 3-of-5 targets for 42 yards and two touchdowns in the Rams' Week 8 win over the Packers.

impact: The sixth-round pick from Texas A&M was forced to step up into a large role in the Cleveland passing game with all of the injuries the Browns have sustained at the wide receiver position. His productive game came in game in which Jarvis Landry caught just two passes, so it should be taken with some degree of salt. That said, the Browns will still be without Rishard Higgins for a the short term and Antonio Callaway has proven to be an unreliable option. Ratley is only an option in the deepest of leagues, but the Browns face a terrible Tampa Bay defense on the road in Week 7 for those that must dig that deep.
report: Damion Ratley caught 6-of-8 targets for 82 yards in Sunday's Week 6 loss to the Chargers.

impact: The sixth-round pick from Texas A&M was forced to step up into a large role in the Cleveland passing game with all of the injuries the Browns have sustained at the wide receiver position. His productive game came in game in which Jarvis Landry caught just two passes, so it should be taken with some degree of salt. That said, the Browns will still be without Rishard Higgins for a the short term and Antonio Callaway has proven to be an unreliable option. Ratley is only an option in the deepest of leagues, but the Browns face a terrible Tampa Bay defense on the road in Week 7 for those that must dig that deep.
report: Damion Ratley caught 6-of-8 targets for 82 yards in Sunday's Week 6 loss to the Chargers.

impact: All four catches came in the first half, including a four-yard touchdown grab with eight seconds remaining in the second quarter. That marked Reed’s first end-zone visit since Week 7 of last year, when he broke out for two touchdowns in a loss to Philadelphia. Reed likely would have done more damage had this been a competitive game, but with Washington running circles around the overmatched Cardinals, there was no reason to air it out in the second half. Finally healthy (knock on wood) after an injury-plagued 2017 campaign, the former Florida Gator is safe to pencil in as a TE1 next week in a mouth-watering matchup against the Colts.
report: Jordan Reed corralled four-of-five targets for 48 yards and a touchdown Sunday in the Redskins’ Week 1 win over the Cardinals.

impact: He went most of the first half without drawing a target, finally getting a look from Alex Smith with six minutes to go in the second quarter. Reed came through with five catches for 51 yards after halftime but also committed a costly fumble in the fourth quarter that essentially handed Indy the game. The 28-year-old has always been a productive player when healthy and that should continue to be the case next week when the Redskins host Green Bay at FedEx Field.
report: Jordan Reed handled six-of-eight targets for 55 yards Sunday in the Redskins’ Week 2 loss to the Colts.

impact: It was a strong statline on an afternoon where Alex Smith completed just 12 passes. Reed's yardage has now gone up each week, though he has not scored since Week 1. He will have a great shot at rectifying that in Week 5 against the Saints. New Orleans' defense has given back all the gains it made in 2017.
report: Jordan Reed caught 4-of-7 targets for 65 yards in the Redskins' Week 3 win over the Packers.

impact: The Panthers are a gorgeous matchup for opposing tight ends, but it was Vernon Davis who took advantage for a wide-open touchdown. Reed did lead the team in targets on a quiet day for Alex Smith. Reed is averaging a modest weekly 4/45 through his first five games, but his usage has remained that of a TE1. There should be big games to come.
report: Jordan Reed caught 5-of-9 targets for 36 yards in the Redskins' Week 6 win over the Panthers.

impact: The good news is Reed's 43 yards were a team-high. The bad news is Reed's 43 yards were a team-high. It's easy to say he's a TE1 based on past performance, but that feeling is beginning to waiver with his third consecutive game under 50 yards. He also has yet to eclipse 70 yards in a single outing this season. His usage remains that of a TE1, so owners are still advised to hang tight and hope to weather the storm.
report: Jordan Reed caught 2-of-4 targets for 43 yards in the Redskins' Week 7 win over the Cowboys.

impact: This was usable PPR production, but the Skins have been able to get nothing going to Reed on throws down the field, leading to poor yardage outputs each week.  Nevertheless, Reed should stay locked into fantasy lineups versus Atlanta's injury-ruined defense in Week 9.
report: Jordan Reed caught 7-of-12 targets for 38 yards in Washington's Week 8 win over the Giants.

impact: He's now finished below 40 receiving yards in five straight games.  Reed had an early catch negated by a penalty, then was kept quiet in a game where Alex Smith completed passes to nine different players and targeted only Maurice Harris (12) more than six times.  Reed still looks like a plus athlete on the field, but his rapport with Smith remains a work in progress even after eight games.  Reed draws a best-case-scenario matchup at Tampa Bay next.
report: Jordan Reed caught 4-of-6 targets for 34 yards in Washington's Week 9 loss to the Falcons.

impact: Reed's six targets led the team while his yards were one behind Maurice Harris for the Redskins' high.  Reed has remained healthy all season but has shown zero upside in the Alex Smith-led offense.  He gets the Texans in Week 11.
report: Jordan Reed caught 4-of-6 targets for 51 yards in the Redskins' Week 10 win over the Bucs.

impact: Reed caught just his second touchdown of the season on Colt McCoy's first throw of Sunday's game.  McCoy replaced Alex Smith, who is almost certainly out for the year with a Theismannian leg injury.  (Joe Theismann himself compared Smith's probable leg fracture to his.)  Reed's 11 targets were easily a team high.  Reed will remain a quality TE1 when Washington faces Dallas on Thanksgiving.
report: Jordan Reed caught 7-of-11 targets for 71 yards and a touchdown in the Redskins' Week 11 loss to Houston.

impact: The Jaguars started Corey Grant, but he managed 10 yards on seven touches and Yeldon showed the hotter hand.  In a game where Jacksonville's passing attack was almost entirely nonexistent, Yeldon led the team in receiving yards.  Leonard Fournette (hamstring) is tentatively due back for Week 4 against the Jets, which would render Yeldon and Grant useless as fantasy options.
report: T.J. Yeldon rushed seven times for 44 yards and caught 6-of-7 targets for 46 yards in the Jaguars' Week 3 loss to Tennessee.

impact: Yeldon replaced an injured Leonard Fournette in the second quarter.  He went untouched on a 31-yard screen for his first touchdown, and added a one-yard goal-line TD in mopup time. With Fournette dealing with a setback, Yeldon could be in line for another start this week. He'll be a plug-and-play RB2 if Fournette sits.
report: T.J. Yeldon had 18 carries for 52 yards and a touchdown and caught three passes for 48 yards and a receiving touchdown in Week 4 against the Jets.

impact: With Corey Grant exiting early, it was all Yeldon in this one. He looked great early in the game, consistently gaining big yardage on the ground. That stopped with the Jaguars down big in the second half, but he kept things going in the passing game. He caught Blake Bortles' only touchdown pass when he easily beat a linebacker on a wheel route from 14 yards out. With Leonard Fournette looking doubtful for Week 6, Yeldon will be a high-end RB2 against the Cowboys.
report: T.J. Yeldon rushed 10 times for 53 yards and hauled in 8-of-10 targets for 69 yards and a touchdown in the Jaguars' Week 5 loss to the Chiefs.

impact: Yeldon never had a chance with Jacksonville playing from behind almost the entire game. With the Jags in catch-up mode, Yeldon saw just three carries in the second half. The 25-year-old has served as Jacksonville's workhorse during Leonard Fournette's absence. If Fournette (hamstring) can't get the green light in Week 7, Yeldon would draw another start against Houston.
report: T.J. Yeldon contributed just 41 yards on eight carries while turning five targets into three catches for 29 yards Sunday in Jacksonville’s Week 6 loss to the Cowboys.

impact: Yeldon operated as Jacksonville’s feature back for one last week; Carlos Hyde will likely take over as the Jags’ primary ball carrier in Week 8 against the Eagles in London. Yeldon should continue to dominate passing-game work until Leonard Fournette (hamstring) returns, but he has devolved from an every-week RB2 to a low-end flex option going forward.
report: T.J. Yeldon rushed 12 times for 28 yards and caught 5-of-7 targets for 40 yards and a touchdown in the Jaguars’ Week 7 loss to Houston.

impact: Yeldon operated as Jacksonville’s feature back for one last week; Carlos Hyde will likely take over as the Jags’ primary ball carrier in Week 8 against the Eagles in London. Yeldon should continue to dominate passing-game work until Leonard Fournette (hamstring) returns, but he has devolved from an every-week RB2 to a low-end flex option going forward.
report: T.J. Yeldon rushed 12 times for 28 yards and caught 5-of-7 targets for 40 yards and a touchdown in the Jaguars’ Week 7 loss to Houston.

impact: As we saw last week when the Browns listed Duke Johnson as the starter over Nick Chubb, these designations mean little. That said, Yeldon is not going to disappear even with Carlos Hyde ready to make his debut, especially in a matchup which favors the pass. Both Yeldon and Hyde are risky FLEX options this week.
report: Jaguars listed T.J. Yeldon as the starter in place of Leonard Fournette for Week 8 against the Eagles.

impact: With the running game going nowhere, Yeldon was the only back who made anything happen early, although 15 of his 18 first-half receiving yards came on a third-and-long screen. He was even more involved after the Jaguars opened up the passing game in the second half, however, and he set up a field goal with a 37-yard catch on a wheel route in the fourth quarter. His 83 receiving yards actually led the team on Sunday. Leonard Fournette is expected back after the bye, but Yeldon should keep at least some of his role in the passing game.
report: T.J. Yeldon hauled in 7-of-9 targets for 83 yards and rushed twice for seven yards in the Jaguars' Week 8 loss to the Eagles.

impact: Yeldon was an afterthought for most of the game with Leonard Fournette back healthy. His only carry of the first half came on a give-up third down, and his two catches came during the two-minute drive. He did add a couple long receptions late, but his touch total will be difficult to predict as long as Fournette is healthy.
report: T.J. Yeldon rushed three times for 12 yards and hauled in 5-of-6 targets for 51 yards in the Jaguars' Week 10 loss to the Colts.

impact: Yeldon has now touched the ball seven and eight times since Leonard Fournette returned to the lineup. He only has marginal value when the Jaguars are chasing points, something they can't be counted on in Week 12 at Buffalo.
report: T.J. Yeldon rushed five times for 23 yards while catching 2-of-3 targets for nine yards in Sunday's Week 11 loss to the Steelers.

impact: His seven targets were tied for third on the team behind A.J. Green and Tyler Boyd, confirming Uzomah's place as a key piece of the offense without Tyler Eifert (leg, I.R.).  Uzomah will remain a TE1 streamer next week against the Chiefs.  Tyler Kroft was in a walking boot this week with a foot injury.
report: C.J. Uzomah caught 6-of-7 targets for 54 yards in the Bengals' Week 6 loss to the Steelers.

impact: Uzomah caught Andy Dalton's only touchdown on a play that capped off a 77-yard second quarter drive. It was his only notable play of the night. Uzomah has been a plug-and-play TE1 since Tyler Eifert went down. He has a plus matchup with the Bucs in Week 8.
report: C.J. Uzomah caught two passes for 13 yards and a touchdown in Week 7 against the Chiefs.

impact: Uzomah tweaked his shoulder early in the game on an injury that looked like a stinger, and he was a non-factor the rest of the way.  Uzomah has flirted with TE1 viability this year, but he isn't a must-hold during Cincy's Week 9 bye.
report: C.J. Uzomah went catch-less on four targets in the Bengals' Week 8 win.

impact: With A.J. Green out of the lineup, there was hope that Uzomah would have a larger role in the Bengals offense, but that didn't happen. Uzomah now has three of fewer catches in every game but one on the season and has just five catches for 36 yards over his past three games. Uzomah is a low-level TE2 as the Bengals head to Baltimore in Week 11.
report: C.J. Uzomah caught 3-of-4 targets for 23 yards in Sunday's Week 10 loss to the Saints.

impact: Despite the losses of A.J. Green (toe) and Tyler Eifert (ankle), Uzomah has barely been playable in fantasy leagues.  He will remain a low-floor streamer when the Bengals host the Browns next.
report: C.J. Uzomah caught 3-of-5 targets for 41 yards in the Bengals' Week 11 loss to the Ravens.

impact: With Randall Cobb (hamstring) and Geronimo Allison (concussion) inactive, Valdes-Scantling and fellow rookie Equanimeous St. Brown got the starts next to Davante Adams. MVS scored a three-yard touchdown on the opening drive of the third quarter after the Packers were shut out in the first two frames, and he had a second touchdown called back as it was ruled he was down at the half-yard line. Lance Kendricks scored the next play.  Valdes-Scantling's 10 targets were third on the team behind Adams (12) and Jimmy Graham (11).  Allison will likely be back Week 6, but Cobb may have a multi-week injury.  Once both are back, MVS will be irrelevant in redraft leagues.
report: Marquez Valdes-Scantling caught 7-of-10 targets for 68 yards and one touchdown in the Packers' Week 5 loss to the Lions.

impact: Randall Cobb and Geronimo Allison were both back from injury, but Valdes-Scantling remained heavily involved. He out-targeted Allison 5-1, though Pro Football Focus charted the two in a snap dead heat. MVS' score came after he beat press coverage on the inside on a go route. Even with the jumbled picture behind Davante Adams, MVS remains worth holding onto as an upside WR5 in fantasy.
report: Marquez Valdes-Scantling caught 2-of-5 targets for 45 yards and a touchdown in the Packers' Week 8 loss to the Rams.

impact: Valdes-Scantling led the Packers in receiving despite getting shutout in the first half. He got most of his yardage on a pair of impressive contested catches late in the third quarter. The Patriots shadowed Valdes-Scantling with Stephon Gilmore after that, but this is another encouraging game. Valdes-Scantling has over 100 yards or a touchdown in four straight weeks. He's locked in as the starter opposite Davante Adams for the rest of the season.
report: Marquez Valdes-Scantling caught 3-of-6 targets for 101 yards in Week 9 against the Patriots.

impact: Aaron Jones' breakout 15/145/2 performance overshadowed (and took away from) the Packers' passing game altogether on Sunday. MVS actually tied Davante Adams (4/57/2) with a team-high seven targets, but Adams was the primary beneficiary since two of his catches hit pay dirt. Rodgers clearly trusts the rookie, though, and he'll undoubtedly have much better performances when game script calls for it. Even when Cobb returns, consider Valdes-Scantling a high-end WR3 the rest of the way.
report: Marquez Valdes-Scantling caught 6-of-7 targets for 44 yards in the Packers' Week 10 romping of the Dolphins.

impact: Trubisky had a solid first half before fizzling over the final two quarters. His only touchdown was a designed run at the goal-line, with the rest of his rushng coming on broken play scrambles. Trubisky had a good rapport with Allen Robinson, who lead the team in receiving. It's a step in the right direction for Trubisky after a rough rookie season, but there's not a ton to get excited about with his Year 2 outlook.
report: Mitchell Trubisky completed 23-of-35 passes for 171 yards in Sunday night's Week 1 loss to the Packers, adding seven carries for 32 yards and a rushing touchdown.

impact: It's been a disgusting start to the season for the sophomore, who is averaging a pitiful 5.4 YPA on his first 69 attempts.  Only Sam Bradford's 4.0 YPA mark has been worse among qualified quarterbacks.  Trubisky should have had a third interception in the end zone at the end of the first half, but CB Justin Coleman flat-out dropped it.  Trubisky's first pick was a terribly underthrown sideline shot to Allen Robinson, while the other was a ball batted at the line of scrimmage.  The touchdowns were a three-yard shovel pass to Trey Burton and an off-balance, 10-yarder to Anthony Miller.  Trubisky flashes upside at rare times but mostly plays wildly inaccurate with a tendency to run.  He's one of the worst fantasy quarterbacks and won't be on the radar next week in Arizona, even against that horrendous defense.
report: Mitchell Trubisky completed 25-of-34 passes for 200 yards, two touchdowns, and two interceptions in the Bears' Week 2 win over the Seahawks.

impact: Trubisky also rushed twice for eight yards, losing a fumble on a scramble. He played with fire on multiple occasions, throwing a few would-be interceptions had defenders secured the ball. Trubisky has now averaged just 5.7 yards per pass attempt through three games and has struggled to connect on anything down the field. The silver lining is that his yards per pass attempt have risen in each game, but Trubisky and the Bears are indeed not the second coming of Sean McVay and Jared Goff if the opening three weeks are any indication of the rest of the season.
report: Mitchell Trubisky completed 24-of-35 passes for 220 yards with one interception in Sunday's Week 3 win over the Cardinals.

impact: He also led the team with 53 yards rushing. Trubisky came only one-score short of tying the NFL record for most touchdown passes in a single game. It was the perfect storm for the second-year pro, who not only found milk carton candidates Trey Burton (2-86-1) and Tarik Cohen (7-121-1 receiving), but who was also helped by the Bucs' ineptitude on defense. Even Taylor Gabriel was involved in Chicago's efforts Sunday, recording a career-high 104 receiving yards and two scores. This can't possibly be expected from Trubisky moving forward, but it's certainly a positive that his yards per attempt have increased in every outing this season. Matt Nagy's offense should continue developing and clicking against the Dolphins after the bye.
report: Mitchell Trubisky completed 19-of-26 passes for 354 yards and six touchdowns in the Bears' Week 4 win over the Buccaneers.

impact: He was dropped for two sacks, which resulted in a loss of 13 yards. Trubisky has now thrown for nine touchdown passes over his last two outings, the same number he had in his first 15 starts. The 2017 first-rounder did almost all of his damage after halftime, throwing for 222 yards on 12-of-16 passing in the second half. Trubisky was far from perfect—he was bailed out on a handful of spectacular catches (the most absurd of the bunch coming on a 47-yard deep heave to Taylor Gabriel in the second quarter) and was intercepted in the end zone on a pass he never should have thrown. But for fantasy purposes, the 24-year-old has done just fine. We'll see how he fares when the Bears host New England in Week 7.
report: Mitchell Trubisky completed 22-of-31 passes for 316 yards with three touchdowns and one interception while adding 47 yards on eight carries Sunday in the Bears’ Week 6 loss to Miami.

impact: Trubisky was just 8-for-20 in the first half, but he also made important plays in big spots including a Hail Mary which fell just inches short on the final play. He converted two third downs early in the game on scrambles, and he did even better on the third drive, making the Patriots pay for a fumble on a spectacular "eight-yard" touchdown scramble in which he escaped several defenders in the backfield. He continued to hurt the Patriots with his legs early in the second half, scrambling for 39 yards down to the one-yard line on the opening touchdown drive. The scrambles eventually dried up, however, and Trubisky struggled to get anything going down the field. His risky throws caught up to him on an interception near the end of the third quarter, and he was picked again early in the fourth on an underthrown pass. He did find Trey Burton for a touchdown late and connected on the Hail Mary, but this was not a good showing. He will look to rebound next week against the Jets.
report: Mitchell Trubisky completed 26-of-50 attempts for 333 yards, two touchdowns, and two interceptions in the Bears' Week 7 loss to the Patriots, adding 81 yards and a touchdown on six carries.

impact: Treadwell dropped his first target of the day on a third down, earning boos from the home crowd.  But he later answered with a nice 16-yard grab where he picked up some YAC and ran through an arm tackle.  Treadwell is unlikely to have any fantasy appeal unless Adam Thielen or Stefon Diggs gets hurt.
report: Laquon Treadwell caught 2-of-4 targets for 18 yards in the Vikings' Week 1 win over the 49ers.

impact: The day started out well for Treadwell, who caught the first touchdown of his career -- really -- in the first quarter. It was downhill from there, however. He dropped what would have been a third-down conversion in the third quarter, and he almost sabotaged the comeback attempt by letting a pass go right through his hands and into a DB's in the fourth quarter. He also ran the wrong route and dropped another pass in overtime. It would not be surprising if his playing time is scaled back moving forward.
report: Laquon Treadwell hauled in 2-of-6 targets for 23 yards and a touchdown in the Vikings' Week 2 tie with the Packers.

impact: Still reeling from hauling in his first career touchdown in Week 2, Treadwell reverted back to being the Vikings' fourth option in their passing game. Had Minnesota not been trailing 27-0 to start the second half, it's a wonder whether he would have even been asked to play all that much. With Adam Thielen (14-105 Sunday), Kyle Rudolph (5-48-1), and Stefon Diggs (4-17) locked into primary roles, Treadwell's good weeks will be far and few between.
report: Laquon Treadwell hauled in all four of his targets for 33 yards in the Vikings' Week 3 loss to the Bills.

impact: A whopping 10 of Thompson’s career-high 13 receptions came after halftime with the Redskins playing from behind. Obviously Thompson had little success as a ball-carrier in this one but he was incredibly efficient as a pass-catcher, hauling in all but one of his 14 targets from Alex Smith. Through two games Thompson has shown zero ill effects from last year’s broken leg and already has the look of a PPR monster. He’ll be a flex consideration against the Packers in Week 3.
report: Chris Thompson rushed for just one yard on four carries but made up for that lack of production by snagging 13 catches for a team-leading 92 yards on 14 targets Sunday in the Redskins’ Week 2 loss to the Colts.

impact: Thompson stunningly drew just two targets on an afternoon where Alex Smith attempted only 20 passes. The Redskins' offense did not have to do much with the Packers making one mistake after another. Thompson should immediately bounce back when the Redskins come off bye against the Saints in Week 5.
report: Chris Thompson rushed six times for 17 yards in the Redskins' Week 3 win over the Packers, gaining zero yards on his lone reception.

impact: Thompson had to leave the game late in the fourth quarter with a ribs injury after Alex Smith threw him a hospital ball at the goal line on a two-point conversion attempt following a Kapri Bibbs rushing score.  The Redskins never got the ball back, and Thompson was announced as questionable to return.  Thompson was very good the first two weeks of the season but has managed just 34 rushing yards and 45 yards through the air on 21 scoreless touches the last two games.  He'll look to rebound next week at home against the Panthers as an RB3 if healthy.
report: Chris Thompson rushed eight times for 17 yards and caught 6-of-8 targets for 45 yards in the Redskins' Week 5 loss to the Saints.

impact: With Dalvin Cook (hamstring) still sidelined, Thomas got a shot as the Vikes' No. 2 back behind Latavius Murray. He drew a red zone target and goal line carry. Perhaps the Jacksonville State UDFA is worth an add in the deepest of Dynasty leagues.
report: Roc Thomas rushed four times for eight yards in the Vikings' Week 5 win over the Eagles, adding a six-yard reception.

impact: With Dalvin Cook (hamstring) still sidelined, Thomas got a shot as the Vikes' No. 2 back behind Latavius Murray. He drew a red zone target and goal line carry. Perhaps the Jacksonville State UDFA is worth an add in the deepest of Dynasty leagues.
report: Roc Thomas rushed four times for eight yards in the Vikings' Week 5 win over the Eagles, adding a six-yard reception.

impact: Both targets came with Dallas playing from behind in the second half. The fact that Thompson, a 29-year-old, undrafted journeyman, is playing significant snaps shows how desperate the Cowboys are for pass-catching help. Thompson can be left on the waiver wire for next week’s matchup against the Lions.
report: Deonte Thompson nabbed both of his targets for 23 yards Sunday in the Cowboys’ Week 3 loss to Seattle.

impact: Both targets came with Dallas playing from behind in the second half. The fact that Thompson, a 29-year-old, undrafted journeyman, is playing significant snaps shows how desperate the Cowboys are for pass-catching help. Thompson can be left on the waiver wire for next week’s matchup against the Lions.
report: Deonte Thompson nabbed both of his targets for 23 yards Sunday in the Cowboys’ Week 3 loss to Seattle.

impact: It was a balanced effort for Thomas, who recorded exactly eight catches for 90 yards in both halves. Thomas capped the second quarter with a six-yard touchdown grab on a play where the Bucs left him completely open. He nearly scored again in the fourth quarter, but was stopped just short of the goal line. Even at full strength the Bucs would have had a hard time defending Thomas, but with Brent Grimes (groin) out and Vernon Hargreaves exiting in the second half, Tampa Bay’s weakened secondary didn’t have a prayer. The third-year stud should stuff the stat sheet again in next week’s home matchup against the Browns.
report: Michael Thomas delivered a team-record 16 catches for 180 yards and a touchdown on 17 targets Sunday in the Saints’ Week 1 loss to the Buccaneers.

impact: Thomas did lose a fumble for the second straight game, but that was his only blemish on a nearly perfect day. Thomas scored both of the Saints' touchdowns, catching a 2-yard score in the third quarter to pull the Saints within a score and then catching a 5-yard touchdown over Denzel Ward to give New Orleans a lead with 2:40 left in the fourth quarter. Thomas now has reeled in 28 receptions through two weeks, which is the most for any player through two weeks in NFL history. Thomas will be a set and forget WR1 option next week when the Saints head to Atlanta.
report: Michael Thomas caught 12-of-13 targets for 89 yards and two touchdowns in Sunday's Week 2 win over the Browns.

impact: Thomas set the tone with a 35-yard gain on the Saints’ first play from scrimmage. He never managed to find the end zone but was always there when Drew Brees needed him. Thomas played a pivotal role in overtime, moving the chains with three catches for 38 yards on the game-clinching drive. Sunday’s 10-spot gives Thomas 38 catches for the year, an NFL record through the first three games. He’s also been incredibly efficient, absorbing an impossible 95 percent of his targets this year. Even with Janoris Jenkins likely to shadow him in Week 4, the red-hot Thomas will remain an appealing WR1 against the Giants.
report: Michael Thomas pulled in all 10 of his targets for 129 receiving yards Sunday in the Saints’ Week 3 victory over Atlanta.

impact: Thomas tallied at least 10 catches and/or one touchdown in each of the first three games entering Sunday.  His four targets were tied with Cameron Meredith for second on the team behind Alvin Kamara's nine, and Drew Brees didn't throw a single touchdown as Kamara rushed for three.  Thomas should bounce back no problem back at home against the Redskins in Week 5.
report: Michael Thomas caught all four of his targets for 47 yards in the Saints' Week 4 win over the Giants.

impact: After seeing 40 combined targets Weeks 1-3, Thomas has been targeted a total of nine times the past two weeks and hasn't scored in either game.  He was obviously never going to continue at that ridiculous three-week pace, but there are so many talented players in this offense with the emergence of Tre'Quan Smith (3-111-2 tonight) and return of Mark Ingram that the Saints can spread the ball around.  Thomas will get a difficult matchup on the road against the Ravens in Week 7 when the Saints come off their bye.
report: Michael Thomas caught 4-of-5 targets for 74 yards in the Saints' Week 5 win over the Redskins.

impact: The catches were Thomas' most since Week 3, while the score was his first since Week 2. Surprisingly, Thomas has failed to clear 10 targets or 75 yards in each of his past three games. He has a tough Week 8 matchup in Xavier Rhodes and the Vikings, though Rhodes could end up missing the game with an ankle injury.
report: Michael Thomas caught 7-of-9 targets for 69 yards and a touchdown in the Saints' Week 7 win over the Ravens.

impact: The catches were Thomas' most since Week 3, while the score was his first since Week 2. Surprisingly, Thomas has failed to clear 10 targets or 75 yards in each of his past three games. He has a tough Week 8 matchup in Xavier Rhodes and the Vikings, though Rhodes could end up missing the game with an ankle injury.
report: Michael Thomas caught 7-of-9 targets for 69 yards and a touchdown in the Saints' Week 7 win over the Ravens.

impact: Thomas got over half his yards on a 44-yard catch from Taysom Hill on the opening drive. He fell victim to gameflow in the second half with the Saints going run heavy. Thomas has at least 70 yards or a touchdown in 6-of-7 games this year. He'll remain a WR1 for Week 9's matchup with the Rams.
report: Michael Thomas caught 5-of-6 targets for 81 yards in the Saints' Week 8 win over the Vikings.

impact: Thomas has been nearly unstoppable all season, and it was not any different in this game. He got things started with a great contested catch for 12 yards against Marcus Peters, who shadowed him to absolutely no success, and just made play after play after that. He finished the first half with six catches for 69 yards on eight targets, was at 10 catches for 121 yards at the end of the third quarter despite the offense falling into a bit of a lull, and iced the game by burning Peters for a 72-yard touchdown with four minutes left in the fourth. That catch broke the Saints’ single-game record for receiving yards and featured a great callback to Joe Horn's cell phone celebration, flip phone and all. Halfway through the season, Thomas is on pace for 140 catches with an absurd 88.6 catch rate. He will be a must-start next week in Cincinnati.
report: Michael Thomas hauled in 12-of-15 targets for 211 yards and a touchdown in the Saints' Week 9 win over the Rams.

impact: Thomas got the game started with a 7-yard touchdown on the opening drive and then added a 17-yard strike with two seconds left in the first half to put the Saints up 35-7 at the break. Thomas is on his way to having the most efficient receiving season in NFL history. Through nine games, Thomas has reeled in 78-of-87 targets on the season with seven touchdowns. Thomas gets the Eagles at home in Week 11.
report: Michael Thomas caught all eight of his targets for 70 yards and two touchdowns in Sunday's Week 10 win over the Bengals.

impact: With Tre’Quan Smith dominating, Thomas was limited to just four targets, but he made the most of them. He got loose for two long gains on each of his two first-half catches, the second of which put him over 1,000 yards for the season. He did even better after the break, coming down with a pinpoint throw from Drew Brees for a 23-yard touchdown, his eighth of the season and fifth in the last five games. By catching all four of his targets, Thomas once again bumped up above a 90 percent catch rate for the year. He will remain a no-doubt WR1 on Thanksgiving against the Falcons.
report: Michael Thomas caught all four of his targets for 92 yards and a touchdown in the Saints' Week 11 win over the Eagles.

impact: Thomas and Chris Manhertz split tight end duties without Greg Olsen (foot) in the lineup.  Thomas' lone misconnection was a brutal drop of a would-be 17-yard touchdown.  He rebounded to catch a ball on third down on the same series to set up Torrey Smith's three-yard score.  Thomas is not a fantasy starter.
report: Ian Thomas caught 2-of-3 targets for 10 yards in the Panthers' Week 2 loss to the Falcons.

impact: Thomas continued to play a ton of snaps in Greg Olsen's (foot) absence, but still isn't doing much with them.  Over the last two weeks, Thomas has 30 scoreless yards on eight targets.  He is a TE2/3 entering Carolina's Week 4 bye.
report: Ian Thomas caught 3-of-5 targets for 20 yards in the Panthers' Week 3 win over the Bengals.

impact: Thomas continued to play a ton of snaps in Greg Olsen's (foot) absence, but still isn't doing much with them.  Over the last two weeks, Thomas has 30 scoreless yards on eight targets.  He is a TE2/3 entering Carolina's Week 4 bye.
report: Ian Thomas caught 3-of-5 targets for 20 yards in the Panthers' Week 3 win over the Bengals.

impact: Thomas now has three touchdowns in two weeks. Without Keke Coutee (hamstring) available in the slot, the Texans primarily leaned on multiple tight end sets, allowing Thomas to stay on the field with Ryan Griffin. Thomas still only saw one target on the day, though, so he need not be considered a viable option unless Griffin sits out again.
report: TE Jordan Thomas hauled in his only target for a touchdown in the Texans' Week 9 win over the Broncos.

impact: Taylor added 77 yards and a touchdown rushing on eight carries to make up for a nondescript passing performance in the heavy rain. His fantasy day is a reminder that even when Taylor is a lackluster passing option, he's still a high-floor fantasy option due to his rushing ability. Taylor will be a popular streaming option Week 2 against the Saints.
report: Browns QB Tyrod Taylor completed 15-of-40 passes for 197 yards with one touchdown and one interception in Sunday's Week 1 game versus the Steelers.

impact: Taylor added 26 yards rushing on four attempts. Taylor was largely nondescript for the majority of Sunday, but connected on a 47-yard bomb to Antonio Callaway that tied the game on 4th down with 1:16 left in the game. Taylor will still remain a high-floor streaming option Week 3 when the Browns host the Jets on Thursday.
report: Tyrod Taylor completed 22-of-30 passes for 246 yards with one touchdown and one interception in Sunday's Week 2 loss versus the Saints.

impact: It will be hard to do this one justice in a blurb, but Taylor's night went as poorly as possible even before he was evaluated for a head injury. With the Jets showing zero respect for his arm, they teed off on the box, making life miserable for Taylor as the crowd chanted for Baker Mayfield. Taylor was one for his first seven, and things never got better. He took three sacks, all three coming on first down. He missed Antonio Callaway on what should have been a wide-open 75-yard touchdown and committee intentional grounding in the end zone. It was painful to watch. Even if Taylor gets cleared, Mayfield will finish the game under center.
report: Tyrod Taylor completed 4-of-14 passes for 19 yards in the Browns' Week 3 game against the Jets before leaving with a potential concussion.

impact: It makes for a cruel end to an extremely ugly night. Especially with the Browns having 10 days to prepare for Week 4, they will go ahead and make the switch at quarterback. Baker Mayfield will start against the Raiders with Taylor backing him up. That's if he can clear the concussion protocol in time. Taylor was going to be benched regardless of his health. His play was that poor through his first 2.5 starts.
report: Tyrod Taylor has been diagnosed with a concussion and is week to week.

impact: He was overshadowed by Emmanuel Sanders, but Thomas overcame a slow start to post a pretty good line. His touchdown came from four yards out and ended up being the game-winner. While Case Keenum's apparent affinity for Sanders is a concern, Thomas will remain a solid WR2 next week against the Raiders.
report: Demaryius Thomas hauled in 6-of-10 targets for 63 yards and a touchdown in the Broncos' Week 1 win over the Seahawks.

impact: Thomas was a non-factor Sunday despite the high target count, including two dropped passes. Through two weeks, Thomas has secured just 11-of-21 targets for 81 yards as it appears the receiver you want to own for fantasy in this offense is Emmanuel Sanders. Thomas will head into a Week 3 matchup versus the Ravens as a WR3 for fantasy purposes.
report: Demaryius Thomas caught 5-of-11 targets for 18 yards in Sunday's Week 2 win over the Raiders.

impact: It still was not a great fantasy day, but Thomas was much more efficient in this one. He made a great catch in the third quarter to help get the offense moving, and he had another long gain called back by a penalty. He did briefly leave with what looked like a knee injury in the fourth quarter, but he returned a few plays later. Assuming he is healthy, Thomas will be a WR2 in a good matchup against the Chiefs next Monday night.
report: Demaryius Thomas hauled in all five of his targets for 63 yards in the Broncos' Week 3 loss to the Ravens.

impact: Thomas was a non-factor for most of the game, then was fortunate to score a 42-yard touchdown deep in garbage time of Denver's 34-16 blowout loss.  This was just the second time Thomas has topped 70 yards over his last 16 games.  Thomas will remain a solid-if-unexciting WR2/3 option when the Broncos host the Rams next.  That game's shootout potential does enhance his Week 6 upside.
report: Demaryius Thomas caught 5-of-6 targets for 105 yards and a touchdown in the Broncos' Week 5 loss to the Jets.

impact: Thomas also drew a 19-yard DPI. 45 of Thomas' yards came on a badly-underthrown sideline deep ball from Case Keenum. Thomas managed to come back to the pass and make a nice grab. He displayed fancy footwork on his one-yard score in the fourth quarter. Thomas has scored in back-to-back games but could have a hard time making it 3-for-3 against the Cardinals' decent pass defense in Week 7.
report: Demaryius Thomas caught 3-of-4 targets for 57 yards and a touchdown in the Broncos' Week 6 loss to the Rams.

impact: It was another silent week for Thomas, who has been held under 70 yards in every game but one this season. Thomas was the intended receiver on Case Keenum's lone interception, which occurred during the fourth quarter. It was a poor throw but Thomas probably could have done more to prevent the interception. The long-time Bronco has drawn trade interest recently and could be moved ahead of Tuesday's trade deadline. If Denver holds onto him, he'll face the Texans at home in Week 9.
report: Demaryius Thomas pulled in three of seven targets for 30 yards Sunday in the Broncos’ Week 8 loss to Kansas City.

impact: All three of his catches came in the first quarter and he wasn't heard from again for the rest of the afternoon. In his defense, the Texans' target tree was dwindled completely without Will Fuller (torn ACL) and Keke Coutee (hamstring), allowing DeAndre Hopkins to run away with the team-lead in targets (12). It still bodes well for Thomas that the Texans decidedly featured him as their No. 2 receiver over Tyler Ervin and Vyncint Smith, both who have been with the team all year. He'll stay a WR3 in Week 11 when the Texans face the Redskins post-bye.
report: Demaryius Thomas hauled in all three of his targets for 61 yards in the Texans' Week 9 victory over the Broncos.

impact: He drew one target and has not so much as caught a pass since the first quarter of Week 9 against Denver.  Keke Coutee returned from his hamstring injury for nine targets in Sunday's win.  As a complementary receiver on a run-first team, Thomas will be difficult to trust as a fantasy starter going forward.
report: Demaryius Thomas was held catch-less in Week 11 against Washington.

impact: The 49ers' slot receiver, Taylor's six targets were tied with Pierre Garcon for second on the team behind George Kittle (9).  However, Taylor is more of a Cole Beasley type who will have a big game here or there but isn't fantasy-relevant outside of deep PPR leagues.  Leave Taylor on the wire.
report: Trent Taylor caught 4-of-6 targets for 28 yards in the 49ers' Week 1 loss to the Vikings.

impact: Even with Marquise Goodwin (quad) on the shelf, the second-year slot man failed to make an impact. Taylor had his moments as a rookie but is off to a quiet start this year with just four catches for 28 yards on eight targets. Outside of dynasty leagues, Taylor doesn’t offer much fantasy appeal.
report: Trent Taylor came up empty on both of his targets Sunday in San Francisco’s Week 2 win over the Lions.

impact: Two words: garbage time. Taylor snoozed through the first half, securing his lone target for a two-yard pickup. But with San Francisco behind in the second half, the young slot receiver feasted with six catches including four on the Niners' final drive. Taylor was also the recipient of a one-yard touchdown, which capped a 14-play, 82-yard drive in the fourth quarter. That play came on a successful fourth-down conversion. Taylor entered Sunday's action with 64 yards all SEASON, so this isn't something fantasy owners should grow accustomed to. The second-year La Tech alum gets the Packers on the road in Week 6.
report: Trent Taylor delivered seven catches for 61 yards and a touchdown on eight targets Sunday in San Francisco’s Week 5 loss to the Cardinals.

impact: Thielen had a really quiet preseason but absolutely tore up the interior of the 49ers' defense, running a good majority of his routes out of the slot.  Thielen's 12 looks were five more than Dalvin Cook and six more than Stefon Diggs to lead the team.  His biggest grab was a 34-yard catch-and-run on third down when the 49ers didn't even cover him.  Thielen should have no trouble answering his breakout 2017 and will be a WR1 next week in Green Bay.
report: Adam Thielen caught 6-of-12 targets for 102 yards in the Vikings' Week 1 win over the 49ers.

impact: Stefon Diggs is getting his as well, but Thielen has been Kirk Cousins’ favorite receiver. He now has 25 targets through two games and, more importantly, came up with a great touchdown catch with defenders all around him to help tie this game late in the fourth quarter. He added a 25-yard catch in overtime to help set up one of the two missed field goals. With the Bills on deck, Thielen should remain locked into fantasy lineups.
report: Adam Thielen hauled in 12-of-13 targets for 131 yards and a touchdown in the Vikings' Week 2 tie with the Packers.

impact: Thielen benefited from negative game script as the Vikings found themselves down 27-0 for the entire second half of play. He's quietly accrued at least 12 targets and eclipsed the 100-yard mark in all three of Minnesota's games this season. Stefon Diggs (4-17 Sunday) remains a factor on the outside, seeing 10 targets against Buffalo, but it's clear who Cousins' favorite receiver between the duo is. Thielen again has the easier path to production Thursday in the slot against the Rams' stout outside corners.
report: Adam Thielen hauled in 14-of-19 targets for 105 yards in the Vikings' Week 3 loss to the Bills.

impact: With the effort, Thielen becomes just the third player in league history to post 100 yards in each of his team's first five games. Thielen's season
report: Adam Thielen caught 7-of-10 targets for 116 yards and a touchdown in the Vikings' Week 5 win over the Eagles.

impact: It's the sixth straight game Thielen has went over 100 yards. The Vikings pass offense went through Thielen, who caught Kirk Cousins' only touchdown on a red-zone pass in the middle of the end-zone. He also had a highlight diving sideline catch in third quarter. Thielen has been the highest floor receiver in the league this year. He'll remain a locked-in WR1 for Week 7 against the Jets.
report: Adam Thielen caught 11-of-15 targets for 123 yards and a touchdown in the Vikings' Week 6 win over the Cardinals.

impact: Thielen got the scoring started with a 34-yard touchdown on the opening drive, beating backup-turned-starter CB Darryl Roberts as he was falling away in the end zone.  With his seventh-straight 100-yard game to open the season, Thielen has set a new record.  Thielen is an obvious elite WR1 and will be involved in a potential shootout next week at home against the Saints.
report: Adam Thielen caught 9-of-10 targets for 110 yards and one touchdown in the Vikings' 37-17, Week 7 win over the Jets.

impact: Thielen got the scoring started with a 34-yard touchdown on the opening drive, beating backup-turned-starter CB Darryl Roberts as he was falling away in the end zone.  With his seventh-straight 100-yard game to open the season, Thielen has set a new record.  Thielen is an obvious elite WR1 and will be involved in a potential shootout next week at home against the Saints.
report: Adam Thielen caught 9-of-10 targets for 110 yards and one touchdown in the Vikings' 37-17, Week 7 win over the Jets.

impact: Thielen went over 100 yards again this week. He also set an NFL record for the most catches in the first eight games of a season. Thielen's touchdown didn’t come until late in the fourth quarter on a goal-line pass from Kirk Cousins. It was another dominant effort from Thielen, but the story of the game was a costly red-zone fumble he lost that flipped the momentum for the Saints. Thielen has been playing at an MVP level this season and will remain a locked-in WR1 for Week 9 against Lions.
report: Adam Thielen caught seven passes for 103 yards and a touchdown in the Vikings' Week 8 loss to the Saints.

impact: Thielen had eclipsed 100 yards receiving in the Vikings' first eight games, setting an NFL record, but that streak is now over.  His seven targets led the team on a day without Stefon Diggs (ribs) in the lineup, but Kirk Cousins attempted just 22 passes with the Vikings winning with relative ease.  Thielen's touchdown was from two yards away.  He also appeared to injure his calf at one point and was getting it wrapped on the sideline while the defense was on the field.  Thielen will get the bye week before going to Chicago in Week 11.
report: Adam Thielen caught 4-of-7 targets for 22 yards and one touchdown in the Vikings' 24-9, Week 9 win over the Lions.

impact: He saw a target in the first quarter, then wasn't heard from again.  Until this offense shows any signs of functional ability, Taywan will be waiver-wire material in fantasy leagues.  He played behind Tajae Sharpe in the opener.
report: Taywan Taylor went catch-less in Week 1 against the Dolphins.

impact: Taylor only saw four targets but made the most of one in particular when he shook off several tackles and ran 18 yards for Tennessee's only offensive score of the day. The team's only other touchdown came on a 66-yard direct-snap pass on fourth down from special teamers Dan Cruikshank and Kevin Byard. Taylor still isn't involved enough to consider him a weekly WR3, but his potential was certainly flashed Sunday. He's worth stashing in deeper leagues.
report: Taywan Taylor caught 3-of-4 targets for 32 yards and one touchdown in the Titans' Week 2 victory over the Texans.

impact: Taylor led the Titans in targets, but no one in this pass-catcher corps was ever going to produce on a day where Marcus Mariota and Blaine Gabbert combined for 108 passing yards.  Despite his big-play ability, Taylor has not yet put enough production or usage in the box score for Week 4 fantasy consideration against Philadelphia.
report: Taywan Taylor caught 4-of-5 targets for 30 yards in the Titans' Week 3 win over the Jaguars.

impact: This is the usage fantasy players were hoping for in the first game without Rishard Matthews. Working as the clear No. 2, Taylor was consistently involved all game, and he made perhaps the most important play of the day when he converted a fourth-and-long in overtime with a 19-yard catch along the sideline. Talented as they come and the No. 2 option in an ascending passing game, Taylor should be rostered in all formats.
report: Taywan Taylor hauled in 7-of-9 targets for 77 yards in the Titans' Week 4 win over the Eagles.

impact: Taylor flashed his big-play potential on a gain of 19, but he also cost the Titans with a first-quarter fumble that Buffalo turned into a Josh Allen rushing TD.  And that proved to be more than the difference in the game as Tennessee fell 13-12.  Taylor will be a WR5 in Week 6 against Baltimore's shutdown secondary.
report: Taywan Taylor caught 3-of-5 targets for 30 yards in the Titans' Week 5 loss to the Bills.

impact: Taylor's involvement has only gone downhill since it (coincidently) peaked a few short weeks ago, now seeing him account for just the fourth-most receiving yards on Tennessee. Despite his obvious athletic edge and explosiveness over incumbent No. 2 Tajae Sharpe, the latter was still heavily used and led the Titans in receiving (33 yards). Taylor is unfortunately only worth a stash in deeper leagues at this point.
report: Taywan Taylor hauled in his only target for a measly 13 yards in the Titans' abysmal Week 6 loss to the Ravens.

impact: Taylor had a bad drop on what would have been a 20-plus yard catch. He's been a non-factor over the last couple weeks and is behind Tajae Sharpe for targets. Taylor is just a dynasty stash.
report: Taywan Taylor one pass for eight yards in Week 7 against the Chargers.

impact: Taylor had a bad drop on what would have been a 20-plus yard catch. He's been a non-factor over the last couple weeks and is behind Tajae Sharpe for targets. Taylor is just a dynasty stash.
report: Taywan Taylor one pass for eight yards in Week 7 against the Chargers.

impact: Tate had a real quiet first half and dropped a couple balls this evening, but he did score the Lions' only offensive touchdown.  The Lions marched right down the field on the first possession of the third quarter, with Tate capping it off with a 24-yard touchdown.  Tate's 15 targets were three more than Kenny Golladay and seven more than Marvin Jones to lead the team.  Fire Tate up as a WR2 with upside next week in a mouthwatering date against the 49ers.
report: Golden Tate caught 7-of-15 targets for 79 yards and one touchdown in the Lions' Week 1 loss to the Jets.

impact: Tate was having a rather quiet day until he broke off an enormous gain in the fourth quarter, torching K’Waun Williams for a 67-yard pickup. That was the longest play from scrimmage for either team, beating Matt Breida’s third-quarter touchdown run by a single yard. The catch was also Tate’s longest since Week 17 of last year when he nabbed a 71-yard touchdown against the Packers. Even with Kenny Golladay taking on a much larger role this year, Tate continues to be a volume monster, amassing 28 targets over his first two games. Fantasy owners can start him with confidence against New England in Week 3.
report: Golden Tate chipped in with seven catches for 109 on 13 targets Sunday in Detroit’s Week 2 loss to the Niners.

impact: He led the Lions in targets and tied for a team high in yards. It was still a mostly quiet night for Tate with Kenny Golladay and Marvin Jones doing all the scoring. Tate doesn’t play in two wide sets, but he’s still getting 80 percent of snaps. He's a Week 4 FLEX against the Cowboys.
report: Golden Tate caught 6-of-8 passes for 69 yards in Week 3 against the Patriots.

impact: It seemed that whenever the Lions needed a big play on Sunday, Tate was there waiting to unleash mayhem on Dallas. The veteran slot man got his day started with a masterful 45-yard touchdown, making Jeff Heath and Jordan Lewis miss on his way to the end zone. Tate came up huge on the Lions' final drive, dusting Xavien Woods for a 35-yard pick-up before capping the drive with a 38-yard touchdown on a deep heave from Matthew Stafford, which gave Detroit a one-point lead with 2:17 left in the fourth quarter. This was Tate's first career game with 100-plus yards and two touchdowns. The stud 30-year-old will hope to keep the train rolling when the Lions return home to face Green Bay in Week 5.
report: Golden Tate secured eight catches for 132 yards and two touchdowns on eight targets Sunday in the Lions’ Week 4 loss to the Cowboys.

impact: Tate came back to earth after his 8-132-2 day in Dallas last week.  Matthew Stafford attempted just 26 passes with the Lions smashing the Packers 24-0 at halftime.  Tate didn't get his first catch until late in the second quarter.  A borderline WR1/2, Tate and the Lions are off until Week 7 at the Dolphins.
report: Golden Tate caught 5-of-7 targets for 42 yards in the Lions' Week 5 win over the Packers.

impact: Tate came back to earth after his 8-132-2 day in Dallas last week.  Matthew Stafford attempted just 26 passes with the Lions smashing the Packers 24-0 at halftime.  Tate didn't get his first catch until late in the second quarter.  A borderline WR1/2, Tate and the Lions are off until Week 7 at the Dolphins.
report: Golden Tate caught 5-of-7 targets for 42 yards in the Lions' Week 5 win over the Packers.

impact: Tate had the most yards from scrimmage of the Lions' "big three" at receiver. It was a quiet day for all involved with the Lions gutting the Dolphins on the ground. The Lions had their biggest rushing day since 1997. With just 78 yards receiving over his past two games, Tate will look to get cooking again as a mid-range WR2 against the Seahawks in Week 8.
report: Golden Tate caught 4-of-6 targets for 36 yards in the Lions' Week 7 win over the Dolphins, adding a 30-yard rush.

impact: Tate had the most yards from scrimmage of the Lions' "big three" at receiver. It was a quiet day for all involved with the Lions gutting the Dolphins on the ground. The Lions had their biggest rushing day since 1997. With just 78 yards receiving over his past two games, Tate will look to get cooking again as a mid-range WR2 against the Seahawks in Week 8.
report: Golden Tate caught 4-of-6 targets for 36 yards in the Lions' Week 7 win over the Dolphins, adding a 30-yard rush.

impact: Tate's seven catches were his most since Week 4, though he's now been held to 50 yards or fewer in three-straight contests. With Matthew Stafford's volume unpredictable so far this season, Tate will be a low-end WR2 for Week 9 against the Vikings.
report: Golden Tate caught 7-of-12 targets for 50 yards in the Lions' Week 8 loss to the Seahawks, adding a three-yard rush.

impact: Tate actually led the team in targets, catches, and yards in a pitiful display from the Eagles' offense. That said, it was promising to see Tate heavily utilized after playing just 29 percent of the snaps in his debut. With his role growing, Tate will be in the FLEX conversation next week against the Giants.
report: Golden Tate hauled in 5-of-8 targets for 48 yards in the Eagles' Week 11 loss to the Saints.

impact: The Dolphins were losing 38-0 when Tannehill was sent to the showers midway through the fourth quarter. The Dolphins' offense got hit by a bus, but Tannehill had plenty of help in the meltdown. C Daniel Kilgore broke his arm, RT Ja'Wuan James got benched and an errant Travis Swanson snap led to a disastrous turnover. Tannehill routinely had no one to throw to thanks to excellent Patriots coverage. His pick was an inexcusable arm punt down the sideline. It was a "burn the tape" effort. Despite today's capsizing, Tannehill will remain a solid QB2 for next week's matchup with the Bengals' struggling defense.
report: Ryan Tannehill completed 11-of-20 passes for 100 yards, zero touchdowns and an interception in the Dolphins' Week 4 game against the Patriots.

impact: He also lost a fumbled that was returned for a touchdown. Tannehill had one of the worst pick-sixes of the year on short-armed throw directly into the Bengals defensive line. He's predictably regressed after exploiting weak matchups to open the season, throwing for under 200 yards in consecutive games. Tannehill won't be on the QB2 radar for Week 6 against Chicago.
report: Ryan Tannehill completed 20-of-35 passes for 185 yards with a touchdown and two interceptions in Miami's Week 5 loss to the Bengals.

impact: It was not the most efficient day, but Sutton showed off his talent on two 20-plus yard catches and worked as the clear No. 3 receiver. He could struggle for consistent targets behind Emmanuel Sanders and Demaryius Thomas, but Sutton offers some deep-league value already and would be a plug-and-play starter if anything happened to the top-two receivers.
report: Courtland Sutton hauled in 2-of-5 targets for 45 yards in the Broncos' Week 1 win over the Seahawks.

impact: Sutton's lowly line was due to two near-misses as he has a 14-yard touchdown called back when he stepped out of bounds as well as another potential 35-yard gain when he failed to catch a pass cleanly down the sideline. The rookie has a promising 11 targets through two games, but has managed just three receptions for 54 yards. He is only a bench stash at this juncture of the season as the Broncos head to Baltimore in Week 3.
report: Courtland Sutton caught 1-of-6 targets for nine yards in Sunday's Week 2 win over the Raiders.

impact: Both of his catches went for big gains, and one converted a third-and-long. Sutton continues to look good when he gets an opportunity, but he has now failed to top two catches in each of the first three games. He is just a bench stash.
report: Courtland Sutton hauled in 2-of-3 targets for 37 yards in the Broncos' Week 3 loss to the Ravens.

impact: Sutton caught an early eight-yard touchdown and drew another end-zone target later on, only to hobble off the field with a leg injury in the second half.  Sutton's status for Week 6 against the Rams is unclear.  His injury led to more playing time for DaeSean Hamilton, who caught three balls for 44 yards.
report: Courtland Sutton caught 2-of-6 targets for 18 yards and a touchdown in the Broncos' Week 5 loss to the Jets.

impact: Sutton was also called for a down-field blocking penalty that cost the Broncos a potential touchdown in the fourth quarter. 41 of Sutton's yards came on an underthrown pass from Case Keenum. His 58 yards were a new season/career-high, which tells you most of what you need to know about Sutton's re-draft value as Keenum's No. 3 wideout.
report: Courtland Sutton caught 3-of-4 targets for 58 yards in the Broncos' Week 6 loss to the Rams.

impact: Sutton led the team with his 78 yards, which was also a career-high for the rookie. The 23-year-old continues to make his living off big plays. His longest catch Sunday came on a 42-yard missile from Case Keenum on the closing drive of the first half. Sutton's volume is still lacking—he's caught just 17 passes all year—but the second-round SMU alum certainly offers breakout potential. He's someone to keep an eye on, especially as rumors swirl of the Broncos potentially dealing Emmanuel Sanders and Demaryius Thomas ahead of Tuesday's trade deadline.
report: Courtland Sutton delivered three catches for 78 yards on four targets Sunday in Denver’s Week 8 loss to the Chiefs.

impact: He nearly hauled in a deep throw for a touchdown from Case Keenum, but the ball was slapped out of his grasp the moment he tried tucking it in. All in all the rookie was used as expected in the team's first game without Demaryius Thomas, leading the team in air yards (67) as the primary downfield threat. TE Jeff Heuerman turned out to be the biggest beneficiary sans Thomas, seeing a team-high 11 targets. Sutton will still struggle with consistent fantasy production (but keep a high ceiling) if he doesn't start seeing more targets moving forward.
report: Courtland Sutton caught 3-of-5 targets for 57 yards in the Broncos' Week 9 loss to the Texans.

impact: As he has throughout the year, Sutton made his living off big plays. The rookie aided a touchdown drive with a 39-yard grab to open the fourth quarter, then made his biggest contribution of the afternoon by pulling in a 30-yard pass from Case Keenum on the Broncos' final possession. That put Denver in field goal range with 20 seconds left in regulation. The 78 yards matched a career-high for Sutton, who has now cleared 50 yards receiving in four of his last five contests. Sutton will try to make it five out of six when he takes the field next week against the Steelers.
report: Courtland Sutton absorbed three of six targets for 78 yards Sunday in the Broncos’ Week 11 win over Los Angeles.

impact: Most of his production including four of his five catches came in the second half. The seven targets were a career-high for Swaim, who entered Sunday’s action having caught just 12 passes over 30 career games. Despite his recent emergence, Swaim is not worth pursuing in fantasy.
report: Geoff Swaim contributed five catches for a team-high 47 yards on seven targets Sunday in the Cowboys’ Week 3 loss to the Seahawks.

impact: Swaim’s third-quarter touchdown, a one-yarder off a play-action pass from Dak Prescott, was the first of his career. The 25-year-old seems to have emerged as the Cowboys’ top receiving tight end—neither Blake Jarwin or Rico Gathers have caught a pass this year—but for streaming purposes, he’s still not someone fantasy owners should be looking at.
report: Geoff Swaim corralled three-of-five targets for 39 yards and a touchdown Sunday in the Cowboys’ Week 4 victory over Detroit.

impact: Swaim didn't move the needle much in this one. He's been the Cowboys' most productive tight end this year, though that's not exactly a high bar to clear. Swaim won't be an appealing streamer against the Redskins next week.
report: Geoff Swaim delivered two catches for 21 yards on two targets Sunday in the Cowboys’ Week 6 win over Jacksonville.

impact: Rookie Dalton Schultz was additionally active for the first time all year, giving the Cowboys four active tight ends on game day. Swaim led the group with 25 receiving yards, but all saw at least one target. If you hadn't streamed Swaim to this point, that ship's sailed.
report: Geoff Swaim clenched all three of his targets for 25 yards in the Cowboys' Week 7 loss to Washington.

impact: Standard day at the office for the tight end.  Swaim has topped 50 yards just once this season and has only one score.  He's not on the fantasy radar.
report: Geoff Swaim caught 4-of-5 targets for 24 yards in the Cowboys' Week 11 win over the Falcons.

impact: He scored a ten-yard touchdown early.  After a lengthy weather delay, Stills came back to burn Titans CB Malcolm Butler for a 75-yard touchdown.  Long blocked from being Miami's top receiver by Jarvis Landry, Stills has now been freed.  He should be loaded into fantasy lineups as an upside WR3 in Week 2 at the Jets.
report: Kenny Stills logged four catches for 106 yards and two touchdowns on only five targets in the Dolphins' Week 1 win over the Titans.

impact: Stills teased his upside with a monster Week 1, then returned to Earth in Week 2 as the Dolphins needed only 17 completions and 168 yards to beat the Jets.  In a low-volume passing offense, Stills will remain a dicey week-to-week proposition as a WR3/flex play.  He does get a plus draw next against Oakland.
report: Kenny Stills caught 2-of-3 targets for 17 yards in the Dolphins' Week 2 win over the Jets.

impact: Stills' score — his third in three games — was a 34-yarder where he got a step on Marcus Gilchrist and Ryan Tannehill threw it where only Stills could grab it in the end zone. Stills has now cleared 60 yards in 2-of-3 games but has just 13 total targets. That is going to make it difficult to provide weekly WR3 value. Stills is a WR4 you can plug in with genuine optimism he will reach his upside.
report: Kenny Stills caught 3-of-5 targets for 61 yards and a touchdown in the Dolphins' Week 3 win over the Raiders.

impact: DeVante Parker (quad) was sidelined, but Stills still posted his second-lowest yardage total of the season. Ryan Tannehill couldn't find any open receivers. With four games in the books, Stills is on pace for 48/896/12. The yards would be the second most of Stills' career. The touchdown pace should dissipate, though Stills does have a nine-TD season to his name.
report: Kenny Stills caught 3-of-6 targets for 40 yards in the Dolphins' Week 4 loss to the Patriots.

impact: Stills was invisible in a game Ryan Tannehill threw for 185 yards. He couldn't get anything going down the field and finished behind Albert Wilson in targets. After a fast start, Stills has been held 50 yards the last two weeks. He'll be a boom/bust WR3 for a Week 6 matchup with Chicago.
report: Kenny Stills caught 2-of-5 passes for 17 yards in the Dolphins' Week 5 loss to the Bengals.

impact: Stills had a goose egg through four quarters before coming down with a miraculous 35-yard grab off a deflection during overtime. Though he was held without a catch in regulation, Stills did contribute a two-point conversion during Miami’s fourth-quarter comeback. The 26-year-old hasn’t been much help to fantasy owners this year, clearing 40 yards receiving just once in his last five games. He’ll take a three-game touchdown drought into next week’s game against Detroit.
report: Kenny Stills managed just one catch for 35 yards on two targets Sunday in the Dolphins’ Week 6 win over Chicago.

impact: Stills pulled up injured on the Dolphins' desperation final drive. Stills also got banged up on his touchdown, where he crashed into a security guard. The Dolphins have moved the field far too close to the end zone. Stills displayed fancy footwork on his score. With Albert Wilson suffering a potentially serious injury today, the Dolphins could be forced to hold onto DeVante Parker.
report: Kenny Stills caught 1-of-3 targets for a five-yard touchdown in the Dolphins' Week 7 loss to the Lions.

impact: Stills did not appear limited in his return from injury, but he was not targeted at all in the first half. He did get on the board early in the third quarter, converting a third down with a 19-yard catch-and-run, but that ended up being his only catch. In a struggling pass offense and with a lot of competition for targets, Stills will not be a recommended fantasy option next week in Green Bay.
report: Kenny Stills caught his only target for 19 yards in the Dolphins' Week 9 win over the Jets.

impact: He's been removed from the team's injury report in back-to-back weeks, but Stills is obviously still limited by an ailing groin (and shoddy play under center). He's totaled just five catches over the last four games, averaging 2.2 targets in that span. If Stills has any hope of turning back the clock to his performance through the first quarter of the season, he'll need to fully heal over the bye. Hopefully Ryan Tannehill, who showed rapport with Stills, returns fully healed, too.
report: Kenny Stills clenched 2-of-3 targets for 26 yards in the Dolphins' Week 10 give-up to the Packers.

impact: Stewart got some run after Wayne Gallman left with an injury, but he was the clear No. 3 back before that. Even if something happened to Saquon Barkley, Stewart would not be an enticing fantasy play. He does not need to be rostered in any format.
report: Jonathan Stewart rushed twice for eight yards in the Giants' Week 1 loss to the Jaguars.

impact: St. Brown made the start as the No. 3 wideout with Randall Cobb and Geronimo Allison out.  He made a sliding 17-yard grab for his first NFL catch and had a late 54-yard pickup to pad the stats.  St. Brown will head back to the bench when Cobb and/or Allison come back, maybe as soon as Week 6.
report: Equanimeous St. Brown caught 3-of-5 targets for 89 yards in the Packers' Week 5 loss to the Lions.

impact: The Lions ended Stafford's suffering with 8:15 left in the fourth quarter with the team trailing 48-17.  Stafford did not play well at all, but he didn't get a lot of help, with his offensive line whiffing on blocks, receivers dropping passes, and the running game again doing nothing.  Two of Stafford's picks went to ILB Darron Lee, and one of them was returned for a touchdown.  Stafford put together one impressive drive, marching 80 yards right down the field in 1:50 on four passes on the first drive of the third quarter, finishing it with a 24-yard touchdown to Golden Tate.  Stafford appeared to injure his left knee at one point, limping badly, and then also got the wind knocked out of him.  He missed one play.  Stafford will look to bounce back next week at the 49ers.
report: Matthew Stafford completed 27-of-46 passes for 286 yards, one touchdown, and four interceptions in the Lions' Week 1 loss to the Jets on Monday night.

impact: He was sacked twice for a loss of 18 yards and also lost a fumble. For Stafford, this was a much better game than his previous outing, a four-interception nightmare against the Jets on Monday Night Football. Though the numbers don’t really reflect it, Stafford still looked a tad off, continually airmailing deep balls downfield including one to a wide-open Marvin Jones that should have gone for an easy touchdown. Stafford did throw a touchdown to Jones later in the game, finding him for a five-yard score with 8:36 remaining in the fourth quarter. Stafford added another touchdown later in the fourth on a 15-yard end-zone heave to tight end Michael Roberts. The Lions made a valiant comeback in the second half but fell just short with Stafford’s fourth-down incompletion sealing the game with 14 seconds remaining. Stafford and the Lions will try to avoid falling to 0-3 next week against New England.
report: Matthew Stafford completed 34-of-53 passes for 347 yards and three touchdowns while adding one rush for eight yards Sunday in the Lions’ Week 2 loss to the 49ers.

impact: Stafford was sharp in this one, completing 12 of his first 13 passes. He played keep-away from the Patriots with clock killing drives. Stafford made a sidearm throw to Kenny Golladay in the red-zone for his first TD before hitting a wide open Marvin Jones from 33 yards out on his second. His only blunder was an interception on the opening drive of the second half. Stafford has rebounded from his rough Week 1 to post consecutive multi-TD games. He'll get a matchup with the Cowboys in Week 4.
report: Matthew Stafford completed 27-of-36 passes for 262 yards, two touchdowns, and an interception in Detroit's Week 3 win over the Patriots.

impact: Stafford was dropped three times for a loss of 21 yards. Playing in his hometown of Dallas, the former first overall pick impressed by going over the 300-yard barrier for the second time this season. Stafford made use of all his receivers but had his most success throwing to Golden Tate, who absorbed all eight of his targets for 132 yards and two touchdowns. His second score gave Detroit a one-point lead with a little over two minutes left in the fourth quarter, though the Cowboys wound up winning on a walk-off field goal by Brett Maher. Stafford and the Lions will hope to avoid falling to 1-4 when they face the Packers next week at Ford Field.
report: Matthew Stafford completed 24-of-30 passes for 307 yards and two touchdowns while adding five yards on two carries Sunday in the Lions’ Week 4 loss to Dallas.

impact: Detroit shocked Green Bay and jumped out to a big 24-0 halftime lead, so Stafford didn't have to do much of anything in the second half despite the Packers threatening a comeback before losing by eight.  Stafford threw just 11 second-half passes and watched LeGarrette Blount score a pair of short touchdowns before the break.  Kenny Golladay also had a 47-yard touchdown called back on a penalty, while Marvin Jones was unable to complete a diving catch on a 42-yard score.  The day could have been a lot bigger for Stafford.  The Lions are now on their bye week.
report: Matthew Stafford completed 14-of-26 passes for 183 yards and two touchdowns in the Lions' Week 5 win over the Packers.

impact: The Dolphins' secondary erased Stafford's elite receiver trio, but he compensated in fantasy by finding TE Michael Roberts for a pair of scores. The Lions rode their running game. No pass catcher drew more than six targets or posted more than 48 yards. Having a quiet roto campaign, Stafford will be a QB2 for Week 8 against the Seahawks' still-feisty defense.
report: Matthew Stafford completed 18-of-22 passes for 217 yards and two touchdowns in the Lions' 32-21, Week 7 win over the Dolphins.

impact: The Dolphins' secondary erased Stafford's elite receiver trio, but he compensated in fantasy by finding TE Michael Roberts for a pair of scores. The Lions rode their running game. No pass catcher drew more than six targets or posted more than 48 yards. Having a quiet roto campaign, Stafford will be a QB2 for Week 8 against the Seahawks' still-feisty defense.
report: Matthew Stafford completed 18-of-22 passes for 217 yards and two touchdowns in the Lions' 32-21, Week 7 win over the Dolphins.

impact: Stafford also lost a fumble. Attempting to climb the pocket, the ball got knocked out from behind. Stafford's pick was an awful decision in the red zone, though the game was already in hand for the Seahawks. Stafford simply did not see Justin Coleman. Stafford's score was a dime to Marvin Jones after he seemed to be going down for a sack. The 40-attempt day was Stafford's first since Week 2. It was a product of the Lions playing from behind all afternoon. Detroit is headed to Minnesota for Week 9.
report: Matthew Stafford completed 27-of-40 passes for 310 yards, two touchdowns and an interception in the Lions' 28-14, Week 8 loss to the Seahawks.

impact: Stafford took a career-high 10 sacks in this one and also lost a fumble on a flat-out dumb improvised pitch to Kerryon Johnson, who wasn't expecting the ball; the Vikings scooped it and returned it for a touchdown to put the game well out of reach.  The Lions were especially terrible in the red zone in this one, settling for a trio of short-ish Matt Prater field goals for their only points.  The trade of Golden Tate really hurt this offense on third down.  Stafford will not be a fantasy play in one-quarterback leagues next week at the Bears.
report: Matthew Stafford completed 25-of-36 passes for 199 scoreless yards in the Lions' 24-9, Week 9 loss to the Vikings.

impact: He was sacked six times for a loss of 45 yards. Stafford salvaged the day somewhat, at least for fantasy purposes, by slinging a pair of fourth-quarter touchdowns, one to Kenny Golladay and another to rookie Kerryon Johnson. Just as he was last week against the Vikings, Stafford spent most of the day running for his life as Chicago's stout pass rush overwhelmed Detroit's nonexistent offensive line. Stafford's first interception wasn't his fault—Marvin Jones fell down on the play, allowing Bryce Callahan to swoop in for an easy pick. He had no one to blame but himself for the second interception, which was essentially an arm punt to Prince Amukamara. Playing on the road against one of the league's toughest defenses, Stafford just didn't have it on Sunday. With Golden Tate gone and Marvin Jones (knee) banged up, the former No. 1 pick will have his work cut out for him when the Panthers come to town in Week 11.
report: Matthew Stafford completed 25-of-42 passes for 274 yards with two touchdowns and two interceptions while adding nine yards on two carries Sunday in the Lions’ Week 10 loss to Chicago.

impact: Stafford had about as nondescript a first half as possible. He threw for just 64 yards on 20 attempts, and the success the Lions found on offense came down to Kerryon Johnson. Stafford should have thrown an interception, but Kenny Golladay was able to wrestle the ball away from the corner. It was much of the same for Stafford in the second half, but he made a couple big plays when it mattered most. The biggest was a beautifully placed throw which Golladay was able to bring in for what amounted to the game-winning score. The Lions might have to lean on Stafford more with Johnson injured -- he left the game in the third quarter -- but he still will not be an exciting fantasy option against the Bears on Thanksgiving.
report: Matthew Stafford completed 23-of-37 passes for 220 yards and a touchdown in the Lions' Week 11 win over the Panthers.

impact: With Ted Ginn (knee) out, Smith saw an increased role and made the most of his three looks.  He scored the 62-yard touchdown where he was literally wide open with no defender within 10 yards of him.  It was the pass play that Brees became the NFL's all-time passing yards leader, passing Peyton Manning.  Smith wasn't done, though, as he reeled in a total dime from Brees for a 35-yard score in the third quarter.  Smith is an exciting Dynasty prospect but figures to play a low-volume role when Ginn is back healthy.  There are just so many mouths to feed.
report: Tre'Quan Smith caught all three of his targets for 111 yards and two touchdowns in the Saints' Week 5 win over the Redskins on Monday night.

impact: Smith almost made a one-handed catch in the end zone in the first quarter but couldn't haul it in. It was a quiet day thereafter, though Smith made an excellent sideline grab. He has six receptions on nine targets in two contests with Ted Ginn sidelined.
